[
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Foreword"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No unabridged edition of <Swiss Family Robinson> exists in English.\nIndeed, the book has been rewritten so many times, by so many\neditors, that it can legitimately be said that that no complete\nedition of the book exists in <em>any</em> language."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Johann David Wyss, a Swiss pastor, originally wrote this book\nto entertain and instruct his four sons. Years later, his son\nJohann (or Jeanâ€”accounts differ) Rudolf Wyss, by then a professor\nof philosophy, persuaded his father to allow him to complete and\nedit the unfinished manuscript. It was published in two volumes\nin Zurich in 1812-1813."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Its French translator, Mme de Montholieu, obtained permission\nto greatly enlarge the book. It was published in five volumes\nfrom 1824 through 1826. The first English edition, abridged,\nwas published in 1814; it was followed by several other English\ntranslations of varying quality. In 1849 W. H. G. Kingston\nre-translated, and greatly abridged, Mme. De Montholieu's\nversion. Most English versions are based on Kingston's abridged\nversion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Despite a vast number of amusing errors in flora and fauna, the\nbook has entertained, and warmed the hearts of, many generations.\nHowever, most modern editions omit an incredible amount even of\nKingston's translation by making small cuttings here and there,\nsome of them maddeningly inept. The Editor's Cut edition from\nPink Tree Press has been based on, and compared with, no fewer\nthan five previous editions, all of them out of copyright. Most,\nthough not all, of the cuttings have been restored. The material\nthat continues to be omitted is of little imaginable interest to\nanyone other than a scholar of nineteenth century literature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Paragraphing has been redone in order to facilitate ease of\nreading. Some archaic spelling and grammar have been retained,\nas they are part of the flavor of the book; they have been changed\nwhere necessary for clarity. The British-style punctuation has\nbeen retained. The lengthy and unnecessary chapter headings have\nbeen omitted. Some parenthetical information is provided, most\noften to define words no longer to be found in many English\ndictionaries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Anne Wingate, Ph.D.\nEditor-in-Chief\nPink Tree Press"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 1"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For many days we had been tempest-tossed. Six times had the darkness\nclosed over a wild and terrific scene, and returning light as often\nbrought but renewed distress, for the raging storm increased in\nfury until on the seventh day all hope was lost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were driven completely out of our course; no conjecture\ncould be formed as to our whereabouts. The crew had lost heart,\nand were utterly exhausted by incessant labour. The riven masts\nhad gone by the board, leaks had been sprung in every direction,\nand the water, which rushed in, gained upon us rapidly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Instead of reckless oaths, the seamen now uttered frantic cries to\nGod for mercy, mingled with strange and often ludicrous vows, to\nbe performed should deliverance be granted. Every man on board\nalternately commended his soul to his Creator, and strove to\nbethink himself of some means of saving his life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My heart sank as I looked round upon my family in the midst of\nthese horrors. Our four young sons were overpowered by terror.\n'Dear children,' said I, 'if the Lord will, He can save us even\nfrom this fearful peril; if not, let us calmly yield our lives\ninto His hand, and think of the joy and blessedness of finding\nourselves for ever and ever united in that happy home above.\nEven death is not too bitter, when it does not separate those\nwho love one another.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At these words my weeping wife looked bravely up, and, as the\nboys clustered round her, she began to cheer and encourage them\nwith calm and loving words. I rejoiced to see her fortitude,\nthough my heart was ready to break as I gazed on my dear ones."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We knelt down together, one after another praying with deep\nearnestness and emotion. Fritz, in particular, besought help\nand deliverance for his dear parents and brothers, as though\nquite forgetting himself. Our hearts were soothed by the never-\nfailing comfort of child-like confiding prayer, and the horrors\nof our situation seemed less overwhelming. 'Ah,' thought I,\n'the Lord will hear our prayer! He will help us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Amid the roar of the thundering waves I suddenly heard the cry\nof 'Land! land!', while at the same instant the ship struck with\na frightful shock, which threw everyone to the deck, and seemed\nto threaten her immediate destruction. Dreadful sounds betokened\nthe breaking up of the ship, and the roaring waters poured in on\nall sides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then the voice of the captain was heard above the tumult, shouting,\n'Lower away the boats! We are lost!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Lost!' I exclaimed, and the word went like a dagger to my heart;\nbut seeing my children's terror renewed, I composed myself,\ncalling out cheerfully, 'Take courage, my boys! We are all above\nwater yet. There is the land not far off, let us do our best to\nreach it. You know God helps those that help themselves! Remain\nwith your mother, while I go on deck to see what is best to be\ndone now.' With that, I left them and went on deck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A wave instantly threw me down; another followed, and then another,\nas I contrived to find my footing. The ship was shattered on all\ndirections, and on one side there was a large hole in the hull."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Forgetting the passengers, the ship's company crowded into the\nlifeboats, and the last who entered cut the davit ropes to cast\neach boat into the sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "What was my horror when through the foam and spray I beheld the\nlast remaining boat leave the ship, the last of the seamen spring\ninto her and push off, regardless of my cries and entreaties that\nwe might be allowed to share their slender chance of preserving\ntheir lives. My voice was drowned in the howling of the blast,\nand even had the crew wished it, the return of the boat was\nimpossible, for the waves were mountain-high."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Casting my eyes despairingly around, I became gradually aware\nthat our position was by no means hopeless, inasmuch as the\nstern of the ship containing our cabin was jammed between two\nhigh rocks, and was partly raised from among the breakers which\ndashed the fore-part to pieces. As the clouds of mist and rain\ndrove past, I could make out, through rents in the vaporous\ncurtain, a line of rocky coast, and, rugged as it was, my heart\nbounded towards it as a sign of help in the hour of need."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Yet the sense of our lonely and forsaken condition weighed heavily\nupon me as I returned to my family, constraining myself to say\nwith a smile, 'Courage, dear ones! Although our good ship will\nnever sail more, she is so placed that our cabin will remain\nabove water, and tomorrow, if the wind and waves abate, I see no\nreason why we should not be able to get ashore.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These few words had an immediate effect on the spirits of my\nchildren, for my family had the habit of trusting in my assurances.\nThe boys at once regarded our problematical chance of escaping as\na happy certainty, and began to enjoy the relief from the violent\npitching and rolling of the vessel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife, however, perceived my distress and anxiety in spite of\nmy forced composure, and I made her comprehend our real situation,\ngreatly fearing the effect of the intelligence on her nerves. Not\nfor a moment did her courage and trust in Providence forsake her,\nand on seeing this, my fortitude revived."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We must find some food, and take a good supper,' said she, 'it\nwill never do to grow faint by fasting too long. We shall require\nour utmost strength tomorrow.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Night drew on apace, the storm was as fierce as ever, and at\nintervals we were startled by crashes announcing further damage\nto our unfortunate ship. We thought of the lifeboats, and feared\nthat all they contained must have sunk under the foaming waves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'God will help us soon now, won't He, father?' said my youngest\nchild."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You silly little thing,' said Fritz, my eldest son, sharply,\n'don't you know that we must not settle what God is to do for\nus? We must have patience and wait His time.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very well said, had it been said kindly, Fritz, my boy. You too\noften speak harshly to your brothers, although you may not mean\nto do so.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A good meal being now ready, my youngsters ate heartily, and\nretiring to rest were speedily fast asleep. Fritz, who was of\nan age to be aware of the real danger we were in, kept watch\nwith us. After a long silence, 'Father,' said he, 'don't you\nthink we might contrive swimming-belts for mother and the boys?\nWith those we might all escape to land, for you and I can swim.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Your idea is so good,' answered I, 'that I shall arrange something\nat once, in case of an accident during the night.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We immediately searched about for what would answer the purpose,\nand fortunately got hold of a number of empty flasks and tin\ncanisters, which we connected two and two together so as to form\nfloats sufficiently buoyant to support a person in the water, and\nmy wife and young sons each willingly put one on. I then provided\nmyself with matches, dry tinder, knives, cord, and other portable\narticles, trusting that, should the vessel go to pieces before\ndaylight, we might gain the shore, not wholly destitute."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, as well as his brothers, now slept soundly. Throughout the\nnight my wife and I maintained our prayerful watch, dreading at\nevery fresh sound some fatal change in the position of the wreck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At length the faint dawn of day appeared, the long weary night was\nover, and with thankful hearts we perceived that the gale had begun\nto moderate; blue sky was seen above us, and the lovely hues of\nsunrise adorned the eastern horizon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I aroused the boys, and we assembled on the remaining portion of\nthe deck, when they, to their surprise, discovered that no one\nelse was on board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hallo, papa! What has become of everybody? Are the sailors gone?\nHave they taken away the boats? Oh, papa! why did they leave us\nbehind? What can we do by ourselves!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My good children,' I replied, 'we must not despair, although we\nseem deserted. See how those on whose skill and good faith we\ndepended have left us cruelly to our fate in the hour of danger.\nGod will never do so. He has not forsaken us, and we will trust\nHim still. Only let us bestir ourselves, and each cheerily do his\nbest. Who has anything to propose?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The sea will soon be calm enough for swimming,' said Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And that would be all very fine for you,' exclaimed Ernest, 'for\nyou can swim, but think of mother and the rest of us! Why not\nbuild a raft and all get on shore together?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We should find it difficult, I think, to make a raft that would\ncarry us safe to shore. However, we must contrive something, and\nfirst let each try to procure what will be of most use to us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Away we all went to see what was to be found, I myself proceeding\nto examine, as of greatest consequence, the supplies of provisions\nand fresh water within our reach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife took her youngest son, Franz, to help her to attend to the\nunfortunate animals on board, who were in a pitiful plight,\nhaving been neglected for several days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz hastened to the arms chest, Ernest to look for tools;\nand Jack went towards the captain's cabin, the door of which\nhe no sooner opened, than out sprang two splendid large dogs,\nwho testified their extreme delight and gratitude by such\ntremendous bounds that they knocked their little deliverer\ncompletely head over heels, frightening him nearly out of his\nwits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack did not long yield either to fear or anger, he presently\nrecovered himself, the dogs seemed to ask pardon by vehemently\nlicking his face and hands, and so, seizing the larger by the\nears, he jumped on his back, and, to my great amusement, coolly\nrode to meet me as I came up the hatchway.  I could not refrain\nfrom laughing at the sight, and I praised his courage, but warned\nhim to be cautious and remember that animals of this species might,\nin a state of hunger, be dangerous."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When we reassembled in the cabin, we all displayed our treasures."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz brought a couple of guns, shot belt, powder-flasks, and\nplenty of bullets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest produced a cap full of nails, a pair of large scissors,\nan axe, and a hammer, while pincers, chisels and augers stuck\nout of all his pockets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Even little Franz* carried a box of no small size, and eagerly\nbegan to show us the 'nice sharp little hooks' it contained.\nHis brothers smiled scornfully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Some editions translate this to Francis,\napparently to avoid confusion with Fritz.\nI see no reason for the change, and am\nretaining the original spelling. Ed."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, done, Franz!' cried I, 'these fish hooks, which you the\nyoungest have found, may contribute more than anything else in\nthe ship to save our lives by procuring food for us. Fritz and\nErnest, you have chosen well.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Will you praise me too?' said my dear wife. 'I have nothing to\nshow, but I can give you good news. Some useful animals are still\nalive: a donkey, two goats, six sheep, a ram, and a cow and a\nfine sow both big with young. I was but just in time to save\ntheir lives by taking food to them. The goats I milked, though\nI do not know how I shall preserve the milk in this dreadful heat.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'All these things are excellent indeed,' said I, 'but my friend\nJack here has presented me with a couple of huge hungry useless\ndogs, who will eat more than any of us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, papa! They will be of use! Why, they will help us to hunt\nwhen we get on shore!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No doubt they will, if ever we do get on shore, Jack; but I\nmust say I don't know how it is to be done.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Can't we each get into a big tub, and float there?' returned he.\n'I have often sailed splendidly like that, round the pond at home.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My child, you have hit on a capital idea,' cried I. 'That is\ncertainly worth trying. Now, Ernest, let me have your tools,\nhammers, nails, saws, augers, and all; and then make haste to\ncollect any tubs you can find!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We very soon found four large casks, made of sound wood and\nstrongly bound with iron hoops; they were floating with many\nother things in the water in the hold, but we managed to fish\nthem out, and place them on the lower deck, which was at that\ntime scarcely above water. They were exactly what I wanted, and\nI succeeded in sawing them across the middle. Hard work it was,\nand we were glad enough to stop and refresh ourselves with goat's\nmilk, wine,* and biscuits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Even as late as this book was written, public\nwater was likely to be polluted. Children as well\nas adults drank alcoholic beverages, often\nconsiderably diluted with water, because it had\nbeen observed that children who did not drink\nplain water were more likely to survive childhood."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My eight tubs now stood ranged in a row near the water's edge,\nand I looked at them with great satisfaction; to my surprise,\nmy wife did not seem to share my pleasure!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I shall never,' said she, 'muster courage to get into one\nof these!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do not be too sure of that, dear wife; when you see my contrivance\ncompleted, you will perhaps prefer it to this immovable wreck.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I next procured a long thin plank on which my tubs could be fixed,\nand the two ends of this I bent upwards so as to form a keel.\nOther two planks were nailed along the sides of the tubs; they,\nalso being flexible, were brought to a point at each end, and\nall firmly secured and nailed together, producing a kind of\nnarrow boat, divided into eight compartments, which I had no\ndoubt would float adequately in calm water. But when we thought\nall was ready for the launch, we found, to our dismay, that the\ngrand contrivance was so heavy and clumsy that even our united\nefforts could not move it an inch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I must have a lever,' cried I. 'Run and fetch the capstan bar!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz quickly brought one and, having formed rollers by cutting\nup a long spar, I raised the forepart of my boat with the bar,\nand my sons placed a roller under it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How is it, father,' inquired Ernest, 'that with that thing you\nalone can do more than all of us together?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I explained, as well as I could in a hurry, the principle of\nArchimedes' lever; from which he said he could move the world\nif he had a point from which his mechanism might operate, and\npromised to have a long talk on the subject of mechanics when\nwe should be safe on land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now made fast a long rope to the stern of our boat, attaching\nthe other end to a beam; then placing a second and third roller\nunder it, we once more began to push, this time with success, and\nsoon our gallant craft was safely launched: so swiftly indeed did\nshe glide into the water that, if the rope had not been well\nsecured, she would have passed beyond our reach. The boys wished\nto jump in directly; but, alas, she leaned so much on one side\nthat they could not venture to do so."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some heavy things being thrown in, however, the boat righted\nitself by degrees, and the boys were so delighted that they\nstruggled which should first leap in to have the fun of sitting\ndown in the tubs. But it was plain to me at once that something\nmore was required to make her perfectly safe, so I contrived\noutriggers to preserve the balance, by nailing long poles across\nat the stem and stern, and fixing at the ends of each empty\nbrandy cask."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then, the boat appearing steady, I got in; and turning it towards\nthe most open side of the wreck, I cut and cleared away\nobstructions, so as to leave a free passage for our departure,\nand the boys brought oars to be ready for the voyage. This\nimportant undertaking we were forced to postpone until the\nnext day, as it was by this time far too late to attempt it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was not pleasant to have to spend another night in so precarious\na situation; but, yielding to necessity, we sat down to enjoy a\ncomfortable supper, for during our exciting and incessant work\nall day we had taken nothing but an occasional biscuit and a\nlittle wine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We prepared for rest in a much happier frame of mind than on the\npreceding day, but I did not forget the possibility of a renewed\nstorm, and therefore made every one put on the belts as before.\nI persuaded my wife (not without considerable difficulty), to\nput on a sailor's dress, assuring her she would find it much\nmore comfortable and convenient for all she would have to go\nthrough."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She at last consented to do this, and left us for a short time,\nreappearing with much embarrassment and many blushes, in a most\nbecoming suit, which she had found in a midshipman's chest.* We\nall admired her costume, and any awkwardness she felt soon\nbegan to pass off; then we retired to our hammocks, where peaceful\nsleep prepared us all for the exertions of the coming day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "At the time this book was written, women always\nwore long skirts. A woman wearing trousers would\nbe considered so shocking that if she were so garbed\non a public street she would probably be arrested\nfor indecency."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We rose up betimes, for sleep weighs lightly on the hopeful as\nwell as on the anxious. After kneeling together in prayer, 'Now\nmy beloved ones,' said I, 'with God's help we are about to effect\nour escape. Let the poor animals we must leave behind, be well\nfed, and put plenty of fodder within their reach: in a few days\nwe may be able to return, and save them likewise. After that,\ncollect everything you can think of which may be of use to us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys joyfully obeyed me; and I selected, from the large\nquantity of stores they got together, canvas to make a tent,\na chest of carpenter's tools, guns, pistols, powder, shot,\nand bullets, rods and fishing tackle, an iron pot, a case of\nportable soup and another of biscuit. These useful articles of\ncourse took the place of the ballast I had hastily thrown in\nthe day before; even so, the boys had brought so many things\nthat we were obliged to leave some of them for a future trip."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With a hearty prayer for God's blessing, we now began to take\nour seats, each in his tub. Just then we heard the cocks begin\nto crow and the chickens to cackle, as though to reproach us\nfor deserting them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why should not the fowls go with us!' exclaimed I. 'If we find\nno food for them, they can be food for us!' Ten hens and a couple\nof cocks were accordingly placed in one of the tubs, and secured\nwith some wire-netting over them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ducks and geese were set at liberty, and took to the water at\nonce, while the pigeons, rejoicing to find themselves on the wing,\nswiftly made for the shore. My wife, who managed all this for me,\nkept us waiting for her some little time, and came at last with a\nbag as big as a pillow in her arms. 'This is my contribution,'\nsaid she, throwing the bag to little Franz, to be, as I thought,\na cushion for him to sit upon, or to protect himself from being\ntossed from side to side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All being ready, we cast off, and moved away from the wreck. My\ngood, brave wife sat in the first compartment of the boat; next\nher was Franz, a sweet-tempered, affectionate little boy, nearly\nsix years old. Then came Fritz, a handsome, spirited young fellow\nof fourteen; the two centre tubs contained the valuable cargo;\nthen came our bold, thoughtless Jack, ten years old; next him\ntwelve-year-old Ernest, my second son, intelligent, well-informed,\nand rather indolent. I myself, the anxious, loving father, stood\nin the stern, endeavouring to guide the raft with its precious\nburden to a safe landing-place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The elder boys took the oars; everyone wore a float belt, and\nhad something useful close to him in case of being thrown into\nthe water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The tide was flowing, which was a great help to the young oarsmen.\nWe emerged from the wreck and glided into the open sea. All eyes\nwere strained to get a full view of the land, and the boys pulled\nwith a will; but for some time we made no progress, as the boat\nkept turning round and round, until I hit upon the right way to\nsteer it, after which we merrily made for the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had left the two dogs, Turk and Juno, on the wreck, as being\nboth large mastiffs we did not care to have their additional\nweight on board our craft; but when they saw us apparently\ndeserting them, they set up a piteous howl, and sprang into\nthe sea. I was sorry to see this, for the distance to the land\nwas so great that I scarcely expected them to be able to\naccomplish it. They followed us, however, and, occasionally\nresting their fore-paws on the outriggers, kept up with us well.\nJack was inclined to deny them this their only chance of safety."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop,' said I, 'that would be unkind as well as foolish; remember,\nthe merciful man regardeth the life of his beast. God has given\nthe dog to man to be his faithful companion and friend.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our passage, though tedious, was safe; but the nearer we approached\nthe shore the less inviting it appeared; the barren rocks seemed\nto threaten us with misery and want."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many casks, boxes and bales of goods floated on the water around\nus. Fritz and I managed to secure a couple of hogsheads, so as\nto tow them alongside. With the prospect of famine before us, it\nwas desirable to lay hold of anything likely to contain provisions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By-and-by we began to perceive that, between and beyond the\ncliffs, green grass and trees were discernible. Fritz could\ndistinguish many tall palms, and Ernest hoped they would prove\nto be cocoanut trees, and enjoyed the thoughts of drinking the\nrefreshing milk."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am very sorry I never thought of bringing away the captain's\ntelescope,' said I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, look here, father!' cried Jack, drawing a little spy-glass\njoyfully out of his pocket."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By means of this glass, I made out that at some distance to the\nleft the coast was much more inviting; a strong current however\ncarried us directly towards the frowning rocks, but I presently\nobserved an opening, where a stream flowed into the sea, and saw\nthat our geese and ducks were swimming towards this place. I\nsteered after them into the creek, and we found ourselves in a\nsmall bay or inlet where the water was perfectly smooth and of\nmoderate depth. The ground sloped gently upwards from the low\nbanks to the cliffs which here retired inland, leaving a small\nplain, on which it was easy for us to land. Everyone sprang\ngladly out of the boat but little Franz, who, lying packed in\nhis tub like a potted shrimp, had to be lifted out by his mother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs had scrambled on shore before us; they received us with\nloud barking and the wildest demonstrations of delight. The\nchickens, geese and ducks kept up an incessant din, added to\nwhich was the screaming and croaking of flamingoes and penguins,\nwhose dominion we were invading. The noise was deafening, but far\nfrom unwelcome to me, as I thought of the good dinners the birds\nmight furnish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as we could gather our children around us on dry land,\nwe knelt to offer thanks and praise for our merciful escape, and\nwith full hearts we commended ourselves to God's good keeping\nfor the time to come. All hands then briskly fell to the work\nof unloading, and, oh, how rich we felt ourselves as we did so!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The poultry we left at liberty to forage for themselves, and\nset about finding a suitable place to erect a tent in which to\npass the night. This we speedily did; thrusting a long spar\ninto a hole in the rock, and supporting the other end by a pole\nfirmly planted in the ground, we formed a framework over which\nwe stretched the sailcloth we had brought; besides fastening\nthis down with pegs, we placed our heavy chests and boxes on\nthe border of the canvas, and arranged hooks so as to be able\nto close up the entrance during the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When this was accomplished, the boys ran to collect moss and\ngrass, to spread in the tent for our beds, while I arranged a\nfireplace, surrounded by large flat stones, near the brook which\nflowed close by. Dry twigs and seaweed were soon in a blaze on\nthe hearth, I filled the iron pot with water, and after I gave\nmy wife several cakes of the portable soup, she established\nherself as our cook, with little Franz to help her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He, thinking his mother was melting some glue for carpentry,\nwas eager to know 'what papa was going to make next?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is to be soup for your dinner, my child. Do you think\nthese cakes look like glue?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes, indeed I do!' replied Franz, 'And I should not much like\nto taste glue soup! Don't you want some beef or mutton, Mamma?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Where can I get it, dear?' said she, 'we are a long way from a\nbutcher's shop! But these cakes are made of the juice of good\nmeat, boiled till it becomes a strong stiff jellyâ€”people take\nthem when they go to sea, because on a long voyage they can only\nhave salt meat, which will not make nice soup.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, leaving a loaded gun with me, took another himself,* and\nwent along the rough coast to see what lay beyond the stream; this\nfatiguing sort of walk not suiting Ernest's fancy, he sauntered\ndown to the beach, and Jack scrambled among the rocks searching\nfor shellfish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Even today all adult male Swiss are required by law\nto possess, and know how and when to use, firearms.\nA father who did not teach his sons these things, as\nwell as firearms safety, would be very neglectful."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was anxious to land the two casks which were floating alongside\nour boat, but on attempting to do so, I found that I could not\nget them up the bank on which we had landed, and was therefore\nobliged to look for a more convenient spot. As I did so, I was\nstartled by hearing Jack shouting for help, as though in great\ndanger. He was at some distance, and I hurried towards him with\na hatchet in my hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The little fellow stood screaming in a deep pool, and as I\napproached, I saw that a huge lobster had caught his leg in its\npowerful claw. Poor Jack was in a terrible fright; kick as he\nwould, his enemy still clung on. I waded into the water, and\nseizing the lobster firmly by the back, managed to make it\nloosen its hold, and we brought it safe to land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack, having speedily recovered his spirits, and anxious to take\nsuch a prize to his mother, caught the lobster in both hands, but\ninstantly received such a severe blow from its tail, that he flung\nit down, and passionately hit the creature with a large stone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This display of temper vexed me. 'You are acting in a very childish\nway, my son,' said I. 'Never strike an enemy in a revengeful\nspirit, or when the enemy is unable to defend itself. The lobster,\nit is true, gave you a bite, but then you, on your part, intend\nto eat the lobster. So the game is at least equal. Next time,\nbe both more prudent and more merciful.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Once more lifting the lobster, Jack ran triumphantly towards\nthe tent. 'Mother, mother! A lobster! A lobster, Ernest! Look\nhere, Franz! Mind, he'll bite you! Where's Fritz?' All came\ncrowding round Jack and his prize, wondering at its unusual\nsize, and Ernest wanted his mother to make lobster soup directly,\nby adding it to what she was now boiling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She, however, begged to decline making any such experiment, and\nsaid she preferred cooking one dish at a time. Having remarked\nthat the scene of Jack's adventure afforded a convenient place\nfor getting my casks on shore, I returned thither and succeeded\nin drawing them up on the beach, where I set them on end, and\nfor the present left them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On my return I resumed the subject of Jack's lobster, and told\nhim he should have the offending claw all to himself when it was\nready to be eaten, congratulating him on being the first to\ndiscover anything useful."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As to that,' said Ernest, 'I found something very good to eat,\nas well as Jack, only I could not get at them without wetting\nmy feet.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Pooh!' cried Jack, 'I know what he sawâ€”nothing but some nasty\nmusselsâ€”I saw them too. Who wants to eat trash like that!\nLobster for me!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I believe them to be oysters, not mussels,' returned Ernest\ncalmly. \"They were stuck to the rocks, so I am sure they are\noysters.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Be good enough, my philosophical young friend, to fetch a few\nspecimens of these oysters in time for our next meal,' said I.\n'We must all exert ourselves, Ernest, for the common good, and\npray never let me hear you object to wetting your feet. See how\nquickly the sun has dried Jack and me.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I can bring some salt at the same time,' said Ernest, 'I remarked\na good deal lying in the crevices of the rocks; it tasted very\npure and good, and I concluded it was produced by the evaporation\nof sea water in the sun.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Extremely probable, learned sir,' cried I, 'but if you had brought\na bag full of this good salt instead of merely speculating so\nprofoundly on the subject, it would have been more to the purpose.\nRun and fetch some directly.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It proved to be salt sure enough, although so impure that it\nseemed useless, till my wife dissolved and strained it, when\nit became fit to put in the soup."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why not use the sea-water itself?' asked Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Because,' said Ernest, 'it is not only salt, but bitter too.\nJust try it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now,' said my wife, tasting the soup with the stick with which\nshe had been stirring it, 'dinner is ready, but where can Fritz\nbe?' she continued, a little anxiously. 'And how are we to eat\nour soup when he does come?' she continued. 'We have neither\nplates nor spoons. Why did we not remember to bring some from\nthe ship?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Because, my dear, one cannot think of everything at once. We\nshall be fortunate if we do not find even more things we have\nforgotten.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"But we can scarcely lift the boiling pot to our mouths,\" she said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was forced to agree. We all looked upon the pot with perplexity,\nrather like the fox in the fable, to whom the stork served up a\ndinner in a jug with a long neck. Silence was at length broken,\nwhen all of us burst into hearty laughter at our own folly in\nnot remembering that spoons and forks were things of absolute\nnecessity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, for a few cocoanut shells!' sighed Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, for half a dozen plates and as many silver spoons!' rejoined\nI, smiling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Really though, oyster-shells would do,' said he, after a\nmoment's thought."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'True, that is an idea worth having! Off with you, my boys, get\nthe oysters and clean out a few shells. And none of you must\ncomplain because the spoons have no handles, and we grease our\nfingers a little in baling the soup out.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack was away and up to his knees in the water in a moment\ndetaching the oysters. Ernest followed more leisurely, and still\nunwilling to wet his feet, stood by the margin of the pool and\ngathered in his handkerchief the oysters his brother threw him;\nas he thus stood he picked up and pocketed a large mussel shell\nfor his own use. As they returned with a good supply we heard a\nshout from Fritz in the distance; we returned it joyfully, and\nhe presently appeared before us, his hands behind his back, and\na look of disappointment upon his countenance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Unsuccessful!' said he."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Really!' I replied. 'Never mind, my boy, better luck next time.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, Fritz!' exclaimed his brothers who had looked behind him.\n'A sucking-pig, a little sucking-pig. Where did you get it? How\ndid you shoot it? Do let us see it!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz then with sparkling eyes exhibited his prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am glad to see the result of your prowess, my boy,' said I;\n'but I cannot approve of deceit, even as a joke; stick to the\ntruth in jest and earnest.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz then told us how he had been to the other side of the stream.\n'So different from this,' he said, 'it is really a beautiful\ncountry, and the shore, which runs down to the sea in a gentle\nslope, is covered with all sorts of useful things from the wreck.\nDo let us go and collect them. And, father, why should we not\nreturn to the wreck and bring off some of the animals? Just think\nof what value the cow would be to us, and what a pity it would be\nto lose her. Let us get her on shore, and we will move over the\nstream, where she will have good pasturage, and we shall be in\nthe shade instead of on this desert, and, father, I do wishâ€”'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop, stop, my boy!' cried I. 'All will be done in good time.\nTomorrow and the day after will bring work of their own. And tell\nme, did you see no traces of our shipmates?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not a sign of them, either on land or sea, living or dead,' he\nreplied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But the sucking-pig,' said Jack, 'where did you get it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was one of several,' said Fritz, 'which I found on the shore;\nalong with some very curious little animals that hopped rather\nthan walked, and every now and then would squat down on their hind\nlegs and rub their snouts with their forepaws. Had not I been\nafraid of losing all, I would have tried to catch one alive,\nthey seemed so tame. But this was more easily taken.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile, Ernest had been carefully examining the animal\nin question."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is no pig,' he said, 'and except for its bristly skin,\ndoes not look like one. See, its teeth are not like those of a\npig, but rather those of a squirrel. In fact,' he continued,\nlooking at Fritz, 'your sucking-pig is an agouti.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Dear me,' said Fritz, 'listen to the great professor lecturing!\nHe is going to prove that a pig is not a pig!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You need not be so quick to laugh at your brother,' said I, in\nmy turn, 'he is quite right. I, too, know the agouti by descriptions\nand pictures, and there is little doubt that this is a specimen.\nThe little animal makes its nest under the roots of trees, and\nlives upon fruit. Its meat is white but dry, having no fat, and never\nentirely loses a certain wild flavour, which is disagreeable\nto Europeans. It is held in great esteem by the natives where\nit lives, especially when the animal has been feeding near the\nsea on plants impregnated with salt. But, Ernest, the agouti\nnot only looks something like a pig, but most decidedly grunts\nlike a porker.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we were thus talking, Jack had been vainly endeavouring to\nopen an oyster with his large knife. 'Here is a simpler way,' said\nI, placing an oyster on the fire; it immediately opened."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now,' I continued, 'who will try this delicacy?' All at first\nhesitated to partake of them, so unattractive did they appear.\nJack, however, tightly closing his eyes and making a face as\nthough about to take medicine, gulped one down. We followed his\nexample, one after the other, each doing so rather to provide\nhimself with a spoon than with any hope of cultivating a taste\nfor oysters."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our spoons were now ready, and gathering round the pot we dipped\nthem in, not, however, without sundry scalded fingers. Ernest\nthen drew from his pocket the large shell he had procured for\nhis own use, and scooping up a good quantity of soup he put it\ndown to cool, smiling at his own foresight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Prudence should be exercised for others, not just for oneself,'\nI remarked. 'Are you so much better than your brothers? Your cool\nsoup will do capitally for the dogs, my boy; take it to them, and\nthen come and eat like the rest of us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest winced at this, but silently taking up his shell he placed\nit on the ground before the hungry dogs, who lapped up its contents\nin a moment; he then returned, and after waiting for the soup to\ncool some more, we all went merrily on with our dinner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we were thus busily employed, we suddenly discovered that\nour dogs, not satisfied with their mouthful of soup, had espied\nthe agouti, and were rapidly devouring it. The boys all began to\nyell, and Fritz first threw a stone at the dogs and then, seizing\nhis gun, flew to rescue it from their hungry jaws. Before I could\nprevent him, he struck one of them with such force that his gun\nwas bent. The poor beasts ran off howling, followed by a shower of\nstones from Fritz, who shouted and yelled at them so fiercely,\nthat if I had not interfered, it was probable he would have\nkilled them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I followed him, and as soon as he would listen to me, represented\nto him how despicable as well as wicked was such an outbreak of\ntemper. 'For,' said I, 'you have hurt, if not actually wounded,\nthe dogs; you have distressed and frightened your mother, and\nyou have spoiled your gun, which would have been so useful.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Though Fritz's passion was easily aroused it never lasted long,\nand speedily recovering himself, immediately he entreated his\nmother's pardon, and expressed his sorrow for his fault."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time the sun was sinking beneath the horizon, and the\npoultry, which had been straying to some little distance, gathered\nround us, and began to pick up the crumbs of biscuit which had\nfallen during our repast. My wife hereupon drew from her mysterious\nbag some handfuls of oats, peas, and other grain, and with them\nbegan to feed the poultry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She at the same time showed me several other seeds of various\nvegetables. 'That was indeed thoughtful,' said I, 'but pray be\ncareful of what will be of such value to us; we can bring plenty\nof damaged biscuits from the wreck, which though of no use as\nfood for us, will suit the fowls very well indeed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The pigeons now flew up to crevices in the rocks, the fowls\nperched themselves on our tent pole, and the ducks and geese\nwaddled off cackling and quacking to the marshy margin of the\nriver. We too were ready for repose, and having loaded our guns,\nand offered up our prayers to God, thanking him for his many\nmercies to us, we commended ourselves to his protecting care,\nand as the last ray of light departed, closed our tent and lay\ndown to rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The children remarked the suddenness of nightfall, for indeed\nthere had been little or no twilight. This convinced me that we\nmust be not far from the equator, for twilight results from the\nrefraction of the sun's rays; the more obliquely these rays fall,\nthe further does the partial light extend, while the more\nperpendicularly they strike the earth the longer do they continue\ntheir undiminished force, until when the sun sinks, they totally\ndisappear, thus producing sudden darkness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 2"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We should have been badly off without the shelter of our tent,\nfor the night proved as cold as the day had been hot, but we\nmanaged to sleep comfortably, every one being thoroughly fatigued\nby the labours of the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The voice of our vigilant cock, which as he loudly saluted the\nrising moon, was the last sound I heard at night, roused me at\ndaybreak, and I then awoke my wife, that in the quiet interval\nwhile yet our children slept, we might take counsel together on\nour situation and prospects. It was plain to both of us that in\nthe first place, we should ascertain if possible the fate of our\nlate companions, and then examine into the nature and resources\nof the country on which we were stranded."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We therefore came to the resolution that, as soon as we had\nbreakfasted, Fritz and I should start on an expedition with\nthese objects in view, while my wife remained near our landing-\nplace with the three younger boys."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Rouse up, rouse up, my boys,' cried I, awakening the children\ncheerfully. 'Come and help your mother to get breakfast ready.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As to that,' said she, smiling, 'we can but set on the pot, and\nboil some more soup!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why! You forget Jack's fine lobster!' replied I. 'What has become\nof it, Jack?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It has been safe in this hole in the rock all night, father. You\nsee, I thought as the dogs seem to like good things, they might\ntake a fancy to that as well as to the agouti.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A very sensible precaution,' remarked I. 'I believe even my\nheedless Jack will learn wisdom in time. It is well the lobster\nis so large, for we shall want to take part with us on our excursion\nto-day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the mention of an excursion, the four children were wild with\ndelight, and, capering around me, clapped their hands for joy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Steady there, steady!' said I, 'you cannot expect all to go.\nSuch an expedition as this would be too dangerous and fatiguing\nfor you younger ones, and this place seems perfectly safe. Fritz\nand I will go alone this time, with one of the dogs, leaving the\nother to defend you. Fritz, prepare the guns, and tie up Flora\nso that she will not follow us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the word 'guns' the poor boy blushed shamefully. He tried in\nvain to straighten his weapon. I left him alone for a short time,\nbut at length I gave him leave to take another, perceiving with\npleasure that the vexation had produced a proper feeling in his mind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A moment later he tried to lay hold of Flora to tie her up, but\nthe dog, recollecting the blows she had so lately received, began\nto snarl and would not go near him. Turk behaved the same, and I\nfound it necessary to call with my own voice to induce them to\napproach us. Fritz then, in tears, entreated some biscuit of his\nmother, declaring that he would rather go without the rest of his\nbreakfast to make his peace with the dogs. He accordingly carried\nthem some biscuit, stroked and caressed them, and in every motion\nseemed to ask their pardon. As of all animals, without excepting\nman, the dog is least addicted to revenge, and at the same time\nis the most sensible of kind usage, Flora instantly relented and\nbegan to lick the hands which fed her; but Turk, who was of a\nmore fierce and independent temper, still held off, and seemed\nto lack confidence in Fritz's advances."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Give him a claw of my lobster,' cried Jack, 'for I meant to\ngive it to you anyway, for your journey.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With that treat, Turk seemed ready to forgive Fritz. We then armed\nourselves, each taking a gun and a game-bag; Fritz, in addition,\nsticking a pair of pistols in his belt, and I a small hatchet in\nmine; breakfast being over, we stowed away the remainder of the\nlobster and some biscuits, with a flask of water, and were ready\nfor a start."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop!' I exclaimed, 'we have still left something very\nimportant undone.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Surely not,' said Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes,' said I, 'we have not yet joined in morning prayer. We are\nonly too ready, amid the cares and pleasures of this life, to\nforget the God to whom we owe all things.' Then having commended\nourselves to his protecting care, I took leave of my wife and\nchildren, and bidding them not wander far from the boat and tent,\nwe parted not without some anxiety on either side, for we knew\nnot what might assail us in this unknown region."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We now found that the banks of the stream were on both sides so\nrocky that we could get down to the water by only one narrow\npassage, and there was no corresponding path on the other side.\nI was glad to see this, however, for I now knew that my wife\nand children were on a comparatively inaccessible spot, the other\nside of the tent being protected by steep and precipitous cliffs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and I pursued our way up the stream until we reached a point\nwhere the waters fell from a considerable height in a cascade, and\nwhere several large rocks lay half covered by the water; by means\nof these we succeeded in crossing the stream in safety. We thus\nhad the sea on our left, and a long line of rocky heights, here\nand there adorned with clumps of trees, stretching away inland\nto the right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had forced our way scarcely fifty yards through the long rank\ngrass, which was here partly withered by the sun and much tangled,\nwhen we were much alarmed on hearing behind us a rustling, and on\nlooking round, we saw the grass waving to and fro, as if some\nanimal were passing through it. Fritz instantly turned and brought\nhis gun to his shoulder, ready to fire the moment the beast\nshould appear."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was much pleased with my son's coolness and presence of mind,\nfor it showed me that I might thoroughly rely upon him on any\nfuture occasion when real danger might occur. This time, however,\nno savage beast rushed out, but our trusty dog Turk, whom, in\nour anxiety at parting, we had forgotten, and who had been sent\nafter us doubtless by my thoughtful wife. I did not fail to\ncommend both the bravery and the discretion of my son, in not\nyielding to even a rational alarm, and for waiting until he was\nsure of the object before he resolved to fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From this little incident, however, we saw how dangerous was our\nposition, and how difficult escape would be should any fierce\nbeast steal upon us unawares: we therefore hastened to make our\nway to the open seashore. Here the scene which presented itself\nwas indeed delightful. A background of hills, the green waving\ngrass, the pleasant groups of trees stretching here and there\nto the very water's edge, formed a lovely prospect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the smooth sand we searched carefully for any trace of our\nhapless companions, but not the mark of a footstep could we find.\n'Shall I fire a shot or two?' said Fritz. 'That would bring our\ncompanions, if they are within hearing.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It would indeed,' I replied, 'or any savages that may be here.\nNo, no; let us search diligently, but as quietly as possible.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But why, father, should we trouble ourselves about them at all?\nThey left us to shift for ourselves, and I for one don't care to\nset eyes on them again.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are wrong, my boy,' said I. 'In the first place, we should\nnot return evil for evil; then, again, they might be of great\nassistance to us in building a house of some sort; and lastly,\nyou must remember that they took nothing with them from the\nvessel, and may be perishing of hunger.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But father, while we are wandering here and losing our time\nalmost without a hope of benefit to them, why should we not\ninstead return to the vessel and save the animals on board?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'When a variety of duties present themselves for our choice,\nwe should always give the preference to that which can confer\nthe most solid advantage,' I replied. 'The saving of the life\nof a man is a more exalted action than contributing to the\ncomfort of a few quadrupeds, whom we have already supplied with\nfood for a few days. Also, the sea is so calm at present that we\nneed not fear that the ship will sink or break up entirely before\nwe can return.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Thus talking, we pushed on until we came to a pleasant grove\nwhich stretched down to the water's edge; here we halted to\nrest, seating ourselves under a large tree, by a rivulet which\nmurmured and splashed along its pebbly bed into the great\nocean before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A thousand gaily plumaged birds flew twittering above us, and\nFritz and I gazed up at them. My son suddenly started up. 'A\nmonkey,' he exclaimed, 'I am nearly sure I saw a monkey.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As he spoke he sprang round to the other side of the tree, and\nin doing so stumbled over a small round object which he handed\nto me, remarking, as he did so, that it was a round bird's nest,\nof which he had often heard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You may have done so,' said I, laughing, 'but you need not\nnecessarily conclude that every round hairy thing is a bird's\nnest; this, for instance, is not one, but a cocoanut. Do you not\nremember reading that a cocoanut is enclosed within a round,\nfibrous covering over a hard shell, which again is surrounded\nby a bulky green hull? In the one you hold in your hand, the\nouter hull has been destroyed by time, which is the reason that\nthe twisted fibers of the inner covering are so apparent. Let\nus now break the shell, and you will see the nut inside.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not without difficulty, we split open the nut, but, to our\ndisgust, found the kernel dry and uneatable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hullo,' cried Fritz, 'I always thought a cocoanut was full\nof delicious sweet liquid, like almond milk.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'So it is,' I replied, 'when young and fresh, but as it ripens\nthe milk becomes congealed, and in course of time is solidified\ninto a kernel. This kernel then dries as you see here, but when\nthe nut falls on favourable soil, the germ within the kernel\nswells until it bursts through the shell, and, taking root, springs\nup a new tree.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I do not understand,' said Fritz, 'how the little germ manages\nto get through this great thick shell, which is not like an almond\nor hazel-nut shell, that is divided down the middle already.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Nature provides for all things,' I answered, taking up the\npieces. 'Look here, do you see these three round holes near the\nstalk; it is through them that the germ obtains egress. Now let\nus find a good nut if we can.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As cocoanuts must be over-ripe before they fall naturally from\nthe tree, it was not without difficulty that we obtained one in\nwhich the kernel was not dried up. It was a little oily and\nrancid, but this was not the time to be too particular. We were\nso refreshed by the fruit that we could defer the repast we\ncalled our dinner* until later in the day, and so spare our stock\nof provisions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "In this book, 'dinner' refers to the midday meal."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Continuing our way through a thicket, which was so densely\novergrown with lianas that we had to clear a passage with our\nhatchets, we again emerged on the seashore beyond, and found an\nopen view, the forest sweeping inland, while on the space before\nus stood at intervals single trees of remarkable appearance.\nThese at once attracted Fritz's observant eye, and he pointed\nto them, exclaiming: 'Oh, what absurd-looking trees, father!\nSee what strange bumps there are on the trunks.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We approached to examine them, and I recognized them as calabash\ntrees, the fruit of which grows in this curious way on the stems,\nand is a species of gourd, from the hard rind of which bowls,\nspoons, and bottles can be made. 'The savages,' I remarked, 'are\nsaid to form these things most ingeniously, using them to contain\nliquids: indeed, they actually cook food in them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, but that is impossible,' returned Fritz. 'I am quite sure\nthis rind would be burnt through directly if it was set on the fire.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I did not say it was set on the fire at all. When the gourd has\nbeen divided in two, and the shell or rind emptied of its contents,\nit is filled with water, into which the fish, or whatever is to\nbe cooked, is put; red-hot stones are added until the water boils;\nthe food becomes fit to eat, and the gourd-rind remains uninjured.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is a very clever plan: very simple too. I daresay I should\nhave hit on it, if I had tried,' said Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The friends of Columbus thought it very easy to make an egg\nstand upon its end when he had shown them how to do it. But now\nsuppose we prepare some of these calabashes, that they may be\nready for use when we take them home.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz instantly took up one of the gourds, and tried to split it\nequally with his knife, but in vain: the blade slipped, and the\ncalabash was cut jaggedly. 'What a nuisance!' said Fritz, flinging\nit down, 'The thing is spoiled; and yet it seemed so simple to\ndivide it properly.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stay,' said I, 'you are too impatient, those pieces are not\nuseless. Do you try to fashion from them a spoon or two while\nI provide a dish.' I then took from my pocket a piece of string,\nwhich I tied tightly round a gourd, as near one end of it as I\ncould; then tapping the string with the back of my knife, it\npenetrated the outer shell. When this was accomplished, I tied\nthe string yet tighter; and drawing the ends with all my might,\nthe gourd fell, divided exactly as I wished."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is clever!' cried Fritz. 'What in the world put that plan\ninto your head?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is a plan,' I replied, 'which savages adopt, as I have learned\nfrom reading books of travel.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, it certainly makes a capital soup-tureen, and a soup-plate\ntoo,' said Fritz, examining the gourd. 'But supposing you had\nwanted to make a bottle, how would you have set to work?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It would be an easier operation than this, if possible. All that\nis necessary, is to cut a round hole at one end, then to scoop\nout the interior, and to drop in several shot or stones; when\nthese are shaken, any remaining portions of the fruit are detached,\nand the gourd is thoroughly cleaned, and the bottle completed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That would not make a very convenient bottle though, father; it\nwould be more like a barrel.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'True, my boy; if you want a more shapely vessel, you must take\nit in hand when it is younger. To give it a neck, for instance,\nyou must tie a bandage round the young gourd while it is still\non the tree, and then all will swell but that part which you have\nchecked.' As I spoke, I filled the gourds with sand, and left\nthem to dry; marking the spot that we might return for them on\nour way back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Are the bottle-shaped gourds I have seen in Europe trained\nsimilarly?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, they are of another species, and what you have seen is\ntheir natural shape.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For three hours or more we pushed forward, keeping a sharp\nlook-out on either side for any trace of our companions, till we\nreached a bold promontory, stretching some way into the sea, from\nwhose rocky summit I knew that we should obtain a good and\ncomprehensive view of the surrounding country. With little\ndifficulty we reached the top, but the most careful survey of\nthe beautiful landscape failed to show us the slightest sign or\ntrace of human beings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before us stretched a wide and lovely bay, fringed with yellow\nsands, either side extending into the distance, and almost lost\nto view in two shadowy promontories; enclosed by these two arms\nlay a sheet of rippling water, which reflected in its depths the\nglorious sun above. The scene inland was no less beautiful; and\nyet Fritz and I both felt a shade of loneliness stealing over us\nas we gazed on its utter solitude."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Cheer up, Fritz, my boy,' said I, presently. 'Remember that we\nchose a settler's life long ago, before we left our own dear\ncountry; we certainly did not expect to be so entirely aloneâ€”but\nwhat matters a few people, more or less? With God's help, let us\nendeavour to live here contentedly, thankful that we were not cast\nupon some bare and inhospitable island. But come, the heat here\nis getting unbearable; let us find some shady place before we are\ncompletely broiled away.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We descended the hill and made for a clump of palm trees, which we\nsaw at a little distance. To reach this, we had to pass through a\ndense thicket of reeds, no pleasant or easy task; for, besides the\ndifficulty of forcing our way through, I feared at every step that\nwe might tread on some venomous snake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sending Turk in advance, I cut one of the reeds, thinking it would\nbe a more useful weapon against a reptile than my gun. I had\ncarried it but a little way, when I noticed a thick juice exuding\nfrom one end. I tasted it, and to my delight, found it sweet and\npleasant. I at once knew that I was standing amongst sugar-canes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Wishing Fritz to make the same discovery, I advised him to cut a\ncane for his defense; he did so, and as he beat the ground before\nhim, the reed split, and his hand was covered with the juice. He\ncarefully touched the cane with the tip of his tongue, then,\nfinding the juice sweet, he did so again with less hesitation;\nand a moment afterwards sprang back to me, exclaiming, 'Oh, father,\nsugar-cane, sugar-cane! Taste it. Oh, how delicious, how\ndelightful! Do let us take a lot home to mother,' he continued,\nsucking eagerly at the cane!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Gently there,' said I, 'take breath a moment, moderation in\nall things, remember. Cut some to take home if you like; only\ndon't take more than you can conveniently carry.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In spite of my warning, my son cut a dozen or more of the largest\ncanes, and stripping them of their leaves, carried them under his\narm. We then pushed through the cane-brake, and reached the clump\nof palms for which we had been making; as we entered it a troop of\nmonkeys, who had been disporting themselves on the ground, sprang\nup, chattering and grimacing, and before we could clearly\ndistinguish them, were at the very top of the trees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was so provoked by their impertinent gestures that he raised\nhis gun, and would have shot one of the poor beasts. 'Stay,' cried\nI, 'never take the life of any animal needlessly. A live monkey\nup in that tree is of more use to us than a dozen dead ones at\nour feet, as I will show you.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Saying this, I gathered a handful of small stones, and threw them\nup towards the apes. The stones did not go near them, but influenced\nby their instinctive mania for imitation, they instantly seized\nall the cocoanuts within their reach, and sent a perfect hail of\nthem down upon us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was delighted with my stratagem, and rushing forward picked\nup some of the finest of the nuts. We drank the milk they contained,\ndrawing it through the holes which I pierced. The milk of a\ncocoanut has not a pleasant flavor, but it is excellent for quenching\nthirst. What we liked best was a kind of solid cream which adheres\nto their shells, and which we scraped off with our spoons."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After this delicious meal, we thoroughly despised the lobster we\nhad been carrying, and threw it to Turk, who ate it gratefully;\nbut far from being satisfied, the poor beast began to gnaw the\nends of the sugar-canes, and to beg for cocoanut. I slung a couple\nof the nuts over my shoulder, fastening them together by their\nstalks, and Fritz having resumed his burden, we began our homeward\nmarch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I soon discovered that Fritz found the weight of his canes\nconsiderably more than he expected: he shifted them from shoulder\nto shoulder, then for a while carried them under his arm, and\nfinally stopped short with a sigh. 'I had no idea,' he said,\n'that a few reeds would be so heavy. How sincerely I pity the\npoor negroes who are made to carry heavy loads of them! Yet how\nglad I shall be when my mother and brothers are tasting them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Never mind, my boy,' I said, 'Patience and courage! Do you not\nremember the story of Aesop and his breadbasket, how heavy he\nfound it when he started, and how light at the end of his journey?\nLet us each take a fresh staff, and then fasten the bundle\ncrosswise with your gun.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We did so, and once more stepped forward. Fritz presently noticed\nthat I from time to time sucked the end of my cane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, come,' said he, 'that's a capital plan of yours, father,\nI'll do that too.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, he began to suck most vigorously, but not a drop of\nthe juice could he extract. 'How is this?' he asked. 'How do you\nget the juice out, father?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Think a little,' I replied, 'you are quite as capable as I am of\nfinding out the way, even if you do not know the real reason of\nyour failure.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, of course,' said he, 'it is like trying to suck marrow from\na marrow bone, without making a hole at the other end.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Quite right,' I said, 'you form a vacuum in your mouth and the\nend of your tube, and expect the air to force down the liquid\nfrom the other end which it cannot possibly enter.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was speedily perfect in the accomplishment of sucking\nsugar-cane, discovering by experience the necessity for a fresh\ncut at each joint or knot in the cane, through which the juice\ncould not flow; he talked of the pleasure of initiating his\nbrothers in the art, and of how Ernest would enjoy the cocoanut\nmilk, with which he had filled his flask.*"
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "M. Wyss's acquaintance with sugar has not extended\nto the sugar cane. The sap does not flow; it is\nembedded in the very fibrous pulp, and the cane\nmust be crushed, and its juice cooked and repeatedly\nrefined, to make the sugar. People enjoying the\ncane in its natural state must chew the pulp,\nwhich is not particularly sweet."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear boy,' said I, 'you need not have added that to your load;\nthe chances are it will be vinegar by the time we get home. In\nthe heat of the sun, it will ferment soon after being drawn\nfrom the nut.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Vinegar! Oh, that would be a horrid bore! I must look directly,\nand see how it is getting on,' cried Fritz, hastily swinging\nthe flask from his shoulder, and tugging out the cork. With a\nloud 'pop' the contents came forth, foaming like champagne."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There now!' said I, laughing as he tasted this new luxury.\n'You will have to exercise moderation again, friend Fritz!\nI daresay it is delicious, but it will go to your head, if\nyou venture deep into your flask.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear father, you cannot think how good it is! Do take some.\nVinegar, indeed! This is like excellent wine.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were both invigorated by this unexpected draught, and went on\nso merrily after it, that the distance to the place where we had\nleft our gourd dishes seemed less than we expected. We found\nthem quite dry, and very light and easy to carry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Just as we had passed through the grove in which we breakfasted,\nTurk suddenly darted away from us, and sprang furiously among a\ntroop of monkeys, which were gambolling playfully on the turf at\na little distance from the trees. They were taken by surprise\ncompletely, and the dog, now really ravenous from hunger, had\nseized one, and was fiercely tearing it to pieces before we could\napproach the spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His luckless victim was the mother of a tiny little monkey,\nwhich, being on her back when the dog flew at her, had hindered\nher flight; the little creature attempted to hide among the\ngrass, and in trembling fear watched the tragic fate of its\nmother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On perceiving Turk's bloodthirsty design, Fritz had eagerly rushed\nto the rescue, flinging away all he was carrying, and losing his\nhat in his haste. All to no purpose as far as the poor mother ape\nwas concerned, and a laughable scene ensued, for no sooner did the\nyoung monkey catch sight of him than at one bound it was on his\nshoulders, and, holding fast by his thick curly hair, it firmly\nkept its seat in spite of all he could do to dislodge it. He\nscreamed and plunged about as he endeavoured to shake or pull\nthe creature off, but all in vain, it only clung the closer to\nhis neck, making the most absurd grimaces."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I laughed so much at this ridiculous scene, that I could scarcely\nassist my terrified boy out of his awkward predicament. Indeed, I\ntold Fritz that the animal, having lost its mother, seemed\ndetermined to adopt Fritz. \"Perhaps he has discovered in you\nsomething of the air of a father of a family.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Or rather,\" Fritz retorted, \"the little rogue has found out that\nhe has to do with a chicken-heart, who shrinks from the idea of\nill-treating an animal which has thrown itself on his protection.\nBut father, he is yanking my hair terribly, and I shall be\nobliged to you to try once more to get him off.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At last, by coaxing the monkey, offering it a bit of biscuit,\nand gradually disentangling its small sinewy paws from the curls\nit grasped so tightly, I managed to relieve poor Fritz, who then\nlooked with interest at the baby ape, no bigger than a kitten,\nas it lay in my arms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What a jolly little fellow it is!' exclaimed he. 'Do let me try\nto rear it, father. I daresay cocoanut milk would do until we can\nbring the cow and the goats from the wreck. If he lives he might\nbe useful to us. I believe monkeys instinctively know what fruits\nare wholesome and what are poisonous.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well,' said I, 'let the little orphan be yours. You bravely and\nkindly exerted yourself to save the mother's life, now you must\ntrain her child carefully, for unless you do so its natural\ninstinct will prove mischievous instead of useful to us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Turk was meanwhile devouring with great satisfaction the little\nanimal's unfortunate mother. Fritz wished to drive him away from\nthe feast, but I could not grudge it him, and reminded Fritz that\ncontinued hunger might have made Turk dangerous to ourselves. We\ndid not think it necessary to wait until he had dined, so we\nprepared to resume our march, conversing as we walked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Let me remind you,\" I said, \"in our situation, it would be\ndangerous to teach the dogs not to attack and kill, if they can,\nwhatever unknown animals they meet. You will see that he will\nsoon regard your little monkey as a member of our family. But\nwe must not discourage him from his fancy for attacking wild\nbeasts. Heaven has bestowed the dog on man to be his safeguard\nand ally, and the horse the same. A man on horseback, accompanied\nby a troop of well-trained dogs, need not fear any species of\nwild beasts, not even the lion nor the hyaena.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Thoughtfully, Fritz replied, \"I feel fortunate that we are in the\npossession of two such creatures; but what a pity that the horses\non board died during our voyage, and left us with only an ass.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Let us take care how we treat even our ass with disdain,\" I told\nhim. \"I wish we had him safe on land. Fortunately he is large and\nstrong. We may train him to do us the same services as are\nperformed by the horse; and it is not improbable that he will\nimprove under our care, given the excellent pasture we will find\nin this climate.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The tiny ape seated itself in the coolest way imaginable on\nFritz's shoulder, I helped to carry his canes, and we were\non some distance before Turk overtook us, looking uncommonly\nwell pleased, and licking his chops as though recalling the\nmemory of his feast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He took no notice of the monkey, but it was very uneasy at\nsight of him, and scrambled down into Fritz's arms, which was\nso inconvenient to him that he devised a plan to relieve himself\nof his burden."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Calling Turk, and seriously enjoining obedience, he seated the\nmonkey on his back, securing it there with a cord, and then\nputting a second string round the dog's neck that he might lead\nhim, he put a loop of the knot into the comical rider's hand,\nsaying gravely, 'Having slain the parent, Mr. Turk, you will\nplease to carry the son.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At first this arrangement mightily displeased them both, but by\nand by they yielded to it quietly; the monkey especially amused\nus by riding along with the air of a person perfectly at his ease."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We look just like a couple of mountebanks on their way to a fair\nwith animals to exhibit,' said I. 'What an outcry the children\nwill make when we appear!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My son inquired to what species of the monkey tribe I thought\nhis protege belonged, which led to a good deal of talk on the\nsubject, and conversation beguiling the way, we found ourselves\nere long on the rocky margin of the stream and close to the rest\nof our party."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Juno was the first to be aware of our approach, and gave notice\nof it by loud barking, to which Turk replied with such hearty\ngoodwill, that his little rider, terrified at the noise his\nsteed was making, slipped from under the cord and fled to his\nrefuge on Fritz's shoulder, where he regained his composure and\nsettled himself comfortably."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Turk, who by this time knew where he was, finding himself free,\ndashed forward to rejoin his friend, and announce our coming. One\nafter another our dear ones came running to the opposite bank,\ntestifying in various ways their delight at our return, and\nhastening up on their side of the river, as we on ours, to the\nford at which we had crossed in the morning. We were quickly on\nthe other side, and, full of joy and affection, our happy party\nwas once more united."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys suddenly perceiving the little animal which was clinging\nclose to their brother, in alarm at the tumult of voices, shouted\nin ecstasy:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A monkey! A monkey! Oh, how splendid! Where did Fritz find him?\nWhat may we give him to eat? Oh, what a bundle of sticks! Look at\nthose curious great nuts father has got!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We could neither check this confused torrent of questions, nor\nget in a word in answer to them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At length when the excitement subsided a little, I was able to\nsay a few words with a chance of being listened to. 'I am truly\nthankful to see you all safe and well, and, thank God, our\nexpedition has been very satisfactory, except that we have\nentirely failed to discover any trace of our shipmates.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'If it be the will of God,' said my wife, 'to leave us alone on\nthis solitary place, let us be content, and rejoice that we are\nall together in safety. I have been uneasy since you left, and\nimagined a thousand evils that might beset you. The day appeared\nan age, but now that I see you once more safe and well, I know\nhow foolish my fears must seem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now we want to hear all your adventures, and let us relieve you\nof your burdens,' added she, taking my game-bag."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack shouldered my gun, Ernest took the cocoanuts, and little\nFranz carried the gourds, Fritz distributed the sugarcanes amongst\nhis brothers, and handing Ernest his gun replaced the monkey on\nTurk's hack. Ernest soon found the burden with which Fritz had\nladen him too heavy to his taste. His mother, perceiving this,\noffered to relieve him of part of the load. He willingly gave up\nthe cocoanuts, but no sooner had he done so than his elder brother\nexclaimed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hullo, Ernest, you surely do not know what you are parting with;\ndid you really intend to hand over those good cocoanuts without\nso much as tasting them?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What? ho! Are they really cocoanuts?' cried Ernest, 'I thought\nthey were bowls! Do let me take them again, mother, do let me\nlook at them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, thank you,' replied my wife with a smile. 'I have no wish to\nsee you again overburdened.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh but I have only to throw away these sticks, which are of no\nuse, and then I can easily carry them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Worse and worse,' said Fritz, 'I have a particular regard for\nthose heavy useless sticks. Did you ever hear of sugar-canes?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The words were scarcely out of his mouth when Ernest began to\nsuck vigorously at the end of the cane with no better result,\nhowever, than Fritz had obtained as we were on the march."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here,' said Fritz, 'let me show you the trick of it,' and he\nspeedily set all the youngsters to work extracting the luscious\njuice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife, as a prudent housekeeper who made much use of sugar,\nwas no less delighted than the children with this discovery; the\nsight of the dishes also pleased her greatly, for she longed to\nsee us eat once more like civilized beings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We went into the kitchen and there found preparations for a truly\nsumptuous meal. Two forked sticks were planted in the ground on\neither side of the fire, on these rested a rod from which hung\nseveral tempting-looking fish, opposite them hung a goose from a\nsimilar contrivance, slowly roasting while the gravy dropped into\na large shell placed beneath it. Franz gave the spit another turn,\nassuring me he had been helping all day to keep the meal from\nburning. In the centre sat the great pot from which issued the\nsmell of a most delicious soup. To crown this splendid array,\nstood an open hogshead full of Dutch cheeses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All this was very pleasant to two hungry travellers, but I was\nabout to beg my wife to spare the poultry until our stock should\nhave increased, when she, perceiving my thought, quickly relieved\nmy anxiety. 'This is not one of our geese,' she said, 'but a wild\nbird Ernest killed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes,' said Ernest, 'it is a penguin, I think, it let me get quite\nclose, so that I knocked it on the head with a stick. Here are its\nhead and feet which I preserved to show you; the bill is, you see,\nnarrow and curved downwards, and the feet are webbed. It had funny\nlittle bits of useless wings, and its eyes looked so solemnly and\nsedately at me, that I was almost ashamed to kill it. It seemed\nquite destitute of any intelligence, so that I was able to kill\nit with a single blow from my stick. Do you not think it must\nhave been a penguin?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have little doubt on the matter, my boy,' and I was about to\nmake a few remarks on the habits of this bird, when my wife\ninterrupted me and begged us to come to dinner and continue our\nnatural history conversation at some future time. Fritz now\nsuddenly recollected his delicious wine, and producing his\nflask, begged his mother to taste it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Try it first yourself,' said I; Fritz did so, and I instantly saw\nby his countenance that the liquor had passed through the first\nstage of fermentation and had become vinegar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Never mind, my boy,' said my prudent wife, when she learned the\ncause of his wry faces, 'we have wine already but no vinegar; I\nam really pleased at the transformation. Mixed with the fat\nwhich has fallen from our bird with roasting, it will make a\nmost delicious sauce which will be as good a relish as a salad.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And so it proved, as a corrective of the wild and fishy flavor\nof the penguin, as well as improving the taste of the fish. We\ndid full justice to the appetizing meal prepared for us, our\ngourds coming for the first time into use, and having done it\nfull justice, I produced the cocoanuts by way of dessert."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here is better food for your little friend,' said I to Fritz,\nwho had been vainly endeavouring to persuade the monkey to taste\ndainty morsels of the food we had been eating. 'The poor little\nanimal has been accustomed to nothing but its mother's milk; fetch\nme a saw, one of you.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then, after extracting the milk of the nuts from their natural\nholes, carefully cut the shells in half, thus providing several\nmore useful basins. The monkey was perfectly satisfied with the\nmilk, and eagerly sucked the corner of a handkerchief dipped in it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sun was now rapidly sinking behind the horizon, and the poultry\nretiring for the night warned us that we must follow their example.\nHaving offered up our prayers, we lay down on our beds, the monkey\ncrouched down between Jack and Fritz, and we were all soon fast\nasleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We did not, however, long enjoy this repose; a loud barking from\nour dogs, who were on guard outside the tent, awakened us, and\nthe fluttering and cackling of our poultry warned us that a foe\nwas approaching. Fritz and I sprang up, and seizing our guns\nrushed out. There we found a desperate combat going on, our\ngallant dogs, surrounded by a dozen or more large jackals,\nwere fighting bravely, four of their opponents lay dead, but\nthe others were in no way deterred by the fate of their comrades."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and I, however, sent bullets through the heads of a couple\nmore, and the rest galloped off. Turk and Juno did not intend\nthat they should escape so cheaply, and pursuing them, they\ncaught, killed, and devoured another of the animals, regardless\nof their near relationship. Fritz wished to save one of the jackals\nthat he might be able to show it to his brothers in the morning;\ndragging therefore the one that he had shot near the tent, he\nconcealed it, and we once more returned to our beds. I told him\nthat in justice, if Turk and Flora were still hungry, we should\ngive this last jackal to them. But they, surfeited, curled up to\nsleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soundly and peacefully we slept until cock-crow next morning, when my\nwife and I awoke. I observed to her that I could not but view with\nalarm the many cares and exertions to be made. 'In the first place, a\njourney to the vessel must be made. This is of absolute necessity, at\nleast, if we would not be deprived of the livestock and other useful\nthings, all of which from moment to moment we risk losing by the first\nheavy sea. What ought we first to resolve on? For example, should not\nour very first endeavour to be the contriving of a better sort of\nhabitation and a more secure retreat from wild beasts, as well as a\nseparate place for our provisions? I own I am at a loss what to begin\nfirst.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Return to the wreck by all means,' replied my wife, cheerfully.\n'Patience, order and perseverance will help us through all our work,\nand I agree with you that a visit to the wreck is without doubt our\nfirst duty. Come, let us wake the children, and set to work without\ndelay.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were soon roused, and Fritz overcoming his drowsiness before the\nothers, ran out for his jackal; it was cold and stiff from the night\nair, and he placed it on its legs before the tent, in a most life-like\nattitude, and stood by to watch the effect upon the family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs were the first to perceive their enemy, and growling, seemed\ninclined to dispose of the animal as they had disposed of its brethren\nin the night, but Fritz called them off. The noise the dogs made,\nhowever, had the effect of bringing out the younger children, and many\nwere the exclamations they made at the sight of the strange animal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A yellow dog!' cried Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A wolf!' exclaimed Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is a striped fox,' said Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hullo,' said Fritz. 'The greatest men may make mistakes. Our\nProfessor does not know a jackal when he sees one.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But really,' continued Ernest, examining the animal, 'I think it is a\nfox.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very well, very well,' retorted Fritz, 'no doubt you know better than\nyour father! He thinks it is a jackal.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come boys,' said I, 'no more of this quarrelling; you are none of you\nvery far wrong, for the jackal partakes of the nature of all three,\ndog, wolf, and fox.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The monkey had come out on Jack's shoulder, but no sooner did it catch\nsight of the jackal, than it fled precipitately back into the tent, and\nhid itself in a heap of moss until nothing was visible but the tip of\nits little nose. Jack soothed and comforted the frightened little\nanimal, and I then summoned them all to prayers, soon after which we\nbegan our breakfast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So severely had we dealt with our supper the previous night, that we\nhad little to eat but the biscuits, which were so dry and hard, that,\nhungry as we were, we could not swallow much. Fritz and I took some\ncheese to help them down, while my wife and younger sons soaked theirs\nin water. Ernest roamed down to the shore, and looked about for\nshellfish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently he returned with a few whelks. 'Ah,' said he, 'if we had but\nsome butter.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My good boy,' I replied, 'Your perpetual \"if, if\", quite annoys me; I\nwould rather eat a bit of cheese with my biscuit at once, than think of\nifs, which bring us so meagre a harvest. Why do you not sit down and\neat cheese like the rest of us?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not while I can get butter,' he said, 'see here, father,' and he\npointed to a large cask, 'that barrel contains excellent salt butter. I\nmade a little opening in it with a knife; and see, I got enough to\nspread nicely upon this piece of biscuit.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Really, Ernest,' I said, 'we are indebted to you. I will open the\ncask.' So saying, I took a knife and carefully cut a small hole, so\nthat I could extract the butter without exposing the mass of it to the\neffects of the air and heat. Filling a cocoanut shell with the good\nDutch butter, we once more sat down, toasting our biscuits before the\nfire and spreading them with butter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we were thus employed, I noticed that the two dogs were lying\nunusually quietly by my side. I at first attributed this drowsiness to\ntheir large meal during the night, but I soon discovered that it arose\nfrom a different cause; the faithful animals had not escaped unhurt\nfrom their late combat, but had received several deep and painful\nwounds, especially about the neck. The dogs began to lick each other on\nthe places which they could not reach with their own tongues, and my\nwife carefully dressed the wounds with butter from which she had\nextracted the salt by washing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'One of the things we must not forget to look for in the vessel,' said\nFritz, 'is a spiked collar for each of the dogs, as a protection to\nthem should they again be called upon to defend themselves and us from\nwild beasts.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh yes,' exclaimed Jack, 'but I can make spiked collars, if mother\nwill give me some help.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Try by all means, my little fellow,' said I, 'and persuade your\nmother to assist you; and now, Fritz,' I continued, 'we must be\nstarting, for you and I are to make a trip to the wreck.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That I will, my boy,' she cried, 'for I would like to see what new\nfancy has come into your head. And all of us must remember that we may\nmake as many new inventions as we can think of. We cannot better employ\nyour time, and if you produce something useful, you will be rewarded\nwith the commendations of all.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I begged the party who were to remain on shore, to keep together as\nmuch as possible, reminded my younger sons to obey their mother in all\nthings, and having arranged a set of signals with my wife that we might\nexchange communications, asked a blessing on our enterprise. I erected\na signal-post, and while Fritz was making preparations for our\ndeparture, hoisted a strip of sailcloth as a flag; this flag was to\nremain hoisted so long as all was well on shore, but should our return\nbe desired, three shots were to be fired and the flag lowered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All was now ready, and warning my wife that we might find it necessary\nto remain all night on the vessel, we tenderly bade adieu and embarked.\nExcept our guns and ammunition we were taking nothing, that we might\nleave as much space as possible for the stowage of a large cargo.\nFritz, however, had resolved to bring his little monkey, that he might\nobtain milk for it as soon as possible."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had not got far from the shore, when I perceived that a current from\nthe river set in directly for the vessel, and though my nautical\nknowledge was not great, I succeeded in steering the boat into the\nfavourable stream, which carried us nearly three-fourths of our passage\nwith little or no trouble to ourselves; then, by dint of hard pulling,\nwe accomplished the whole distance, and, entering through the breach,\ngladly made fast our boat and stepped on board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our first care was to see to the animals, who greeted us with\njoyâ€”lowing, bellowing, and bleating as we approachedâ€”not that the\npoor beasts were hungry, for they were all still well supplied with\nfood, but they were apparently pleased by the mere sight of human\nbeings. We removed any partly spoiled food and added a fresh supply,\nalong with fresh water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz then placed his monkey by one of the goats, and the little\nanimal immediately sucked the milk with evident relish, chattering and\ngrinning all the while; the monkey provided for, we refreshed ourselves\nwith a plentiful meal. 'Now,' said I, 'we have plenty to do; where\nshall we begin?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Let us fix a mast and sail to our boat,' answered Fritz, 'for the\ncurrent which brought us out will not take us back; whereas the fresh\nbreeze we met would help us immensely had we but a sail.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Quite startled, I demanded, 'What makes you think of this at so\ncritical a time, when we have so many necessities to attend to?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I must confess,' he said, 'that I found it very difficult to row for\nso long a time, though I assure you I did my best and did not spare my\nstrength. I noticed that, though the wind blew strong in my face,\ntowards land, the current continued to carry us out. Now, as the\ncurrent will be of no use in our way back, I was thinking that we might\nmake the wind supply its place. Our boat will be very heavy when we\nhave loaded it with all the things we mean to take away, and I am\nafraid that I shall not be strong enough to row to land.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You have reasoned well, my boy,' I replied, 'and let us set to work at\nonce. Even so, we must take care not to overload the boat, as that\nmight risk our sinking or force us to throw supplies overboard.' I\nchose a stout spar to serve as a mast, and having made a hole in a\nplank nailed across one of the tubs we, with the help of a rope and a\ncouple of blocks, stepped it and secured it with stays."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then discovered a lug-sail, which had belonged to one of the ship's\nboats; this we hoisted; and our craft was ready to sail. Fritz begged\nme to decorate the mast-head with a red streamer, to give our vessel a\nmore finished appearance. Smiling at this childish but natural vanity,\nI complied with his request. I then contrived a rudder, that I might be\nable to steer the boat; for though I knew that an oar would serve the\npurpose, it was cumbrous and inconvenient."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While I was thus employed, Fritz examined the shore with his glass, and\nsoon announced that the flag was flying and all was well."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So much time had now slipped away, that we found we could not return\nthat night, as I had wished. We signalled our intention of remaining on\nboard, and then spent the rest of our time in taking out the stones we\nhad placed in the boat for ballast, and stowed in their place heavy\narticles, of value to us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ship had sailed for the purpose of supplying a young colony; she\nhad therefore on board every conceivable article we could desire in our\npresent situation; our only difficulty indeed was to make a wise\nselection. Fritz seemed sanguine that we would be able to return for\nmore, but of that I was far from certain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A large quantity of powder and shot we first secured, and as Fritz\nconsidered that we could not have too many weapons, we added three\nexcellent guns, and a whole armful of swords, daggers and knives. We\nremembered that knives and forks and spoons were necessary, we\ntherefore laid in a large stock of them, and kitchen utensils of all\nsorts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Exploring the captain's cabin, we discovered a service of silver-plate\nand a cellaret of good old wine; we then went over the stores, and\nsupplied ourselves with potted meats, portable soups, Westphalian hams,\nsausages, a bag of maize and wheat, and a quantity of other seeds and\nvegetables. I then added a barrel of sulphur for matches, and as much\nstring, cordage, and sailcloth as I could find."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz reminded me that sleeping on the ground, even with the leaves and\nmoss the boys had collected, had been both cold and hard, and prevailed\nupon me to increase our cargo by some hammocks and blankets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All thisâ€”with nails, tools and agricultural implementsâ€”completed our\ncargo, and sank our boat so low, that I should have been obliged to\nlighten her had not the sea been calm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Night drew on and a large fire, lighted by those on shore, showed us\nthat all was well. We replied by hoisting four ship's lanterns, and two\nshots announced us that our signal was perceived."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ship seemed to be in so wretched a condition that the least\ntempest, such as might arise unexpectedly during the night, must\ncomplete her destructions. We resigned ourselves to sleeping in our\nsmall boat, which appeared safer than the great vessel. So, with a\nheartfelt prayer for the safety of our dear ones on shore, we retired,\nand Fritz at all events was soon sound asleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For a while I could not sleep, the thought of my wife and\nchildrenâ€”alone and unprotected, save by the great dogsâ€”disturbed my\nrest. The night at length passed away. At daybreak Fritz and I arose,\nand went on deck. I brought the telescope to bear upon the shore, and\nwith pleasure saw the flag still waving in the morning breeze; while I\nkept the glass directed to the land, I saw the door of the tent open,\nand my wife appear and look steadfastly towards us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I at once hoisted a white flag, and in reply, the flag on shore was\nthrice dipped. Oh, what a weight seemed lifted from my heart as I saw\nthe signal!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz,' I said, 'now that I have had a sight of your mother, my next\nconcern is for the animals on board. Let us endeavour to save the lives\nof some of them, at least, and to take them with us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Would it be possible to make a raft,' suggested Fritz, 'and get them\nall on it and in that way take them to shore?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But how could we induce a cow, an ass, and a sow either to get upon a\nraft or, when there to remain motionless and quiet? The sheep and goats\none might perhaps find means to remove, they being of a more docile\ntemper; but for the larger animals, I am at a loss as to how to\nproceed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We could tie a long rope around the sow's neck,' Fritz now proposed,\n'and throw her without ceremony into the sea. Her immense bulk will be\nsure to sustain her above water, and by the rope, we can draw her after\nthe boat.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'An excellent idea,' I replied, 'but unfortunately it is of no use but\nfor the pig;* and she is the one I care least about preserving.' In\nfact, I had an idea how to proceed, but I desired to allow Fritz to\ninvent a solution."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "In fact all of the animals would have been able to float,\nthough swimming against the strong current would have been\ndifficult. The solution chosen does not address this problem\nat all."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well,' said Fritz, 'I can think of nothing else, unless indeed we make\nthem such swimming-belts as you made for the children.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Really, my boy, that idea is worth having. I am not joking, indeed,' I\ncontinued, as I saw him smile, 'we may get every one of the animals\nashore in that way.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, I caught a fine sheep, and proceeded to put our plan into\nexecution. I first fastened a broad piece of linen round its belly, and\nto this attached some corks and empty tins; then with Fritz's help, I\nflung the animal into the seaâ€”it sank, but a moment afterwards rose\nand floated famously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah!' exclaimed Fritz, 'we will treat them all like that.' We then\nrapidly caught the other animals and provided them one after the other\nwith a similar contrivance. The cow and ass gave us more trouble than\ndid the others. For them we required something more buoyant than the\nmere cork; we at last found some empty casks and fastened two to each\nanimal by thongs passed under its belly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This done, the whole herd were ready to start, and we brought the ass\nto one of the ports to be the first to be launched. After some\nmaneuvering we got him in a convenient position, and then a sudden\nheave sent him plunging into the sea. He sank, and then, buoyed up by\nthe casks, emerged head and back from the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cow, sheep and goats followed him one after the other, and then the\nsow alone remained. She seemed, however determined not to leave the\nship; she kicked, struggled and squealed so violently, that I really\nthought we should be obliged to abandon her. Indeed, we found it\nnecessary to put a muzzle on her to prevent her from biting before we\ncould tie a large piece of cork under her body. At length, after much\ntrouble, we succeeded in sending her out of the port after the others,\nand when once in the water, such was the old lady's energy that she\nquickly distanced them, and was the first to reach the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had fastened to the horns or neck of each animal a cord with a\nfloat attached to the end, and now embarking, we gathered up these\nfloats, set sail, and steered for shore, drawing our herd after us. I\nsaw, now, how impossible it would have been for us to have succeeded in\nour enterprise without the aid of a sail; the weight of the goods sank\nthe boat so low in the water that none of our exertions would have\nallowed us to row such a distance. But with the sail, we proceeded so\ncompletely to our satisfaction that were able to get some biscuits and\nenjoyed a midday meal; then, while Fritz amused himself with his\nmonkey, I took up my glass and tried to make out how our dear ones on\nshore were employing themselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As I was thus engaged, a sudden shout from Fritz surprised me. I\nglanced up; there stood Fritz with his gun to his shoulder, pointing it\nat a huge shark. The monster was making for one of the finest sheep; he\nturned on his side to seize his prey; as the white of his belly\nappeared Fritz fired. The shot took effect, and our enemy disappeared,\nleaving a trace of blood on the calm water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, my boy,' I cried, 'you will become a crack shot one of\nthese days; but I trust you will not often have such dangerous game to\nshoot.' Fritz's eyes sparkled at his success and my praise, and\nreloading his gun, carefully watched the water. But the shark did not\nagain appear, and borne onwards by the breeze, we quickly neared the\nshore. Steering the boat to a convenient landing place, I cast off the\nropes which secured the animals, and let them get ashore as best they\nmight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There was no sign of my wife or children when we stepped on land, but a\nfew moments afterwards they appeared, and with a shout of joy ran\ntowards us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were thankful to be once more united, and after asking and replying\nto a few preliminary questions, proceeded to release our herd from\ntheir swimming belts, which, though so useful in the water, were\nexceedingly inconvenient on shore. My wife was astonished at the\napparatus. 'How clever you are,' said she."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am not the inventor,' I replied, 'the honour is due to Fritz. He not\nonly thought of this plan for bringing off the animals, but saved one\nat least of them from a most fearful death.' And I then told them how\nbravely he had encountered the shark. My wife was delighted with her\nson's success, but declared that she would dread our trips to the\nvessel more than ever, knowing that such savage fish inhabited the\nwaters."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, Ernest and I began the work of unloading our craft, while Jack,\nseeing that the poor donkey was still encumbered with his\nswimming-belt, tried to free him from it. But the donkey would not\nstand quiet, and the child's fingers were not strong enough to loosen\nthe cordage; finally, therefore, he scrambled upon the animal's back,\nand urging him on with hand and foot, trotted towards us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come, my boy,' I said, 'no one must be idle here, even for a moment;\nyou will have riding practise enough hereafter; dismount and come and\nhelp us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack was soon on his feet. 'But I have not been idle all day,' he\nsaid, 'look here!' and he pointed to a belt round his waist. It was a\nbroad belt of yellow skin in which he had stuck a couple of pistols and\na knife. 'And see,' he added, 'what I have made for the dogs. Here,\nJuno, Turk,' the dogs came bounding up at his call, and I saw that they\nwere each supplied with a collar of the same skin, in which were\nfastened nails, which bristled round their necks in a most formidable\nmanner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Capital, capital! my boy,' said I, 'but where did you get your\nmaterials, and who helped you?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Except in sewing,' said my wife, 'he had little assistance, and as for\nthe materials, Fritz's jackal supplied us with the skin, and the\nneedles and thread came out of my wonderful bag. You little think how\nmany useful things may be had from that same bag; it is woman's duty\nand nature, you know, to see after trifles.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz evidently did not approve of the use to which his jackal's hide\nhad been devoted, and holding his nose, begged his little brother to\nkeep at a distance. 'Really, Jack,' he said, 'you should have cured the\nhide before you used it, the smell is disgusting, don't come near me.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It's not the hide that smells at all,' retorted Jack, 'it is your\nnasty jackal itself that you left in the sun.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, boys,' said I, 'no quarrelling here; do you, Jack, help your\nbrother to drag the carcase to the sea, and if your belt smells after\nthat you must take it off and dry it better.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The jackal was dragged off, and we then finished our work of unloading\nour boat. When this was accomplished we started for our tent, and\nfinding there no preparation for supper, I said, 'Fritz, let us have a\nWestphalian ham.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest,' said my wife, smiling, 'let us see if we cannot conjure up\nsome eggs.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz got out a splendid ham and carried it to his mother\ntriumphantly, while Ernest set before me a dozen white balls with\nparchment-like coverings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Turtles' eggs!' said I. 'Well done, Ernest, where did you get them?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That,' replied my wife, 'shall be told in due course when we relate\nour adventures; now we will see what they will do towards making a\nsupper for you; with these and your ham I do not think we shall\nstarve.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Leaving my wife to prepare supper, we returned to the shore and\nbrought up what of the cargo we had left there; then, having collected\nour herd of animals (except for the sow, which ran away, and the ducks\nand geese which deserted us for a nearby marshy swamp), we returned to\nthe tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The meal which awaited us was as unlike the first supper we had there\nenjoyed as possible. My wife had improvised a table of a board laid on\ntwo casks, on this was spread a white damask tablecloth, on which were\nplaced knives, forks, spoons and plates for each person. A tureen of\ngood soup first appeared, followed by a capital omelette, then slices\nof the ham; and finally some Dutch cheese, butter and biscuits, with a\nbottle of the captain's canary wine, completed the repast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we thus regaled ourselves, I related to my wife our adventures,\nand then begged she would remember her promise and tell me all that had\nhappened in my absence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 3"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I will spare you a description,' said my wife, 'of our first day's\noccupations; truth to tell, I spent the time chiefly in anxious thought\nand watching your progress and signals. I rose very early this morning,\nand with the utmost joy perceiving your signal that all was right,\nhastened to reply to it, and then while my sons yet slumbered, I sat\ndown and began to consider how our position could be improved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"For it is perfectly impossible,\" said I to myself, \"to live much\nlonger where we are now. The sun beats burningly the livelong day on\nthis bare rocky spot, our only shelter is this poor tent, beneath the\ncanvas of which the heat is even more oppressive than on the open\nshore. Why should not I and my little boys exert ourselves as well as\nmy husband and Fritz? Why should not we too try to accomplish something\nuseful?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"If we could but exchange this melancholy and unwholesome abode for\na pleasant shady dwelling-place, we should all improve in health and\nspirits. Among those delightful woods and groves where Fritz and his\nfather saw so many charming things, I feel sure there must be some\nlittle retreat where we could establish ourselves comfortably; there\nmust be, and I will find it.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'By this time the boys were up, and I observed Jack very quietly and\nbusily occupied with his knife about the spot where Fritz's jackal lay.\nWatching his proceedings, I saw that he had cut two long narrow strips\nof the animal's skin, which he cleaned and scraped very carefully, and\nthen taking a handful of great nails out of his pocket, he stuck them\nthrough the skin points outwards, after which he cut strips of canvas\nsailcloth twice as broad as the thongs, doubled them, and laid them on\nthe raw side of the skin so as to cover the broad flat nail heads."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'At this point of the performance, Master Jack came to me with the\nagreeable request that I would kindly stitch the canvas and (moist)\nskin together for him. I gave him needles and thread, but could not\nthink of depriving him of the pleasure of doing it himself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'However, when I saw how good-humouredly he persevered in the work with\nhis awkward unskilful fingers, I took pity upon him, and conquering the\ndisgust I felt, finished lining the skin dog-collars he had so\ningeniously contrived. After this I was called upon to complete in the\nsame way a fine belt of skin he had made for himself. I advised him to\nthink of some means by which the skin might be kept from shrinking."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest, although rather treating Jack's manufacture with ridicule,\nproposed a sensible-enough plan, which Jack forthwith put in execution.\nHe nailed the skin, stretched flat, on a board, and put it in the sun\nto dry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My scheme of a journey was agreed to joyously by my young companions.\nPreparations were instantly set on foot: weapons and provisions\nprovided: the two elder boys carrying guns, while they gave me charge\nof the water flask, and a small hatchet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Leaving everything in as good order as we could at the tent, we\nproceeded towards the stream, accompanied by the dogs. Turk, who had\naccompanied you on your first expedition, seemed immediately to\nunderstand that we wished to pursue the same route, and proudly led the\nway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As I looked at my two young sons, each with his gun, and considered\nhow much the safety of the party depended on these little fellows, I\nfelt grateful to you, dear husband, for having acquainted them in\nchildhood with the use of firearms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Filling our water-jar, we crossed the stream, and went on to the\nheight from whence, as you described, a lovely prospect is obtained, at\nthe sight of which a pleasurable sensation of buoyant hope, to which I\nhad long been a stranger, awoke within my breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A pretty little wood in the distance attracted my notice\nparticularly, and thither we directed our course. But soon finding it\nimpossible to force our way through the tall strong grass which grew in\ndense luxuriance higher than the children's heads, we turned towards\nthe open beach on our left, and following it we reached a point much\nnearer the little wood, when, quitting the strand, we made towards it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We had not entirely escaped the tall grass, however and with the\nutmost fatigue and difficulty were struggling through the reeds, when\nsuddenly a great rushing noise terrified us all dreadfully. A very\nlarge and powerful bird sprang upward on the wing. Both boys attempted\nto take aim, but the bird was far away before they were ready to fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Oh dear, what a pity!\" exclaimed Ernest; \"now if I had only had my\nlight gun, and if the bird had not flown quite so fast, I should have\nbrought him down directly!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Oh yes,\" said I, \"no doubt you would be a capital sportsman if only\nyour game would always give you time to make ready comfortably.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"But I had no notion that anything was going to fly up just at our\nfeet like that,\" cried he."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"A good shot,\" I replied, \"must be prepared for surprises: neither\nwild birds nor wild beasts will send you notice that they are about to\nfly or to run.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"What sort of bird can it have been?' inquired Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Oh, it certainly must have been an eagle,\" answered little Franz, \"it\nwas so very big!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Just as if every big bird must be an eagle!\" replied Ernest, in a\ntone of derision."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Let's see where he was sitting, at all events!\" said I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack sprang towards the place, and instantly a second bird, rather\nlarger than the first, rushed upward into the air, with a most\nstartling noise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The boys stood staring upwards, perfectly stupefied, while I laughed\nheartily, saying, \"Well, you are first-rate sportsmen, to be sure! You\ncertainly will keep my larder famously well supplied!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'At this, Ernest coloured up, and looked inclined to cry, while Jack\nput on a comical face, pulled off his cap, and with a low bow, called\nafter the fugitive, \"Adieu for the present, sir! I live in hopes of\nanother meeting!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'On searching the ground carefully, we discovered a rude sort of nest\nmade untidily of dry grass. It was empty, although we perceived broken\negg-shells at no great distance, and concluded that the young brood had\nescaped among the grass, which, in fact, we could see was waving at a\nlittle distance, as the little birds ran through it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Now look here, Franz,\" said Ernest, presently, \"just consider how\nthis bird could by any possibility have been an eagle. Eagles never\nbuild on the ground, neither can their young leave the nest and run as\nsoon as they are out of the egg. That is a peculiarity of the\ngallinaceous tribe of birds alone, to which then these must belong. The\nspecies, I think, is indicated by the white belly and dull red colour\nof the wing coverts which I observed in these specimens, and I believe\nthem to be bustards, especially as I noticed in the largest the fine\nmoustache-like feathers over the beak, peculiar to the Great Bustard.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"My dear boy!\" I said, \"your eyes were actively employed, I must\nconfess, if your fingers were unready with the gun. And after all, it\nis just as well, perhaps, that we have not thrown the bustard's family\ninto mourning.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Thus chatting, we at length approached my pretty wood. Numbers of\nbirds fluttered and sang among the high branches, but I did not\nencourage the boys in their wish to try to shoot any of the happy\nlittle creatures. We were lost in admiration of the trees of this\ngrove, and I cannot describe to you how wonderful they are, nor can you\nform the least idea of their enormous size without seeing them\nyourself. What we had been calling a wood proved to be a group of about\na dozen trees only, and, what was strange, the roots sustained the\nmassive trunks exalted in the air, forming strong arches, and props and\nstays all around each individual stem, which was firmly rooted in the\ncentre."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I gave Jack some twine, and scrambling up one of the curious open-air\nroots, he succeeded in measuring round the trunk itself, and made it\nout to be about eighteen yards. I saw no sort of fruit, but the foliage\nis thick and abundant, throwing delicious shade on the ground beneath,\nwhich is carpeted with soft green herbage, and entirely free from\nthorns, briars, or bushes of any kind. It is the most charming\nresting-place that ever was seen, and I and the boys enjoyed our midday\nmeal immensely in this glorious palace of the woods, so grateful to our\nsenses after the glare and heat of our journey thither."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The dogs joined us after a while. They had lingered behind on the\nsea-shore, and I was surprised to see them lie down and go comfortably\nto sleep without begging for food, as they do usually when we eat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The longer we remained in this enchanting place, the more did it\ncharm my fancy; and if we could but manage to live in some sort of\ndwelling up among the branches of those grand, noble trees, I should\nfeel perfectly safe and happy. It seemed to me absurd to suppose we\nshould ever find another place half so lovely, so I determined to\nsearch no further, but return to the beach and see if anything from the\nwreck had been cast up by the waves, which we could carry away with us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Before starting, Jack persuaded me to sit quietly a little longer, and\nfinish making his belt and the spike-collars for the dogs, for you must\nknow that the child had actually been carrying the board on which these\nwere stretched all this time, so that they should get the full benefit\nof the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As they were now quite dry, I completed them easily, and Jack girded\non the belt with great pride, placing his pistols in it, and marching\nabout in a most self-important style, while Ernest fitted the collars\non the two dogs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'On reaching the shore, we found it strewed with many articles,\ndoubtless of value, but all too heavy for us to lift. We rolled some\ncasks, however, beyond high-water mark, and dragged a chest or two also\nhigher on the beach; and, while doing so, observed that our dogs were\nbusy among the rocks. They were carefully watching the crevices and\npools, and every now and then would pounce downwards and seize\nsomething which they swallowed with apparent relish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"They are eating crabs,\" said Jack. \"No wonder they have not seemed\nhungry lately.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And, sure enough, they were catching the little green crabs with\nwhich the water abounded. These, however, did not apparently entirely\nsatisfy them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Some time afterwards, just as we were about to turn inland towards the\nford, we noticed that Juno was scraping in the sand, and turning up\nsome round substances, which she hastily devoured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest went to see what these were, and reported in his calm way that\nthe dog had found turtles' eggs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Oh,\" cried I, \"then let us by all means share in the booty!\" Mrs.\nJuno, however, did not at all approve of this, and it was with some\ndifficulty that we drove her aside while we gathered a couple of dozen\nof the eggs, stowing them in our provision bags. While thus employed,\nwe caught sight of a sail which appeared to be merrily approaching the\nshore beyond the cliffs. Ernest declared it must be our raft. Little\nFranz, always having the fear of savages before his eyes, began to look\nfrightened, and for a moment I myself was doubtful what to think."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'However, we hastened to the stream; and, crossing it by the\nstepping-stones, came in sight of the landing-place, where we joyfully\nmet you."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now I hope you approve of the proceedings of your exploring party, and\nthat tomorrow you will do me the favour of packing everything up, and\ntaking us away to live amongst my splendid trees.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Aye, little wife,' said I, 'so that is your idea of comfort and\nsecurity is it! A tree, I do not know how many feet high, on which we\nare to perch and roost like the birds? If we had but wings or a\nballoon, it would, I own, be a capital plan.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Laugh as much as you like,' returned my wife, 'my idea is not so\nabsurd as you make it out. We should be safe up there from jackals'\nvisits during the night. And I know I have seen at home in Switzerland,\nquite a pretty arbour, with a strong floor, up among the branches of a\nlime tree, and we went up a staircase to reach it. Why could not we\ncontrive a place like that, where we could sleep safely at night?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I will consider the idea seriously, my wife,' said I, 'perhaps\nsomething may come of it, after all! Meantime, as we have finished\nsupper, and night is coming on, let us commend ourselves to Almighty\nprotection and retire to rest.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Beneath the shelter of our tent, we all slept soundly as marmots,\nuntil break of day; when, my wife and I awaking, took counsel together\nas to future proceedings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Referring to the task she had the previous evening proposed for me, I\nremarked that to undertake it would involve so many difficulties that\nit was highly necessary to look closely into the subject."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In the first place,' said I, 'I am unwilling hastily to quit a spot to\nwhich I am convinced we were providentially led as a landing-place. See\nhow secure it is; guarded on all sides by these high cliffs, and\naccessible only by the narrow passage to the ford, while from this\npoint it is so easy to reach the ship that the whole of its valuable\ncargo is at our disposal. Suppose we decide to stay patiently here for\nthe presentâ€”until, at least, we have brought on shore everything we\npossibly can?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I agree with you to a certain extent, dear husband,' replied she, 'but\nyou do not know how dreadfully the heat among the rocks tries me. It is\nalmost intolerable to us who remain here all day while you and Fritz\nare away out at sea, or wandering among the shady woods, where cool\nfruits refresh, and fair scenes delight you."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As to the contents of the ship, an immense deal has been cast ashore,\nand I would much rather give up all the remainder, and be spared the\npainful anxiety it gives me when you even talk of venturing again on\nthe faithless deep.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, I must admit that there is much right on your side,' I\ncontinued; 'suppose we were to remove to your chosen abode, and make\nthis rocky fastness our magazine and place of retreat in case of\ndanger. I could easily render it still more secure, by blasting\nportions of the rock with gunpowder. But a bridge must be constructed\nin the first place, to enable us to cross bag and baggage.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, I shall be parched to death before we can leave this place, if a\nbridge has to be made,' cried my wife impatiently. 'Why not just take\nour things on our backs and wade across as we have done already? The\ncow and the donkey could carry a great deal.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That they will have to do, in whatever fashion we make the move,' said\nI; 'but bags and baskets we must have, to put things in, and if you\nwill turn your attention to providing those, I will set about the\nbridge at once. It will be wanted not once, but continually; the stream\nwill probably swell and be impassable at times, and even as it is, an\naccident might happen.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, well!' cried my wife, 'I submit to your opinion; only pray set\nabout it without delay, for I long to be off. It is an excellent idea\nto make a strong place among the cliffs here; the gunpowder especially,\nI shall be delighted to see stored here when we go away, for it is\nfrightfully dangerous to keep so much as we have close to our\nhabitation.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Gunpowder is indeed the most dangerous and at the same time the most\nuseful thing we have,' said I, 'and for both these reasons we must be\nespecially careful of it. In time I will hollow out a place in the rock\nwhere we can store it safe from either fire or damp.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this morning's consultation we had settled the weighty question of\nour change of abode, and also chalked out work for the day. When the\nchildren heard of the proposed move their joy was boundless; they began\nat once to talk of it as our 'journey to the Promised Land', and only\nregretted that time must be 'wasted', as they said, in bridge-building\nbefore it could be undertaken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone being impatient for breakfast that work might be begun at\nonce, the cow and goats were milked, and, having enjoyed a comfortable\nmeal of biscuit boiled in milk, I prepared to start for the wreck, in\norder to obtain planks for the proposed bridge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest as well as Fritz accompanied me, and we were soon within the\ninfluence of the current, and were carried swiftly out to sea. Fritz\nwas steering, and we had no sooner passed beyond the islet at the\nentrance of the bay, so as to come in sight of its seaward beach, than\nwe were astonished to see a countless multitude of sea-birds, gulls and\nothers, which rose like a cloud into the air, disturbed by our\napproach, and deafened us by their wild and screaming cries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz caught up his gun, and would have sent a shot among them had I\npermitted it. I was very curious to find out what could be the great\nattraction for all this swarm of feathered fowl; and, availing myself\nof a fresh breeze from the sea, I set the sail and directed our course\ntowards the island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The swelling sail and flying pennant charmed Ernest, while Fritz bent\nhis keen eyes eagerly towards the sandy shore, where the flocks of\nbirds were again settling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently he shouted, 'Aha, now I see what they are after! They have\ngot a huge monster of a fish there, and a proper feast they are making!\nLet's have a nearer look at it, father!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We could not take our boat very close in, but we managed to effect a\nlanding at a short distance from the festive scene; and, securing the\nraft by casting a rope round a large stone, we cautiously drew near the\nobject of interest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It proved to be a monstrous fish, on whose flesh these multitudes of\nbirds were ravenously feeding; and it was extraordinary to watch the\nferocity, the envy, the gluttony, and all manner of evil passions,\nexhibited among the guests at this banquet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There was nothing on this sandy beach when we passed yesterday, I am\ncertain, father,' said Fritz. 'It seems strange to see this creature\nstranded here.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, Fritz!' cried Ernest, 'it must be the shark! Your shark, you\nknow! I believe I can see where you hit him in the head.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are right, I do believe, Ernest,' said I, 'though I think your\nimagination only can distinguish the gunshot wounds among all the\npecking and tearing of the voracious birds there. Just look, boys, at\nthose terrific jaws, beneath the strangely projecting snout. See the\nrows upon rows of murderous teeth, and thank God we were delivered from\nthem! Let us try if we can induce these greedy birds to spare us a bit\nof the shark's skin; it is extremely rough, and when dry may be used\nlike a file.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest drew the ramrod from his gun, and charged so manfully into the\ncrowd, that striking right and left he speedily killed several, whilst\nmost of the others took to flight. Fritz detached some broad strips of\nskin with his knife, and we returned towards the boat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Perceiving with satisfaction that the shore was strewn with just the\nsort of boards and planks I wanted, I lost no time in collecting them;\nand, forming a raft to tow after us, we were in a short time able to\ndirect our course homeward, without visiting the wreck at all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we sailed along, extremely well pleased with our good fortune,\nFritz, by my direction, nailed part of the shark's skin flat on boards\nto dry in the sun and the rest on the rounded mast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Will that be a good idea, father?' inquired he, 'it will be quite bent\nand crooked when it hardens.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is just what I want it to be,' said I, 'we may happen to find it\nuseful in that form as well as flat. It would be beautiful shagreen*\nwith which we could smooth and polish wood.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Rough leather used like sandpaper"
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I thought,' remarked Ernest, 'that shagreen was made from asses'\nhides.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And you thought rightly,' said I. 'The best shagreen is prepared in\nTurkey, Persia, and Tartary, from the skins of horses and asses. In\nthese skins, the roughness is produced artificially; while the skin is\nnewly flayed and still soft, hard grains of corn are spread on the\nunder surface, and pressed into it as it dries. These grains are\nafterward removed, and the roughness imparted to the appearance of the\nskin remains indelibly; shagreen is useful in polishing joiners' work,\nand it is made in France from the rough skin of a hideous creature\ncalled the angel-fish.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Angel-fish!' exclaimed Fritz; 'what a name to give to anything\n\"hideous,\" father!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There are bad angels as well as good ones,' observed Ernest, in his\ndry, quiet way; 'it is better to leave people to see for themselves\nwhich is meant.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time we were close in shore; and, lowering the sail, we soon\nhad our craft with the raft in tow, safely moored to the bank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No one was in sight, not a sound to be heard, so with united voice we\ngave a loud cheery halloo, which after a while was answered in shrill\ntones, and my wife with her two boys came running from behind the high\nrocks between us and the stream, each carrying a small bundle in a\nhandkerchief, while little Franz held aloft a landing-net."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our return so soon was quite unexpected, and they anxiously inquired\nthe reason, which we soon explained; and then the mysterious bundles\nwere opened, and a great number of fine crawfish displayed; whose\nefforts to escape by scuttling away in every direction, directly they\nwere placed in a heap on the ground, caused immense fun and laughter as\nthe boys pursued and brought them back, only to find others scrambling\noff in a dozen different ways."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, father, have we not done well, today!' cried Jack, 'did you ever\nsee such a splendid crawfish? Oh, there were thousands of them, and I\nam sure we have got two hundred here at least. Just look at their\nclaws!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No doubt you were the discoverer of these fine crabs, eh, Jack?' said"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No! Fancy young Franz being the lucky man!' answered he. 'He and I\nwent towards the stream while mother was busy, just to look for a good\nplace for the bridge. Franz was picking up pebbles and alabasters, some\nbecause they were so pretty, some to strike sparks with in the dark,\nand some he insisted were \"gold.\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Jack! Jack!\" cried he presently, \"come and see the crabs on Fritz's\njackal!\" You know we threw it away there, and to be sure it was\nswarming with these creatures. Are you glad we have found them, father?\nWill they be good to eat?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very excellent, my boy, and we may be thankful that food for our\nwants is thus provided day by day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When each party had related the day's adventures, and while my wife was\ncooking the crawfish, we went to bring our store of planks to land.\nEven this apparently simple operation required thought, and I had to\nimprovise rope-harness for the cow and the donkey, by which we could\nmake them drag each board separately from the water's edge to the\nmargin of the stream."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack showed me where he thought the bridge should be, and I certainly\nsaw no better place, as the banks were at that point tolerably close to\none another, steep, and of about equal height."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How shall we find out if our planks are long enough to reach across?'\nsaid I. 'A surveyor's table would be useful now.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What do you say to a ball of string, father?' said Ernest. 'Tie one\nend to a stone, throw it across, then draw it back, and measure the\nline!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Adopting my son's idea, we speedily ascertained the distance across to\nbe eighteen feet. Then allowing three feet more at each side, I\ncalculated twenty-four feet as the necessary length of the boards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The question as to how the planks were to be laid across was a\ndifficult one. We resolved to discuss it during dinner, to which we\nwere now summoned. And my wife, as we sat resting, displayed to me her\nneedlework. With hard labour had she made two large canvas bags for the\nass to carry. Having no suitable needle, she had been obliged to bore\nthe hole for each stitch with a nail, and gained great praise for her\ningenuity and patience."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Dinner was quickly dispatched, as we were all eager to continue our\nengineering work. A scheme had occurred to me for conveying one end of\na plank across the water, and I set about it in this way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There fortunately were one or two trees close to the stream on either\nside; I attached a rope pretty near one end of a beam, and slung it\nloosely to the tree beside us; then, fastening a long rope to the other\nend, I crossed with it by means of broken rocks and stones, and having\na pulley and block, I soon arranged the rope on a strong limb of the\nopposite tree, again returning with the end to our own side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Now putting my idea to the proof, I brought the ass and the cow, and\nfastening this rope to the harness I had previously contrived for them,\nI drove them steadily away from the bank. To my great satisfaction, and\nthe surprise and delight of the boys, the end of the plank which had\nbeen laid alongside the stream began gently to move, rose higher,\nturned, and soon projecting over the water continued to advance, until,\nhaving described the segment of a circle, it reached the opposite bank."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I stopped my team, the plank rested on the ground, the bridge was\nmade! So at least thought Fritz and Jack, who in a moment were lightly\nrunning across the narrow way, shouting joyfully as they sprang to the\nother side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our work was now comparatively easy. A second and third plank were laid\nbeside the first; and when these were carefully secured at each end to\nthe ground and to the trees, we very quickly laid short boards side by\nside across the beams, the boys nailing them lightly down as I sawed\nthem in lengths; and when this was done, our bridge was pronounced\ncomplete."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing could exceed the excitement of the children. They danced to and\nfro on the wonderful structure, singing, shouting and cutting the\nwildest capers. I must confess I heartily sympathized with their\ntriumphant feelings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Now that the work was done, we began to feel how much we were\nfatigued, and gladly returned to our tent for refreshment and repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning, while we breakfasted, I made a little speech to my sons\non the subject of the important move we were about to make, wishing to\nimpress them with a sense of the absolute necessity of great caution."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Remember,' said I, 'that, although you all begin to feel very much at\nyour ease here, we are yet complete strangers to a variety of dangers\nwhich may surprise us unawares. I charge you, therefore, to maintain\ngood order, and keep together on the march. No darting off into\nbye-ways, Jack. No lingering behind to philosophize, Ernest. And now\nall hands to work.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The greatest activity instantly prevailed in our camp. Some collected\nprovisions, others packed kitchen utensils, tools, ropes, and hammocks,\narranging them as burdens for the cow and ass."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife pleaded for a seat on the latter for her little Franz, and\nassuring me likewise that she could not possibly leave the poultry,\neven for a night, nor exist an hour without her magic bag, I agreed to\ndo my best to please her, without downright cruelty to animals."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Away ran the children to catch the cocks and hens. Great chasing,\nfluttering and cackling ensued; but with no success whatever, until my\nwife recalled her panting sons, and, scattering some handfuls of grain\nwithin the open tent, soon decoyed the fowls and pigeons into the\nenclosure; where, when the curtain was dropped, they were easily\ncaught, tied together, and placed on the cow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This amiable and phlegmatic animal had stood calmly chewing the cud,\nwhile package after package was disposed on her broad back, nor did she\nnow object even to this noisy addition to her load. I placed a couple\nof half-hoops over all; and, spreading sailcloth on them, put the fowls\nin darkness, and they rapidly became quiet; and the cow, with the\nappearance of having a small waggon on her back, was ready to start."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz was firmly seated on the ass, amidst bags and bundles of all\nsorts and sizes; they rose about him like cushions and pillows, and his\ncurly head rested on the precious magic bag, which surmounted all the\nrest. Having filled the tent with the things we left behind, closing it\ncarefully, and ranging chests and casks around it, we were finally\nready to be off, each well equipped and in the highest spirits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and his mother led the van. Franz (the young cavalier), and the\nsober-minded cow followed them closely."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack conducted the goats; one of these had also a rider, for Knips the\nmonkey was seated on his foster-mother, whose patience was sorely tried\nby his restlessness and playful tricks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sheep were under Ernest's care, and I brought up the rear of this\npatriarchal band, while the two dogs kept constantly running backwards\nand forwards in the character of aides-de-camp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We seem delightfully like those simple and pastoral tribes I have read\nof,' said Ernest, as we proceeded, 'whose whole lives are spent in\nshifting from place to place, without any wish to settle.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes,' said I. 'Among the Arabs, Tartars, and some other Eastern\nnations, this mode of life is natural. They for that reason are called\nNomads."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These tribes are amply provided with camels and horses, and effect\ntheir journeys more quickly and conveniently than we are likely to do\nwith these deliberate quadrupeds of ours. Whatever you young folks may\nthink, I suspect your mother and I will be quite satisfied with one\nsuch undertaking. At least I hope she will be contended with the nest\nshe intends me to build for her up in her wonderful trees.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With honest pride I introduced my wife to my bridge, and after\nreceiving from her what I considered well-merited praise for my skill\nin its construction, we passed over it in grand procession, reinforced\nunexpectedly on the opposite side by the arrival of our cross-grained\nold sow. The perverse creature had obstinately resisted our attempts to\nbring her with us, but finding herself deserted, had followed of her\nown accord, testifying in the most unmistakable manner, by angry grunts\nand squeals, her entire disapproval of our proceedings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I soon found we must, as before, turn down to the sea beach, for not\nonly did the rank grass impede our progress, but it also tempted the\nanimals to break away from us, and, but for our watchful dogs, we might\nhave lost several of them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the firm, open sands we were making good way, when to my annoyance,\nboth our dogs suddenly left us, and springing into the thick cover to\nour right, commenced a furious barking, following by howling as if in\nfear and violent pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not for a moment doubting that some dangerous animal was at hand, I\nhastened to the spot, remarking as I went the characteristic behaviour\nof my three older sons."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz cocked his gun and advanced boldly, but with caution. Ernest\nlooked disconcerted, and drew back, but got ready to fire, while Jack\nhurried after Fritz without so much as unslinging his gun from his\nshoulders."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before I could come up with them, I heard Jack shouting excitedly:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father! Father! Come quickly! A huge porcupine! A most enormous\nporcupine!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sure enough, the dogs were rushing round and round a porcupine, and\nhaving attempted to seize it, were already severely wounded by its\nquills. Each time they came near, the creature, with a rattling noise,\nbristled up its spines."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Somewhat to my amusement, while we were looking at the curious defense\nthis creature was making, little Jack stepped close up to it, with a\npocket pistol in his hand, and shot it dead, making sure of it by a\ncouple of hearty raps on the head, and then giving way to a burst of\nboyish exultation, he called upon us to help to convey his prize to his\nmother. This it was not by any means easy to do. Sundry attempts\nresulted in bloody fingers, till Jack, taking his pocket-handkerchief,\nand fastening one corner round its neck, ran off, dragging it after him\nto where his mother awaited us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hullo, mother! Here's a jolly beast, isn't it? I shot it, and it's\ngood to eat! Father says so! I only wish you had seen how it terrified\nthe dogs, and heard the rattling and rustling of its spines. Oh, it is\na fearful creature!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, examining it carefully, pronounced its incisor teeth, its ears\nand feet, to resemble those of the human race, and pointed out the\ncurious crest of stiff hairs on its head and neck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have read of another species,' said he, 'called the tuft-tailed\nporcupine, which must be even more curious-looking than this is. It has\nshort flat quills, and a scaly tail ending in an extraordinary tuft,\nlike a bunch of narrow strips of parchment. It cannot be such a\ndisagreeable enemy to encounter as this fellow.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Were you not afraid, Jack,' asked I, 'lest the porcupine should cast\nsome of his quills like darts at you?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Of course not,' returned he, 'I know well enough that is nothing but a\nfable!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A fable!' said I, 'why look at your mother! She is drawing five or six\nspines out of each of the dogs!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, those stuck into them when they so fiercely fell upon it in their\nattack. Those are the shortest quills, and seem very slightly fixed in\nits skin. The long quills bent aside when Juno pressed against them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are perfectly right, my boy,' said I, 'there is no truth in the\nold idea of shooting out the spines. But now, shall we leave this\nprickly booty of yours, or attempt to take it with us?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, please, father, let us take it! Why, it is good to eat!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Smiling at the child's eagerness, and willing to please him, I made a\nsomewhat awkward bundle of the porcupine, wrapping it in several folds\nof cloth, and added it to the donkey's load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our party then resumed the march, which, with little interruption, was\ncontinued steadily, until we came in sight of our future place of\nresidence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The wonderful appearance of the enormous trees, and the calm beauty of\nthe spot altogether, fully came up to the enthusiastic description\nwhich had been given to me. And my wife gladly heard me say that if an\nabode could be contrived among the branches, it would be the safest and\nmost charming home in the world."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We hastily unloaded the ass and cow, securing them, as well as the\nsheep and goats, by tying their fore-feet loosely together."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The doves and poultry were set at liberty, and we sat down to rest\namong the soft herbage while we laid our plans for the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz soon left us, but presently two shots were fired, and he\nappeared holding a fine tiger-cat by the hind legs, which, with the\nintensest delight, he exhibited to each in turn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, Fritz!' cried I. 'Our cocks and hens would have had an\nunfortunate night of it but for this lucky shot of yours. It is to be\nhoped he has left no companion near at hand. You must be on the\nlook-out.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How curious it seems,' remarked Ernest, 'that God should create\nhurtful animals like this.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To our feeble and narrow vision many of the ways of the Infinite and\nEternal Mind are incomprehensible,' I replied. 'What our limited reason\ncannot grasp, let us be content to acknowledge as the workings of\nAlmighty power and wisdom, and thankfully trust in that \"Rock,\" which,\nwere it not higher than we, would afford no sense of security to the\nimmortal soul."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That animals should prey upon one another is a means of preserving a\ndue balance in the world of nature. What beautiful and warm furs are\nprocured by hunters just in those countries where no other covering\nwould defend the inhabitants from the wintery cold!â€”As, for instance,\nthe skins of bears, wolverines, and arctic foxes, wild cats, and many\nothers.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The skin of the seal, or sea dog, is also valuable,' said Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is,' I replied, 'and in its own element that creature preys on fish\nas the dog did on land animals before his race became domesticated by\nman. But now, Fritz, tell us how you obtained your prize.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Observing that something moved among the branches,' said he, 'I went\nsoftly round the tree with my gun, and making sure the creature was a\nwild cat I fired and brought it down. It was severely wounded, but,\nrising in a fury, it attempted to climb the tree, when I luckily having\na loaded pistol, gave it a quietus. And do tell me, father, what sort\nof cat it is.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is a mercy the brute did not fly at your throat instead of\nattempting to escape,' said I. 'It belongs to a fierce and\nblood-thirsty raceâ€”that of the ocelots or tiger-cats, natives of the\ntropical parts of America. I should say this was a margay, and as it\nwould have proved a cruel foe, not only of our poultry, but also of our\nsheep and goats, I am well pleased that you have rid us of it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'May I have the beautiful skin, father? And will you tell me what will\nbe the best use to make of it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I advise you to skin the animal very carefully, and of the handsome\nblack and yellow tail, make a hunting-belt for yourself. The pawsâ€”let\nme seeâ€”why, I fancy the paws might be made famous cases for knife,\nfork and spoon, and look well hanging from the belt. The skin of the\nbody you had better preserve until you find some suitable use for it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father, what a splendid plan!' cried Jack. 'Do tell me some good\nuse for my porcupine.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think its feet may make cases also; at least, you may try. The\nquills, I am sure, may be used for packing needles, and for tipping\narrows, and I should try to make defensive armour for the dogs out of\nthe rest. They may fall in with foes more dangerous than any we have\nyet seen.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To be sure, father, the very thing!' shouted Jack in high glee. 'I\nhave seen pictures of boar-hunts, in which the dogs were protected by a\nsort of leather coat of mail. That will be grand!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After giving this advice, I got no peace until I had shown my boys how\nto act upon it, and in a short time each had his prize fastened up by\nthe hind legs, and carefully slitting the skin, was stripping it from\nthe carcase."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, meanwhile, was fetching large flat stones in order to form a\nfire-place, while Franz gathered sticks, as his mother was anxious to\nprepare some food."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What sort of tree do you suppose this to be, father?' inquired\nErnest, seeing me examining that under which we were encamping. 'Is not\nthe leaf something like a walnut?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There is a resemblance, but in my opinion these gigantic trees must be\nmangroves or wild figs. I have heard their enormous height described,\nand also the peculiarity of the arching roots supporting the main trunk\nraised above the soil.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Just then little Franz came up with a large bundle of sticks, and his\nmouth full of something he was eating with evident satisfaction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, mother!' cried he, 'this is so good! So delicious!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Greedy little boy!' exclaimed she in a fright. 'What have you got\nthere? Don't swallow it, whatever you do. Very likely it is poisonous!\nSpit it all out this minute!' And his anxious mother quickly extracted\nfrom the rosy little mouth the remains of a small fig."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Where did you find this?' said I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There are thousands lying among the grass yonder,' replied the little\nboy. 'They taste very nice. I thought poison was nasty. Do you think\nthey will hurt me? The pigeons and the hens are gobbling them up with\nall their might and main, papa!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think you have no cause for alarm, dear wife,' I said. 'The trees\nseem to be the fig-bearing mangrove of the Antilles. But remember,\nFranz, you must never eat anything without first showing it to me,\nnever mind how good it seems."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'If birds and monkeys eat a fruit or vegetable, it is usually safe to\nbelieve it wholesome,' added I, turning to the other boys, who\ninstantly taking the hint, coaxed Franz to give them the figs he still\nhad in his pocket, and ran to offer them to Knips, who was closely\nwatching the skinning of the tiger-cat and porcupine, apparently giving\nhis opinion on the subject with much chattering and gesticulation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here, Knips, allow me to present you with a fig!' cried Jack, holding\none out to the funny little creature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Knips took it readily, and after turning it about, and sniffing and\nsmelling it, he popped it into his mouth, with such a droll grimace of\ndelight and satisfaction that the boys all laughed and clapped their\nhands, crying 'Bravo, Knips! You know a good thing when you see it,\ndon't you, old fellow! Hurrah!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife, with her mind set at rest on the question of the figs, now\ncontinued her preparations for dinner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The flesh of the margay was given to the dogs, but part of the\nporcupine was put on the fire to boil, while we reserved the rest for\nroasting."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I employed myself in contriving needles for my wife's work, by boring\nholes at one end of the quills, which I did by means of a red hot nail,\nand I soon had a nice packet of various sizes, which pleased her\nimmensely. I also laid plans for making proper harness for our beasts\nof burden, but could not attempt to begin that while so many wants more\npressing demanded attention."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We examined the different trees, and chose one which seemed most\nsuited to our purpose. The branches spread at a great height above us,\nand I made the boys try if it were possible to throw sticks or stones\nover one of these, my intention being to construct a rope ladder if we\ncould once succeed in getting a string across a strong bough."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Finding we could not succeed in that way, I resolved other schemes in\nmy mind, and meantime went with Jack and Fritz to a small brook close\nby, where I showed them how to place the skins to steep and soften in\nthe water, with stones placed on them to keep them beneath the surface."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When dinner was over, I prepared our night quarters. I first slung our\nhammocks from the roots of the tree, which, meeting above us, formed an\narched roof, then covering the whole with sailcloth, we made a\ntemporary tent, which would at least keep off the night damps and\nnoxious insects."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Leaving my wife engaged in making a set of harness for the ass and cow,\nwhose strength I intended to employ the following day in drawing the\nbeams up to our tree, I walked down with Fritz and Ernest to the beach\nto look for wood suitable for building our new abode and also to\ndiscover, if possible, some light rods to form a ladder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For some time we hunted in vain, nothing but rough driftwood was to be\nseen, utterly unfit for our purpose. Ernest at length pointed out a\nquantity of bamboos half buried in the sand. These were exactly what I\nwanted, and stripping them of their leaves I cut them into lengths of\nabout five feet each; these I bound in bundles to carry to the tree,\nand then began to look about for some slight reeds to serve as arrows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I presently saw what I required in a copse at a little distance. We\nadvanced cautiously lest the thicket should contain some wild beast or\nvenomous serpent. Juno rushed ahead; as she did so a flock of\nflamingos, which had been quietly feeding, rose in the air. Fritz\ninstantly firing brought a couple of the birds to the ground, the rest\nof the squadron sailing away in perfect order, their plumage\ncontinually changing, as they flew, from beautiful rose to pure white,\nas alternately their snowy wings and rosy breasts were visible."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One of those which fell was perfectly dead, but the other appeared only\nslightly wounded in the wing, for it made off across the swampy ground.\nI attempted to follow, but soon found that progress was impossible on\nthe marsh; Juno, however, chased the bird and, seizing it, speedily\nbrought it to my feet. Fritz and Ernest were delighted at the sight of\nour prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What a handsome bird!' exclaimed they. 'Is it much hurt? Let us tame\nit and let it run about with the fowls.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Its plumage is much more brilliant than that of the dead one,'\nremarked Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes,' said Ernest, 'this is a full-grown bird, while yours is\nyounger; it is some years before they reach perfection. See what long\nactive legs it has, like those of a stork, while with its great webbed\nfeet it can swim faster than a goose. Earth, air, or water is all the\nsame to the flamingo, it is equally at home in any one of the three.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well,' said Fritz, 'let us take the dead one to mother and get her to\nintroduce it to the other element and see what it will make of that; if\nit is young and tender, as you say, it should make a delicious roast.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and Ernest then carried the birds and bamboos to the tree, while\nI proceeded to cut my reeds. I chose those which had flowered, knowing\nthat they were harder, and having cut a sufficient quantity of these, I\nselected one or two of the tallest canes I could find to assist me in\nmeasuring the height of the tree. I then bound them together and\nreturned to my family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do you mean to keep this great hungry bird Fritz has brought?' said my\nwife. 'It is another mouth to feed, remember, and provisions are still\nscarce.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Luckily,' I replied, 'the flamingo will not eat grain like our\npoultry, but will be quite satisfied with insects, fish, and little\ncrabs, which it will pick up for itself. Pray reassure yourself,\ntherefore, and let me see to the poor bird's wound.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, I procured some wine and butter and anointing the wing,\nwhich though hurt was not broken, I bound it up, and then took the bird\nto the stream where I fastened it by a long cord to a stake and left it\nto shift for itself. In a few days the wound was healed, and the bird,\nsubdued by kind treatment, became rapidly tame."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While I was thus employed my sons were endeavouring to ascertain the\nheight of the lowest branch of the tree from the ground. They had\nfastened together the long reeds I had brought with them, and were\ntrying to measure the distance, but in vain; they soon found that were\nthe rods ten times their length they could not touch the branch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hello, my boys,' I said, when I discovered what they were about,\n'that is not the way to set to work. Geometry will simplify the\noperation considerably; with its help the altitude of the highest\nmountains are ascertained; we may, therefore, easily find the height of\nthat branch.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, I measured out a certain distance from the base of the tree\nand marked the spot, and then by means of a rod, whose length I knew,\nand imaginary lines, I calculated the angle subtended by the trunk of\nthe tree from the ground to the root of the branch. This done, I was\nable to discover the height required, and, to the astonishment of the\nyounger children, announced that we should henceforth live thirty feet\nabove the ground. This I wanted to know, that I might construct a\nladder of the necessary length."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Telling Fritz to collect all our cord, and the others to roll all the\ntwine into a ball, I sat down and taking the reeds, speedily\nmanufactured half a dozen arrows and feathered them from the dead\nflamingo. I then took a strong bamboo, bent it and strung it so as to\nform a bow. When the boys saw what I had done they were delighted, and\nbegged to have the pleasure of firing the first shot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, no!' said I, 'I did not make this for mere pleasure, nor is it\neven intended as a weapon, the arrows are pointless. Elizabeth,' I\ncontinued to my wife, 'can you supply me with a ball of stout thread\nfrom your wonderful bag?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Certainly,' replied she, 'I think that a ball of thread was the first\nthing to enter the bag,' and diving her hand deep in, she drew out the\nvery thing I wanted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, boys,' I said, 'I am going to fire the first shot,' and I\nfastened one end of the thread to one of my arrows and aimed at a\nlarge branch above me. The arrow flew upwards and bore the thread over\nthe branch and fell at our feet. Thus was the first step in our\nundertaking accomplished. Now for the rope ladder!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz had obtained two coils of cord each about forty feet in length;\nthese we stretched on the ground side by side; then Fritz cut the\nbamboos into pieces of two feet for the steps of the ladder, and as he\nhanded them to me, I passed them through knots which I had prepared in\nthe ropes, while Jack fixed each end with a nail driven through the\nwood. When the ladder was finished, I carried over the bough a rope by\nwhich it might be hauled up. This done, I fixed the lower end of the\nladder firmly to the ground by means of stakes, and all was ready for\nan ascent. The boys who had been watching me with intense interest were\neach eager to be first."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack shall have the honour,' said I, 'as he is the lightest, so up\nwith you, my boy, and do not break your neck.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack, who was as active as a monkey, sprang up the ladder and quickly\ngained the top."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Three cheers for the nest!' he exclaimed, waving his cap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah, hurrah, hurrah for our jolly nest! What a grand house we will\nhave up here; come along, Fritz!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His brother was soon by his side, and with a hammer and nails secured\nthe ladder yet more securely. I followed with an axe, and took a survey\nof the tree. It was admirably suited to our purpose; the branches were\nvery strong and so closely interwoven that no beams would be required\nto form a flooring, but when some of the boughs were lopped and cleared\naway, a few planks would be quite sufficient."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now called for a pulley, which my wife fastened to the cord hanging\nbeside the ladder, I hauled it up, and finding the boys rather in my\nway, told them to go down while I proceeded to fasten the pulley to a\nstout branch above me, that we might be able to haul up the beams we\nshould require the next day. I then made other preparations that there\nmight be no delay on the morrow, and a bright moon having arisen, I by\nits light continued working until I was quite worn out, and then at\nlength descended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I reached the ground, but to my surprise found that the two boys were\nnot there. They had not been seen. A moment afterwards, however, all\nanxiety was dispelled, for amongst the topmost boughs I heard their\nyoung voices raised in the evening hymn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Instead of descending, they had, while I was busy, climbed upwards, and\nhad been sitting in silent admiration of the moonlight scene, high\nabove me. They now joined us, and my wife showed me the results of her\nlabour. She had made two complete sets of harness. I congratulated her\nupon her success, and we then sat down to supper."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On a cloth spread out upon the grass were arranged a roast shoulder of\nporcupine, a delicious bowl of soup made from a piece of the same\nanimal, cheese, butter, and biscuits, forming a most tempting repast.\nHaving done this ample justice, we collected our cattle, and the\npigeons and fowls having retired to roost on the neighbouring trees,\nand on the steps of our ladder, we made up a glorious fire to keep off\nany prowling wild beasts, and ourselves lay down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The children, in spite of the novelty of the hammocks, were quickly\nasleep. In vain I tried to follow their example; a thousand anxious\nthoughts presented themselves, and as quickly as I dispelled them\nothers rose in their place. The night wore on, and I was still awake;\nthe fire burned low, and I rose and replenished it with dry fuel. Then\nagain I climbed into my hammock, and towards morning fell asleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Early next morning we were astir, and dispersed to our various\noccupations. My wife milked the goats and cow, while we gave the\nanimals their food, after which we went down to the beach, to collect\nmore wood for our building operations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To the larger beams we harnessed the cow and ass, while we ourselves\ndragged up the remainder. Fritz and I then ascended the tree, and\nfinished the preparations I had begun the night before; all useless\nboughs we lopped off, leaving a few about six feet from the floor, from\nwhich we might sling our hammocks, and others still higher, to support\na temporary roof of sailcloth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife made fast the planks to a rope passed through the block I had\nfixed to the bough above us, and by this means Fritz and I hauled them\nup. These we arranged side by side on the foundation of boughs, so as\nto form a smooth solid floor, and round this platform built a bulwark\nof planks, and then throwing the sailcloth over the higher branches, we\ndrew it down and firmly nailed it. Our house was thus enclosed on three\nsides, for behind the great trunk protected us, while the front was\nleft open to admit the fresh sea breeze which blew directly in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then hauled up our hammocks and bedding and slung them from the\nbranches we had left for that purpose. A few hours of daylight still\nremaining, we cleared the floor from leaves and chips, and then\ndescended to fashion a table and a few benches from the remainder of\nthe wood. After working like slaves all day, Fritz and I flung\nourselves on the grass, while my wife arranged supper on the table we\nhad made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come,' said she at length, 'come and taste flamingo stew, and tell me\nhow you like it. Ernest assured me that it would be much better stewed\nthan roasted, and I have been following his directions.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Laughing at the idea of Ernest turning scientific cook we sat down. The\nfowls gathered round us to pick up the crumbs, and the tame flamingo\njoined them, while Master Knips skipped about from one to the other,\nchattering and mimicking our gestures continually."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To my wife's joy, the sow appeared shortly after, and was presented\nwith all the milk that remained from the day's stock that she might be\npersuaded to return every night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For,' said my wife, 'this surplus milk is really of no use to us, as\nit will be sour before the morning in this hot climate.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are quite right,' I replied, 'but we must contrive to make it of\nuse. The next time Fritz and I return to the wreck we will bring off a\nchurn amongst the other things we require.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Must you really go again to that dreadful wreck?' said my wife\nshuddering. 'You have no idea how anxious I am when you are away\nthere.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Go we must, I am afraid,' I replied, 'but not for a day or two yet.\nCome, it is getting late. We and the chickens must go to roost.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We lit our watch fires, and, leaving the dogs on guard below, ascended\nthe ladder. Fritz, Ernest and Jack were up in a moment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Their mother followed very cautiously, for though she had originated\nthe idea of building a nest, she yet hesitated to entrust herself at\nsuch a terrific height from the ground. When she was safely landed in\nthe house, taking little Franz on my back, I let go the fastenings\nwhich secured the lower end of the ladder to the ground, and swinging\nto and fro, slowly ascended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then for the first time we stood all together in our new home. I drew\nup the ladder, and, with a greater sense of security than I had enjoyed\nsince we landed on the island, offered up our evening prayer, and\nretired for the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 4"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning all were early awake, and the children sprang about the\ntree like young monkeys."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What shall we begin to do, father?' they cried. 'What do you want us\nto do, today?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Rest, my boys,' I replied, 'rest.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Rest?' repeated they. 'Why should we rest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Six days shalt thou labour and do all that thou hast to do, but on\nthe seventh, thou shalt do no manner of work.\" This is the seventh\nday,' I replied, 'on it, therefore, let us rest.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What, is it really Sunday?' said Jack, 'How jolly! Oh, I won't do any\nwork; but I'll take a bow and arrow and shoot, and we'll climb about\nthe tree and have fun all day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is not resting,' said I, 'that is not the way you are accustomed\nto spend the Lord's day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No! But then we can't go to church here, and there is nothing else to\ndo.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We can worship here as well as at home,' said I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But there is no church, no clergyman and no organ,' said Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The leafy shade of this great tree is far more beautiful than any\nchurch,' I said, 'there will we worship our Creator. Come, boys, down\nwith you: turn our dining hall into a breakfast room.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The children, one by one, slipped down the ladder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear Elizabeth,' said I, 'this morning we will devote to the\nservice of the Lord, and by means of a parable, I will endeavor to give\nthe children some serious thought; but, without books, or the\npossibility of any of the usual Sunday occupations, we cannot keep them\nquiet the whole day; afterward, therefore I shall allow them to pursue\nany innocent recreation they choose, and in the cool of the evening we\nwill take a walk.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife entirely agreed with my proposal, and having breakfasted, the\nfamily assembled round me, as we sat in the pleasant shade on the\nfresh, soft grass."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After singing some hymns and offering heartfelt prayers to the\nAlmighty Giver of all good, I told the children I would relate to them\na parable instead of preaching a sermon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, that would be delightful! I like the parables in the Bible better\nthan anything,' said Franz. 'When can we hear you read out of the Bible\nagain, father?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, my little boy, your words reproach me,' returned I. 'While\neagerly striving to procure from the ship would feed our bodies and\nprovide for their comfort, I blush to think that I have neglected the\nBread of Life, the word of God. I shall search for a Bible on my next\nreturn to the wreck: although our own books were nearly all destroyed,\nI am pretty sure to find one.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At these words my wife arose, and fetching her magic bag, she drew from\nit a copy of the Holy Scriptures, which I thankfully received from her\nhand; and after reading aloud from its sacred pages, I spoke as\nfollows:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A Great King, ruling in power and splendor over a vast realm of light\nand love, possessed within its boundaries a desolate and unfruitful\nisland. This spot he made the object of his special care; and,\nlavishing on it all the varied resources of his might and goodness, it\nbloomed in beauty, and became the happy residence of a band of\ncolonists, who were charged not only with the cultivation and\nimprovement of the soil, but each, individually, was bound to cherish\nin his soul the spirit of love and true allegiance to his Sovereign."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While this faithful union was maintained, the colony flourished; and\nthe noblest virtues exalted and rendered happy the existence of every\nmember of the race."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That a discontented and rebellious spirit should ever have infected\nthese fortunate subjects of so loving a master, seems incredible, yet\nit was so; disobedience and pride brought misery and punishment, the\nfair prospects of the colony were blighted, the labours of the\ncolonists were unblessed, and total separation from the parent kingdom\nseemed inevitable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A message of pardonâ€”of free forgivenessâ€”was nevertheless accorded to\nthese rebels; and to all who, humbly accepting it, molded their future\nlives to the will of the Great King (now revealed in a character even\nmore gracious than before), was held out the promise of removal at last\nfrom among the ruins caused by the great rebellion, to the glory and\nundimmed splendor of the realm of Light and Blessedness.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having interested the children, I then, leaving allegory, pressed\nsimply and earnestly home to each young heart the truths I sought to\nteach; and, with a short prayer for a blessing on my words, brought the\nservice to a close."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After a thoughtful pause, we separated, and each employed himself as he\nfelt disposed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took some arrows, and endeavoured to point them with porcupine\nquills."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz came to beg me make a little bow and arrow for him to shoot\nwith, while Fritz asked my advice about the tiger-cat skin and the\ncases he was to contrive from it. Jack assisted with the arrow-making,\nand inserting a sharp spine at one end of each reed made it fast with\npack-thread, and began to wish for glue to ensure its remaining firm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, Jack! Mamma's soup is as sticky as anything!' cried Franz. 'Shall\nI run and ask for a cake of it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, no, little goose! Better look for some real glue in the\ntool-box.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There he will find glue, to be sure,' said I, 'and the soup would\nscarcely have answered your purpose. But Jack, my boy, I do not like to\nhear you ridicule your little brother's idea. Some of the most valuable\ndiscoveries have been the result of thoughts which originally appeared\nno wiser than his.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While thus directing and assisting my sons, we were surprised by\nhearing a shot just over heads; at the same moment two small birds fell\ndead at our feet, and looking up, we beheld Ernest among the branches,\nas bending his face joyfully towards us, he cried, 'Well hit! Well hit!\nA good shot, wasn't it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then slipping down the ladder, and picking up the birds, he brought\nthem to me. One was a kind of thrush, the other a small dove called the\nortolan, and esteemed a very great delicacy on account of its exquisite\nflavour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the figs on which these birds came to feed were only just beginning\nto ripen, it was probable that they would soon flock in numbers to our\ntrees; and by waiting until we could procure them in large quantities,\nwe might provide ourselves with valuable food for the rainy season, by\nplacing them, when half cooked, in casks with melted lard or butter\npoured over them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time Jack had pointed a good supply of arrows, and\nindustriously practised archery. I finished the bow and arrows for\nFranz, and expected to be left in peace; but the young man next\ndemanded a quiver, and I had to invent that also, to complete his\nequipment. It was easily done by stripping a piece of bark from a small\ntree, fitting a flat side and a bottom to it, and then a string.\nAttaching it to his shoulders, the youthful hunter filled it with\narrows and went off; looking, as his mother said, like an innocent\nlittle Cupid, bent on conquest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not long after this, we were summoned to dinner, and all right\nwillingly obeyed the call."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During the meal I interested the boys very much by proposing to decide\non suitable names for the different spots we had visited on this coast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For,' said I, 'it will become more and more troublesome to explain\nwhat we mean, unless we do so. Besides which, we shall feel much more\nat home if we can talk as people do in inhabited countries: instead of\nsaying, for instance, \"the little island at the mouth of our bay, where\nwe found the dead shark\", \"the large stream near our tent, across which\nwe made the bridge\", \"that wood where we found cocoanuts, and caught\nthe monkey\", and so on. Let us begin by naming the bay in which we\nlanded. What shall we call it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oyster Bay,' said Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, no!â€”Lobster Bay,' cried Jack, 'in memory of the old fellow who\ntook a fancy to my leg!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think,' observed his mother, 'that, in token of gratitude for our\nescape, we should call it Safety Bay.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This name met with general approbation, and was forthwith fixed upon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Other names were quickly chosen. Our first place of abode we called\nTentholm; the islet in the bay, Shark's Island; and the reedy swamp,\nFlamingo Marsh. It was some time before the serious question of a name\nfor our leafy castle could be decided. But finally it was entitled\nFalconhurst; and we then rapidly named the few remaining points:\nProspect Hill, the eminence we first ascended; Cape Disappointment,\nfrom whose rocky heights we had strained our eyes in vain search for\nour ship's company; and Jackal River, as a name for the large stream at\nour landing place, concluded our geographical nomenclature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the afternoon the boys went on with their various employments.\nFritz finished his cases, and Jack asked my assistance in carrying out\nhis plan of making a cuirass for Turk, out of the porcupine skin. After\nthoroughly cleansing the inside, we cut and fitted it round the body of\nthe patient dog; then when strings were sewn on, and it became\ntolerably dry, he was armed with this ingenious coat of mail, and a\nmost singular figure he cut!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Juno strongly objected to his friendly approaches, and got out of his\nway so fast as she could; and it was clear that he would easily put to\nflight the fiercest animal he might encounter, while protected by\narmour at once defensive and offensive. I determined to make also a\nhelmet for Jack out of the remainder of the skin, which to his infinite\ndelight I speedily did."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Amid these interesting occupations the evening drew on, and after a\npleasant walk among the sweet glades near our abode, we closed our\nSabbath day with prayer and a glad hymn of praise, retiring to rest\nwith peaceful hearts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning, I proposed an expedition to Tentholm, saying I wished to\nmake my way thither by a different route. We left the tree well armed;\nI and my three elder sons each carrying a gun and game-bag, while\nlittle Franz was equipped with his bow and quiver full of arrows. A\nmost curious party we formed: Fritz adorned with his belt of margay\nskin, and Jack, with his extraordinary headdress, looked like a couple\nof young savages."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Their mother and I walked together; she, of the whole party, being the\nonly one unarmed, carried a jar in which to get butter from Tentholm;\nwe were preceded by the dogs Turk armed most effectually with his\ncuirass of porcupine skin, and Juno keeping at a respectful distance\nfrom so formidable a companion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Master Knips fully intended to mount his charger as usual; but when he\nsaw him arrayed apparently in a new skin, he approached him carefully,\nand touching him with one paw, discovered that such a hide would make\nanything but an agreeable seat; the grimace he made was most comical,\nand chattering vociferously he bounded towards Juno, skipped on her\nback, seated himself, and soon appeared perfectly reconciled to the\nchange of steed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The flamingo saw us starting, and, having been much petted during the\nlast day or two, considered himself entitled to accompany us; for some\ntime he kept beside the children, following first one and then another\nas they explored the wood on either side; their irregular course,\nhowever, at length disgusted him, and, abandoning them, he walked\nsedately by my side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We strolled on in the cool evening air, following the course of the\nstream. The boys roamed ahead of me, intent on exploration."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently I heard a joyful shout, and saw Ernest running at full speed\ntowards me, followed by his brothers. In his hand he held a plant, and,\npanting for breath, and with sparkling eyes, he held it up to me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Potatoes! Potatoes, father,' he gasped out."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes,' said Jack, 'acres and acres of potatoes!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear Ernest,' said I, for there was no mistaking the flower and\nleaf, and the light clear-green bulbous roots, 'you have indeed made a\ndiscovery; with the potato we shall never starve.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But come and look at them,' said Jack, 'come and feast your eyes on\nthousands of potatoes.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We hurried to the spot: there, spread out before us, was a great tract\nof ground, covered with the precious plant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It would have been rather difficult,' remarked Jack, 'not to have\ndiscovered such a great field.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very likely,' replied Ernest, smiling, 'but I doubt if you would have\ndiscovered that it was a potato field.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Perhaps not,' said Jack, 'you are quite welcome, at all events, to the\nhonour of the discovery; I'll have the honour of being the first to get\na supply of them.' So saying, he dug up, with hands and knife, a number\nof plants, and filled his game-bag with the roots. The monkey followed\nhis example, and scratching away with his paws most cleverly, soon had\na heap beside him. So delighted were we with the discovery, and so\neager were we to possess a large supply of the roots, that we stopped\nnot digging until every bag, pouch and pocket was filled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some wished to return at once to Falconhurst, to cook and taste our new\nacquisition; but this I overruled, and we continued our march, heavily\nladen, but delighted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How,' said I, 'can we thank the Giver of all these blessings,\nsufficiently?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh,' said Franz, 'we can say, \"We thank thee, O Lord, for all thy\ngoodness and mercy; and bless us for Jesus Christ's sake. Amen.\"'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That would not be sufficient,' said Fritz. 'Do you think it would be\nenough just to say to father and mother: \"Thank you for all you do,\"\nand not to show that we were really thankful, by loving them and doing\nwhat we can to please them?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are quite right, Fritz,' said I; 'Franz did not say all that was\nnecessary, he should have added, \"Give me grace to do Thy will, and to\nobey Thee in all things.\"'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we thus talked, we reached the head of our streamlet, where it fell\nfrom the rocks above in a beautiful, sparkling, splashing cascade. We\ncrossed and entered the tall grass on the other side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We forced our way through with difficulty, so thick and tangled were\nthe reeds. Beyond this, the landscape was most lovely. Rich tropical\nvegetation flourished on every side: the tall stately palms, surrounded\nby luxuriant ferns; brilliant flowers and graceful creepers; the\nprickly cactus, shooting up amidst them; aloe, jasmine and\nsweet-scented vanilla; the Indian pea and, above all, the regal\npineapple*, loaded the breath of the evening breeze with their rich\nperfume. The boys were delighted with the pineapple, and so eagerly did\nthey fall to, that my wife had to caution them that there were no\ndoctors on our territory, and that if they became ill, they would have\nto cure themselves as best they might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "At this point the author seems to assume that pineapples\ngrow on trees. They do not."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This advice, however, seemed to have small effect on my sons, and\nshowing Knips what they wanted, they sent him after the ripest and best\nfruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While they were thus employed, I examined the other shrubs and bushes.\nAmong these I presently noticed one which I knew well from description\nto be the karatas."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come here, boys,' I said, 'here is something of far more value than\nyour pineapples. Do you see that plant with long pointed leaves and\nbeautiful red flower? That is the karatas. The filaments of the leaves\nmake capital thread, while the leaves themselves, bruised, form an\ninvaluable salve. The pith of this wonderful plant may be used either\nfor tinder or bait for fish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Suppose, Ernest, you had been wrecked here, how would you have made a\nfire without matches, or flint and steel?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As the savages do,' replied he, 'I would rub two pieces of wood\ntogether until they kindled.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Try it,' I said, 'but, if you please, try it when you have a whole day\nbefore you, and no other work to be done, for I am certain it would be\nnight before you accomplished the feat. But see here,' and I broke a\ndry twig from the karatas, and peeling off the bark, laid the pith upon\na stone. I struck a couple of pebbles over it, and, they emitting a\nspark, the pith caught fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were delighted with the experiment. I then drew some of the\nthreads from the leaves, and presented them to my wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But what,' said Fritz, 'is the use of all these other prickly plants,\nexcept to annoy one? Here, for instance, is a disagreeable little\ntree.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is an Indian fig,' said I. 'It grows best on dry, rocky ground;\nfor most of its nourishment is derived from the air. Its juice is used,\nI believe, medicinally, while its fruit is pleasant and wholesome.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Master Jack was off in a moment when he heard of a new delicacy, and\nattempted to gather some of the fruit, but in vain; the sharp thorns\ndefied his efforts, and with bleeding hands and rueful countenance, he\nreturned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I removed the thorns from his hands, and making a sharp wooden skewer,\nI thrust it into a fig, and quickly twisted it from its branch and\nsplit it open with a knife, still holding it upon the skewer. The rest\nfollowed my example, and we regaled ourselves upon the fruit, which we\nfound excellent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest carefully examined the fig he was eating. 'What', he exclaimed,\npresently, 'are these little red insects? They cling all over the\nfruit, and I cannot shake them off. Can they be cochineal?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He handed me the fig, and I examined it attentively."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are quite right, my boy,' I said, 'there is no doubt this is the\nreal cochineal. However, though it is worth its weight in gold to\nEuropean traders, it is of little use to us, I am afraid, unless any of\nyou care to appear in gay colours. The cochineal, you know, forms the\nmost lovely scarlet dye.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, thank you,' said Jack, 'but we will take a lot of it when we go\nhome again. Now let us find something more useful to us.' And they\nthereupon plied me incessantly with questions concerning every plant\nand shrub we passed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop, stop,' I said at length. 'The most learned naturalist would be\nmuch puzzled with many of these trees; and I, who have never seen any\nof them before, and know them merely by description, cannot pretend to\ntell you the names, or explain to you the use of one quarter of them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Discussing, however, the properties of such shrubs as I did know, we at\nlength reached Tentholm. Everything was safe, and we set to work to\ncollect what we wanted. I opened the butter cask from which my wife\nfilled her pot. Fritz saw after the ammunition, and Jack and Ernest ran\ndown to the beach to capture the geese and ducks. This they found no\neasy matter, for the birds, left so long alone, were shy, and nothing\nwould induce them to come on shore and be caught. Ernest at length hit\nupon an ingenious plan."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He took some pieces of cheese, and tied them to long strings. This bait\nhe threw into the water, and the hungry ducks instantly made a grab at\nit; then with a little skilful manoeuvring he drew them on shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While Jack and he were thus busily employed catching and tying the\nrebels together by the feet, we procured a fresh supply of salt, which\nwe packed upon Turk's back, first relieving him of his coat of mail.\nThe birds we fastened to our game-bags, and carefully closing the door\nof our tent, started homewards by the sea-shore. After a cheerful and\npleasant walk, we once more reached our woodland abode. I released the\nbirds, and, clipping their wings to prevent their leaving us,\nestablished them on the stream. Then, after a delicious supper of\npotatoes, milk and butter, we ascended our tree and turned in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having remarked a great deal of driftwood on the sands the preceding\nevening, it occurred to me that it would be well to get some of it, and\nmake a kind of sledge, so that the labour of fetching what we wanted\nfrom our stores at Tentholm might not fall so heavily on ourselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I awoke early and roused Ernest as my assistant, wishing to encourage\nhim to overcome his natural fault of indolence. After a little\nstretching and yawning, he got up cheerfully, pleased with the idea of\nan expedition while the others still slept, and we made our way to the\nbeach, taking with us the donkey, who drew a large broad bough, which I\nexpected to find useful in bringing back our load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we went along, I remarked to Ernest that I supposed he was rather\nsorry for himself, and grudged leaving his cosy hammock and pleasant\ndreams at this untimely hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father, do not laugh at my laziness! Indeed I mean to cure myself\nof it. I am very glad to go with you. I intended to shoot some more of\nthe ortolans this morning, but there will be plenty of time afterwards.\nThe boys will be shooting at them, I daresay, but I don't expect they\nwill have any great luck.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why not, pray?' inquired I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I don't believe they will know what shot to use at first, and,\nbesides, they will most likely shoot upwards at the birds and be sure\nto miss them, on account of the great height and thickness of the\nbranches and foliage.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, Ernest, you certainly possess the gifts of prudence and\nreflection, as well as observation. These are valuable; but sudden\naction is so often necessary in life, that I advise you to cultivate\nthe power of instantly perceiving and deciding what must be done in\ncases of emergency. Presence of mind is a precious quality, which,\nalthough natural in some characters, may be acquired to a certain\ndegree by all who train themselves to it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Once on the seashore, our work was quickly accomplished, for selecting\nthe wood I thought fit for my purpose, we laid it across the broad\nleafy branch, and, with some help from us, the donkey dragged a very\nfair load of it homewards, with the addition of a small chest which I\nraised from among the sand which nearly covered it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We heard the boys popping away at the birds as we drew near. They\nhastened to meet us, and inquired where we had been, looking curiously\nat the chest, which I allowed them to open, while I asked my wife to\nexcuse our 'absence without leave'; and after submitting to her gentle\nreprimand, I explained my plan for a sledge, which pleased her greatly,\nand she already imagined it loaded with her hogshead of butter, and on\nits way from Tentholm to Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The chest proved to be merely that of a common sailor, containing his\nclothes, very much wetted by the sea water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys exhibited an array of several dozen birds, and related,\nduring breakfast, the various incidents of failure and success which\nhad attended their guns. Ernest had rightly guessed the mistakes they\nwould make, but practise was making them perfect, and they seemed\ndisposed to continue their sport, when their mother, assuring them that\nshe could not use more birds than those already killed, asked if I did\nnot think some means of snaring them might be contrived, as much powder\nand shot would be expended if they fired on at this rate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Entirely agreeing with this view of the subject, I desired the lads to\nlay aside their guns for the present, and the younger ones readily\napplied themselves to making snares of the long threads drawn from the\nleaves of the karatas in a simple way I taught them, while Fritz and\nErnest gave me substantial assistance in the manufacture of the new\nsledge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were busily at work, when a tremendous disturbance among our fowls\nled us to suppose that a fox or wild cat had got into their midst. The\ncocks crowed defiantly, the hens fluttered and cackled in a state of\nthe wildest excitement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We hastened towards them, but Ernest remarking Master Knips slipping\naway, as though conscious of some misdemeanour, went to watch him, and\npresently caught him in the act of eating a new-laid egg, which he had\ncarried off and hidden among the grass and roots. Ernest found several\nothers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These were very welcome to my wife, for hitherto the hens had not\npresented us with any eggs. Hereafter she determined to imprison the\nmonkey every morning until the eggs had been collected."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soon after this, as Jack was setting the newly made snares among the\nbranches, he discovered that a pair of our own pigeons were building in\nthe tree. It was very desirable to increase our stock of these pretty\nbirds, and I cautioned the boys against shooting near our tree while\nthey had nests there, and also with regard to the snares, which were\nmeant only to entrap the wild-fig-eaters."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Although my sons were interested in setting the snares, they by no\nmeans approved of the new order to economize on ammunition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No doubt they had been discussing this hardship, for little Franz came\nto me with a brilliant proposal of his own."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Papa,' said he, 'why should not we begin to plant some powder and shot\nimmediately? It would be so much more useful than bare grain for the\nfowls.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His brothers burst into a roar of laughter, and I must confess I found\nit no easy matter to keep my countenance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come, Ernest,' said I, 'now we have had our amusement, tell the\nlittle fellow what gunpowder really is.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is not seed at all, Franz,' Ernest explained. 'Gunpowder is made of\ncharcoal, sulphur and saltpetre, mixed cleverly together; so you see it\ncannot be sown like corn, any more than shot can be planted like peas\nand beans.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My carpentering meantime went on apace. In order to shape my sledge\nwith ends properly turned up in front, I had chosen wood which had been\npart of the bow of the vessel, and was curved in the necessary way for\nmy purpose. Two pieces, perfectly similar, formed the sides of my\nsleigh, or sledge, and I simply united these strongly by fixing short\nbars across them. Then, when the ropes of the donkey's harness were\nattached to the raised points in front, the equipage was complete and\nready for use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My attention had been for some time wholly engrossed by my work, and I\nonly now observed that the mother and her little boys had been busily\nplucking above two dozen of the wild birds, and were preparing to roast\nthem, spitted in a row on a long, narrow sword blade, belonging to one\nof our ship's officers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It seemed somewhat wasteful to cook so many at once, but my wife\nexplained that she was getting them ready for the butter-cask I was\ngoing to fetch for her on the new sledge, as I had advised her to\npreserve them half-cooked, and packed in butter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Amused at her promptitude, I could do nothing less than promise to go\nfor her cask directly after dinner. For her part, she resolved in our\nabsence to have a grand wash of linen and other clothes, and she\nadvised me to arrange regular baths for all the boys in future."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Early in the afternoon Ernest and I were ready to be off. Fritz\npresented us each with a neat case of margay skin to hang at our\ngirdles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We harnessed both cow and ass to the sledge and, accompanied by Juno,\ncheerfully took our departure, choosing the way by the sands, and\nreaching Tentholm without accident or adventure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There, unharnessing the animals, we began at once to load the sledge,\nnot only with the butter-cask, but with a powder-chest, a barrel of\ncheese, and a variety of other articlesâ€”ball, shot, tools and Turk's\narmour, which had been left behind on our last visit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our work had so closely engaged our attention, that when we were ready\nto leave it and go in search of a good bathing-place, we discovered\nthat our two animals had wandered quite out of sight, having crossed\nthe bridge to reach the good pasture beyond the river."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I sent Ernest after them, and went alone to the extremity of the bay.\nIt terminated in bold and precipitous cliffs, which extended into the\ndeep water, and rose abruptly so as to form an inaccessible wall of\nrock and crag. Swampy ground, overgrown with large canes, intervened\nbetween me and these cliffs. I cut a large bundle of the reeds, and\nreturned to Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was some time before I found him, comfortably extended full length\non the ground near the tent, and sleeping as sound as a top, while the\ncow and the ass, grazing at will, were again making for the bridge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Get up, Ernest, you lazy fellow!' exclaimed I, much annoyed, 'Why\ndon't you mind your business? Look at the animals! They will be over\nthe river again!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No fear of that, father,' returned he, with the utmost composure. 'I\nhave taken a couple of boards off the bridge. They won't pass the gap.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I could not help laughing at the ingenious device by which the boy had\nspared himself all trouble; at the same time I observed that it is\nwrong to waste the precious moments in sleep when duty has to be\nperformed. I then bid him go and collect some salt, which was wanted at\nhome, while I went to bathe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On coming back, much refreshed, I again missed Ernest, and began to\nwonder whether he was still gathering salt, or whether he had lain down\nsomewhere to finish his nap, when I heard him loudly calling: 'Father,\nfather! I've caught a fish! An immense fellow he is. I can scarcely\nhold him, he drags the line so!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Hastening towards the spot, I saw the boy lying in the grass, on a\npoint of land close to the mouth of the stream, and with all his might\nkeeping hold of a rod. The line was strained to the utmost by the\nfrantic efforts of a very large fish, which was attempting to free\nitself from the hook."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I quickly took the rod from him, and giving the fish more line, led him\nby degrees into shallow water. Ernest ran in with his hatchet and\nkilled him. It proved to be a salmon of full fifteen pounds weight, and\nI was delighted to think of taking such a valuable prize to them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is capital, Ernest!' cried I. 'You have cleared yourself for once\nof the charge of laziness! Let us now carry this splendid salmon to the\nsledge. I will clean and pack it for the journey, that it may arrive in\ngood condition, while you go and take a bath in the sea.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All this being accomplished, we harnessed our beasts to the well-laden\nvehicle, and replacing the boards on the bridge, commenced the journey\nhome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We kept inland this time, and were skirting the borders of a grassy\nthicket, when Juno suddenly left us, and plunging into the bushes, with\nfierce barking hunted out, right in front of us, the most\nsingular-looking creature I ever beheld. It was taking wonderful flying\nleaps, apparently in a sitting posture, and got over the ground at an\nastonishing rate. I attempted to shoot it as it passed, but missed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, who was behind me, observed its movements very coolly, and\nseeing that the dog was puzzled, and that the animal, having paused,\nwas crouching among the grass, went cautiously nearer, fired at the\nspot he had marked, and shot it dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The extraordinary appearance of this creature surprised us very much.\nIt was as large as a sheep, its head was shaped like that of a mouse;\nits skin also was of a mouse-colour; it had long ears like a hare, and\na tail like a tiger's. The fore-paws resembled those of a squirrel, but\nthey seemed only half-grown while the hind legs were enormous, and so\nlong, that when upright on them the animal would look as if mounted on\nstilts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For some time we stood silently wondering at the remarkable creature\nbefore us. I could not recollect to have seen or heard of any such."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, father,' said Ernest at last, 'I should say this was about the\nqueerest beast to be met with anywhere. I am glad I knocked it over.\nHow they will all stare when I carry it home!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You have had a lucky day altogether, certainly,' said I, 'but I\ncannot think what this animal can be. Examine its teeth, and let us see\nto what class of mammalia it belongs. We may be led to guess at its\nname in that way.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I see four sharp incisor teeth, fatherâ€”two upper, and two under, as a\nsquirrel has.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah! Then he is a rodent. What rodents can you remember, Ernest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I do not know them all, but there are the mouse, the marmot, the\nsquirrel, the hare, the beaver, the jerboaâ€”'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The jerboa!' I exclaimed, 'The jerboa! Now we shall have it. This is\nreally very like a jerboa, only far larger. It must be a kangaroo, one\nof the class of animals which has a pouch or purse beneath the body, in\nwhich its young can take refuge. They were discovered in New Holland,\nby the great Captain Cook, and I congratulate you on being the first to\nobtain a specimen in New Switzerland!' I added, laughing, as I\nextemporised the name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The kangaroo was added to the already heavy load on our sledge, and we\nproceeded slowly, arriving late at Falconhurst, but meeting with the\nusual bright welcome. Very eager and inquisitive were the glances\nturned towards the sledge, for the load piled on it surpassed all\nexpectation: we on our part staring in equal surprise at the\nextraordinary rig of the young folks who came to meet us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One wore a long night-shirt, which, with a belt, was a convenient\nlength in front, but trailed behind in orthodox ghost fashion. Another\nhad on a very wide pair of trousers, braced up so short that each\nlittle leg looked like the clapper in a bell. The third, buttoned up in\na pea-jacket which came down to his ankles, looked for all the world\nlike a walking portmanteau."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Amid much joking and laughter, my wife explained that she had been\nwashing all day, and while their clothes were drying, the boys amused\nthemselves by dressing up in things they found while rummaging the\nsailor's chest, and had kept them on, that Ernest and I might see the\nmasquerade. It certainly amused us, but made me regret that so little\nbelonging to ourselves had been saved from the wreck, in consequence of\nwhich the children had scarcely a change of linen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Turning now to our new acquisitions, we excited great interest by\nexhibiting each in turn; the large salmon, but more especially the\nkangaroo, surprised and delighted everyone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz alone wore a look expressive of dissatisfaction, and I saw that\nhe was envious of his younger brother's success. Vexed that so noble a\nprize had fallen to Ernest's gun, instead of his own, he treated it\nrather slightingly; but I could see that he was struggling against his\njealous feelings, and he, after a while, succeeded in recovering his\ngood humour, and joined pleasantly in the conversation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What a famous day's sport you have had altogether!' said he, coming\nclose up to me. 'It will be my turn to go out with you next, will it\nnot, father? Just about here there is nothing to shoot, and I have\nfound it very dull.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Still you have been doing your duty, my dear boy; you were entrusted\nwith the care of the family, and a youth of manly character will not\ndepend for happiness on mere excitement.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the shades of night approached, we made haste to conclude the day's\nwork, by preparing the kangaroo, part for immediate use, and part for\nsalting. The animals were fed, and a plentiful allowance of salt made\nto them. Our own supper of broiled salmon and potatoes was dispatched\nwith great appetite, and we retired, with thankful hearts, to sound and\nwell-earned repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 5"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning, while the breakfast was getting ready, I attended to the\nbeautiful skin of the kangaroo, which I was anxious to preserve entire;\nand afterwards, when Fritz had prepared everything in readiness for our\ntrip to the wreck, I called Ernest and Jack in order to give them some\nparting injunctions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They, however, had disappeared directly after breakfast, and their\nmother could only guess that, as we required potatoes, they might have\ngone to fetch a supply. I desired her to reprove them, on their return,\nfor starting away without leave; but, as it appeared they had taken\nTurk, I satisfied myself that no harm was likely to befall them,\nalthough it was not without reluctance that I left my dear wife alone\nwith little Franz, cheering her with hopes of our speedy return with\nnew treasures from the wreck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Advancing steadily on our way, we crossed the bridge at Jackal River,\nwhen suddenly, to our no small astonishment, Jack and Ernest burst out\nof a hiding-place where they had lain in wait for us, and were\nenchanted with the startling effect of their unexpected appearance upon\ntheir unsuspecting father and brother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was evident that they fully believed they might now go with us to\nthe wreck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To this notion I at once put a decided stop, although I could not find\nit in my heart to scold the two merry rogues for their thoughtless\nfrolic, more especially as I particularly wished to send back a message\nto my wife. I told them they must hurry home, so as not to leave their\nmother in suspense, although, as they were already so far, they might\ncollect some salt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And I instructed them to explain that, as my work on board would take\nup a long time, she must try to bear with our absence for a night. This\nI had meant to say when we parted, but my courage had failed, knowing\nhow much she would object to such a plan, and I had resolved to return\nin the evening."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On consideration, however, of the importance of constructing a raft,\nwhich was my intention in going, and finishing it without a second\ntrip, I determined to remain on board for the night, as the boys had,\nunintentionally, given me the chance of sending a message to that\neffect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Goodbye boys, take care of yourselves! We're off,' shouted Fritz, as I\njoined him in the tub-boat, and we shoved off."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The current carried us briskly out of the bay; we were very soon\nmoored safely alongside the wreck, and scrambling up her shattered\nsides, stood on what remained of the deck, and began at once to lay our\nplans. I wanted to make a raft fit to carry on shore a great variety of\narticles far too large and heavy for our present boat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A number of empty water-casks seemed just what was required for a\nfoundation: we closed them tightly, pushed them overboard, and\narranging twelve of them side by side in rows of three, we firmly\nsecured them together by means of spars, and then proceeded to lay a\ngood substantial floor of planks, which was defended by a low bulwark.\nIn this way we soon had a first-rate raft, exactly suited to our\npurpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It would have been impossible to return to land that same evening, for\nwe were thoroughly fatigued by our labours, and had eaten only the\nlight refreshment we had brought in our wallets, scarcely desisting a\nmoment from our work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Rejoicing that we were not expected home, we now made an excellent\nsupper from the ship's provisions, and then rested for the night on\nspring mattresses, a perfect luxury to us, after our hard and narrow\nhammocks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning we actively set about loading the raft and boat: first\ncarrying off the entire contents of our own cabins; and, passing on to\nthe captain's room, we removed the furniture, as well as the doors and\nwindow-frames, with their bolts, bars and locks. We next took the\nofficers' chests, and those belonging to the carpenter and gunsmith;\nthe contents of these latter we had to remove in portions, as their\nweight was far beyond our strength."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One large chest was filled with an assortment of fancy goods, and\nreminded us of a jeweller's shop, so glittering was the display of gold\nand silver watches, snuff-boxes, buckles, studs, chains, rings and all\nmanner of trinkets; these, and a box of money, drew our attention for a\ntime; but more useful to us at present was a case of common knives and\nforks, which I was glad to find, as more suited to us than the smart\nsilver ones we had previously taken on shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To my delight we found, most carefully packed, a number of young fruit\ntrees; and we read on the tickets attached to them the names, so\npleasant to European ears, of the apple, pear, chestnut, orange,\nalmond, peach, apricot, plum, cherry and vine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cargo, which had been destined for the supply of a distant colony,\nproved, in fact, a rich and almost inexhaustible treasure to us.\nIronmongery, plumber's tools, lead, paint, grind-stones, cart wheels,\nand all that was necessary for the work of a smith's forge, spades and\nplough-shares, sacks of maize, peas, oats, and wheat, a hand-mill, and\nalso the parts of a saw-mill so carefully numbered that, were we strong\nenough, it would be easy to put it up, had been stowed away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So bewildered were we by the wealth around us that for some time we\nwere at a loss as to what to remove to the raft. It would be\nimpossible to take everything; yet the first storm would complete the\ndestruction of the ship, and we should lose all we left behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Selecting a number of the most useful articles, however, including of\ncourse the grain and the fruit trees, we gradually loaded our raft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fishing lines, reels, cordage, and a couple of harpoons were put on\nboard, as well as a mariner's compass. Fritz, recollecting our\nencounter with the shark, placed the harpoons in readiness; and amused\nme by seeming to picture himself a whaler, flourishing his harpoon in\nmost approved fashion. Early in the afternoon, both our craft were\nheavily laden, and we were ready to make for the shore. The voyage was\nbegun with considerable anxiety, as, with the raft in tow, there was\nsome danger of an accident."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But the sea being calm and the wind favourable, we found we could\nspread the sail, and our progress was very satisfactory. Presently,\nFritz asked me for the telescope, as he had observed something curious\nfloating at a distance. Then handing it back, he begged me to examine\nthe object; which I soon discovered to be a turtle asleep on the water,\nand of course unconscious of our approach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do, father, steer towards it!' exclaimed he. I accordingly did so,\nthat he might have a nearer look at the creature. Little did I suspect\nwhat was to follow. The lad's back was turned to me, and the broad sail\nwas between us, so that I could not perceive his actions; when, all of\na sudden, I experienced a shock, and the thrill as of line running\nthrough a reel. Before I had time to call out, a second shock, and the\nsensation of the boat being rapidly drawn through the water, alarmed\nme."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz, what are you about?' cried I. 'You are sending us to the\nbottom.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have him, hurrah! I have him safe!' shouted he, in eager\nexcitement. To my amazement, I perceived that he really had struck the\ntortoise with a harpoon; a rope was attached to it, and the creature\nwas running away with us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Lowering the sail and seizing my hatchet, I hastened forward, in order\nto cut the line, and cast adrift at once turtle and harpoon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father! Do wait!' pleaded the boy. 'There is no danger just yet! I\npromise to cut the line myself the instant it is necessary! Let us\ncatch this turtle if we possibly can.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear boy, the turtle will be a very dear bargain, if he upsets all\nour goods into the sea, even if he does not drown us too. For heaven's\nsake, be careful! I will wait a few minutes, but the instant there is\ndanger, cut the line.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the turtle began to make for the open sea, I hoisted the sail\nagain; and, finding the opposition too much for it, the creature again\ndirected its course landward, drawing us rapidly after it. The part of\nthe shore for which the turtle was making was considerably to the left\nof our usual landing-place. The beach there shelved very gradually, and\nat some distance from land we grounded with a sharp shock, but\nfortunately without a capsize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The turtle was evidently greatly exhausted, and no wonder, since it had\nbeen acting the part of a steam tug, and had been dragging, at full\nspeed, a couple of heavily laden vessels. Its intention was to escape\nto land; but I leaped into the water, and wading up to it, dispatched\nit with my axe. Such was its tenacity of life, however, that it did not\ncease its struggles, until I had actually severed its head from its\nbody."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we were by no means far from Falconhurst, Fritz gave notice of our\napproach by firing off his gun, as well as shouting loudly in his glee;\nand, while we were yet engaged in securing our boats and getting the\nturtle on shore, the whole family appeared in the distance hastening\neagerly towards us; and our new prize, together with the well-laden\nboat and raft, excited the liveliest interest; my wife's chief\npleasure, however, consisted in seeing us safely back, as our night's\nabsence had disturbed her, and she was horrified by the description of\nour dangerous run in the wake of the fugitive turtle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Being anxious to remove some of our goods before night, the boys ran\noff to fetch the sledge; while I, having no anchor, contrived to moor\nthe boats by means of some of the heavy blocks of iron we had brought.\nIt required our united strength to get the turtle hoisted on to the\nsledge, its weight being prodigious; we found it, indeed, with the\naddition of the sapling fruit-trees, quite a sufficient load."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then made the best of our way home, chatting merrily about our\nvarious adventures. The first thing to be done on arriving was to\nobtain some of the turtle's flesh to cook for supper. To my wife this\nappeared necessarily a work of time, as well as of difficulty; but I\nturned the beast on its back, and soon detached a portion of the meat\nfrom the breast with a hatchet, by breaking the lower shell; and I then\ndirected that it should be cooked, with a little salt, shell and all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But let me first cut away this disgusting green fat,' said my wife,\nwith a little shudder. 'See how it sticks all over the meat. No one\ncould eat anything so nasty.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Leave the fat, whatever you do!' exclaimed I. 'Why, my dear, that is\nthe very best part, and the delight of the epicures. If there be really\ntoo much, cut some off-it can be used as lard, and let the dogs make a\nsupper of the refuse.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And the handsome shell!' cried Fritz. 'I should like to make a\nwater-trough of that, to stand near the brook, and be kept always full\nof clear water. How useful it would be!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is a capital idea,' I replied, 'and we may manage it easily, if\nwe can find clay so as to make a firm foundation on which to place it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, as to clay,' said Jack, 'I have a grand lump of clay there under\nthat root.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, my lad! When did you find it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'He found a bed of clay near the river this morning,' said his mother,\n'and came home in such a mess, I had regularly to scrape his clothes\nand wash him thoroughly!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, mother, I can only tell you I should never in all my days have\nfound the clay, if I had not slipped and fallen amongst it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That I can well believe,' returned his mother, 'only, to hear your\ntalk this morning, one would have thought your discovery of clay the\nresult of very arduous search indeed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'When you have ended the question of the clay and the turtle-shell,'\nsaid Ernest, 'I should like to show you some roots I found today; they\nare getting rather dry now. They look something like radishes, although\nthe plant itself was almost a bush; but I have not ventured to taste\nthem, although our old sow was devouring them at a great rate.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In that you did wisely, my boy. Swine eat many things injurious to\nmen. Let me see your roots. How did you discover them?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I was rambling in the wood this morning, and came upon the sow, very\nbusy grubbing under a small bush, and eating something ravenously; so I\ndrove her away, and found a number of these roots, which I brought for\nyou to see.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Indeed, Ernest,' I exclaimed, after taking the roots in my hand and\nconsidering them attentively, 'I am inclined to believe that you have\nreally made a brilliant discovery! If this proves to be, as I expect,\nthe manioc root, we might lose every other eatable we possess, and yet\nnot starve. In the West Indies, cakes called cassava bread are made\nfrom it; and, already having potatoes, we shall be very independent if\nwe can succeed in preparing flour from these roots. Great care must be\ntaken in the manufacture to express the juice, otherwise the flour may\nbe injurious and even poisonous."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'If we can collect a sufficient quantity, we will attempt bread-making.\nI think I know how to set about it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Finding there was still time to make another trip with the sledge, I\nwent off with the elder boys, leaving Franz with his mother; and we all\nlooked forward with satisfaction to the prospect of the princely supper\nthey were to have ready for us, for our day's work had been none of the\nlightest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have been thinking about my turtle, father,' said Fritz, as we went\nalong, 'is not the shell very valuable? Surely beautiful combs, boxes,\nand a number of ornamental things are made of tortoise-shell, and if\nso, it seems a pity to use it for a water-trough.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Your turtle, Fritz, is only fit for eating, its shell is worthless as\nregards ornament; whereas the species whose shell is prized so much is\nunfit for food. Tortoiseshell is subjected to the action of heat, the\nouter layer peels off, leaving a beautifully marked, semi-transparent\nsurface, which is susceptible of a very high polish.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sledge quickly received its second load from the raft. Chests, four\ncart-wheels and the hand-mill were placed on it, with all manner of\nsmaller articles, and we lost no time in returning to Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife welcomed us joyfully, for she said we had been regularly\noverworked during the last two days. 'However, now you are come home to\nrest,' said she, 'and you little think what refreshment awaits you here\nin the shade. Come and see my cellar!' and she smilingly exhibited a\nsmall cask, half sunk in the ground, and well sheltered with leaves and\nbranches."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah! You wonder where this came from,' continued my wife; 'well, I\nfound it myself on the sands, today, while you were all absent; and\nfancying it was wine of some sort, I got it up here on purpose to be\nready for you. The boys are most anxious to know what sort of wine it\nwill prove to be.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the simplest method of ascertaining this, I inserted a straw at the\nvent-hole, and presently announced that in all my life I had never\nenjoyed a more delicious draught of canary sack. My wife was immensely\npleased to find that her exertions in my behalf had not been thrown\naway, and the boys pressed round me, armed with straws, and begging for\na taste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After so strongly expressing my own enjoyment of the wine, it seemed\nunreasonable to deny them this, and I let them come in turns, but was\nspeedily obliged to call a halt; for the rogues got so eager and\nexcited that I had to reprove them for their greediness, and warn them\nof the risk they ran of being intoxicated."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Supper was more to the purpose; and, as the turtle proved delicious, it\nwas heartily enjoyed, and gave us strength to haul the mattresses we\nhad brought from the ship, up into our sleeping-rooms, so that very\nrefreshing slumbers closed the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Early next morning, I got up without rousing any of the others,\nintending to pay a visit to the beach; for I had my doubts about the\nsafety of my vessels on the open shore. The dogs were delighted when I\ndescended the ladder, and bounded to meet me; the cocks crowed and\nflapped their wings; two pretty kids gambolled around; all was life and\nenergy: the ass alone seemed disinclined to begin the day, and, as I\nespecially required his services, this was unfortunate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I put his morning dreams to flight, however, and harnessed him to the\nsledge; the cow, as she had not been milked, enjoyed the privilege of\nfurther repose, and with the rest of the family, I left her dozing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My fears as to the safety of the boats were soon dispelled, for they\nwere all right; and, being in haste to return, the load I collected\nfrom their freight was but a light one, and the donkey willingly\ntrotted home with it, he, as well as I, being uncommonly ready for\nbreakfast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Approaching the tree, not a sound was to be heard, not a soul was to be\nseen, although it was broad day; and great was my good wife's surprise,\nwhen, roused by the clatter and hullabaloo I made, she started up, and\nbecame aware of the late hour!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What can have made us oversleep ourselves like this?' she exclaimed.\n'It must be the fault of those mattresses, they are delightful, but\nreally too lulling; see the children are sound asleep still.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With much stretching and many yawns, the boys at last came tumbling\ndown from the tree, rubbing their eyes and seeming but half awake;\nErnest last, as usual."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come, my boys,' said I, 'this will never do! Your beds were too\nluxurious last night, I see.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In my own opinion, however, I felt there was something else to blame\nbesides the comfortable mattresses, and I made a mental resolve that\nthe captain's fine canary should be dealt with very sparingly in\nfuture. 'So now for prayers and breakfast,' I continued, 'and then off\nto work; I must have our cargo landed in time to get the boats off with\nthe next tide.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By dint of downright hard work, we accomplished this, and I got on\nboard with Fritz as soon as they were afloat; the rest turned\nhomewards, but Jack lingered behind with such imploring looks, that I\ncould not resist taking him with me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My intention had been simply to take the vessels round to the harbour\nin Safety Bay, but the calm sea and fine weather tempted me to make\nanother trip to the wreck. It took up more time than I expected, so\nthat, when on board, we could only make a further examination of the\ncargo, collect a few portable articles and then avail ourselves of the\nsea-breeze which would fail us later in the evening."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To Jack the pleasure of hunting about in the hold, was novel and\ncharming, and very soon a tremendous rattling and clattering heralded\nhis approach with a wheelbarrow, in the highest spirits at his good\nfortune in having found such a capital thing in which to bring home\npotatoes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was followed by Fritz, whose news was still more important. He had\nfound, carefully packed and enclosed within partitions, what appeared\nto be the separate parts of a pinnace, with rigging and fittings\ncomplete, even to a couple of small brass guns. This was a great\ndiscovery, and I hastened to see if the lad was right. Indeed he was,\nbut my pleasure was qualified by a sense of the arduous task it would\nbe to put such a craft together so as to be fit for sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For the present, we had barely time to get something to eat and hurry\ninto the boat, where were collected our new acquisitions, namely, a\ncopper boiler, iron plates, tobacco-graters, two grindstones, a small\nbarrel of powder, and another of flints, two wheelbarrows besides\nJack's, which he kept under his own especial care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we drew near the shore, we were surprised to see a number of little\nfigures ranged in a row along the water's edge, and apparently gazing\nfixedly at us. They seemed to wear dark coats and white waistcoats, and\nstood quite still with their arms dropping by their sides, only every\nnow and then one would extend them gently, as though longing to embrace\nus."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah! Here at last come the pigmy inhabitants of the country to welcome\nus!' cried I, laughing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father!' exclaimed Jack, 'I hope they are Lilliputians! I once\nread in a book about them, so there must be such people you know, only\nthese look rather too large.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You must be content to give up the Lilliputians and accept penguins,\nmy dear Jack,' said I. 'We have not before seen them in such numbers,\nbut Ernest knocked one down, if you remember, soon after we landed.\nThey are excellent swimmers, but helpless on land, as they can neither\nfly nor run.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were gradually approaching the land as I spoke, and no sooner was\nthe water shallow, than out sprang Jack from his tub, and wading\nashore, took the unsuspecting birds by surprise, and with his stick\nlaid half a dozen, right and left, either stunned or dead at his feet.\nThe rest escaped into the water, dived, and disappeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As these penguins are disagreeable food, on account of their strong\noily taste, I was sorry Jack had attacked them; but going to examine\nthem when we landed, some of the fallen arose from their swoon, and\nbegan solemnly to waddle away, upon which we caught them, and tying\ntheir feet together with long grass, laid them on the sand to wait\nuntil we were ready to start."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The three wheelbarrows then each received a load, the live penguins\nseated gravely were trundled along by Jack, and away we went at a great\nrate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The unusual noise of our approach set the dogs barking furiously, but\ndiscovering us, they rushed forward with such forcible demonstrations\nof delight, that poor little Jack, who, as it was, could scarcely\nmanage his barrow, was fairly upset, penguins and all. This was too\nmuch for his patience, and it was absurd to see how he started up and\ncuffed them soundly for their boisterous behaviour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This scene, and the examination of our burdens, caused great\nmerriment: the tobacco-grater and iron plates evidently puzzling\neverybody."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I sent the boys to catch some of our geese and ducks, and bid them\nfasten a penguin to each by the leg, thinking that it was worth while\nto try to tame them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife had exerted herself in our absence to provide a good store of\npotatoes, and also of manioc root. I admired her industry, and little\nFranz said, 'Ah, father! I wonder what you will say when mother and I\ngive you some Indian corn, and melons, and pumpkins and cucumbers!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, you little chatterbox!' cried she. 'You have let out my secret! I\nwas to have the pleasure of surprising your father when my plants were\ngrowing up.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, the poor disappointed little mother!' said I. 'Never mind! I am\ncharmed to hear about it. Only do tell me, where did those seeds come\nfrom?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Out of my magic bag, of course!' replied she. 'And each time I have\ngone for potatoes, I have sown seeds in the ground which was dug up to\nget them; and I have planted potatoes also.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, you wise little woman!' I exclaimed, 'Why, you are a model\nof prudence and industry!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But,' continued she, 'I do not half like the appearance of those\ntobacco-graters you have brought. Is it possible you are going to make\nsnuff? Do, pray, let us make sure of abundance of food for our mouths,\nbefore we think of our noses!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Make your mind easy, my wife. I have not the remotest intention of\nintroducing the dirty, ridiculous habit of snuffing into your family!\nPlease to treat my graters with respect, however, because they are to\nbe the means of providing you with the first fresh bread you have seen\nthis many a long day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What possible connection can there be between bread and\ntobacco-graters? I cannot imagine what you mean, and to talk of bread\nwhere there are no ovens is only tantalizing.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, you must not expect real loaves,' said I. 'But on these flat iron\nplates I can bake flat cakes or scones, which will be excellent bread;\nI mean to try at once what I can do with Ernest's roots. And first of\nall, I want you to make me a nice strong canvas bag.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This my wife willingly undertook to do, but she evidently had not much\nfaith in my powers as a baker, and I saw her set on a good potful of\npotatoes before beginning to work, as though to make sure of a meal\nwithout depending on my bread."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Spreading a large sailcloth on the ground, I summoned my boys and set\nto work. Each took a grater and a supply of well-washed manioc root,\nand when all were seated round the clothâ€”'Once, twice, thrice! Off!'\ncried I, beginning to rub a root as hard as I could against the rough\nsurface of my grater. My example was instantly followed by the whole\nparty, amid bursts of merriment, as each remarked the funny attitude\nand odd gestures of his neighbours while vehemently rubbing, rasping,\ngrating and grinding down the roots allotted to him. No one was tempted\nby the look of the flour to stop and taste it, for in truth it looked\nmuch like wet sawdust."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Cassava bread is highly esteemed in many parts of the New World, and I\nhave even heard that some Europeans there prefer it to the wheaten\nbread of their own country. There are various species of manioc. One\nsort grows quickly, and its roots ripen in a very short time. Another\nkind is of somewhat slower growth. The roots of the third kind do not\ncome to maturity for two years. The two first are poisonous, if eaten\nraw, yet they are preferred to the last, which is harmless, because\nthey are so much more fruitful, and the flour produced is excellent, if\nthe scrapings are carefully pressed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What is the good of pressing them, father?' inquired Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is in order to express the sap, which contains the poison. The dry\npith is wholesome and nourishing. Still, I do not mean to taste my\ncakes, until I have tried their effect on our fowls and the ape.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time our supply of roots being reduced to damp powder, the\ncanvas bag was filled with it, and tying it tightly up, I attempted to\nsqueeze it, but soon found that mechanical aid was necessary in order\nto express the moisture."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My arrangements for this purpose were as follows. A strong straight\nbeam was made flat on one side, smooth planks were laid across two of\nthe lower roots of our tree; on these we placed the sack, above the\nsack another plank, and over that the long beam; one end was passed\nunder a root near the sack, the other projected far forward. And to\nthat we attached all the heaviest weights we could think of, such as an\nanvil, iron bars and masses of lead. The consequent pressure on the bag\nwas enormous, and the sap flowed from it to the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Will this stuff keep any time?' inquired my wife, who came to see how\nwe were getting on. 'Or must all this great bagful be used at once? In\nthat case we shall have to spend the whole of tomorrow in baking\ncakes.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not at all,' I replied, 'once dry, the flour in barrels will keep\nfresh a long time. We shall use a great deal of this, however, as you\nshall see.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do you think we might begin now, father?' said Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There does not seem the least moisture remaining.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Certainly,' said I. 'But I shall only make one cake today for an\nexperiment; we must see how it agrees with Master Knips and the hens\nbefore we set up a bakehouse in regular style.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took out a couple of handfuls of flour for this purpose, and with a\nstick loosened and stirred the remainder, which I intended should again\nbe pressed. While an iron plate placed over a good fire was getting\nhot, I mixed the meal with water and a little salt, kneaded it well,\nand forming a thick cake, laid it on the hot plate when, one side\npresently becoming a nice yellow brown colour, it was turned and was\nquickly baked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It smelt so delicious, that the boys quite envied the two hens and the\nmonkey, who were selected as the subjects of this interesting\nexperiment, and they silently watched them gobbling up the bits of cake\nI gave them, until Fritz turned to me, saying, 'Suppose the cake is\npoisonous, what effect will it have on the creatures? Will they be\nstupefied, or will they suffer pain?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That depends upon the nature of the poison. Some cause violent pain,\nas colchicum, hellebore, and aconite. Others produce stupefaction and\nparalysis, as opium, hemlock, and prussic acid; while others again, as\nstrychnine, are followed by violent convulsions, or, as belladonna, by\ndelirium."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The effects of course vary according to the quantity taken, and such\nremedies should be applied as will best counteract the effect of each\npoison: emetics in any case, to remove as much as possible of the\nnoxious substance, combined with oils and mucilaginous drinks to soothe\nand protect the stomach in the case of irritants; stimulants, such as\nspirits, ammonia, or strong coffee to rouse from the stupor of the\nnarcotics; and sedative drugs, which are perhaps in themselves poisons,\nto counteract the over stimulation of the nerves caused by the\nconvulsant poisons."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But now let us think no more of poisons; here is supper ready and we\nneed not be afraid to eat roast penguin and potatoes.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner said than done; we left the fowls picking up the least crumb\nthey could find of the questionable food, and assembled to enjoy our\nevening meal of roast penguin. The potatoes were as usual excellent,\nthe penguin really not so bad as I expected, although fishy in taste\nand very tough."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning every one expressed the tenderest concern as to the\nhealth of Knips and the hens; and lively pleasure was in every\ncountenance when Jack, who ran first to make the visit of inquiry,\nbrought news of their perfect good health and spirits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No time was now to be lost, and bread-baking commenced in earnest. A\nlarge fire was kindled, the plates heated, the meal made into cakes,\neach of the boys busily preparing his own, and watching the baking most\neagerly. Mistakes occurred, of course, some of the bread was burnt,\nsome not done enough; but a pile of nice tempting cakes was at length\nready, and with plenty of good milk we breakfasted right royally, and\nin high spirits at our success."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soon after, whilst feeding the poultry with the fragments of the\nrepast, I observed that the captive penguins were quite at ease among\nthem and as tame as the geese and ducks; their bonds were therefore\nloosed, and they were left as free as the other fowls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 6"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having now discovered how to provide bread for my family, my thoughts\nbegan to revert to the wreck and all the valuables yet contained within\nit. Above all, I was bent on acquiring possession of the beautiful\npinnace, and aware that our united efforts would be required to do the\nnecessary work, I began to coax and persuade my wife to let me go in\nforce with all the boys except Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She very unwillingly gave her consent at last, but not until I had\nfaithfully promised never to pass a night on board. I did so with\nreluctance, and we parted, neither feeling quite satisfied with the\narrangement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were delighted to go in so large a party, and merrily carried\nprovision-bags filled with cassava-bread and potatoes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Reaching Safety Bay without adventure, we first paid a visit to the\ngeese and ducks which inhabited the marsh there, and having fed them\nand seen they were thriving well, we buckled on each his cork-belt,\nstepped into the tub-boat, and, with the raft in tow, steered straight\nfor the wreck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When we got on board, I desired the boys to collect whatever came\nfirst to hand, and load the raft to be ready for our return at night,\nand then we made a minute inspection of the pinnace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I came to the conclusion that difficulties, well-nigh insuperable, lay\nbetween me and the safe possession of the beautiful little vessel. She\nlay in a most un-get-at-able position at the further end of the hold,\nstowed in so confined and narrow a space, that it was impossible to\nthink of fitting the parts together there. At the same time these parts\nwere so heavy, that removing them to a convenient place piece by piece\nwas equally out of the question."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I sent the boys away to amuse themselves by rummaging out anything they\nliked to carry away, and sat down quietly to consider the matter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As my eyes became used to the dim light which entered the compartment\nthrough a chink or crevice here and there, I perceived how carefully\nevery part of the pinnace was arranged and marked with numbers, so that\nif only I could bestow sufficient time on the work, and contrive space\nin which to execute it, I might reasonably hope for success."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Room! Room to work in, boys! That's what we need in the first place!'\nI cried, as my sons came to see what plan I had devised, for so great\nwas their reliance on me, that they never doubted the pinnace was to be\nours."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fetch axes, and let us break down the compartment and clear space all\nround.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To work we all went, yet evening drew near, and but little impression\nwas made on the mass of woodwork around us. We had to acknowledge that\nan immense amount of labour and perseverance would be required before\nwe could call ourselves the owners of the useful and elegant little\ncraft, which lay within this vast hulk like a fossil shell embedded in\na rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Preparations for returning to shore were hastily made, and we landed\nwithout much relish for the long walk to Falconhurst, when, to our\ngreat surprise and pleasure, we found my wife and little Franz at\nTentholm awaiting us. She had resolved to take up her quarters there\nduring the time we should be engaged on the wreck. 'In that way you\nwill live nearer your work, and I shall not quite lose sight of you!'\nsaid she, with a pleasant smile."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are a good, sensible, kind wife,' I exclaimed, delighted with her\nplan, 'and we shall work with the greater diligence, that you may\nreturn as soon as possible to your dear Falconhurst.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come and see what we have brought you, mother!' cried Fritz. 'A good\naddition to your stores, is it not?' and he and his brothers exhibited\ntwo small casks of butter, three of flour, corn, rice, and many other\narticles welcome to our careful housewife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our days were now spent in hard work on board, first cutting and\nclearing an open space round the pinnace, and then putting the parts\ntogether. We started early and returned at night, bringing each time a\nvaluable freight from the old vessel. At length, with incredible\nlabour, all was completed. The pinnace stood actually ready to be\nlaunched, but imprisoned within massive wooden walls which defied our\nstrength."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It seemed exactly as though the graceful vessel had awakened from\nsleep, and was longing to spring into the free blue sea, and spread her\nwings to the breeze. I could not bear to think that our success so far\nshould be followed by failure and disappointment. Yet no possible means\nof setting her free could I conceive, and I was almost in despair, when\nan idea occurred to me which, if I could carry it out, would effect her\nrelease without further labour or delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Without explaining my purpose, I got a large cast-iron mortar, filled\nit with gunpowder, secured a block of oak to the top, through which I\npierced a hole for the insertion of the match, and this great petard I\nso placed, that when it exploded, it should blow out the side of the\nvessel next which the pinnace lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then securing it with chains, that the recoil might do no damage, I\ntold the boys I was going ashore earlier than usual, and calmly\ndesired them to get into the boat. Then lighting a match I had\nprepared, and which would burn some time before reaching the powder, I\nhastened after them with a pounding heart, and we made for the land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We brought the raft close in shore and began to unload it; the other\nboat I did not haul up, but kept her ready to put off at a moment's\nnotice; my anxiety was unobserved by anyone, as I listened with\nstrained nerves for the expected sound. It came!â€”a flash! a mighty\nroarâ€”a grand burst of smoke!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife and children, terror-stricken, turned their eyes towards the\nsea, whence the startling noise came, and then in fear and wonder,\nlooked to me for some explanation. 'Perhaps,' said my wife, as I did\nnot speak, 'perhaps you have left a light burning near some of the\ngunpowder, and an explosion has taken place.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not at all unlikely,' replied I quietly, 'we had a fire below when we\nwere caulking the seams of the pinnace. I shall go off at once and see\nwhat has happened. Will anyone come?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys needed no second invitation, but sprang into the boat, while I\nlingered to reassure my wife by whispering a few words of explanation,\nand then joining them, we pulled for the wreck at a more rapid rate\nthan we ever had done before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No alteration had taken place in the side at which we usually boarded\nher, and we pulled round to the further side, where a marvellous sight\nawaited us. A huge rent appeared, the decks and bulwarks were torn\nopen, the water was covered with floating wreckageâ€”all seemed in\nruins; and the compartment where the pinnace rested was fully revealed\nto view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There sat the little beauty, to all appearance uninjured; and the\nboys, whose attention was taken up with the melancholy scene of ruin\nand confusion around them, were astonished to hear me shout, in\nenthusiastic delight, 'Hurrah! She is ours! The lovely pinnace is won!\nWe shall be able to launch her easily after all. Come, boys, let us see\nif she has suffered from the explosion, which has set her free.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys gazed at me for a moment, and then guessing my secret, 'You\nplanned it yourself, you clever, cunning father! Oh, that machine we\nhelped to make, was on purpose to blow it up!' cried they; and eagerly\nthey followed me into the shattered opening, where, to my intense\nsatisfaction, I found everything as I could wish and the captive in\nno way a sufferer from the violent measures I had adopted for her\ndeliverance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were deeply interested in examining the effects of the\nexplosion, and in the explanation I gave them, of the principle, and\nproper way to manage a petard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was evident that the launch could now be effected without much\ntrouble; I had been careful to place rollers beneath the keel, so that\nby means of levers and pulleys we might, with our united strength, move\nher forward towards the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A rope was attached by which to regulate the speed of the descent, and\nthen, all hands putting their shoulders to the work, the pinnace began\nto slide from the stocks, and finally slipped gently and steadily into\nthe water, where she floated as if conscious it was her native element;\nwhile we, wild with excitement, cheered and waved enthusiastically."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then only remained long enough to secure our prize carefully at the\nmost sheltered point, and went back to Tentholm, where we accounted for\nthe explosion; saying that having blown away one side of the ship, we\nshould be able to obtain the rest of its contents with a very few more\ndays' work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These days were devoted to completing the rigging, the mounting of her\ntwo little brass guns, and all necessary arrangements about the\npinnace. It was wonderful what martial ardour was awakened by the\npossession of a vessel armed with two real guns. The boys chattered\nincessantly about savages, fleets of canoes, attack, defence and final\nannihilation of the invaders."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I assured them that, brilliant as their victories would doubtless be,\nwe should have good cause to thank God if their fighting powers and\nnew-born valour were never put to the test."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The pinnace was fully equipped and ready to sail, while yet no idea of\nthe surprise we were preparing for her had dawned upon my wife, and I\npermitted the boys, who had kept the secret so well, to fire a salute\nwhen we entered the bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Casting off from the ship, and spreading the sail, our voyage began.\nThe pinnace glided swiftly through the water, I stood at the helm,\nErnest and Jack manned the guns, and Fritz gave the word of command,\n'Fire!' Bang! bang! rattled out a thrilling report, which echoed and\nre-echoed among the cliffs, followed by our shouts and hurrahs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife and her little boy rushed hastily forward from near the tent,\nand we could plainly see their alarm and astonishment; but speedily\nrecognizing us, they waved joyfully, and came quickly to the\nlanding-place to meet us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By skilful management we brought the pinnace near a projection of the\nbank, and Fritz assisted his mother to come on board, where,\nbreathless with haste and excitement, she exclaimed, 'You dear,\nhorrid, wonderful people, shall I scold you or praise you? You have\nfrightened me out of my wits! To see a beautiful little ship come\nsailing in was startling enough, for I could not conceive who might be\non board, but the report of your guns made me tremble with fearâ€”and\nhad I not recognized your voices directly after, I should have run away\nwith Franz Heaven knows where!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But have you really done all this work yourselves?' she continued,\nwhen we had been forgiven for terrifying her with our vainglorious\nsalute. 'What a charming little yacht! I should not be afraid to sail\nin this myself.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After the pinnace had been shown off, and received the admiration she\ndeserved, while our industry, skill, and perseverance met with\nboundless praise, 'Now,' said my wife, 'you must come with me, and see\nhow little Franz and I have improved our time every day of your\nabsence.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We all landed and, with great curiosity, followed my wife up the river\ntowards the cascade; where, to our astonishment, we found a garden\nneatly laid out in beds and walks; and she continued, 'We don't\nfrighten people by firing salutes in honour of our performances;\nalthough, by and by, I too shall want fire in a peaceable form. Look at\nmy beds of lettuce and cabbages, my rows of beans and peas! Think what\ndelicious dinners I shall be able to cook for you, and give me credit\nfor my diligence.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear wife!' I exclaimed. 'This is beautiful! You have done\nwonders! Did you not find the work too hard?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The ground is light and easy to dig hereabouts,' she replied. 'I have\nplanted potatoes, and cassava-roots, there is space for sugar-canes,\nand the young fruit trees, and I shall want you to contrive to irrigate\nthem, by leading water from the cascades in hollow bamboos. Up by the\nsheltering rocks I mean to have pineapples* and melons, they will look\nsplendid when they spread there. To shelter the beds of European\nvegetables from the heat of the sun, I have planted seeds of maize\nround them. The shadow of the tall plants will afford protection from\nthe burning rays. Do you think that is a good plan?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "The author now thinks pineapples grow on vines. They do not."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I do indeed; the whole arrangement is capital. Now, as sunset\napproaches, we must return to the tent for supper and rest, for both of\nwhich we are all quite ready.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The time passed in happy talk over our many new interests; everyone had\nthe pleasant sensation which attends successful labour, as well as\nexperiencing the joy of affording unexpected pleasure to others; and I\nespecially pointed out to my sons how true, genuine happiness consists\nin that, rather than in mere self-gratification."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning, my wife said: 'If you can exist on shore long enough to\nvisit Falconhurst, dear husband, I should like you to attend to the\nlittle fruit trees. I fear they have been too much neglected. I have\nwatered them occasionally, and spread earth over the roots as they lay,\nbut I could not manage to plant them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You have done far more than I could have expected, my wife,' I\nreplied, 'and provided you do not ask me to give up the sea\naltogether, I most willingly agree to your request, and will go to\nFalconhurst as soon as the raft is unloaded, and everything safely\narranged here.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Life on shore was an agreeable change for us all, and the boys went\nactively to work, so that the stores were quickly brought up to the\ntent, piled in order, and carefully covered with sailcloths, fastened\ndown by pegs all round. The pinnace, being provided with an anchor, was\nproperly moored, and her elegant appearance quite altered the look of\nour harbour, hitherto occupied only by the grotesque tub-boat, and flat\nuninteresting raft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Taking an ample supply of everything we should require at Falconhurst,\nwe were soon comfortably reestablished in that charming abode, its\npeaceful shade seeming more delightful than ever, after the heat and\nhard work we had lately undergone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Several Sundays had passed during our stay at Tentholm, and the\nwelcome Day of Rest now returned again, to be observed with heartfelt\ndevotion and grateful praise. I did not attempt too much in the form of\npreaching, as I could not have secured the attention of my hearers to\nany long-winded discourses, but they were interested in the Bible\nreading and simple instructions I drew from it, and their young voices\njoined sweetly in favorite hymns, which my wife sang from memory."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the evening, I desired my boys to let me see their dexterity in\nathletic exercises, such as running, leaping, wrestling, and climbing;\ntelling them that they must keep up the practise of these things, so as\nto grow strong active men, powerful to repel and cope with danger, as\nwell as agile and swift-footed to escape from it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No man can be really courageous and self-reliant without an inward\nconsciousness of physical power and capability."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I want to see my sons strong, both morally and physically,' said I;\n'that means, little Franz,' as the large blue eyes looked inquiringly\nup at me, 'brave to do what is good and right, and to hate evil, and\nstrong to work, hunt and provide for themselves and others, and to\nfight if necessary.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the following day, the boys seeming disposed to carry out my wishes\nby muscular exercise of all sorts, I encouraged them by saying, I meant\nto prepare a curious new weapon for them, only they must promise not to\nneglect the practise of archery: as to their guns, I had no reason to\nfear they would be laid aside."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Taking a long cord, I attached a leaden bullet to each end, and had\ninstantly to answer a storm of questions as to what this could possibly\nbe for."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is a miniature lasso,' said I. 'The Mexicans, Patagonians, and\nvarious tribes of South America, make use of this weapon in hunting,\nwith marvellous dexterity, only, having no bullets, they fasten stones\nto their ropes, which are immensely longer than this. One end is swung\nround and round the mounted hunter's head, and then cast with skill and\nprecision towards the animal he wishes to strike; immediately drawing\nit back, he can repeat the blow, and either kill or wound his prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Frequently, however, the intention is to take the animal, wild horse,\nor buffalo, or whatever it may be, alive; and in that case, the lasso\nis thrown, while riding in hot pursuit, in such a way as to make the\nstone twist many times round the neck, body or legs of the fugitive,\narresting him even in full career.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father, what a splendid contrivance! Will you try it now? There is\nthe donkey, father! Do catch the donkey.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not at all certain of my powers, I declined to practise upon a live\nsubject, but consented to make a trial of skill by aiming at the stump\nof a tree at no great distance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My success surpassed my own expectations; the stump was entwined by the\ncord in such a way as to leave no doubt whatever as to the feasibility\nof the wonderful performances I described; and I was assailed by\npetitions from the boys, each anxious to possess a lasso of his own,\nwithout a moment's delay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the manufacture was simple, their wishes were speedily gratified,\nand lasso-practise became the order of the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, who was the most active and adroit, besides having, of course,\nthe greatest muscular strength, soon became skilled in the art."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "That night a change came over the weather, and early next morning I\nperceived that a gale of wind was getting up. From the height of our\ntrees I could see that the surface of the sea was in violent agitation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was with no small satisfaction that I thought of our hard-won\npinnace, safely moored in the harbour, and recollected that there was\nnothing to call us to the wreck for the next few days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My attention was by no means monopolized by my sons and their\namusements. The good mother had much to show me demanding my approval,\nadvice, or assistance, as the case might be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A good supply of wild pigeons and ortolans had been snared, partly\ncooked and preserved in lard. Of these she showed me her small cask\nwell filled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then the nests of various pairs of tame pigeons were exhibited, but her\nchief care was the unpromising condition of her dear little fruit\ntrees, for, having been forgotten, they were so dry and withered, that\nunless planted without further delay, she feared we should lose them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This needful work we set about, therefore, at once, proposing\nafterwards an excursion to the Calabash Wood, in order to manufacture a\nlarge supply of vessels and utensils of all sorts and sizes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every one was inclined for this expedition; consequently the planting\nof the orchard was carried on with surprising vigour, but was not\ncompleted until towards evening; and then all sorts of arrangements\nwere made for an early start next day. My wife and Franz were to be of\nthe party, and their equipment took some time, for we meant to make a\ngrand family excursion attended by our domestic pets and servants!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By sunrise we were all astir, and everything quickly made ready for a\nstart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sledge loaded with ammunition and baskets of provisions, and drawn\nby the donkey, was to be used for carrying home our gourd\nmanufactures, as well as any other prize we might fall in with."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Turk, as usual, headed the procession, clad in his coat of mail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then came the boys with their guns and game-bags. Their mother and I\nfollowed, and behind trotted Juno not in very good spirits, poor\ndog!â€”because Master Knips, who had no idea of being left alone, must\nneeds ride on her back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On this occasion I took two guns with me, one loaded with shot for\ngame, another with ball for our defence against beasts of prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Flamingo Marsh was quickly crossed, and the magnificent country beyond\nlay extended in all its beauty and fertility before our eyes. It was\nnew to my wife and two of the boys, and the lovely prospect enchanted\nthem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Here Fritz and Jack turned aside into the bush, where presently loud\nbarking was followed by the quick report of a gun, and a large bird,\nwhich had risen from the thicket, fell heavily to the ground before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Far from resigning itself, however, to death or captivity, it sprang to\nits feet, and, unable to fly, rushed away with extraordinary speed,\nhotly pursued by the excited dog, while Fritz ran panting in the same\ndirection, and Juno, eager to join the chase, sprang aside so suddenly,\nthat her rider was flung unceremoniously on the sand, as she darted to\nintercept the retreat of the active bird. This she cleverly\naccomplished, but its defence was maintained so fiercely, as it struck\nout with its powerful legs and sharp claws, that neither Fritz nor the\ndogs could master it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I hastened to their assistance, and found Juno holding on nobly by the\nwing she had seized, while the bird, which proved to be a magnificent\nbustard, struggled and fought fiercely. Watching my opportunity, I\nthrew a large handkerchief over it, and with difficulty succeeded in\nbinding its legs and wings. It was borne in triumph to the rest of our\nparty, who meantime had been reclining on the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What have you got?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What has Fritz shot?' cried the boys, starting up at our approach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A bustard! Oh, that is splendid!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To be sure, it is the one we missed that day, don't you remember,\nmother? Ah, ha! Old fellow, you are done for this time!' said Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think this is a hen bustard, it is the mother bird,' said Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, yes, poor thing!' exclaimed my wife, in a tone of concern. 'It is\nmost likely the same, and I know she had a brood of young birds, and\nnow they will be left unprotected and miserable. Had we not better let\nher go?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, my dear, kind-hearted wife, that was weeks and weeks ago! Those\nlittle birds are all strong and big by this time, and I daresay Mrs.\nBustard here has forgotten all about them. Besides, she is badly\nwounded, and we must try to cure the hurt. If we succeed, she will be a\nvaluable addition to our poultry-yard; if we cannot, you shall roast\nher for dinner.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Resuming our march, we next arrived at the Monkey Grove, which was the\nscene of the tragicomic adventure by which Fritz became the guardian of\nthe orphan ape."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While he amused us all by a lively and graphic description of the\nscene, Ernest was standing apart under a splendid cocoanut palm,\ngazing in fixed admiration at the grand height of the stem, and its\nbeautiful graceful crown of leaves. The cluster of nuts beneath these\nevidently added interest to the spectacle, for, drawing quietly near\nhim, I heard a long-drawn sigh, and the words:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It's awfully high! I wish one would fall down!' Scarcely had he\nuttered these words, than, as if by magic, down plumped a huge nut at\nhis feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boy was quite startled, and sprang aside, looking timidly upwards,\nwhen, to my surprise, down came another."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, this is just like the fairy tale of the wishing-cap!' cried\nErnest. 'My wish is granted as soon as formed!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I suspect the fairy in this instance is more anxious to pelt us and\ndrive us away, than to bestow dainty gifts upon us,' said I. 'I think\nthere is most likely a cross-grained old ape sitting up among those\nshadowy leaves and branches.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We examined the nuts, thinking they were perhaps old ones, and had\nfallen, in consequence, naturally, but they were not even quite ripe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Anxious to discover what was in the tree, we all surrounded it, gaping\nand gazing upwards with curious eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hollo! I see him!' shouted Fritz presently. 'Oh, a hideous creature!\nWhat can it be? Flat, round, as big as a plate, and with a pair of\nhorrid claws! Here he comes! He is going to creep down the tree!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At this, little Franz slipped behind his mother, Ernest took a glance\nround to mark a place of retreat, Jack raised the butt-end of his gun,\nand every eye was fixed on the trunk of the tree, down which a large\nland-crab commenced a leisurely descent. As it approached within reach,\nJack hit at it boldly, when it suddenly dropped the remaining distance,\nand opening its great claws, sidled after him with considerable\nrapidity, upon which he fairly turned tail and ran."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We all burst into a roar of laughter, which soon made him face about,\nand then, to our infinite amusement, the little fellow prepared for a\nfresh onset; laying down all he was carrying, pulling off his jacket\nand spreading it wide out in both hands, he returned to the charge,\nsuddenly threw his garment over the creature, wrapped it well round it,\nand then pummelled it with all the strength of his fists."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For a few minutes I could do nothing but laugh, but then running to him\nwith my hatchet, I struck several sharp blows on his bundle, which we\nopened carefully, and found within the land-crab perfectly dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, this is an ugly rascal!' cried Jack. 'If he hadn't been so\nhideous, I should not have dealt so severely with him. I wasn't a bit\nafraid. What is the creature's name?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is a crab, a land-crab,' said I, 'of which there are many\nvarieties, and this, I think, is called a cocoanut crab, or at least it\ndeserves the name, for it is evidently very fond of eating these nuts,\nsince it takes the trouble to climb the trees for them; the difficulty\nof getting at the kernel, too, is considerable. You showed no little\npresence of mind, Jack, when you thought of catching it in your jacket;\nin fact it might have been more than a match for you otherwise, for\nsome are most determined fighters, and are very swift too. Now let us\ntake it, as well as the nuts, to the sledge, and go on our way.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Progress became difficult, for we were constantly stopped in passing\nthrough the wood, by having to cut away the hanging boughs and creeping\nplants which interlaced them. Ernest was behind, and by and by called\nme back to see what proved to be an important discovery; from the\nseveral stalks of one of these creepers flowed clear cold water, and I\nrecognized the 'liane rouge', which is known in America, and is so\nprecious to the thirsty hunter or traveller."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This is truly one of God's good gifts to man! The boys were much\ndelighted with this curious plant. 'Only fancy, mother,' said Ernest,\nas he showed it to her, 'how cheering and refreshing to find this if\none were lost and alone in a vast forest, wandering for days and days\nwithout being near a proper spring of water.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But are you certain it is safe to drink this?' asked she. I assured\nher it was so, and advised the boys to cut enough to quench the thirst\nof the whole party, including our animals. This they did, only finding\nit necessary, as with the sugar canes, to cut air holes above the\njoints."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After struggling onward for a short time, we emerged from the thickets\ninto open ground, and saw the calabash trees in the distance. As we\ndrew near, their curious appearance and singular fruit caused much\nsurprise and also amusement, for we were speedily established among the\ntrees, where, as I chose and cut down the gourds most likely to be\nuseful, every one engaged merrily in the work of cutting, carving,\nsawing and scooping some manner of dish, bowl, cup, jar or platter,\naccording to his several taste or ability."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were to dine here, and after a time Fritz and Jack began to prepare\na fireplace, their great ambition being to heat the stones red hot, and\ncook the crab in a hollow gourd. Their mother, therefore, left them to\ntheir own devices, and attended to the hungry animals, unharnessing the\nass to graze, and giving cocoanut milk to the poor little monkey, who\nhad been obliged to travel in a covered basket for some time, lest he\nshould be lost in the woods. The wounded bustard had been completely\nforgotten, and from heat and thirst was suffering greatly until her\nfriendly care revived it, and it was tied to a tree and allowed to move\nabout, its fierce spirit greatly tamed by adversity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cooking operations came to a stand soon after the fire was\nlighted, for it appeared that we had no more water in the jars we had\nbrought, so the boys proposed to go in search of a spring. I agreed to\naccompany them; Ernest also wished to join us, and as our intention was\nto examine merely the surrounding wood, I saw no objection to leaving\ntheir mother and Franz for a short time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Very soon after our exploration began, Ernest, who was in front,\nturned with a face of terror, shouting, 'A wild boar! An immense wild\nboar, father! Do come quick!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And, sure enough, I heard a loud snorting and puffing as some large\nanimal passed hastily through the thick underwood beyond us. 'After\nhim, lads, after him!' cried I, hurrying forwards. 'Call the dogs!\nStand ready to fire!' And we pressed through the bushes to the spot\nwhere Ernest had seen the creature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ground was grubbed up, and some potatoes lay about, showing that we\nhad disturbed him at his mid-day meal. Ernest and Jack were more\ndisposed to gather the roots than to follow up the chase. Fritz and I\nalone went after the dogs, who eagerly pushed on, and by the sounds we\nheard had evidently attacked the boar at no great distance. Terrific\nbarking, snarling and grunting, guided us to the scene of action, and\nwe beheld our mastiffs one on each side of a large respectable-looking\npig, holding on by the great ears, while the animal, on seeing us,\nappeared rather to beseech our interference than to propose to offer a\ndesperate resistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a moment the truth became apparent! The captive grunter was no\nfierce native of the forest, but our own runaway sow! Our excitement\nhad been wound to so high a pitch, that the discovery was quite a\nshock, and we felt half angry with the creature who had disappointed\nus; then the absurdity of the whole thing made us laugh heartily, and\ncalling off the dogs, the old lady was released from her ignominious\nposition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our laughter resounding through the wood, brought Ernest and Jack from\ntheir potatoes, to see what was going on."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Much use you two would have been suppose we had required help,' cried\nFritz, as they too recognized their old friend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah, well, you see,' returned Jack, 'Ernest and I had a sort of a kind\nof presentiment that this was going to be the old sow. And just look at\nour fine potatoes!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A good deal of joking on the subject ensued, but was interrupted by\nErnest, who drew our attention to fruit resembling apples on the\nsurrounding bushes, and on the grass beneath them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sow was making amends for the fright and pain she had endured by\nmunching and crunching this fruit at a great rate. Fritz feared that it\nmight be the poisonous manchineel, against which I once warned them,\nbut on examining it, I was induced to pronounce a more favourable\nopinion, and we collected a quantity in hopes that, if the monkey\napproved of it as well as the old sow, we might be able to enjoy a\nfeast ourselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All this time not a drop of water had we seen, and our own thirst\nincreasing, we felt eager to procure some before returning to our\nresting-place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack preceded us, and we made our way towards a high rock, which rose\nabove the thickets, when he suddenly startled us by a loud cry of 'A\ncrocodile! Father! Father! A crocodile!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Nonsense, boy! A crocodile of all things, in this dry, parched\nforest, where we can't get so much as a mouthful of water!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On advancing to where Jack stood, I perceived that his mistake was not\nso very silly after all, for I beheld an iguana, one of the largest of\nthe lizard species, and a truly formidable-looking fellow. I was glad\nto assure Jack that the strange creature he had found was perfectly\nharmless, and that its flesh being esteemed a delicacy, it would be a\nvaluable prize to carry back with us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In another moment Fritz would have fired, but arresting his\nhandâ€”'Your shot,' I said, 'would probably only wound the animal, and\nbeing extremely tenacious of life, it would certainly escape us; we\nmust gain possession of the sleeping beauty by a gentler method.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are not going to kiss it, are you, father?' asked Jack, with a\ngrin. I tried to rebuke him for his impertinence, but, failing, I\ncommenced operations. I first attached a cord and running-noose to a\nstout stick, and holding a light switch in my other hand, I began to\napproach the creature with soft, slow steps, while the boys looked on\nwith the utmost curiosity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently I began very softly to whistle a sweet, yet very lively air,\nwhich I continued more and more distinctly as I drew near the lizard;\nuntil, awaking, it seemed to listen with pleasureâ€”raising its head as\nthough better to catch the sounds, or to discover whence they came."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When near enough, I began gently to stroke and tickle him with the\nwand, continuing to whistle the prettiest tunes I could think of; and\nthe lizard gave signs of pleasurable contentment, stretching his limbs\nand moving his tail in token of enjoyment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Suddenly, availing myself of a movement of his head, I cast the noose\nover it, drew the cord tight and, placing my foot on the body, I was\nabout to kill it by piercing the nostrilâ€”almost the only vulnerable\npart in this singular reptileâ€”when Jack received such a slap from its\ntail, which it was furiously driving in all directions, as sent him\nrolling over like a nine-pin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the same time he opened his jaws, when the boys took fright at the\nrow of sharp teeth, and thinking that the sooner he was dead the\nbetter, were for battering him with sticks; but I assuring them my\nmethod would kill him more quickly and without pain, thrust my rod into\nhis nostril, on which the blood flowed and the lizard soon expired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys seemed to think me as wonderful a person as a snake-charmer,\nand the success of my stratagem, as well as of the means by which the\nlizard was slain, called forth great admiration, since they never had\nheard of the animal, nor of the method of capturing it so commonly\npractised in the West Indies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Now came the question of how we were to carry this unwieldy burden. I\nhad a great dislike to killing any creature and leaving it useless\nbehind me; so, without more ado, I fairly took it on my back, and\nmarched off with it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we came towards the Calabash Wood, we could hear the voices of the\ndeserted mother and child calling us in anxious tones; for indeed our\nprotracted absence alarmed them. We shouted joyously in reply, and our\nappearance, as we issued from the woods, afforded them welcome relief\nfrom their fears, although the dreadful creature on my back startled\nthem not a little."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There was so much to tell, so much to be seen, that for a time hunger\nand thirst were forgotten; and no one thought even of the water we had\nvainly gone in search of, until Master Knips, having slyly possessed\nhimself of some of our new-found apples, was discovered munching away\nand enjoying them amazinglyâ€”which instantly gave the boys a strong\nwish to eat some also; and as the bustard likewise pecked at them\nwithout hesitation, I felt sure there could be no danger; and on\ntasting them, I concluded it was the fruit of the guava, a West Indian\nplant, which we were delighted to have."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Although refreshing, this fruit rather sharpened than appeased our\nappetites, and we were glad to eat the provisions we had brought from\nhome, without waiting to cook anything, as we had originally intended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was, in fact, high time to move homewards, and we thought it best\nnot to encumber ourselves with the sledge and the greater part of its\nload, but to leave it until the next day. The ass was laden with the\niguana and the bustard; and little Franz, tired as he was, looked in\nvain for a spare seat on its back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our road home lay through a majestic forest of oak trees, beneath\nwhich lay numberless acorns, some of which we gathered as we went\nalong; and at length, before night closed in, we all reached\nFalconhurst in safety. When supper was ready, we were thankful to\nrecruit our exhausted strength by eating heartily of a piece of\nbroiled iguana, with potatoes and roast acorns, which tasted like\nexcellent chestnuts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 7"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The first thing to be done on the following day was to return to the\nCalabash Wood, to fetch the sledge with the dishes, bowls and baskets\nwe had made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz alone accompanied me. I desired the other boys to remain with\ntheir mother, intending to explore beyond the chain of rocky hills, and\nthinking a large party undesirable on the occasion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Passing through the wood of evergreen oaks, we observed our sow\nfeasting on the acorns, evidently not a whit the worse for the fright\nwe had given her the previous dayâ€”in fact, she appeared more friendly\ndisposed towards us than usual, possibly considering us as her\ndeliverers from the jaws of the savage dogs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many birds tenanted this grove, and were undisturbed by our movements,\nuntil Fritz fired and shot a beautiful blue jay, and a couple of\nparakeets, one a brilliant scarlet, the other green and gold. Fritz was\nin the act of reloading his gun, when an unaccountable noise struck our\nears, and put us instantly on the alert, because it appeared like the\ndull thumping sound of a muffled drum, and reminded us of the possible\npresence of savages."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With the greatest caution we drew nearer the sound, concealing\nourselves among the low bushes and thick grass and creepers, until we\nreached an open glade; where, standing on an old prostrate log, was a\nbeautiful bird, about the size of a cock, of a rich chestnut brown\ncolour, finely mottled with dark brown and grey. On the shoulders were\ncurious tufts of velvety black feathers, glossed with green. He was\nruffling his wings, erecting his tail and neck feathers, strutting and\nwheeling about in a most strange and stately fashion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After manoeuvring for some time in this manner, greatly to the\nedification of a party of birds resembling him but without any ruff,\nwho, assembled round the stump, were enjoying his performances, he\nspread out his tail like a fan, stiffened his wings, and began to\nstrike with them in short, rapid beats, faster and faster, until a\nrumbling sound like very distant thunder was produced, and the whirring\nwings enveloped him as in a cloud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This was the drumming noise which had alarmed us, increased, as I\nimagine, by the wing strokes falling at times on the decayed and\nhollow stump on which the curious pantomime was acted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was watching it with the utmost interest, when a shot from behind me\nwas fired, and in a moment the play was at an end; my over-hasty son\nhad changed the pretty comedy into a sad and needless tragedy. The\nenthusiastic drummer fell dead from his perch, and the crowd of\nadmiring companions fled in dismay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cruel interruption of a scene so rare and remarkable annoyed me\nextremely, and I blamed Fritz for firing without my leave. I felt sure\nthe bird was the ruffed grouse, and a very fine specimen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We placed it on the ass, which was patiently awaiting our return, and\nwent on our way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sledge was quite safe where we had left it; it was early in the\nday, and I resolved to explore, as I had intended, the line of cliff\nand rocky hills, which, at more or less distance from the seashore,\nextended the whole length of coast known or visible to us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I desired to discover an opening, if any existed, by which to\npenetrate the interior of the country, or to ascertain positively that\nwe were walled in and isolated on this portion of the coast. Leaving\nCalabash Wood behind us, we advanced over ground covered with manioc,\npotatoes and many plants unknown to us; pleasant streamlets watered the\nfruitful soil, and the view on all sides was open and agreeable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some bushes attracted my notice, loaded with small white berries, of\npeculiar appearance like wax, and very sticky when plucked. I\nrecognized in this a plant called by botanists Myrica cerifera, and\nwith much pleasure explained to Fritz that, by melting and straining\nthese berries, we might easily succeed in making candles, and afford\nvery great satisfaction to his mother, who did not at all approve of\nhaving to lay her work aside and retire to rest the moment the sun set."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The greenish wax to be obtained would be more brittle than bees' wax,\nbut it would burn very fairly, and diffuse an agreeable perfume. Having\nthe ass with us, we lost no time in gathering berries enough to fill\none of the large canvas bags he carried, and we then continued our\nroute."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Very soon we met with another natural curiosity, the curious\nappearance of which surprised us much. This was the abode, under one\nroof, of a whole colony of birds, about the size of yellowhammers, but\nof plain brown plumage. The nests were built in a mass round the stem\nand among the branches of a tree standing alone, and a kind of roof\nformed of grass, straws and fibres covered them all, and sheltered the\ncommunity from rain and the heat of the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There were numbers of openings into the irregular sides of the group of\ndwellings, the nests resembling different apartments in a house common\nto all; twigs and small branches emerged here and there from the walls,\nand served as perches for the young birds, and resting-places and posts\nof observation for all. The general appearance of the establishment\nreminded us of a huge bath-sponge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The feathered inhabitants swarmed in and out by thousands, and we saw\namong them many beautiful little parrots, who seemed in many instances\nto contest possession of the nest with the lawful owners."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, being an expert climber and exceedingly anxious to examine the\nnests more closely, ascended the tree, hoping to obtain one or two\nyoung birds, if any were hatched. He put his hand into several holes,\nwhich were empty; but at last his intended theft and robbery met with\nrepulse and chastisement he little expected; for, reaching far back\ninto a nest, his finger was seized and sharply bitten by a very strong\nbeak, so that with a cry he withdrew his hand, and shook it vigorously\nto lessen the pain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Recovering from the surprise, he again and more resolutely seized the\nunkind bird, and, despite its shrieks and screams, drew it from its\nretreat, crammed it into his pocket, buttoned up his coat and slid\nquickly to the ground, pursued by numbers of the captive's relations,\nwho darted from the other holes and flew round the robber, screeching\nand pecking at him in a rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz's prize was not one of the real owners of the nests, which were\nthose of the sociable grosbeak, but a very pretty, small, green parrot,\nwith which he was greatly pleased, and which he at once determined to\ntame and teach to speak; for the present, it was carefully remanded to\nprison in his pocket."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This curious colony of birds afforded us matter of conversation as we\nwent on our way; their cheerful sociable habits, and the instinct which\nprompted them to unite in labour for the common good, appearing most\nwonderful to us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Examples of the kind, however,' said I, 'are numerous, in various\nclasses of animals. Beavers, for instance, build and live together in a\nvery remarkable way. Among insects, bees, wasps, and ants are well\nknown as social architects; in like manner, the coral insect works\nwonders beneath the ocean waves, by force of perseverance and united\neffort.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have often watched ants at work,' said Fritz; 'it is most amusing to\nsee how they carry on the various works and duties of their\ncommonwealth.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Have you ever noticed how much trouble they take with the eggs?'\ninquired I, to see how far he understood the process; 'carrying them\nabout in the warmth of the sun until they are hatched?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ah! That is rather the chrysalis of the antworm, or larva, which is\nproduced from an egg. I know they are called ants' eggs, but strictly\nspeaking, that is incorrect.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are perfectly right, my boy. Well, if you have taken so much\ninterest in watching the little ants of your native country, how\ndelighted and astonished you would be to see the wonders performed by\nthe vast tribes of large ants in foreign lands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Some of these build heaps or nests, four or six feet high and\nproportionately broad, which are so strong and firm that they defy\nequally sunshine and rain. They are, within, divided into regular\nstreets, galleries, vaults, and nurseries. So firmly are these mounds\nbuilt, that with interior alterations, a deserted one might be used for\na baking-oven."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The ant, although respected since the days of King Solomon as a model\nof industry, is not in itself an attractive insect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It exudes a sticky moisture, its smell is unpleasant, and it destroys\nand devours whatever eatable comes in its way. Although in our own\ncountry it does little harm, the large ants of foreign lands are most\ndestructive and troublesome; it being very difficult to check their\ndepredations. Fortunately they have enemies by whose exertions their\nnumbers are kept down; birds, other insects, and even four-footed\nbeasts prey upon them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Chief among the latter is the ant-eater, or tamanoir, of South\nAmerica, a large creature six or seven feet in length, covered with\nlong coarse hair, drooping like a heavy plume over the hind quarters.\nThe head is wonderfully elongated and very narrow; it is destitute of\nteeth, and the tongue resembles somewhat a large great red earth-worm.\nIt has immensely strong curved claws, with which it tears and breaks\ndown and scratches to pieces the hard walls of the ant-heaps; then,\nprotruding its sticky tongue, it coils and twists it about among the\nterrified millions disturbed by its attack; they adhere to this\nhorrible invader, and are drawn irresistibly backward into the hungry,\ntoothless jaws awaiting them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The little ant-eater is not more than about twenty-one inches in\nlength, has a shorter and more natural looking head, and fine silky\nfur. It usually lives in trees.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was pleased to find my memory served me so well on this subject, as\nit interested my boy amazingly; and occupied us for a considerable time\nwhile we traveled onward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Arriving presently at a grove of tall trees, with very strong, broad,\nthick leaves, we paused to examine them; they bore a round fig-like\nfruit, full of little seeds and of a sour harsh taste."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz saw some gummy resin exuding from cracks in the bark, and it\nreminded him of the boyish delight afforded by collecting gum from\ncherry-trees at home, so that he must needs stop to scrape off as much\nas he could. He rejoined me presently, attempting to soften what he had\ncollected in his hands; but finding it would not work like gum, he was\nabout to fling it away, when he suddenly found that he could stretch\nit, and that it sprang back to its original size."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh father, only look! This gum is quite elastic! Can it possibly be\nindia-rubber?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What!' cried I, 'Let me see it! A valuable discovery that would be,\nindeed; and I do believe you are perfectly right!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why would it be so very valuable, father?' inquired Fritz. 'I have\nonly seen it used for rubbing out pencil marks.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'India-rubber,' I replied, 'or, more properly, caoutchouc, is a milky\nresinous juice which flows from certain trees in considerable\nquantities when the stem is purposely tapped."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These trees are indigenous to the South American countries of Brazil,\nGuiana, and Cayenne. The natives, who first obtained it, used it to\nform bottles by smearing earthen flasks with repeated coatings of the\ngum when just fresh from the trees, and when hardened and sufficiently\nthick, they broke the mold, shook out the fragments, and hung the\nbottles in the smoke, when they became firmer, and of a dark color."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While moist, the savages were in the habit of drawing rude figures and\nlines on the resin by way of adornment; these marks you may have\nobserved, for the bottles obtained from the natives by the Spaniards\nand Portuguese have for years been brought to Europe, and cut into\nportions to be sold for use in drawing. Caoutchouc can be put to many\nuses, and I am delighted to have it here, as we shall, I hope, be able\nto make it into different forms; first and foremost, I shall try to\nmanufacture boots and shoes.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soon after making this discovery, we reached the cocoanut wood, and saw\nthe bay extending before us, and the great promontory we called Cape\nDisappointment, which hitherto had always bounded our excursions. In\npassing through the wood, I remarked a smaller sort of palm, which,\namong its grand companions, I had not previously noticed. One of these\nhad been broken by the wind, and I saw that the pith had a peculiar\nmealy appearance, and I felt convinced that this was the world-renowned\nsago-palm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the pith I saw some fat worms or maggots, and suddenly recollected\nthat I had heard of them before as feeding on the sago, and that in the\nWest Indies they are eaten as a delicacy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I felt inclined to try what they tasted like; so at once kindling a\nfire, and placing some half dozen, sprinkled with salt, on a little\nwooden spit, I set them to roast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Very soon rich fat began to drop from them, and they smelt so\ntemptingly good, that all repugnance to the idea of eating worms\nvanished; and, putting one like a pat of butter on a baked potato, I\nboldly swallowed it, and liked it so much, that several others followed\nin the same way. Fritz also summoned courage to partake of this novel\nfood; which was a savoury addition to our dinner of baked potatoes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Being once more ready to start, we found so dense a thicket in the\ndirect route, that we turned aside without attempting to penetrate it,\nand made our way towards the sugar-brake near Cape Disappointment. This\nwe could not pass without cutting a handsome bundle of sugar-canes, and\nthe donkey carried that, in addition to the bag of wax berries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In time we reached the sledge in Calabash Wood: the ass was unloaded,\neverything placed on the sledge, and our patient beast began calmly and\nreadily to drag the burden he had hitherto borne on his back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No further adventure befell us, and we arrived in the evening at\nFalconhurst, where our welcome was as warm as usualâ€”all we had to\ntell, listened to with the greatest interest, all we had to show, most\neagerly examined, the pretty green parakeet enchanting the boys most\nparticularly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "An excellent supper was ready for us, and with thankful hearts we\nenjoyed it together; then, ascending to our tree-castle, and drawing up\nthe ladder after us, we betook ourselves to the repose well earned and\ngreatly needed after this fatiguing day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The idea of candle-making seemed to have taken the fancy of all the\nboys; and next morning they woke, one after the other, with the word\ncandle on their lips. When they were thoroughly roused they continued\nto talk candles; all breakfast-time, candles were the subject of\nconversation; and after breakfast they would hear of nothing else but\nsetting to work at once and making candles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'So be it,' said I, 'let us become chandlers.' I spoke confidently,\nbut, to tell the truth, I had in my own mind certain misgivings as to\nthe result of our experiment. In the first place, I knew that we lacked\na very important ingredientâ€”animal fat, which is necessary to make\ncandles burn for any length of time with brilliancy. Besides this, I\nrather doubted how far my memory would recall the various operations\nnecessary in the manufacture."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Of all this, however, I said nothing; and the boys, under my\ndirection, were soon at work. We first picked off the berries and\nthrew them into a large shallow iron vessel placed on the fire. The\ngreen sweet-scented wax was rapidly melted, rising to the surface of\nthe juice yielded by the berries. This we skimmed off and placed in a\nseparate pot by the fire, ready for use, repeating the operation\nseveral times, until we had collected sufficient liquid wax for our\npurpose. I then took the wicks my wife had prepared, and dipped them\none after the other into the wax, handing them as I did so to Fritz,\nwho hung them up on a bush to dry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The coating they thus obtained, was not very thick; but, by repeating\nthe operation several times, they at length assumed very fair\nproportions, and became real sturdy candles. Our wax being at an end,\nwe hung these in a cool shady place to harden; and that same night we\nsat up like civilized beings three whole hours after sunset, and\nFalconhurst was for the first time brilliantly illuminated."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were all delighted with the success of our experiment. 'You are\nindeed clever,' said my wife, 'I only wish that with your ingenuity you\nwould show me how to make butter. Day after day, I have the annoyance\nof seeing a large supply of good cream go bad under my very eyes,\nsimply because I have no use to which to put it. Invent a plan, please\ndo.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think that perhaps I can help you,' I replied after a little\nconsideration, 'not that I can claim the honour of the invention of my\nplan, that is due to the Hottentots. I will see what I can do. Jack,\nbring me one of our gourd bottles.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took the gourd, one of those I had previously prepared, with a small\nhole at one end and well hollowed-out and cleaned; this I partially\nfilled with cream and then corked up the hole tightly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here, boys,' said I, 'you can continue the operation while I turn\ncarpenter and make a cart to take the place of our sledge.' I gave them\ntheir directions, and then set about my own work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They fixed four posts in the ground, and to them fastened a square\npiece of sailcloth by four cords attached to the corners. In this\ncradle they placed the gourd of cream, and each taking a side, rolled\nit backwards and forwards continuously for half an hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now,' I cried, looking up from my work, 'open the gourd and take the\ncontents to your mother, with my compliments.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They did so; and my good wife's eyes were delighted with the sight of a\nlarge lump of capital fresh butter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With my son's assistance the cart was in time completed; a clumsy\nvehicle it was, but strong enough for any purpose to which we might put\nit, and, as it proved, of immense use to us in collecting the harvest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then turned our attention to our fruit trees, which we had planted\nin a plot ready for transplanting. The walnut, cherry, and chestnut\ntrees we arranged in parallel rows so as to form a shady avenue from\nFalconhurst to Family-bridge; and between them we laid down a tolerable\nroad, that we might have no difficulty in reaching Tentholm, be the\nweather bad as it might."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We planted the vines round the arched roots of our great mangrove, and\nthe rest of the trees in suitable spots; some near Falconhurst, and\nothers away over Jackal river, to adorn Tentholm. Tentholm had been the\nsubject of serious thoughts to me for some time past, and I now turned\nall my attention thither. It was not my ambition to make it beautiful,\nbut to form of it a safe place of refuge in a case of emergency."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My first care, therefore, was to plant a thick prickly hedge, capable\nof protecting us from any wild animal, and forming a tolerable obstacle\nto the attack of even savages, should they appear. Not satisfied with\nthis, however, we fortified the bridge, and on a couple of hillocks\nmounted two guns which we brought from the wreck, and with whose angry\nmouths we might bark defiance at any enemy, man or beast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Six weeks slipped away while we were thus busily occupied, six weeks of\nhard yet pleasant labour. We greeted each Sunday and its accompanying\nrest most gratefully, and on that day always especially thanked God for\nour continued health and safety."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I soon saw that this hard work was developing in the boys remarkable\nstrength, and this I encouraged by making them practise running,\nleaping, climbing, and swimming; I also saw, however, that it was\nhaving a less satisfactory effect upon their clothes, which, though a\nshort time before remarkably neat, were now, in spite of mending and\npatching, most untidy and disreputable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I determined, therefore, to pay another visit to the wreck, to\nreplenish our wardrobe and to see how much longer the vessel was\nlikely to hold together. Three of the boys and I went off in the\npinnace. The old ship seemed in much the same condition as when we had\nleft her, a few more planks had gone, but that was all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come, boys,' cried I, 'not an article of the slightest value must be\nleft on board; rummage her out to the very bottom of her hold.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They took me at my word: sailors' chests, bales of cloth and linen, a\ncouple of small guns, ball and shot, tables, benches, window shutters,\nbolts and locks, barrels of pitch, all were soon in a heap on the deck.\nWe loaded the pinnace and went on shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We soon returned with our tub-boat in tow, and after a few more trips\nnothing was left on board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'One more trip,' said I to my wife, before we started again, 'and\nthere will be the end of the brave ship which carried us from\nSwitzerland. I have left two barrels of gunpowder on board, and mean to\nblow her up.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before we lighted the fuse, I discovered a large copper cauldron which\nI thought I might save. I made fast to it a couple of empty casks, that\nwhen the ship went up it might float. The barrels were placed, the\ntrain lighted, and we returned on shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The supper was laid outside the tent, at a spot from whence we might\nobtain a good view of the wreck. Darkness came on. Suddenly a vivid\npillar of fire rose from the black waters, a sullen roar boomed across\nthe sea, and we knew that our good old ship was no more."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had planned the destruction of the vessel, we knew that it was for\nthe best; and yet that night we went to bed with a feeling of sadness\nin our hearts, as though we had lost a dear old friend."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning all our sadness was dispelled, and it was with pleasure\nthat we saw the shore lined with a rich store of planks and beams, the\nremnants of the wreck. I soon found, too, the copper cauldron which was\nsuccessfully floated by the casks; this I got on shore, and hauling it\nup among the rocks, stored under it the powder casks we had landed the\nday before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Collecting all these valuables gave us some little trouble, and while\nwe were thus engaged my wife brought us good news. She had discovered\nthat two ducks and a goose had each reared a large family among the\nreeds by the river; and they presently appeared waddling past us,\napparently vastly well-pleased with their performance. We greeted them\njoyfully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah!' cried Ernest. 'We'll be able to afford duck and green peas\nsome day soon, and imagine we're once more civilized mortals.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sight of these birds reminded me of our family at Falconhurst, and\nI announced my intention of paying them a visit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone was delighted, and everyone would come with me. As we\napproached Falconhurst I noticed that several young trees in our\navenue were considerably bent by the wind, and this resolved me to make\nan expedition next day to cut bamboos for their support."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As Fritz was the only one besides myself who had visited Cape\nDisappointment and the surrounding country, my wife and the younger\nboys begged hard to be allowed to accompany me. I consented; and next\nmorning we started, bringing with us the cart, drawn by the cow and\nass, and laden with everything necessary for an expedition of several\ndaysâ€”a tent, provisions, a large supply of ammunition, and all sorts\nof implements and utensils; for I intended to make a great collection\nof fruits and the produce of different trees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was a lovely morning, and passing gaily through the plantations of\npotatoes, manioc and cassavas, we came to the nests of the sociable\ngrosbeak, the sight of which charmed the children immensely."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We reached the wax trees, and there I called a halt, for I wished to\ngather a sack or two of the berries that we might renew our stock of\ncandles. The berries were soon plucked; and I stored them away amongst\nthe bushes, marking the spot that we might find them on our return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now for the caoutchouc tree,' said I, 'now for waterproof boots and\nleggings to keep your feet dry, Ernest.' To the caoutchouc tree we\ndirected our steps, and were soon busily engaged in stabbing the bark\nand placing vessels beneath to catch the sap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We again moved forward; and, crossing the palm wood, entered upon a\ndelightful plain bounded on one side by an extensive field of waving\nsugar-cane, on the other by a thicket of bamboos and lovely palms,\nwhile in front stretched the shining sea, calm and noiseless."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How beautiful!' exclaimed Jack. 'Let us pitch our tent here and stay\nhere always instead of living at Falconhurst. It would be jolly.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very likely,' replied I, 'and so would be the attacks of wild beasts;\nimagine a great tiger lying in wait in the thicket yonder, and pouncing\nout on us at night. No, no, thank you, I much prefer our nest in the\ntree, or our impregnable position at Tentholm. We must make this our\nheadquarters for the present, however; for, though perhaps dangerous,\nit is the most convenient spot we shall find. Call a halt and pitch the\ntent.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our beasts were quickly unyoked, the tent arranged, a large fire lit,\nsupper prepared, and we dispersed in various directions, some to cut\nbamboos, and some to collect sugar-cane. We then returned; and, as\nsupper was still not quite ready and the boys were hungry, they decided\nto obtain some cocoanuts. This time, however, no assistance was to be\nhad from either monkeys or land-crabs, and they gazed up with longing\neyes at the fruit above them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We can climb,' said Fritz, 'up with you, boys.' Jack and he each\nrushed at one of the smooth slippery trunks; right vigorously they\nstruggled upwards, but to no purpose; before they had accomplished one\nquarter of the distance they found themselves slipping rapidly to the\nground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here, you young athletes,' cried I, 'I foresaw this difficulty, and\nhave provided for it.' So saying I held up buskins of shark's skin\nwhich I had previously prepared, and which I now bound on to their\nlegs. Thus equipped they again attempted the ascent, and with a loop of\nrope passed round their body and the trunk of the tree, quickly reached\nthe summit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife joined me, and together we watched the boys as they ascended\ntree after tree, throwing down the best fruit from each. They then\nreturned, and jestingly begged Ernest to produce the result of his\nlabour. The professor had been lying on the grass gazing at the palms;\nbut, on this sarcastic remark, he sprang to his feet. 'Willingly,' he\nexclaimed, and seizing a pair of buskins he quickly donned them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Give me a cocoanut shell,' said he. I gave him one, and he put it in\nhis pocket. He ran to a tree, and, with an agility which surprised us\nall, quickly reached the top."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner had he done so than Fritz and Jack burst into a roar of\nlaughter. He had swarmed a tree which bore no nuts. Ernest apparently\nheard them; for, as it seemed in a fit of anger, he drew his knife and\nsevered the leafy crest, which fell to the ground. I glanced up at him,\nsurprised at such a display of temper. But a bright smile greeted me,\nand in a merry tone he shouted:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack, pick that palm-cabbage up and take it to father; that is only\nhalf my contribution, and it is worth all your nuts put together.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He spoke truly: the cabbage-palm is rare, and the tuft of leaves at its\nsummit is greatly prized by the South Americans for its great delicacy\nand highly nutritive qualities."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Bravo!' I cried. 'You have retrieved your character; come down and\nreceive the thanks of the company, what are you waiting up there for?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am coming presently,' he replied, 'with the second half of my\ncontribution; I hope it will be as fully appreciated as the first.' In\na short time he slipped down the tree, and, advancing to his mother,\npresented her with the nutshell he had taken up with him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here,' he said, 'is a wine which the greatest connoisseur would\nprize. Taste it, mother.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The shell was filled with a clear rosy liquor, bright and sparkling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife tasted it. 'Excellent, excellent,' she exclaimed. 'Your very\ngood health, my dear boy!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We drank the rosy wine in turn, and Ernest received hearty thanks from\nall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was getting late, and while we were enjoying our supper before our\ntent, our donkey, who had been quietly browsing near us, suddenly set\nup a loud bray, and, without the least apparent cause, pricked up his\nears, threw up his heels, and galloped off into the thicket of bamboos.\nWe followed for a short distance, and I sent the dogs in chase, but\nthey returned without our friend, and, as it was late, we were obliged\nto abandon the chase."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was annoyed by this incident, and even alarmed; for not only had we\nlost the ass, but I knew not what had occasioned his sudden flight. I\nknew not whether he was aware, by instinct, of the approach of some\nfierce wild beast. I said nothing of this to my family, but, making up\nan unusually large fire, I bade them sleep with their weapons by their\nsides, and we all lay down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A bright morning awoke us early, and I rose and looked out, thinking\nthat perhaps our poor donkey might have been attracted by the light of\nthe fires, and have returned. Alas, not a sign of him was to be seen.\nAs we could not afford to lose so valuable a beast, I determined to\nleave no attempt untried to regain him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We hurriedly breakfasted, and, as I required the dogs to assist me in\nthe search, I left my elder sons to protect their mother, and bade Jack\nget ready for a day's march. This arrangement delighted him, and we\nquickly set out."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For an hour or more we trudged onwards, directed by the print of the\nass's hoofs. Sometimes we lost the track for a while, and then again\ndiscovered it as we reached softer soil. Finally this guide failed us\naltogether, for the donkey seemed to have joined in with a herd of some\nlarger animals, with whose hoof-prints his had mingled."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now almost turned back in despair, but Jack urged me to continue the\nsearch. 'For,' said he, 'if we once get upon a hill we shall see such a\nlarge herd as this must be at almost any distance. Do let us go on,\nfather.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I consented, and we again pushed forwards, through bushes, and over\ntorrents, sometimes cutting our way with an axe, and sometimes plunging\nknee-deep through a swamp. We at length reached the border of a wide\nplain, and on it, in the distance, I could see a herd of animals,\nbrowsing on the rich grass. It struck me that it might be the very herd\nto which our good donkey had joined himself; and, wishing to ascertain\nwhether this was so, I resolved to make a detour through a bamboo\nmarsh, and get as near as possible to the animals without disturbing\nthem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bamboos were huge, many of them over thirty feet in height; and, as\nwe made our way through them, I remembered an account of the giant cane\nof South America, which is greatly prized by the Indians on account of\nits extreme usefulness; the reeds themselves make masts for their\ncanoes, while each joint will form a cask or box."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was delighted, for I had little doubt that the bamboos we were among\nwere of the same species. I explained this to Jack, and as we discussed\nthe possibility of cutting one down and carrying a portion of it home,\nwe reached the border of the marsh, and emerged upon the plain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There we suddenly found ourselves face to face with the herd which we\nsoughtâ€”a herd of buffaloes. They looked up, and stared at us\ninquisitively, but without moving. Jack would have fired, but I checked\nhim. 'Back to the thicket,' I said, 'and keep back the dogs!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We began to retreat, but before we were again under cover, the dogs\njoined us; and, in spite of our shouts and efforts to restrain them,\nthey dashed forwards, and seized a buffalo calf."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This was a signal to the whole herd to attack us. They bellowed\nloudly, pawed the ground, and tore it up with their horns, and then\ndashed madly towards us. We had not time to step behind a rock before\nthe leader was upon us. So close was he that my gun was useless. I drew\na pistol and fired. He fell dead at my feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His fall checked the advance of the rest. They halted, snuffed the air,\nturned tail and galloped off across the plain. They were gone, but the\ndogs still held gallantly to the calf. They dragged and tussled with\nhim, but with their utmost efforts could not bring him to the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "How to assist them without shooting the poor beast, I knew not; and\nthis I was unwilling to do, for I hoped that, if we could but capture\nhim alive, we might in time manage to tame him, and use him as a beast\nof burden. Jack's clever little head, however, suddenly devised a plan\nfor their aid, and with his usual promptitude he at once put it into\nexecution."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He unwound the lasso, which was coiled round his body, and, as the\nyoung bull flung up his heels, he cast it and caught him by his hind\nlegs. The noose drew tight, and in a twinkling the beast was upon the\nground. We fastened the other end of the cord round a stout bamboo,\ncalled off the dogs, and the animal was at our mercy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now we have got him,' said Jack, as he looked at the poor beast,\nlying panting on the ground, 'what are we to do with him?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I will show you,' said I; 'help me to fasten his forelegs together,\nand you shall see the next operation.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bull, thus secured, could not move; and while Jack held his head I\ndrew my knife and pierced the cartilage of his nose, and when the blood\nflowed less freely, passed a stout cord through the hole. I felt some\nrepugnance at thus paining the animal, but it was a case of necessity,\nand I could not hesitate. We united the ends of the cord, freed the\nanimal, set him upon his legs, and subdued and overawed, he followed us\nwithout resistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now turned my attention to the dead buffalo, but as I could not then\nskin it, I contented myself with cutting off the most delicate parts,\nits tongue, and a couple of steaks, and, packing them in salt in my\nwallet, abandoned the rest to the dogs. They fell upon it greedily, and\nwe retired under the shade to enjoy a meal after our hard work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs, however, were not to have undisputed possession of the\ncarcase; vultures, crows and other birds of prey, with that marvellous\ninstinct which always leads them to a dead body, quickly filled the\nair, and, with discordant cries, swooped down upon the buffalo. An\namusing contest ensued; the dogs again and again drove off the\nintruders, and they, as often, returned reinforced by others who\nswarmed to the spot. Jack, with his usual impetuosity, wished to send a\nshot in amongst the robber band, but I prevented him, for I knew that\nthe bird or two he might kill would be of no use to us, while his shot\nwould not drive away the rest, even had we wished it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Both we and the dogs were at length satisfied, and as it was getting\nlate, I determined to give up for the present the search for the ass,\nand to return to our camp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We again made our way through the bamboos, but before we left the\nthicket, I cut down one of the smallest of the reeds, the largest of\nwhose joints would form capital little barrels, while those near the\ntapering top would serve as moulds for our next batch of candles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The buffalo, with a dog on either side and the rope through his nose,\nwas following us passively, and we presently induced him to submit to a\npackage of our goods laid upon his back. We pushed rapidly forward,\nJack eager to display our latest acquisition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we repassed the rocky bed of a stream we had crossed in the\nmorning, Juno dashed ahead, and was about to rush into a cleft between\nthe rocks, when the appearance of a large jackal suddenly checked her\nfurther progress. Both dogs instantly flew at the animal, and though\nshe fought desperately, quickly overpowered and throttled her. From the\nway the beast had shown fight, I concluded that her young must be close\nby, probably within the very cleft Juno was about to enter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Directly Jack heard this, he wished to creep in and bring out the\nyoung jackals. I hesitated to allow him to do so, for I thought it\npossible that the male jackal might be still lying in wait within the\ncave. We peered into the darkness, and after a while, Jack declared he\ncould discern the little yellow jackals, and that he was quite sure the\nold one was not there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He then crept in, followed closely by the dogs, and presently emerged\nbearing in his arms a handsome cub of a beautiful golden yellow and\nabout the size of a small cat. He was the only one of the brood he had\nmanaged to save, for Turk and Juno, without pity for their youth or\nbeauty, had worried all the rest. I did not much regret this, however,\nfor I firmly believe that, had he saved them, Jack would have insisted\nupon bringing up the whole litter. As it was I considered that one\njackal was, with our young bull, quite sufficient an addition to our\nlivestock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During the halt we had made, I had fastened the buffalo to a small\ntree, and as I now was again about to move on, I recognized it as the\ndwarf-palm, whose long sharp leaves form an excellent barrier if it is\nplanted as a hedge. I determined to return and get some young plants to\nstrengthen our hedge at Tentholm. It was late before we reached our\ncamp, where we found our family anxiously awaiting our return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sight of the new animals delighted the children immensely, and in\ntheir opinion amply compensated for the loss of our poor donkey. Jack\nhad to answer a host of questions concerning their capture, and to give\na minute account of the affray with the buffaloes. This he did, with\ngraphic power certainly, but with so much boasting and\nself-glorification, that I was obliged to check him, and give a plain\nand unvarnished account of the affair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Supper-time arrived, and as we sat at that meal, for which Jack and I\nwere heartily thankful, my wife and her party proceeded to give an\naccount of their day's work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest had discovered a sago-palm, and had, after much labour,\ncontrived to fell it. Franz and his mother had collected dry wood, of\nwhich a huge heap now stood before the tent sufficient to keep up a\nfire all the rest of the time we should stay on the spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz had gone off shooting and had secured a good bag. While they had\nbeen thus variously employed, a troop of apes had visited the tent, and\nwhen they returned, they found the place ransacked and turned upside\ndown. The provisions were eaten and gnawed, the potatoes thrown about,\nthe milk drunk and spilt, every box had been peeped into, every pot and\npan had been divested of its lid, the palisade round the hut had been\npartly destroyed, nothing had been left untouched."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Industriously had the boys worked to repair the damage, and when we\nreturned not a sign was to be seen of the disorder. No one would have\nguessed what had occurred from the delicious supper we were eating."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After matters had been again arranged, Fritz had gone down to the\nshore and, amongst the rocks at Cape Disappointment, had discovered a\nyoung eaglet which Ernest declared to be a Malabar or Indian eagle; he\nwas much pleased with his discovery, and I recommended him to bring the\nbird up and try to train it to hunt as a falcon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Look here though, boys,' said I, 'you are now collecting a good many\npets, and I am not going to have your mother troubled with the care of\nthem all; each must look after his own, and if I find one neglected,\nwhether beast or bird, I set it at liberty. Mark that and remember it!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife looked greatly relieved at this announcement, and the boys\npromised to obey my directions. Before we retired for the night I\nprepared the buffalo-meat I had brought; I lit a large fire of green\nwood, and in the smoke of this thoroughly dried both the tongue and\nsteaks. We then properly secured all the animals, Jack took his little\npet in his arms, and we lay down and were soon fast asleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At daybreak we were on foot, and began to prepare for a return to\nFalconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are not going to despise my sago, I hope,' said Ernest, 'you have\nno idea what a trouble it was to cut it down, and I have been thinking\ntoo that if we could but split the tree, we might make a couple of long\nuseful troughs which might, I think, be made to carry water from Jackal\nRiver to Tentholm. Is my plan worth consideration?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Indeed it is,' I replied, 'and at all events we must not abandon such\na valuable prize as a sago-palm. I would put off our departure for a\nday, rather than leave it behind.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We went to the palm, and with the tools we had with us attempted to\nsplit the trunk. We first sawed off the upper end, and then with an axe\nand saw managed to insert a wedge. This accomplished, our task was less\ndifficult, for with a heavy mallet we forced the wedge in further and\nfurther, until at length the trunk was split in twain. From one half of\nthe trunk we then removed the pith, disengaging it, with difficulty,\nfrom the tough wood fibres; at each end, however, I left a portion of\nthe pith untouched, thus forming a trough in which to work the sago."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, boys,' said I, when we had removed the pith from the other half\nof the trunk, 'off with your coats and turn up your shirt-sleeves; I am\ngoing to teach you to knead.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were all delighted, and even little Franz begged to be allowed to\nhelp. Ernest brought a couple of pitchers of water, and throwing it in\namongst the pith, we set to work right heartily. As the dough was\nformed and properly kneaded, I handed it to my wife who spread it out\non a cloth in the sun to dry. This new occupation kept us busy until\nthe evening, and when it was at length completed we loaded the cart\nwith the sago, a store of cocoanuts and our other possessions, that we\nmight be ready to start early on the following morning."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the sun rose above the horizon, we packed up our tent and set\nforth, a goodly caravan. I thought it unfair to the cow to make her\ndrag such a load as we now had alone, and determined if possible to\nmake the young buffalo take the place of our lost donkey; after some\npersuasion he consented, and soon put his strength to the work and\nbrought the cart along famously. As we had the trough slung under the\ncart we had to choose the clearest possible route, avoiding anything\nlike a thicket; we, therefore, could not pass directly by the\ncandleberry and caoutchouc trees, and I sent Ernest and Jack aside to\nvisit the store we had made on our outward journey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They had not long been gone when I was alarmed by a most terrible\nnoise accompanied by the furious barking of the dog and shouts from\nJack and Ernest. Thinking that the boys had been attacked by some wild\nbeast, I ran to their assistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A most ludicrous scene awaited me when I reached the spot. They were\ndancing and shouting round and round a grassy glade, and I as nearly as\npossible followed their example, for in the centre, surrounded by a\npromising litter, lay our old sow, whose squeals, previously so\nalarming, were now subsiding into comfortable grunts of recognition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I did not join my boys in their triumphal dance, but I was\nnevertheless very much pleased at the sight of the flourishing family,\nand immediately returned to the cart to obtain biscuits and potatoes\nfor the benefit of the happy mother. Jack and Ernest meanwhile pushed\nfurther on, and brought back the sack of candleberries and the\ncaoutchouc, and as we could not then take the sow with us, we left her\nalone with her family and proceeded to Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The animals were delighted to see us back again, and received us with\nmanifestations of joy, but looked askance at the new pets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The eagle especially came in for shy glances, and promised to be no\nfavourite. Fritz, however, determined that his pet should at present do\nno harm, secured him by the leg to a root of the fig-tree and uncovered\nhis eyes. In a moment the aspect of the bird was changed; with his\nsight returned all his savage instincts, he flapped his wings, raised\nhis head, darted to the full length of his chain, and before anyone\ncould prevent him seized the unfortunate parrot which stood near, and\ntore it to pieces. Fritz's anger rose at the sight, and he was about to\nput an end to the savage bird."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop,' said Ernest, 'don't kill the poor creature, he is but\nfollowing his natural instincts; give him to me, and I will tame him.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz hesitated. 'No, no,' he said, 'I don't want really to kill the\nbird, but I can't give him up; tell me how to tame him, and you shall\nhave Master Knips.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very well,' replied Ernest, 'I will tell you my plan, and, if it\nsucceeds, I will accept Knips as a mark of your gratitude. Take a pipe\nand tobacco, and send the smoke all round his head, so that he must\ninhale it; by degrees he will become stupefied, and his savage nature\nfrom that moment subdued.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was rather inclined to ridicule the plan, but knowing that\nErnest generally had a good reason for anything of the sort that he\nproposed, he consented to make the attempt. He soon seated himself\nbeneath the bird, who still struggled furiously, and puffed cloud after\ncloud upwards, and as each cloud circled round the eagle's head he\nbecame quieter and quieter, until he sat quite still, gazing stupidly\nat the young smoker."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Capital!' cried Fritz, as he hooded the bird, 'capital, Ernest; Knips\nis yours.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 8"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning the boys and I started with the cart laden with our\nbundles of bamboos to attend to the avenue of fruit trees. The buffalo\nwe left behind, for his services were not needed, and I wished the\nwound in his nostrils to become completely cicatrized before I again\nput him to work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were not a moment too soon; many of the young trees which before\nthreatened to fall had now fulfilled their promise, and were lying\nprostrate on the ground, others were bent, some few only remained\nerect. We raised the trees, and digging deeply at their roots, drove in\nstout bamboo props, to which we lashed them firmly with strong broad\nfibres."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Papa,' said Franz, as we were thus engaged, and he handed me the\nfibres as I required them, 'are these wild or tame trees?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, these are wild trees, most ferocious trees,' laughed Jack, 'and we\nare tying them up lest they should run away, and in a little while we\nwill untie them and they will trot about after us and give us fruit\nwherever we go. Oh, we will tame them; they shall have a ring through\ntheir noses like the buffalo!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That's not true,' replied Franz, gravely, 'but there are wild and tame\ntrees, the wild ones grow out in the woods like the crab-apples, and\nthe tame ones in the garden like the pears and peaches at home. Which\nare these, papa?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'They are not wild,' I replied, 'but grafted or cultivated or, as you\ncall them, tame trees. No European tree bears good fruit until it is\ngrafted!' I saw a puzzled look come over the little boy's face as he\nheard this new word, and I hastened to explain it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Grafting,' I continued, 'is the process of inserting a slip or twig of\na tree into what is called an eye; that is, a knot or hole in the\nbranch of another. This twig or slip then grows and produces, not such\nfruit as the original stock would have borne, but such as the tree from\nwhich it was taken would have produced. Thus, if we have a sour crab\ntree, and an apple tree bearing fine ribston pippins, we would take a\nslip of the latter, insert it in an eye of the former, and in a year or\ntwo the branch which it would then grow would be laden with good\napples.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But,' asked Ernest, 'where did the slips of good fruit come from, if\nnone grow without grafting?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'From foreign countries,' I replied. 'It is only in the cold climate of\nour part of the world that they require this grafting; in many parts of\nthe world, in more southern latitudes than ours, the most luscious\nfruit trees are indigenous to the soil, and flourish and bear sweet,\nwholesome fruit, without the slightest care of attention being bestowed\nupon them; while in England and Germany, and even in France, these same\ntrees require the utmost exertion of horticultural skills to make them\nbring forth any fruit whatever."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Thus, when the Romans invaded England they found nothing in the way of\nfruit trees but the crab-apple, nut bushes, and bramble bushes, but by\ngrafting on these, fine apples, filberts, and raspberries were\nproduced, and it was the same in our own dear Switzerlandâ€”all our\nfruit trees were imported.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Were cherries, father? May we not even call cherries Swiss? I always\nthought they grew nowhere else.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am afraid we cannot even claim cherries as our own, not even the\nname of them; they are called cherries from Cerasus, a state of Pontus,\nin Asia, whence they were brought to Europe by Lucullus, a Roman\ngeneral, about seventy years before Christ."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hazelnuts also come from Pontus; walnuts, again, came originally from\nPersia. As for grapes, they are of the greatest antiquity. We hear, if\nyou remember, of Noah cultivating vines, and they have been brought\nfrom one place to another until they now are to be found in most parts\nof the civilized world.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do you think all these trees will grow?' asked Fritz, as we crossed\nJackal River and entered our plantation at Tentholm. 'Here are lemons,\npomegranates, pistachio nuts, and mulberries.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have little doubt of it,' I replied, 'we are evidently within the\ntropics, where such trees as these are sure to flourish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These pines, now, come from France, Spain, and Italy; the olives from\nArmenia and Palestine; the figs originally from the island of Chios;\nthe preaches and apricots from Persia; plums from Damascus in Syria,\nand the pears of all sorts from Greece."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'However, if our countries have not been blessed in the same way with\nfruit, we have been given wisdom and skill, which has enabled us to\nimport and cultivate the trees of other lands.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We thus talked and worked until every tree that required the treatment\nwas provided with a stout bamboo prop, and then, with appetites which a\ngourmand might well have envied, we returned to Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I think my good wife was almost alarmed at the way we fell upon the\ncorned beef and palm-cabbage she set before us, but at length these\ngood things produced the desired effect, and one after another declared\nhimself satisfied. As we sat reclining after our labour and digesting\nour dinner we discussed the various projects we had in contemplation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I wish,' said my wife, 'that you would invent some other plan for\nclimbing to the nest above us; I think that the nest itself is perfect,\nI really wish for nothing better, but I should like to be able to get\nto it without scaling that dreadful ladder every time; could you not\nmake a flight of steps to reach it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I carefully thought over the project, and turned over every plan for\nits accomplishment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It would be impossible, I am afraid,' said I, 'to make stairs\noutside, but within the trunk it might be done. More than once have I\nthought that this trunk might be hollow or partly so, and if such be\nthe case our task would be comparatively easy. Did you not tell me the\nother day that you noticed bees coming from a hole in the tree?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, yes,' said little Franz, 'and I went to look at them and one flew\nright against my face and stung me, and I almost cried, but I didn't.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Brave little boy,' said I. 'Well, now, if the trunk be sufficiently\nhollow to contain a swarm of bees, it may be for all we can tell hollow\nthe greater part of its length, for like the willow in our own country\nit might draw all its nourishment through the bark, and in spite of its\nreal unsoundness retain a flourishing appearance.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Master Jack, practical as usual, instantly sprang to his feet to put my\nconjecture to the proof. The rest followed his example, and they were\nall soon climbing about like squirrels peeping into the hole, and\ntapping the wood to discover by sound how far down the cavity extended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They forgot, in their eagerness, who were the tenants of this\ninteresting trunk. They were soon reminded of it, however, for the\nbees, disturbed by this unusual noise, with an angry buzz burst out and\nin an instant attacked the causers of the annoyance; they swarmed round\nthem, stung them on the hands, face, and neck, settled in their hair,\nand pursued them as they ran to me for assistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was with difficulty that we got rid of the angry insects, and were\nable to attend to the boys. Jack, who had been the first to reach the\nhole, had fared the worst and was soon a most pitiable sight, his face\nswelled to an extraordinary degree, and it was only by the constant\napplication of cold earth that the pain was alleviated. They were all\neager to commence an organized attack upon the bees at once, but for an\nhour or more by reason of their pain they were unable to render me much\nassistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the meanwhile I made my arrangements. I first took a large calabash\ngourd, for I intended to make a beehive, that, when we had driven the\ninsects from their present abode, we might not lose them entirely. The\nlower half of the gourd I flattened, I then cut an arched opening in\nthe front for a doorway, made a straw roof as a protection from the\nrain and heat, and the little house was complete."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing more however could then be done, for the irritated bees were\nstill angrily buzzing round the tree. I waited till dark, and then when\nall the bees had again returned to their trunk, with Fritz's assistance\nI carefully stopped up every hole in the tree with wet clay, that the\nbees might not issue forth next morning before we could begin\noperations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Very early were we up and at work. I first took a hollow cane, and\ninserted one end through the clay into the tree; down this tube with\npipe and tobacco I smoked most furiously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The humming and buzzing that went on within was tremendous; the bees\nevidently could not understand what was going to happen. I finished my\nfirst pipeful, and putting my thumb over the end of the cane, I gave\nthe pipe to Fritz to refill. He did so and I again smoked. The buzzing\nwas now becoming less noisy, and was subsiding into a mere murmur. By\nthe time I had finished this second pipe all was still; the bees were\nstupefied."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now then, Fritz,' said I, 'quick with a hammer and chisel, and stand\nhere beside me.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was up in a moment, and, together, we cut a small door by the side\nof the hole; this door however, we did not take out, but we left it\nattached by one corner that it might be removed at a moment's notice,\nthen giving the bees a final dose of tobacco smoke, we opened it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Carefully but rapidly we removed the insects, as they clung in\nclusters to the sides of the tree, and placed them in the hive\nprepared for their reception. As rapidly I then took every atom of wax\nand honey from their storehouse, and put it in a cask I had made ready\nfor the purpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bees were now safely removed from the trunk, but I could not tell\nwhether, when they revived from their temporary stupor, they might not\nrefuse to occupy the house with which I had presented them, and insist\non returning to their old quarters. To prevent the possibility of this\noccurrence I took a quantity of tobacco, and, placing it upon a board\nnailed horizontally within the trunk, I lighted it and allowed it to\nburn slowly that the fumes might fill the cavity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was well I did so, for, as the bees returned to consciousness, they\nleft their pretty hive and buzzed away to the trunk of the tree. They\nseemed astonished at finding this uninhabitable, and an immense deal of\nnoisy humming ensued. Round and round they flew, backwards and forwards\nbetween the gourd and tree, now settling here and now there, until, at\nlength, after due consideration, they took possession of the hive and\nabandoned their former habitation to us the invaders of their\nterritory. By the evening they were quite quiet, and we ventured to\nopen the cask in which we had stored our plunder."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We first separated the honey from the honeycomb and poured it off into\njars and pots; the rest we then took and threw into a vessel of water\nplaced over a slow fire. It soon boiled and the entire mass became\nfluid. This we placed in a clean canvas bag, and subjected to a heavy\npressure. The honey was thus soon forced out, and we stored it in a\ncask, and, though not perhaps quite equal to the former batch in\nquality, it was yet capital. The wax that remained in the bag I also\ncarefully stored, for I knew it would be of great use to me in the\nmanufacture of candles. Then after a hard day's work we turned in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The internal architecture of the tree had now to be attended to, and\nearly the following morning we prepared for the labourious task. A door\nhad first to be made, so at the base of the trunk we cut away the bark\nand formed an opening just the size of the door we had brought from the\ncaptain's cabin, and which, hinges and all, was ready to be hung."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The clearing of the rotten wood from the centre of the trunk occupied\nus some time, but at length we had the satisfaction of seeing it\nentirely accomplished, and, as we stood below, we could look up the\ntrunk, which was like a great smooth funnel, and see the sky above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was now ready for the staircase, and first we erected in the centre\na stout sapling to form an axis round which to build the spiral stairs;\nin this we cut notches to receive the steps, and corresponding notches\nin the tree itself to support the outer ends. The steps themselves we\nformed carefully and neatly of planks from the wreck, and clenched them\nfirmly in their places with stout nails."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Upwards and upwards we built, cutting windows in the trunk as we\nrequired, to admit light and air, until we were flush with the top of\nthe centre pole. On this pole we erected another to reach the top of\nthe tree, and securing it firmly, built in the same way round it until\nwe at length reached the level of the floor of the nest above."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To make the ascent of the stairs perfectly easy we ran a hand-rail on\neither side, one round the centre pillar, and the other following the\ncurve of the trunk."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This task occupied us a whole month, and by the end of that period, so\naccustomed had we become to having a definite piece of work before us\nthat we began to consider what other great alteration we should\nundertake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were, however, of course not neglecting the details of our colonial\nestablishment. There were all the animals to be attended to; the goats\nand sheep had both presented us with additions to our flock, and these\nfrisky youngsters had to be seen after; to prevent them straying to any\ngreat distance, for we had no wish to lose them, we tied round their\nnecks little bells, which we had found on board the wreck, and which\nwould assist us to track them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Juno, too, had a fine litter of puppies, but, in spite of the\nentreaties of the children, I could not consent to keep more than two,\nand the rest disappeared in that mysterious way in which puppies and\nkittens are wont to leave the earth. To console the mother, as he said,\nbut also, I suspect, to save himself considerable trouble, Jack placed\nhis little jackal beside the remaining puppies, and, to his joy, found\nit readily adopted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The other pets were also flourishing, and were being usefully trained.\nThe buffalo, after giving us much trouble, had now become perfectly\ndomesticated, and was a very useful beast of burden, besides being a\ncapital steed for the boys. They guided him by a bar thrust through the\nhole in his nose, which was now perfectly healed, and this served the\npurpose just as a bit in the mouth of a horse. I began his education by\nsecuring round him a broad girth of buffalo-hide and fastening to it\nvarious articles, to accustom him to carrying a burden. By degrees he\npermitted this to be done without making the slightest resistance, and\nsoon carried the panniers, before borne by the ass, readily and\nwillingly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then made Master Knips sit upon his back and hold the reins I had\nprepared for him, that the animal might become accustomed to the\nfeeling of a rider, and finally allowed Fritz himself to mount."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The education of the eagle was not neglected. Fritz every day shot\nsmall birds for his food, and these he placed sometimes between the\nwide-spreading horns of the buffalo or goat, and sometimes upon the\nback of the great bustard, that he might become accustomed to pounce\nupon living prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These lessons had their due effect, and the bird, having been taught to\nobey the voice and whistle of his master, was soon allowed to bring\ndown small birds upon the wing, when he stooped and struck his quarry\nin most sportsmanlike manner. We kept him well away from the\npoultry-yard lest his natural instincts should show themselves, and he\nshould put an untimely end to some of our feathered pets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Neither was Master Knips allowed to remain idle, for Ernest, now that\nhe was in his possession, wished to train him to be of some use. With\nJack's help he made a little basket of rushes, which he so arranged\nwith straps that it might be easily fitted on to the monkey's back.\nThus equipped he was taught to mount cocoanut palms and other lofty\ntrees, and to bring down their fruit in the hamper."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack was not so successful in his educational attempts. Fangs, as he\nhad christened his jackal, used his fangs indeed, but only on his own\naccount; nothing could persuade him that the animals he caught were not\nat once to be devoured, consequently poor Jack was never able to save\nfrom his jaws anything but the tattered skin of his prey. Not\ndisheartened, however, he determined that Fangs could be trained, and\nthat he would train him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These, and suchlike employments, afforded us the rest and recreation we\nrequired while engaged in the labourious task of staircase building."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Among my minor occupations, I applied myself to the improvement of our\ncandles. Though the former batch had greatly delighted us at first, yet\nwe were soon obliged to acknowledge that the light they gave was\nimperfect, and their appearance was unsightly; my wife, too, begged me\nto find some substitute for the threads of our cotton neck-ties*, which\nI had previously used as wicks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Not what we today call neckties, but rather a soft band of\ncloth worn loosely around the neck and used as a sweatband,\nto keep sweat and dirt from lodging in the neckband of the\nshirt. A collar at this time was a separate piece of cloth,\nbuttoned on and worn only for at least semi-formal\noccasions."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To give the proper shape and smoothness to the candles, I determined to\nuse the bamboo moulds I had prepared. My first idea was to pour the wax\nin at the end of the mould, and then when the candles were cooled to\nslip them out; but I was soon convinced that this plan would not\nsucceed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I therefore determined to divide the moulds lengthways, and then,\nhaving greased them well, we might pour the melted wax into the two\nhalves bound tightly together, and so be able to take out the candles\nwhen cool without injuring them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The wicks were my next difficulty, and as my wife positively refused to\nallow us to devote our ties and handkerchiefs for the purpose, I took a\npiece of inflammable wood from a tree, a native of the Antilles, which\nI thought would serve our purpose; this I cut into long slips, and\nfixed in the centres of the moulds. My wife, too, prepared some wicks\nfrom the fibres of the karata tree, which she declared would beat mine\ncompletely out of the field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We put them to the proof. On a large fire we placed a pot, in which we\nprepared our wax mixtureâ€”half bees' wax and half wax from the\ncandleberries. The moulds carefully preparedâ€”half with karata fibre,\nand half with wooden splint wicksâ€”stood on their ends in a tub of cold\nwater, ready to receive the wax."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were filled; the wax cooled; the candles taken out and subjected\nto the criticism of all hands. When night drew on, they were formally\ntested. The decision was unanimous: neither gave such a good light as\nthose with the cotton wicks; but even my wife declared that the light\nfrom mine was far preferable to that emitted by hers, for the former,\nthough rather flaring, burned brilliantly, while the latter gave out\nsuch a feeble and flickering flame that it was almost useless."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then turned shoemaker, for I had promised myself a pair of\nwaterproof boots, and now determined to make them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Taking a pair of socks, I filled them with sand, and then coated them\nover with a thin layer of clay to form a convenient mould; this was\nsoon hardened in the sun, and was ready for use. Layer after layer of\ncaoutchouc I brushed over it, allowing each layer to dry before the\nnext was put on, until at length I considered that the shoes were of\nsufficient thickness. I dried them, broke out the clay, secured with\nnails a strip of buffalo-hide to the soles, brushed that over with\ncaoutchouc, and I had a pair of comfortable, durable,\nrespectable-looking waterproof boots."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was delighted; orders poured in from all sides, and soon everyone in\nthe family was likewise provided for."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One objection to Falconhurst was the absence of any spring close by, so\nthat the boys were obliged to bring water daily from the stream; and\nthis involving no little trouble, it was proposed that we should carry\nthe water by pipes from the stream to our present residence. A dam had\nto be thrown across the river some way up stream, that the water might\nbe raised to a sufficient height to run to Falconhurst. From the\nreservoir thus made we led the water down by pipes into the turtle's\nshell, which we placed near our dwelling, and from which the\nsuperfluous water flowed off through the hole made in it by Fritz's\nharpoon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This was an immense convenience, and we formally inaugurated the\ntrough by washing therein a whole sack of potatoes. Thus day after day\nbrought its own work, and day after day saw that work completed. We had\nno time to be idle, or to lament our separation from our fellow\ncreatures."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One morning, as we were completing our spiral staircase, and giving it\nsuch finish as we were capable of, we were suddenly alarmed by hearing\na most terrific noise, the roaring or bellowing of a wild beast; so\nstrange a sound was it, that I could not imagine by what animal it was\nuttered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack thought it perhaps a lion, Fritz hazarded a gorilla, while Ernest\ngave it as his opinion, and I thought it possible that he was right,\nthat it was a hyaena."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Whatever it is,' said I, 'we must prepare to receive it; up with you\nall to the nest while I secure the door.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then arming the dogs with their collars, I sent them out to protect the\nanimals below, closed the door, and joined my family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every gun was loaded, every eye was upon the watch. The sound drew\nnearer, and then all was still; nothing was to be seen. I determined to\ndescend and reconnoitre, and Fritz and I carefully crept down; with our\nguns at full cock we glided amongst the trees; noiselessly and quickly\nwe pushed on further and further; suddenly, close by, we heard the\nterrific sound again. Fritz raised his gun, but almost as quickly again\ndropped it, and burst into a hearty fit of laughter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There was no mistaking those dulcet tonesâ€”hee-haw, hee-haw, hee-haw,\nresounded through the forest, and our ass braying his approach right\nmerrily appeared in sight. To our surprise, however, our friend was not\nalone: behind him trotted another animal, an ass no doubt, but slim and\ngraceful as a horse. We watched their movements anxiously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz,' I whispered, 'that is an onager. Creep back to Falconhurst and\nbring me a piece of cordâ€”quietly now!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While he was gone, I cut a bamboo and split it halfway down to form a\npair of pincers, which I knew would be of use to me should I get near\nthe animal. Fritz soon returned with the cord, and I was glad to\nobserve also brought some oats and salt. We made one end of the cord\nfast to a tree, and at the other end made a running noose. Silently we\nwatched the animals as they approached, quietly browsing; Fritz then\nrose, holding in one hand the noose, and in the other some oats and\nsalt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ass, seeing his favourite food thus held out, advanced to take it;\nFritz allowed him to do so, and he was soon munching contentedly. The\nstranger, on seeing Fritz, started back; but finding her companion show\nno signs of alarm, was reassured, and soon approached sniffing, and was\nabout to take some of the tempting food."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a moment the noose left Fritz's adroit hand and fell round her\nneck; with a single bound she sprang backwards the full length of the\ncord, the noose drew tight, and she fell to the earth half strangled. I\nat once ran up, loosened the rope and replaced it by a halter; and\nplacing the pincers upon her nose, secured her by two cords fastened\nbetween two trees, and then left her to recover herself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone hastened up to examine the beautiful animal as she rose from\nthe ground and cast fiery glances around. She lashed out with her heels\non every side; and, giving vent to angry snorts, struggled violently to\nget free. All her endeavours were vain: the cords were stout, and after\na while she quieted down and stood exhausted and quivering."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then approached: she suffered me to lead her to the roots of our\ntree, which for the present formed our stables, and there I tied her up\nclose to the donkey, who was likewise prevented from playing truant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning I found the onager after her night's rest as wild as\never, and as I looked at the handsome creature I almost despaired of\never taming her proud spirit. Every expedient was tried, and at length,\nwhen the animal was subdued by hunger, I thought I might venture to\nmount her; and having given her the strongest curb and shackled her\nfeet, I attempted to do so. She was as unruly as ever, and as a last\nexpedient I resolved to adopt a plan which, though cruel, was I knew\nattended with wonderful success by the American Indians, by whom it is\npractised."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Watching a favourable opportunity, I sprang upon the onager's back, and\nseizing her long ear in my teeth, in spite of her kicking and plunging,\nbit it through. The result was marvellous, the animal ceased plunging,\nand, quivering violently, stood stock-still."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From that moment we were her masters, the children mounted her one\nafter the other, and she carried them obediently and quietly. Proud,\nindeed, did I feel as I watched this animal, which naturalists and\ntravellers have declared to be beyond the power of man to tame, guided\nhither and thither by my youngest son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Additions to our poultry yard reminded me of the necessity of\nproviding some substantial shelter for our animals before the rainy\nseason came on; three broods of chickens had been successfully hatched,\nand the little creatures, forty in all, were my wife's pride and\ndelight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We began by making a roof over the vaulted roots of our tree, forming\nthe framework of bamboo canes which we laid close together and bound\ntightly down; others we fixed below as supports. The interstices were\nfilled up with clay and moss; and coating the whole over with a mixture\nof tar and lime-water, we obtained a firm balcony, and a capital roof\nimpervious to the severest fall of rain. I ran a light rail round the\nbalcony to give it a more ornamental appearance, and below divided the\nbuilding into several compartments. Stables, poultry yard, hay and\nprovision lofts, dairy, kitchen, larder and dining-hall were united\nunder one roof."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our winter-quarters were now completed, and we had but to store them\nwith food. Day after day we worked, bringing in provisions of every\ndescription."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we were one evening returning from gathering potatoes, it struck me\nthat we should take in a store of acorns; and sending the two younger\nboys home with their mother and the cart, I took a large canvas bag,\nand with Fritz and Ernest, the former mounted on his onager, and the\nlatter carrying his little favourite, Knips, made a detour towards the\nAcorn Wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We reached the spot, tied Lightfoot to a neighbouring tree, and began\nrapidly to fill the sack. As we were thus engaged, Knips sprang\nsuddenly into a bush close by, from which, a moment afterwards, issued\nsuch strange cries that Ernest followed to see what could be the\nmatter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come!' he shouted, 'Come and help me! I've got a couple of birds and\ntheir eggs. Quick! Ruffed grouse!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We hurried to the spot. There was Ernest with a fluttering, screaming\nbird in either hand; while, with his foot, he was endeavouring to\nprevent his greedy little monkey from seizing the eggs. We quickly tied\nthe legs of the birds, and removing the eggs from the nest, placed them\nin Ernest's hat; while he gathered some of the long, broad grass, with\nwhich the nest was woven, and which grew luxuriantly around, for Franz\nto play at sword-drill with."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then loaded the onager with the acorns and moved homewards. The eggs\nI covered carefully with dry moss, that they might be kept warm, and as\nsoon as possible I handed them over to my wife who managed the mother\nso cleverly that she induced her to return to the eggs, and in a few\ndays, to our great delight, we had fifteen beautiful little Canadian\nchicks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz was greatly pleased with the 'swords' his brother brought him;\nbut having no small companion on whom to exercise his valour, he amused\nhimself for a short time in hewing down imaginary foes, and then cut\nthe reeds in slips, and plaited them to form a whip for Lightfoot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The leaves seemed so pliable and strong, that I examined them to see to\nwhat further use they might be put. Their tissue was composed of long\nsilky fibres. A sudden thought struck meâ€”this must be New Zealand\nflax. I could not rest till I had announced this invaluable discovery\nto my wife. She was no less delighted than I was."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Bring me the leaves!' she exclaimed. 'Oh, what a delightful\ndiscovery! No one shall now be clothed in rags; just make me a\nspindle, and you shall soon have shirts and stockings and trousers, all\ngood homespun! Quick, Fritz, and bring your mother more leaves!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We could not help smiling at her eager zeal; but Fritz and Ernest\nsprang on their steeds, and soon the onager and buffalo were galloping\nhome again, each laden with a great bundle of flax. The boys dismounted\nand deposited their offering at their mother's feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Capital!' she exclaimed. 'I shall now show you that I am not at all\nbehindhand in ingenuity. This must be retted, carded, spun and woven,\nand then with scissors, needle and thread I will make you any article\nof clothing you choose.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We decided that Flamingo Marsh would be the best spot for the\noperation of steeping or 'retting' the flax, and next morning we set\nout thither; the cart drawn by the ass, and laden with the bundles,\nbetween which sat Franz and Knips, while the rest of us followed with\nspades and hatchets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I described to my boys as we went along the process of retting, and\nexplained to them how steeping the flax leaves destroys the useless\nmembrane, while the strong fibres remain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we were employed in making beds for the flax and placing it in\nthem, we observed several nests of the flamingo. These are most\ncuriously and skilfully made of glutinous clay, so strong that they can\nneither be overturned nor washed away. They are formed in the shape of\nblunted cones, and placed point downwards; at the upper and broader end\nis built a little platform to contain the eggs, on which the female\nbird sits, with her long legs in the water on either side, until the\nlittle birds are hatched and can take to the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For a fortnight we left the flax to steep, and then taking it out and\ndrying it thoroughly in the sun, stored it for future use at\nFalconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Daily did we load our cart with provisions to be brought to our\nwinter-quarters: manioc, potatoes, cocoanuts, sweet acorns,\nsugar-canes, were all collected and stored in abundanceâ€”for grumbling\nthunder, lowering skies, and sharp showers warned us that we had no\ntime to lose. Our corn was sowed, our animals housed, our provisions\nstored, when down came the rain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To continue in our nest we found impossible, and we were obliged to\nretreat to the trunk, where we carried such of our domestic furniture\nas might have been injured by the damp. Our dwelling was indeed\ncrowded: the animals and provisions below, and our beds and household\ngoods around us, hemmed us in on every side; by degrees, by dint of\npatience and better packing, we obtained sufficient room to work and\nlie down in; by degrees, too, we became accustomed to the continual\nnoise of the animals and the smell of the stables."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The smoke from the fire, which we were occasionally obliged to light,\nwas not agreeable; but in time even that seemed to become more\nbearable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To make more space, we turned such animals as we had captured, and who\ntherefore might be imagined to know how to shift for themselves,\noutside during the daytime, bringing them under the arched roots only\nat night. To perform this duty Fritz and I used to sally forth every\nevening, and as regularly every evening did we return soaked to the\nskin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To obviate this, my wife, who feared these continual wettings might\ninjure our health, contrived waterproofs: she brushed on several layers\nof caoutchouc over stout shirts, to which she attached hoods; she then\nfixed to these duck trousers, and thus prepared for each of us a\ncomplete waterproof suit, clad in which we might brave the severest\nrain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In spite of our endeavours to keep ourselves busy, the time dragged\nheavily. Our mornings were occupied in tending the animals; the boys\namused themselves with their pets, and assisted me in the manufacture\nof carding-combs and a spindle for their mother. The combs I made with\nnails, which I placed head downwards on a sheet of tin about an inch\nwide; holding the nails in their proper positions I poured solder round\ntheir heads to fix them to the tin, which I then folded down on either\nside of them to keep them perfectly firm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the evening, when our room was illuminated with wax candles, I\nwrote a journal of all the events which had occurred since our arrival\nin this foreign land; and, while my wife was busy with her needle and\nErnest making sketches of birds, beasts and flowers with which he had\nmet during the past months, Fritz and Jack taught little Franz to read."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Week after week rolled by. Week after week saw us still close\nprisoners. Incessant rain battered down above us, constant gloom hung\nover the desolate scene."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
