  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 9"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The winds at length were lulled, the sun shot his brilliant rays\nthrough the riven clouds, the rain ceased to fallâ€”spring had come. No\nprisoners set at liberty could have felt more joy than we did as we\nstepped forth from our winter abode, refreshed our eyes with the\npleasant verdure around us, and our ears with the merry songs of a\nthousand happy birds, and drank in the pure balmy air of spring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our plantations were thriving vigorously. The seed we had sown was\nshooting through the moist earth. All nature was refreshed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our nest was our first care: filled with leaves and broken and torn by\nthe wind, it looked indeed dilapidated. We worked hard, and in a few\ndays it was again habitable. My wife begged that I would now start her\nwith the flax, and as early as possible I built a drying-oven, and then\nprepared it for her use; I also, after some trouble, manufactured a\nbeetle-reel and spinning-wheel, and she and Franz were soon hard at\nwork, the little boy reeling off the thread his mother spun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was anxious to visit Tentholm, for I feared that much of our\nprecious stores might have suffered. Fritz and I made an excursion\nthither. The damage done to Falconhurst was as nothing compared to the\nscene that awaited us. The tent was blown to the ground, the canvas\ntorn to rags, the provisions soaked, and two casks of powder utterly\ndestroyed. We immediately spread such things as we hoped yet to\npreserve in the sun to dry."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The pinnace was safe, but our faithful tub-boat was dashed in pieces,\nand the irreparable damage we had sustained made me resolve to contrive\nsome safer and more stable winter-quarters before the arrival of the\nnext rainy season. Fritz proposed that we should hollow out a cave in\nthe rock, and though the difficulties such an undertaking would present\nappeared almost insurmountable, I yet determined to make the attempt;\nwe might not, I thought, hew out a cavern of sufficient size to serve\nas a room, but we might at least make a cellar for the more valuable\nand perishable of our stores."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some days afterwards we left Falconhurst with the cart laden with a\ncargo of spades, hammers, chisels, pickaxes and crowbars, and began our\nundertaking. On the smooth face of the perpendicular rock I drew out in\nchalk the size of the proposed entrance, and then, with minds bent on\nsuccess, we battered away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Six days of hard and incessant toil made but little impression; I do\nnot think that the hole would have been a satisfactory shelter for even\nMaster Knips; but we still did not despair, and were presently rewarded\nby coming to softer and more yielding substance; our work progressed,\nand our minds were relieved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the tenth day, as our persevering blows were falling heavily, Jack,\nwho was working diligently with a hammer and crowbar, shouted:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Gone, father! Fritz, my bar has gone through the mountain!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Run round and get it,' laughed Fritz, 'perhaps it has dropped into\nEuropeâ€”you must not lose a good crowbar.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But, really, it is through; it went right through the rock; I heard it\ncrash down inside. Oh, do come and see!' he shouted excitedly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We sprang to his side, and I thrust the handle of my hammer into the\nhole he spoke of; it met with no opposition, I could turn it in any\ndirection I chose. Fritz handed me a long pole; I tried the depth with\nthat. Nothing could I feel. A thin wall, then, was all that intervened\nbetween us and a great cavern."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With a shout of joy, the boys battered vigorously at the rock; piece by\npiece fell, and soon the hole was large enough for us to enter. I\nstepped near the aperture, and was about to make a further examination,\nwhen a sudden rush of poisonous air turned me giddy, and shouting to my\nsons to stand off, I leaned against the rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When I came to myself I explained to them the danger of approaching any\ncavern or other place where the air has for a long time been stagnant.\n'Unless air is incessantly renewed it becomes vitiated,' I said, 'and\nfatal to those who breathe it. The safest way of restoring it to its\noriginal state is to subject it to the action of fire; a few handfuls\nof blazing hay thrown into this hole may, if the place be small,\nsufficiently purify the air within to allow us to enter without\ndanger.' We tried the experiment. The flame was extinguished the\ninstant it entered. Though bundles of blazing grass were thrown in, no\ndifference was made.*"
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "What actually happens is that the oxygen supply becomes\nlow. If there is sufficient oxygen to maintain a flame, the\naction of the flame increases air circulation, which then\nbrings in more oxygen. The flame goes out if the oxygen\nsupply is insufficient for its supply; in this case, it\ntakes the fireworks to create adequate circulation. The next\ntorch is able to blaze not because the air is purified, but\nbecause the oxygen is now sufficient to feed the fire."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I saw that we must apply some more efficacious remedy, and sent the\nboys for a chest of signal-rockets we had brought from the wreck. We\nlet fly some dozens of these fiery serpents, which went whizzing in and\ndisappeared at apparently a vast distance from us. Some flew like\nradiant meteors round, lighted up the mighty circumference and\ndisplayed, as by a magician's wand, a sparkling glittering roof. They\nlooked like avenging dragons driving a foul malignant fiend out of a\nbeauteous palace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We waited for a little while after these experiments, and I then again\nthrew in lighted hay. It burned clearly; the air was purified."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and I enlarged the opening, while Jack, springing on his\nbuffalo, thundered away to Falconhurst to bear the great and\nastonishing news to his mother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Great must have been the effect of Jack's eloquence on those at home,\nfor the timbers of the bridge were soon again resounding under the\nswift but heavy tramp of his steed; and he was quickly followed by the\nrest of our party in the cart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All were in the highest state of excitement. Jack had stowed in the\ncart all the candles he could find, and we now, lighting these,\nshouldered our arms and entered. I led the way, sounding the ground as\nI advanced with a long pole, that we might not fall unexpectedly into\nany great hole or chasm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Silently we marchedâ€”my wife, the boys, and even the dogs seeming\noverawed with the grandeur and beauty of the scene We were in a grotto\nof diamondsâ€”a vast cave of glittering crystal; the candles reflected\non the walls a golden light, bright as the stars of Heaven, while great\ncrystal pillars rose from the floor like mighty trees, mingling their\nbranches high above us and drooping in hundreds of stalactites, which\nsparkled and glittered with all the colours of the rainbow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The floor of this magnificent palace was formed of hard, dry sand, so\ndry that I saw at once that we might safely take up our abode therein,\nwithout the slightest fear of danger from damp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From the appearance of the brilliant crystals round about us, I\nsuspected their nature. I tasted a piece. This was a cavern of\nrock-salt. There was no doubt about itâ€”here was an unlimited supply of\nthe best and purest salt!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But one thing detracted from my entire satisfaction and delightâ€”large\ncrystals lay scattered here and there, which, detached from the roof,\nhad fallen to the ground; this, if apt to recur, would keep us in\nconstant peril. I examined some of the masses and discovered that they\nhad been all recently separated, and therefore concluded that the\nconcussion of the air, occasioned by the rockets, had caused their\nfall. To satisfy ourselves, however, that there were no more pieces\ntottering above us, we discharged our guns from the entrance, and\nwatched the effect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing more fellâ€”our magnificent abode was safe. We returned to\nFalconhurst with minds full of wonder at our new discovery, and plans\nfor turning it to the best possible advantage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing was now talked of but the new house, how it should be\narranged, how it should be fitted up. The safety and comfort of\nFalconhurst, which had at first seemed so great, now dwindled away in\nour opinion to nothing; it should be kept up we decided merely as a\nsummer residence, while our cave should be formed into a winter house\nand impregnable castle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our attention was now fully occupied with this new house. Light and air\nwere to be admitted, so we hewed a row of windows in the rock, where we\nfitted the window-cases we had brought from the officers' cabins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We brought the door, too, from Falconhurst, and fitted it in the\naperture we had made. The opening in the trunk of the tree I\ndetermined to conceal with bark, as less likely to attract the notice\nof wild beasts or savages should they approach during our absence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cave itself we divided into four parts: in front, a large\ncompartment into which the door opened, subdivided into our sitting,\neating and sleeping apartments; the right-hand division, containing our\nkitchen and workshop, and the left our stables; behind all this, in the\ndark recess of the cave, was our storehouse and powder-magazine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having already undergone one rainy reason, we knew well its\ndiscomforts, and thought of many useful arrangements in the laying-out\nof our dwelling. We did not intend to be again smoke-dried; we,\ntherefore, contrived a properly built fireplace and chimney; our stable\narrangements, too, were better, and plenty of space was left in our\nworkshop that we should not be hampered in even the most extensive\noperations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our frequent residence at Tentholm revealed to us several important\nadvantages which we had not foreseen. Numbers of splendid turtles often\ncame ashore to deposit their eggs in the sand, and their delicious\nflesh afforded us many a sumptuous meal. When more than one of these\ncreatures appeared at a time, we used to cut off their retreat to the\nsea, and, turning them on their backs, fasten them to a stake, driven\nin close by the water's edge, by a cord passed through a hole in their\nshell. We thus had fresh turtle continually within our reach; for the\nanimals throve well thus secured, and appeared in as good condition,\nafter having been kept thus for several weeks, as others when freshly\ncaught. Lobsters, crabs and mussels also abounded on the shore. But\nthis was not all; an additional surprise awaited us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we were one morning approaching Tentholm, we were attracted by a\nmost curious phenomenon. The waters out to sea appeared agitated by\nsome unseen movement, and as they heaved and boiled, their surface,\nstruck by the beams of the morning sun, seemed illuminated by flashes\nof fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Over the water where this disturbance was taking place hovered\nhundreds of birds, screaming loudly, which ever and anon would dart\ndownwards, some plunging beneath the water, some skimming the surface.\nThen again they would rise and resume their harsh cries. The shining,\nsparkling mass then rolled onwards, and approached in a direct line our\nbay, followed by the feathered flock above. We hurried down to the\nshore to further examine this strange sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was convinced as we approached that it was a shoal or bank of\nherrings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner did I give utterance to my conjecture, than I was assailed by\na host of questions concerning this herring-bank, what it was, and what\noccasioned it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A herring-bank,' I said, 'is composed of an immense number of\nherrings swimming together. I can scarcely express to you the huge size\nof this living bank, which extends over a great area many fathoms deep.\nIt is followed by numbers of great ravenous fish, who devour quantities\nof the herrings, while above hover birds, as you have just seen, ready\nto pounce down on stragglers near the top. To escape these enemies, the\nshoal makes for the nearest shore, and seeks safety in those shallows\nwhere the large fish cannot follow. But here it meets with a third\ngreat enemy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It may escape from the fish, and elude the vigilance of sharp-sighted\nbirds, but from the ingenuity of man it can find no escape. In one year\nmillions of these fish are caught, and yet the roes of only a small\nnumber would be sufficient to supply as many fish again.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soon our fishery was in operation. Jack and Fritz stood in the water\nwith baskets, and baled out the fish, as one bales water with a bucket,\nthrowing them to us on the shore. As quickly as possible we cleaned\nthem, and placed them in casks with salt, first a layer of salt, and\nthen a layer of herrings, and so on, until we had ready many casks of\npickled fish."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the barrels were filled, we closed them carefully, and rolled them\naway to the cool vaults at the back of our cave. Our good fortune,\nhowever, was not to end here. A day after the herring fishery was over,\nand the shoal had left our bay, a great number of seals appeared,\nattracted by the refuse of the herrings which we had thrown into the\nsea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Though I feared they would not be suitable for our table, we yet\nsecured a score or two for the sake of their skins and fat. The skins\nwe drew carefully off for harness and clothing, and the fat we boiled\ndown for oil, which we put aside in casks for tanning, soap-making, and\nburning in lamps."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These occupations interfered for some time with our work at Rock\nHouse; but as soon as possible we again returned to our labour with\nrenewed vigour. I had noticed that the salt crystals had for their base\na species of gypsum, which I knew might be made of great service to us\nin our building operations as plaster."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As an experiment, I broke off some pieces, and, after subjecting them\nto great heat, reduced them to powder. The plaster this formed with\nwater was smooth and white, and as I had then no particular use to\nwhich I might put it, I plastered over some of the herring casks, that\nI might be perfectly certain that all air was excluded. The remainder\nof the casks I left as they were, for I presently intended to preserve\ntheir contents by smoking."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To do this, the boys and I built a small hut of reeds and branches, and\nthen we strung our herrings on lines across the roof. On the floor we\nlit a great fire of brushwood and moss, which threw out a dense smoke,\ncurling in volumes round the fish, and they in a few days seemed\nperfectly cured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "About a month after the appearance of the herrings we were favoured by\na visit from other shoals of fish. Jack espied them first, and called\nto us that a lot of young whales were off the coast. We ran down and\ndiscovered the bay apparently swarming with great sturgeon, salmon, and\ntrout, all making for the mouth of Jackal River, that they might ascend\nit and deposit their spawn amongst the stones."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack was delighted at his discovery. 'Here are proper fish!' he\nexclaimed, 'none of your paltry fry. How do you preserve these sorts of\nfish? Potted, salted or smoked?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not so fast,' said I, 'not so fast; tell me how they are to be\ncaught, and I will tell you how they are to be cooked.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh! I'll catch them fast enough,' he replied, and darted off to Rock\nHouse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While I was still puzzling my brains as to how I should set to work, he\nreturned with his fishing apparatus in hand: a bow and arrow, and a\nball of twine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the arrow-head he had fastened a barbed spike, and had secured the\narrow to the end of the string. Armed with this weapon, he advanced to\nthe river's edge."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His arrow flew from the bow, and, to my surprise, struck one of the\nlargest fish in the side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Help, father, help!' he cried, as the great fish darted off, carrying\narrow and all with it. 'Help! Or he will pull me into the water.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I ran to his assistance, and together we struggled with the finny\nmonster. He pulled tremendously, and lashed the water around him; but\nwe held the cord fast, and he had no chance of escape. Weaker and\nweaker grew his struggles, and, at length, exhausted by his exertions\nand loss of blood, he allowed us to draw him ashore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was a noble prize, and Fritz and Ernest, who came up just as we\ncompleted his capture, were quite envious of Jack's success."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not to be behindhand, they eagerly rushed off for weapons themselves.\nWe were soon all in the water, Fritz with a harpoon, Ernest with a rod\nand line, and I myself, armed like Neptune, with an iron trident, or\nmore properly speaking, perhaps, a pitchfork. Soon the shore was strewn\nwith a goodly number of the finest fishâ€”monster after monster we drew\nto land. At length Fritz, after harpooning a great sturgeon full eight\nfeet long, could not get the beast ashore; we all went to his\nassistance, but our united efforts were unavailing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The buffalo!' proposed my wife, and off went Jack for Storm. Storm was\nharnessed to the harpoon rope, and soon the monstrous fish lay panting\non the sand. We at length, when we had captured as many fish as we\ncould possibly utilize, set about cleaning and preparing their flesh.\nSome we salted, some we dried like the herrings, some we treated like\nthe tunny of the Mediterraneanâ€”we prepared them in oil."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Of the roe of the sturgeon I decided to form caviare, the great\nRussian dish. I removed from it all the membranes by which it is\nsurrounded, washed it in vinegar, salted it, pressed out all the\nmoisture caused by the water-absorbing properties of the salt, packed\nit in small barrels and stowed it away in our storehouse."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I knew that of the sturgeon's bladder the best isinglass is made, so\ncarefully collecting the air-bladders from all those we had killed, I\nwashed them and hung them up to stiffen. The outer coat or membrane I\nthen peeled off, cutting the remainder into strips, technically called\nstaples."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These staples I place in an iron pot over the fire, and when they had\nbeen reduced to a proper consistency I strained off the glue through a\nclean cloth, and spread it out on a slab of stone in thin layers,\nletting them remain until they were dry. The substance I thus obtained\nwas beautifully transparent, and promised to serve as an excellent\nsubstitute for glass in our window-frames."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fortunately, in this beautiful climate little or no attention was\nnecessary to the kitchen garden, the seeds sprang up and flourished\nwithout apparently the slightest regard for the time or season of the\nyear. Peas, beans, wheat, barley, rye and Indian corn, seemed\nconstantly ripe, while cucumbers, melons, and all sorts of other\nvegetables grew luxuriantly. The success of our garden at Tentholm\nencouraged me to hope that my experiment at Falconhurst had not failed,\nand one morning we started to visit the spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we passed by the field from which the potatoes had been dug, we\nfound it covered with barley, wheat, rye and peas in profusion. I\nturned to my wife in amazement. 'Where has this fine crop sprung from?'\nsaid I."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'From the earth,' she replied, laughing, 'where Franz and I sowed the\nseed I brought from the wreck. The ground was ready tilled by you and\nthe boys; all we had to do was to scatter the seed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was delighted at the sight, and it augured well, I thought, for the\nsuccess of my maize plantation. We hurried to the field. The crop had\nindeed grown well, and what was more, appeared to be duly appreciated.\nA tremendous flock of feathered thieves rose as we approached. Amongst\nthem Fritz espied a few ruffed grouse, and, quick as thought, unhooding\nhis eagle, he started him off in chase, then sprang on his onager and\nfollowed at full gallop. His noble bird marked out the finest grouse,\nand, soaring high above it, stooped and bore his prey to the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was close at hand, and springing through the bushes he saved the\nbird from death, hooded the eagle's eyes, and returned triumphantly.\nJack had not stood idle, for slipping his pet Fangs, he had started him\namong some quails who remained upon the field, and to my surprise the\njackal secured some dozen of the birds, bringing them faithfully to his\nmaster's feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then turned our steps towards Falconhurst, where we were refreshed\nby a most delicious drink my wife prepared for us; the stems of the\nyoung Indian corn crushed, strained, and mixed with water and the juice\nof the sugar-cane."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then made preparations for an excursion the following day, for I\nwished to establish a sort of semicivilized farm at some distance from\nFalconhurst, where we might place some of our animals which had become\ntoo numerous with our limited means to supply them with food. In the\nlarge cart, to which we harnessed the buffalo, cow, and ass, we placed\na dozen fowls, four young pigs, two couple of sheep, and as many goats,\nand a pair of hens and one cock grouse. Fritz led the way on his\nonager, and by a new track we forced a passage through the woods and\ntall grasses towards Cape Disappointment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The difficult march was at length over, and we emerged from the forest\nupon a large plain covered with curious little bushes; the branches of\nthese little shrubs and the ground about them were covered with pure\nwhite flakes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Snow! Snow!' exclaimed Franz. 'Oh, mother, come down from the cart and\nplay snowballs. This is jolly; much better than the ugly rain.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was not surprised at the boy's mistake, for indeed the flakes did\nlook like snow; but before I could express my opinion, Fritz declared\nthat the plant must be a kind of dwarf cotton-tree. We approached\nnearer and found he was rightâ€”soft fine wool enclosed in pods, and\nstill hanging on the bushes or lying on the ground, abounded in every\ndirection. We had indeed discovered this valuable plant. My wife was\ncharmed; and gathering a great quantity in three capacious bags, we\nresumed our journey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Crossing the cotton-field, we ascended a pretty wooded hill. The view\nfrom the summit was glorious: luxuriant grass at our feet stretching\ndown the hillside, dotted here and there with shady trees, among which\ngushed down a sparkling brook, while below lay the rich green forest,\nwith the sea beyond."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "What better situation could we hope to find for our new farm? Pasture,\nwater, shade and shelter, all were here."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We pitched our tent, built our fireplace, and, leaving my wife to\nprepare our repast, Fritz and I selected a spot for the erection of our\nshed. We soon found a group of trees so situated that the trunks would\nserve as posts for our intended building. Thither we carried all our\ntools, and then, as the day was far advanced, enjoyed our supper, and\nlay down upon most comfortable beds which my wife had prepared for us\nwith the cotton."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The group of trees we had selected was exactly suited to our purpose,\nfor it formed a regular rectilinear figure, the greatest side of which\nfaced the sea. I cut deep mortices in the trunks about ten feet from\nthe ground, and again ten feet higher up to form a second storey. In\nthese mortices I inserted beams, thus forming a framework for my\nbuilding, and then, making a roof of laths, I overlaid it with bark,\nwhich I stripped from a neighbouring tree, and fixed with acacia\nthorns, and which would effectually shoot off any amount of rain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While clearing up the scraps of bark and other rubbish for fuel for our\nfire, I noticed a peculiar smell, and stooping down I picked up pieces\nof the bark, some of which, to my great surprise, I found was that of\nthe terebinth tree, and the rest that of the American fir. The goats,\ntoo, made an important discovery amongst the same heap, for we found\nthem busily routing out pieces of cinnamon, a most delicious and\naromatic spice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'From the fir,' said I to the boys, 'we get turpentine and tar, and\nthus it is that the fir tree becomes such a valuable article of\ncommerce. So we may look forward to preparing pitch for our yacht with\ntar and oil, you know, and cart-grease, too, with tar and fat. I do not\nknow that you will equally appreciate the terebinth tree; a gum issues\nfrom incisions in the bark which hardens in the sun, and becomes as\ntransparent as amber; when burned it gives forth a most delicious\nperfume, and when dissolved in spirits of wine, forms a beautiful\ntransparent varnish.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The completion of our new farm-house occupied us several days; we wove\nstrong lianas and other creepers together to form the walls to the\nheight of about six feet; the rest, up to the roof, we formed merely of\na latticework of laths to admit both air and light. Within we divided\nthe house into three parts; one subdivided into stalls for the animals;\na second fitted with perches for the birds, and a third, simply\nfurnished with a rough table and benches, to serve as a\nsleeping-apartment for ourselves, when we should find it necessary to\npay the place a visit. In a short time the dwelling was most\ncomfortably arranged, and as we daily filled the feeding-troughs with\nthe food the animals best liked, they showed no inclination to desert\nthe spot we had chosen for them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Yet, hard as we had worked, we found that the provisions we had\nbrought with us would be exhausted before we could hope to be able to\nleave the farm. I therefore dispatched Jack and Fritz for fresh\nsupplies."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During their absence, Ernest and I made a short excursion in the\nneighbourhood, that we might know more exactly the character of the\ncountry near our farm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Passing over a brook which flowed towards the wall of rocks, we\nreached a large marsh, and as we walked round it, I noticed with\ndelight that it was covered with the rice plant growing wild in the\ngreatest profusion. Here and there only were there any ripe plants, and\nfrom these rose a number of ruffed grouse, at which both Ernest and I\nlet fly. Two fell, and Fangs, who was with us, brought them to our\nfeet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we advanced, Knips skipped from the back of his steed Juno and\nbegan to regale himself on some fruit, at a short distance off; we\nfollowed the little animal and found him devouring delicious\nstrawberries. Having enjoyed the fruit ourselves, we filled the hamper\nKnips always carried, and secured the fruit from his pilfering paws\nwith leaves fixed firmly down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then took a sample of the rice seeds to show my wife, and we\ncontinued our journey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently we reached the borders of the pretty lake which we had seen\nbeyond the swamp. The nearer aspect of its calm blue waters greatly\ncharmed us, and still more so, the sight of numbers of black swans,\ndisporting themselves on the glassy surface, in which their stately\nforms and graceful movements were reflected as in a mirror. It was\ndelightful to watch these splendid birds, old and young swimming\ntogether in the peaceful enjoyment of life, seeking their food, and\npursuing one another playfully in the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I could not think of breaking in upon their happy beautiful existence\nby firing among them, but our dog Juno was by no means so considerate;\nfor all at once I heard a plunge, and saw her drag out of the water a\nmost peculiar-looking creature, something like a small otter, but not\nabove twenty-two inches in length, which she would have torn to pieces,\nhad we not hurried up and taken it from her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This curious little animal was of a soft dark brown colour, the fur\nbeing of a lighter shade under the belly; its feet were furnished with\nlarge claws, and also completely webbed, the head small, with deeply\nset eyes and ears, and terminating in a broad flat bill like that of a\nduck."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This singularity seemed to us so droll that we both laughed heartily,\nfeeling at the same time much puzzled to know what sort of animal it\ncould possibly be. For want of a better, we gave it the name of the\n'Beast with a Bill'*, and Ernest willingly undertook to carry it, that\nit might be stuffed and kept as a curiosity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "A platypus. The next time they encounter one, he knows its name."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After this we returned to the farm, thinking our messengers might soon\narrive, and sure enough, in about a quarter of an hour, Fritz and Jack\nmade their appearance at a brisk trot, and gave a circumstantial\naccount of their mission."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "NOTE: To get supplies, about fourteen paragraphs earlier.\n   But what else did they do? Something is left out."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was pleased to see that they had fulfilled their orders\nintelligently, carrying out my intentions in the spirit and not\nblindly to the letter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning we quitted the farm (which we named Woodlands), after\nproviding amply for the wants of the animals, sheep, goats and poultry,\nwhich we left there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Shortly afterwards, on entering a wood, we found it tenanted by an\nenormous number of apes, who instantly assailed us with showers of\nfir-cones, uttering hideous and angry cries, and effectually checking\nour progress, until we put them to flight by a couple of shots, which\nnot a little astonished their weak minds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz picked up some of their missiles, and, showing them to me, I\nrecognized the cone of the stone-pine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'By all means gather some of these cones, boys,' said I; 'you will find\nthe kernel has a pleasant taste, like almonds, and from it we can, by\npressing, obtain an excellent oil. Therefore I should like to carry\nsome home with us.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A hill, which seemed to promise a good view from its summit, next\nattracted my notice, and, on climbing it we were more than repaid for\nthe exertion by the extensive and beautiful prospect which lay spread\nbefore our eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The situation altogether was so agreeable, that here also I resolved to\nmake a settlement, to be visited occasionally, and, after resting\nawhile and talking the matter over we set to work to build a cottage\nsuch as we had lately finished at Woodlands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our experience there enabled us to proceed quickly with the work, and\nin a few days the rustic abode was completed, and received, by Ernest's\nchoice, the grand name of Prospect Hill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My chief object in undertaking this expedition had been to discover\nsome tree from whose bark I could hope to make a useful light boat or\ncanoe. Hitherto I had met with none at all fit for my purpose, but, not\ndespairing of success, I began, when the cottage was built, to examine\ncarefully the surrounding woods, and, after considerable trouble, came\nupon two magnificent tall straight trees, the bark of which seemed\nsomething like that of the birch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Selecting one whose trunk was, to a great height, free from branches,\nwe attached to one of the lower of these boughs the rope ladder we had\nwith us, and, Fritz ascending it, cut the bark through in a circle; I\ndid the same at the foot of the tree, and then, from between the\ncircles, we took a narrow perpendicular slip of bark entirely out, so\nthat we could introduce the proper tools by which gradually to loosen\nand raise the main part, so as finally to separate it from the tree\nuninjured and entire. This we found possible, because the bark was\nmoist and flexible."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Great care and exertion were necessary, as the bark became detached, to\nsupport it, until the whole was ready to be let gently down upon the\ngrass. This seemed a great achievement; but our work was by no means\nended, nor could we venture to desist from it, until, while the\nmaterial was soft and pliable, we had formed it into the shape we\ndesired for the canoe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In order to do this, I cut a long triangular piece out of each end of\nthe roll, and, placing the sloping parts one over the other, I drew the\nends into a pointed form and secured them with pegs and glue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This successful proceeding had, however, widened the boat, and made it\ntoo flat in the middle, so that it was necessary to put ropes round it,\nand tighten them until the proper shape was restored, before we could\nallow it to dry in the sun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This being all I could do without a greater variety of tools, I\ndetermined to complete my work in a more convenient situation, and\nforthwith dispatched Fritz and Jack with orders to bring the sledge\n(which now ran on wheels taken from gun-carriages) that the canoe might\nbe transported direct to the vicinity of the harbour at Tentholm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During their absence I fortunately found some wood naturally curved,\njust suited for ribs to support and strengthen the sides of the boat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the two lads returned with the sledge, it was time to rest for the\nnight; but with early dawn we were again busily at work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sledge was loaded with the new boat, and everything else we could\npack into it, and we turned our steps homewards, finding the greatest\ndifficulty, however, in getting our vehicle through the woods. We\ncrossed the bamboo swamp, where I cut a fine mast for my boat, and came\nat length to a small opening or defile in the ridge of rocks, where a\nlittle torrent rushed from its source down into the larger stream\nbeyond; here we determined to make a halt, in order to erect a great\nearth wall across the narrow gorge, which, being thickly planted with\nprickly pear, Indian-fig, and every thorny bush we could find, would in\ntime form an effectual barrier against the intrusion of wild beasts,\nthe cliffs being, to the best of our belief, in every other part\ninaccessible."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For our own convenience we retained a small winding path through this\nbarrier, concealing and defending it with piles of branches and thorns,\nand also we contrived a light drawbridge over the stream, so that we\nrendered the pass altogether a very strong positron, should we ever\nhave to act on the defensive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This work occupied two days, and continuing on our way, we were glad to\nrest at Falconhurst before arriving (quite tired and worn out) at\nTentholm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It took some time to recruit our strength after this long and\nfatiguing expedition, and then we vigorously resumed the task of\nfinishing the canoe. The arrangements, I flattered myself, were\ncarried out in a manner quite worthy of a shipbuilder; a mast, sails\nand paddles were fitted, but my final touch, although I prized it\nhighly and considered it a grand and original idea, would no doubt have\nexcited only ridicule and contempt had it been seen by a naval man."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My contrivance was this: I had a couple of large air-tight bags, made\nof the skins of the dog-fish, well tarred and pitched, inflated, and\nmade fast on each side of the boat, just above the level of the water.\nThese floats, however much she might be loaded, would effectually\nprevent either the sinking or capsizing of my craft."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I may as well relate in this place what I omitted at the time of its\noccurrence. During the rainy season our cow presented us with a\nbull-calf, and that there might never be any difficulty in managing\nhim, I at a very early age, pierced his nose and placed a short stick\nin it, to be exchanged for a ring when he was old enough. The question\nnow came to be, who should be his master, and to what should we train\nhim?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why not teach him,' said Fritz, 'to fight with wild animals and\ndefend us, like the fighting bulls of the Hottentots? That would be\nreally useful!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am sure I should much prefer a gentle bull to a fighting one!'\nexclaimed his mother. 'But do you mean to say tame oxen can be taught\nto act rationally on the defensive?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I can but repeat what I have heard or read,' replied I, 'as regards\nthe race of Hottentots who inhabit the south of Africa, among all sorts\nof wild and ferocious animals."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The wealth of these people consists solely in their flocks and herds,\nand for their protection, they train their bulls to act as guards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These courageous animals keep the rest from straying away, and when\ndanger threatens, they give instant notice of it, drive the herd\ntogether in a mass, the calves and young cows being placed in the\ncentre; around them the bulls and strong oxen make a formidable circle\nwith their horned heads turned to the front, offering determined\nresistance to the fiercest foe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These fighting bulls will even sometimes rush with dreadful bellowing\nto meet the enemy; and should it be a mighty lion or other strong and\ndaring monster, sacrifice their own lives in defence of the herd."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is said that formerly, when Hottentot tribes made war on one\nanother, it was not unusual to place a troop of these stout-hearted\nwarriors in the van of the little army, when their heroism led to\ndecisive victory on one side or the other."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But,' continued, I, 'although I can see you are all delighted with my\ndescription of these fine warlike animals, I think we had better train\nthis youngster to be a peaceable bull. Who is to have charge of him?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest thought it would be more amusing to train his monkey than a\ncalf. Jack, with the buffalo and his hunting jackal, had quite enough\non his hands. Fritz was content with the onager. Their mother was voted\nmistress of the old grey donkey. And I myself being\nsuperintendent-in-chief of the whole establishment of animals, there\nremained only little Franz to whose special care the calf could be\ncommitted."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What say you, my boyâ€”will you undertake to look after this little\nfellow?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh yes, father!' he replied. 'Once you told me about a strong man, I\nthink his name was Milo, and he had a tiny calf, and he used to carry\nit about everywhere. It grew bigger and bigger, but still he carried it\noften, till at last he grew so strong that when it was quite a great\nbig ox, he could lift it as easily as ever. And so you see, if I take\ncare of our wee calf and teach it to do what I like, perhaps when it\ngrows big I shall still be able to manage it, and thenâ€”oh, papaâ€”do\nyou think I might ride upon it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I smiled at the child's simplicity, and his funny application of the\nstory of Milo of Crotona."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The calf shall be yours, my boy. Make him as tame as you can, and we\nwill see about letting you mount him some day; but remember he will be\na great bull long before you are nearly a man. Now what will you call\nhim?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Shall I call him \"Grumble\", father? Hear what a low muttering noise he\nmakes!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Grumble\" will do famously.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Grumble, Grumble. Oh, it beats your buffalo's name hollow, Jack!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not a bit,' said he, 'why, you can't compare the two names. Fancy\nmother saying, \"Here comes Franz on Grumble, but Jack riding on the\nStorm.\" Oh, it sounds sublime!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We named the two puppies Bruno and Fawn, and so ended this important\ndomestic business."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For two months we worked steadily at our salt-cave, in order to\ncomplete the necessary arrangement of partition walls, so as to put the\nrooms and stalls for the animals in comfortable order for the next long\nrainy season, during which time, when other work would be at a\nstandstill, we could carry on many minor details for the improvement of\nthe abode."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We levelled the floors first with clay; then spread gravel mixed with\nmelted gypsum over that, producing a smooth hard surface, which did\nvery well for most of the apartments; but I was ambitious of having one\nor two carpets, and set about making a kind of felt in the following\nway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I spread out a large piece of sailcloth, and covered it equally all\nover with a strong liquid, made of glue and isinglass, which saturated\nit thoroughly. On it we then laid wool and hair from the sheep and\ngoats, which had been carefully cleaned and prepared, and rolled and\nbeat it until it adhered tolerably smoothly to the cloth. Finally it\nbecame, when perfectly dry, a covering for the floor of our\nsitting-room by no means to be despised."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One morning, just after these labours at the salt-cave were completed,\nhappening to awake unusually early, I turned my thoughts, as I lay\nwaiting for sunrise, to considering what length of time we had now\npassed on this coast, and discovered, to my surprise, that the very\nnext day would be the anniversary of our escape from the wreck. My\nheart swelled with gratitude to the gracious God, who had then granted\nus deliverance, and ever since had loaded us with benefits; and I\nresolved to set tomorrow apart as a day of thanksgiving, in joyful\ncelebration of the occasion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My mind was full of indefinite plans when I rose, and the day's work\nbegan as usual. I took care that everything should be cleaned, cleared\nand set in order both outside and inside our dwelling: none, however,\nsuspecting that there was any particular object in view. Other more\nprivate preparations I also made for the next day. At supper I made the\ncoming event known to the assembled family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Good people! do you know that tomorrow is a very great and important\nday? We shall have to keep it in honour of our merciful escape to this\nland, and call it Thanksgiving-Day.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone was surprised to hear that we had already been twelve months\nin the countryâ€”indeed, my wife believed I might be mistaken, until I\nshowed her how I had calculated regularly ever since the 31st of\nJanuary, on which day we were wrecked, by marking off in my almanac the\nSundays as they arrived for the remaining eleven months of that year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Since then,' I added, 'I have counted thirty-one days. This is the 1st\nof February. We landed on the 2nd; therefore tomorrow is the\nanniversary of the day of our escape. As my bookseller has not sent me\nan almanac for the present year, we must henceforth reckon for\nourselves.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, that will be good fun for us,' said Ernest. 'We must have a long\nstick, like Robinson Crusoe, and cut a notch in it every day, and count\nthem up every now and then, to see how the weeks and months and years\ngo by.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is all very well, if you know for certain the number of days in\neach month, and in the year. What do you say, Ernest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The year contains 365 days, 5 hours, 48 minutes and 45 seconds,'\nreturned he promptly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Perfectly correct!' said I, smiling, 'but you would get in a mess with\nthose spare hours, minutes, and seconds in a year or two, wouldn't\nyou?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not at all! Every four years I would add them all together, make a\nday, stick it into February, and call that year leap year.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, Professor Ernest! We must elect you astronomer royal in\nthis our kingdom, and let you superintend and regulate everything\nconnected with the lapse of time, clocks and watches included.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before they went to sleep, I could hear my boys whispering among\nthemselves, about 'father's mysterious allusions' to next day's\nfestival and rejoicings; but I offered no explanation, and went to\nsleep, little guessing that the rogues had laid a counter-plot, far\nmore surprising than my simple plan for their diversion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing less than a roar of artillery startled me from sleep at\ndaybreak next morning. I sprang up and found my wife as much alarmed as\nI was by the noise, otherwise I should have been inclined to believe it\nfancy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz! Dress quickly and come with me!' cried I, turning to his\nhammock. Lo, it was empty! Neither he nor Jack were to be seen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Altogether bewildered, I was hastily dressing, when their voices were\nheard, and they rushed in shouting:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah! Didn't we rouse you with a right good thundering salute?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But perceiving at a glance that we had been seriously alarmed, Fritz\nhastened to apologize for the thoughtless way in which they had sought\nto do honour to the Day of Thanksgiving, without considering that an\nunexpected cannon-shot would startle us unpleasantly from our slumbers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We readily forgave the authors of our alarm, in consideration of the\ngood intention which had prompted the deed, and, satisfied that the day\nhad at least been duly inaugurated, we all went quietly to breakfast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Afterwards we sat together for a long time, enjoying the calm beauty of\nthe morning, and talking of all that had taken place on the memorable\ndays of the storm a year ago; for I desired that the awful events of\nthat time should live in the remembrance of my children with a\ndeepening sense of gratitude of our deliverance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Therefore I read aloud passages from my journal, as well as many\nbeautiful verses from the Psalms, expressive of joyful praise and\nthanksgiving, so that even the youngest among us was impressed and\nsolemnized at the recollections of escape from a terrible death, and\nalso led to bless and praise the name of the Lord our Deliverer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Dinner followed shortly after this happy service, and I then announced\nfor the afternoon a 'Grand Display of Athletic Sports', in which I and\nmy wife were to be spectators and judges."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father, what a grand idea!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, how jolly! Are we to run races?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And prizes! Will there be prizes, father?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The judges offer prizes for competition in every sort of manly\nexercise,' replied I. 'Shooting, running, riding, leaping, climbing,\nswimming, we will have an exhibition of your skill in all. Now for it!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Trumpeters! Sound for the opening of the lists.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Uttering these last words in a stentorian voice and wildly waving my\narms towards a shady spot, where the ducks and geese were quietly\nresting, had the absurd effect I intended."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Up they all started in a fright, gabbling and quacking loudly, to the\ninfinite amusement of the children, who began to bustle about in eager\npreparations for the contest, and begging to know with what they were\nto begin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Let us have shooting first, and the rest when the heat of the day\ndeclines. Here is a mark I have got ready for you,' said I, producing a\nboard roughly shaped like a kangaroo, and of about the size of one.\nThis target was admired, but Jack could not rest satisfied till he had\nadded ears, and a long leather strap for a tail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was then fixed in the attitude most characteristic of the creature,\nand the distance for firing measured off. Each of the three competitors\nwas to fire twice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz hit the kangaroo's head each time; Ernest hit the body once; and\nJack, by a lucky chance, shot the ears clean away from the head, which\nfeat raised a shout of laughter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A second trial with pistols ensued, in which Fritz again came off\nvictor."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then desiring the competitors to load with small shot, I threw a\nlittle board as high as I possibly could up in the air, each in turn\naiming at and endeavouring to hit it before it touched the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In this I found to my surprise that the sedate Ernest succeeded quite\nas well as his more impetuous brother Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As for Jack, his flying board escaped wholly uninjured. After this\nfollowed archery, which I liked to encourage, foreseeing that a time\nmight come when ammunition would fail; and in this practise I saw with\npleasure that my elder sons were really skilful, while even little\nFranz acquitted himself well."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A pause ensued, and then I started a running match. Fritz, Ernest and\nJack were to run to Falconhurst, by the most direct path. The first to\nreach the tree was to bring me, in proof of his success, a penknife I\nhad accidentally left on the table in my sleeping-room."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At a given signal, away went the racers in fine style. Fritz and Jack,\nputting forth all their powers, took the lead at once, running in\nadvance of Ernest, who started at a good steady pace, which I predicted\nhe would be better able to maintain than such a furious rate as his\nbrothers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But long before we expected to see them back, a tremendous noise of\ngalloping caused us to look with surprise towards the bridge, and Jack\nmade his appearance, thundering along on his buffalo, with the onager\nand the donkey tearing after him riderless, and the whole party in the\nwildest spirits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hollo!' cried I. 'What sort of foot-race do you call this, Master\nJack?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He shouted merrily as he dashed up to us; then flinging himself off,\nand saluting us in a playful way:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I very soon saw,' said he, 'that I hadn't a chance; so renouncing all\nidea of the prize, I caught Storm, and made him gallop home with me, to\nbe in time to see the others come puffing in. Lightfoot and old Grizzle\nchose to join meâ€”I never invited them!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By and by the other boys arrived, Ernest holding up the knife in token\nof being the winner; and after hearing all particulars about the\nrunning, and that he had reached Falconhurst two minutes before Fritz,\nwe proceeded to test the climbing powers of the youthful athletes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In this exercise Jack performed wonders. He ascended with remarkable\nagility the highest palms whose stems he could clasp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And when he put on the shark-skin buskins, which enabled him to take\nfirm hold of larger trees, he played antics like a squirrel or a\nmonkey: peeping and grinning at us, at first on one side of the stem,\nand then on the other, in a most diverting way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and Ernest climbed well, but could not come near the grace and\nskill of their active and lively young brother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Riding followed, and marvellous feats were performed, Fritz and Jack\nproving themselves very equal in their management of their different\nsteeds. I thought the riding was over, when little Franz appeared from\nthe stable in the cave, leading young Grumble the bull-calf, with a\nneat saddle of kangaroo hide, and a bridle passed through his nose\nring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The child saluted us with a pretty little air of confidence,\nexclaiming:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, most learned judges, prepare to see something quite new and\nwonderful! The great bull-tamer, Milo of Crotona, desires the honour of\nexhibiting before you.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then taking a whip, and holding the end of a long cord he made the\nanimal, at the word of command, walk, trot and gallop in a circle round\nhim. He afterwards mounted, and showed off Grumble's somewhat awkward\npaces."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sports were concluded by swimming-matches, and the competitors\nfound a plunge in salt water very refreshing after their varied\nexertions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz showed himself a master in the art. At home in the element, no\nmovement betokened either exertion or weariness. Ernest exhibited too\nmuch anxiety and effort, while Jack was far too violent and hasty, and\nsoon became exhausted. Franz gave token of future skill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time, as it was getting late, we returned to our dwelling, my\nwife having preceded us in order to make arrangements for the ceremony\nof prize-giving."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We found her seated in great state, with the prizes set out by her\nside."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys marched in, pretending to play various instruments in\nimitation of a band, and then all four, bowing respectfully, stood\nbefore her, like the victors in a tournament of old, awaiting the\nreward of valour from the Queen of Beauty, which she bestowed with a\nfew words of praise and encouragement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, to his immense delight, received as the prize for shooting and\nswimming, a splendid double-barrelled rifle, and a beautiful\nhunting-knife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To Ernest, as winner of the running-match, was given a handsome gold\nwatch."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For climbing and riding, Jack had a pair of silver-plated spurs, and a\nriding whip, both of which gave him extraordinary pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz received a pair of stirrups, and a driving whip made of\nrhinoceros hide, which we thought would be of use to him in the\ncharacter of bull-trainer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the ceremony was supposed to be over, I advanced, and solemnly\npresented to my wife a lovely work-box, filled with every imaginable\nrequirement for a lady's work-table, which she accepted with equal\nsurprise and delight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The whole entertainment afforded the boys such intense pleasure, and\ntheir spirits rose to such a pitch, that nothing would serve them but\nanother salvo of artillery in order to close with befitting dignity and\nhonour so great a day. They gave me no peace till they had leave to\nsquander some gunpowder, and then at last their excited feelings\nseeming relieved, we were able to sit down to supper; shortly\nafterwards we joined in family worship and retired to rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Soon after the great festival of our grand Thanksgiving Day I\nrecollected that it was now the time when, the figs at Falconhurst\nbeing ripe, immense flocks of ortolans and wild pigeons were attracted\nthither, and as we had found those preserved last year of the greatest\nuse among our stores of winter provisions, I would not miss the\nopportunity of renewing our stock; and therefore, laying aside the\nbuilding work, we removed with all speed to our home in the tree, where\nsure enough we found the first detachment of the birds already busy\nwith the fruit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In order to spare ammunition, I resolved to concoct a strong sort of\nbird-lime, of which I had read in some account of the Palm Islanders,\nwho make it of fresh caoutchouc mixed with oil, and of so good a\nquality that it has been known to catch even peacocks and turkeys."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and Jack were therefore dispatched to collect some fresh\ncaoutchouc from the trees, and as this involved a good gallop on Storm\nand Lightfoot, they nothing loth set off."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They took a supply of calabashes, in which to bring the gum, and we\nfound it high time to manufacture a fresh stock of these useful\nvessels. I was beginning to propose an expedition to the Gourd-tree\nwood, regretting the time it would take to go such a distance, when my\nwife reminded me of her plantation near the potato-field."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There to our joy we found that all the plants were flourishing, and\ncrops of gourds and pumpkins, in all stages of ripeness, covered the\nground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Selecting a great number suited to our purpose, we hastened home, and\nbegan the manufacture of basins, dishes, plates, flasks and spoons of\nall sorts and sizes, with even greater success than before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the riders returned with the caoutchouc, they brought several\nnovelties besides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A crane, for example, shot by Fritz, and an animal which they called a\nmarmot, but which to me seemed much more like a badger."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Aniseed, turpentine and wax berries for candles, they had also\ncollected, and a curious root which they introduced by the name of the\nmonkey plant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And pray wherefore \"monkey plant\", may I ask?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, for this reason, father,' answered Fritz. 'We came upon an open\nspace in the forest near Woodlands, and perceived a troop of monkeys,\napparently engaged as Jack said, in cultivating the soil! Being curious\nto make out what they were at, we tied up the dogs, as well as Storm\nand Lightfoot, and crept near enough to see that the apes were most\nindustriously grubbing up and eating roots. This they did in a way that\nnearly choked us with laughter, for when the root was rather hard to\npull up, and the leaves were torn off, they seized it firmly in their\nteeth, and flung themselves fairly heels-over-head in the most\nludicrous fashion you ever saw, and up came the root unable to resist\nthe leverage!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Of course we wanted to see what this dainty morsel was like, so we\nloosed the dogs, and the apes cleared out double quick, leaving plenty\nof the roots about. We tasted them, and thought them very nice. Will\nyou try one?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The plant was quite new to me, but I imagined it might be what is\ncalled in China 'ginseng', and there prized and valued beyond\neverything. The children being curious to hear more about this\nginseng, I continued:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In China it is considered so strengthening and wholesome, that it is\nused as a sort of universal medicine, being supposed to prolong human\nlife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The emperor alone has the right to permit it to be gathered, and\nguards are placed round land where it grows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ginseng is to be found in Tartary, and has lately been discovered in\nCanada; it is cultivated in Pennsylvania, because the Americans\nintroduce it secretly into China as smuggled merchandise.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz then continued:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After this we went on to Woodlands; but mercy on us! What a confusion\nthe place was in! Everything smashed or torn, and covered with mud and\ndirt; the fowls terrified, the sheep and goats scattered, the contents\nof the rooms dashed about as if a whirlwind had swept through the\nhouse.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What!' I exclaimed, while my wife looked horrified at the news,\nconjuring up in her imagination hordes of savages who would soon come\nand lay waste Falconhurst and Tentholm as well as Woodlands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How can that have happened? Did you discover the authors of all this\nmischief?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh,' said Jack, 'it was easy to see that those dreadful monkeys had\ndone it all. First they must have got into the yards and sheds, and\nhunted the fowls and creatures about; and then I daresay the cunning\nrascals put a little monkey in at some small opening, and bid him\nunfasten the shuttersâ€”you know what nimble fingers they have. Then of\ncourse the whole posse of them swarmed into our nice tidy cottage and\nskylarked with every single thing they could lay paws on, till perhaps\nthey got hungry all at once, and bethought them of the \"ginseng\", as\nyou call it, out in the woods yonder, where we found them so busy\nrefreshing themselves, the mischievous villains!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While we were gazing at all this ruin in a sort of bewilderment,'\npursued Fritz, 'we heard a sound of rushing wings and strange ringing\ncries as of multitudes of birds passing high above us, and looking up\nwe perceived them flying quickly in a wedge-shaped flock at a great\nheight in the air. They began gradually to descend, taking the\ndirection of the lake, and separated into a number of small detachments\nwhich followed in a long straight line, and at a slower rate, the\nmovements of the leaders, who appeared to be examining the\nneighbourhood. We could now see what large birds they must be, but\ndared not show ourselves or follow them, lest they should take alarm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Presently, and with one accord, they quickened their motion, just as\nif the band had begun to play a quick march after a slow one, and\nrapidly descended to earth in a variety of lively ways, and near enough\nfor us to see that they must be cranes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Some alighted at once, while others hovered sportively over them. Many\ndarted to the ground, and, just touching it, would soar again upward\nwith a strong but somewhat heavy flight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After gambolling in this way for a time, the whole multitude, as\nthough at the word of command, alighted on the rice-fields, and began\nto feast on the fresh grain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We thought now was our time to get a shot at the cranes and\ncautiously approached; but they were too cunning to let themselves be\nsurprised, and we came unexpectedly upon their outposts or sentinels,\nwho instantly sprang into the air uttering loud trumpet-like cries,\nupon which the whole flock arose and followed them with a rush like a\nsudden squall of wind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We were quite startled, and it was useless to attempt a shot; but\nunwilling to miss the chance of securing at least one of the birds, I\nhastily unhooded my eagle, and threw him into the air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'With a piercing cry he soared away high above them, then shot\ndownwards like an arrow, causing wild confusion among the cranes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The one which the eagle attacked, sought to defend itself; a struggle\nfollowed, and they came together to the ground not far from where we\nstood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hastening forward, to my grief I found the beautiful crane already\ndead. The eagle, luckily unhurt, was rewarded with a small pigeon from\nmy game-bag."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After this we went back to Woodlands, got some turpentine and a bag of\nriceâ€”and set off for home.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz's interesting story being ended, and supper ready, we made trial\nof the new roots, and found them very palatable, either boiled or\nstewed; the monkey plant, however, if it really proved to be the\nginseng of the Chinese, would require to be used with caution, being of\nan aromatic and heating nature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We resolved to transplant a supply of both roots to our kitchen\ngarden."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 10"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the following morning we were early astir; and as soon as breakfast\nwas over, we went regularly to work with the bird-lime. The tough,\nadhesive mixture of caoutchouc oil and turpentine turned out well."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys brought rods, which I smeared over, and made them place among\nthe upper branches, where the fruit was plentiful, and the birds most\ncongregated."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The prodigious number of the pigeons, far beyond those of last year,\nreminded me that we had not then, as now, witnessed their arrival at\ntheir feeding-places, but had seen only the last body of the season, a\nmere party of stragglers, compared to the masses which now weighed down\nthe branches of all the trees in the neighbourhood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sweet acorns of the evergreen oaks were also patronized; large\nflocks were there congregated; and from the state of the ground under\nthe trees it was evident that at night they roosted on the branches.\nSeeing this, I determined to make a raid upon them by torchlight, after\nthe manner of the colonists in Virginia."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meantime, the bird-lime acted well: the pigeons alighting, stuck fast.\nThe more they fluttered and struggled, the more completely were they\nbedaubed with the tenacious mixture, and at length, with piteous cries,\nfell to the ground, bearing the sticks with them. The birds were then\nremoved, fresh lime spread, and the snare set again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys quickly became able to carry on the work without my\nassistance; so, leaving it to them, I went to prepare torches, with\npinewood and turpentine, for the night attack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack presently brought a very pretty pigeon, unlike the rest, to show\nme, as he felt unwilling to kill it; and seeing that it must be one of\nour own European breed, which we wished to preserve until their numbers\ngreatly increased, I took the trembling captive, and gently cleaned its\nfeet and wings with oil and ashes from the stiff, sticky mess with\nwhich it was bedaubed, placing it then in a wicker cage, and telling\nJack to bring me any others like it which were caught. This he did; and\nwe secured several pairs, greatly to my satisfaction, as having\nnecessarily let them go free when we landed, they had become quite\nwild, and we derived no advantage from them: whereas now we would have\na cot, and pigeon-pie whenever we liked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When evening drew on, we set out for the wood of sweet acorns,\nprovided merely with long bamboo canes, torches and canvas sacks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These weapons appeared very curious, and insufficient to the children;\nbut their use was speedily apparent: for darkness having come upon us\nalmost before we reached the wood, I lighted the torches, and\nperceived, as I expected, that every branch was thickly laden with\nortolans and wild pigeons, who were roosting there in amazing numbers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Suddenly aroused by the glare of light, confusion prevailed among the\nterrified birds, who fluttered helplessly through the branches, dazzled\nand bewildered, and many falling, even before we began to use the\nsticks, were picked up, and put in the bags."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When we beat and struck the branches, it was as much as my wife and\nFranz could do to gather up the quantities of pigeons that soon lay on\nthe ground. The sacks were speedily quite full. We turned homewards,\nand on reaching Falconhurst, put our booty in safety, and gladly\nwithdrew to rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The following day was wholly occupied in plucking, boiling, roasting\nand stewing, so that we could find time for nothing else; but next\nmorning a great expedition to Woodlands was arranged, that measures\nmight there be taken to prevent a repetition of the monkey invasion. I\nhoped, could I but catch the mischievous rascals at their work of\ndestruction, to inflict upon them such a chastisement as would\neffectually make them shun the neighbourhood of our farm for the\nfuture."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife provided us with a good store of provisions, as we were likely\nto be absent several days, while she, with Franz and Turk, remained at\nhome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took with me abundance of specially prepared birdlime, far stronger\nthan that which we used for the pigeons; a number of short posts,\nplenty of string, and a supply of cocoanut shells and gourds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The buffalo carried all these things, and one or two of the boys\nbesides. I myself bestrode the ass, and in due time we arrived at a\nconvenient spot in the forest, near Woodlands, well concealed by thick\nbushes and underwood, where we made a little encampment, pitching the\nsmall tent and tethering the animals. The dogs, too, were tied up, lest\nthey should roam about, and betray our presence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We found the cottage quite quiet and deserted; and I lost no time in\npreparing for the reception of visitors, hoping to be all ready for\nthem, and out of sight before they arrived."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We drove the stakes lightly into the ground, so as to form an\nirregular paling round the house, winding string in and out in all\ndirections between them, thus making a kind of labyrinth, through which\nit would be impossible to pass without touching either the stakes or\nthe cords."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everything was plentifully besmeared with bird-lime; and basins of the\nmixture were set in all directions, strewed with rice, maize, and other\ndainties for bait."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Night came without any interruption to our proceedings; and all being\nthen accomplished, we retired to rest beneath the shelter of our little\ntent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Very early in the morning we heard a confused noise, such as we knew\nbetokened the approach of a large number of apes. We armed ourselves\nwith strong clubs and cudgels, and holding the dogs in leash, made our\nway silently behind the thickets, till, ourselves unseen, we could\ncommand a view of all that went on; and strange indeed was the scene\nwhich ensued!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The noise of rustling, crackling and creaking among the branches, with\nhorrid cries, and shrieks, and chattering, increased to a degree\nsufficient to make us perfectly giddy; and then out from the forest\npoured the whole disorderly rabble of monkeys, scrambling, springing,\nleaping from the trees, racing and tumbling across the grassy space\ntowards the house; when, at once attracted by the novelties they saw,\nthey made for the jars and bowls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They seemed innumerable; but the confused, rapid way in which they\nswarmed hither and thither, made it difficult to judge accurately of\ntheir numbers. They dashed fearlessly through and over the palings in\nall directions, some rushing at the eatables, some scrambling on to the\nroof, where they commenced tugging at the wooden pegs, with a view to\nforcing an entrance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Gradually, however, as they rambled over the place, all in turn became\nbesmeared with our bird-lime on head, paws, back or breast. The\nwretched predicament of the apes increased every instant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some sat down, and with the most ludicrous gestures, tried to clean\nthemselves. Others were hopelessly entangled in stakes and cordage,\nwhich they trailed about after them, looking the picture of bewildered\ndespair."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Others, again, endeavoured to help one another, and stuck fast\ntogether: the more they pulled, and tugged, and kicked, the worse\nbecame their plight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many had the gourds and cocoanut shells lumbering and clattering about\nwith them, their paws having been caught when they sought to obtain the\nrice or fruit we had put for bait."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Most ridiculous of all was the condition of one old fellow, who had\nfound a calabash, containing palm wine, and, eagerly drinking it, was\nimmediately fitted with a mask, for the shell stuck to his forehead and\nwhiskers, of course covering his eyes; and he blundered about, cutting\nthe wildest capers in his efforts to get rid of the encumbrance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Numbers took to flight; but, as we had spread bird-lime on several of\nthe trees around, many apes found themselves fixed to, or hanging from\nthe branches, where they remained in woeful durance, struggling and\nshrieking horribly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The panic being now general, I loosed the three dogs, whose impatience\nhad been almost uncontrollable, and who now rushed to the attack of the\nunfortunate monkeys, as though burning with zeal to execute justice\nupon desperate criminals."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The place soon had the appearance of a ghastly battlefield; for we were\nobliged to do our part with the clubs and sticks, till the din of\nhowling, yelling, barking, in every conceivable tone of rage and pain,\ngave place to an awful silence, and we looked with a shudder on the\nshocking spectacle around us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At least forty apes lay mangled and dead, and the boys began to be\nquite sad and downhearted, till I, fully sharing their feelings,\nhastened to turn their thoughts to active employment in removing and\nburying the slain, burning the stakes, cordage, bowls, everything\nconcerned in the execution of our deadly stratagem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After that we betook ourselves to the task of restoring order to our\ndismantled cottage; and seeking for the scattered flock of sheep,\ngoats, and poultry, we gradually collected them, hoping to settle them\nonce more peacefully in their yards and sheds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While thus engaged, we repeatedly heard a sound as of something heavy\nfalling from a tree. On going to look, we found three splendid birds,\ncaught on some of the limed sticks we had placed loose in the branches."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Two of these proved to be a variety of the Blue Molucca pigeon; the\nthird I assumed to be the Nicobar pigeon, having met with descriptions\nof its resplendent green, bronze, and steely-blue plumage; and I was\npleased to think of domesticating them, and establishing them as first\ntenants of a suitable dwelling near the cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'First tenants, father!' said Fritz. 'Do you expect to catch more like\nthese?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Not exactly catch them; I mean to practise a secret art. Much can be\ndone by magic, Fritz!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Further explanation I declined to give."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few days, Woodlands was once more set in order, and everything\nsettled and comfortable, so that we returned without further adventure\nto Falconhurst, where we were joyfully welcomed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every one agreed that we must go at once to Tentholm, to make the\nproposed pigeon-house in the rock. Several other things there also\nrequiring our attention, we made arrangements for a prolonged stay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My plan for the pigeon-house was to hollow out an ample space in the\ncliff, facing towards Jackal river, and close to our rocky home,\nfitting that up with partitions, perches and nesting-places; while a\nlarge wooden front was fitted on to the opening, with entrance-holes,\nslides, or shutters, and a broad platform in front, where the birds\ncould rest, and walk about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When, after the work of a few weeks, we thought it was fit for\nhabitation, I set the other children to work at some distance from our\ncavern, and summoning Fritz:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, my faithful assistant,' said I, 'it is time to conjure the new\ncolonists to their settlement here. Yes,' I continued, laughing at his\npuzzled look. 'I mean to play a regular pigeon-dealer's trick. You must\nknow such gentry are very ingenious, not only in keeping their own\npigeons safe, but in adding to their numbers by attracting those of\nother people. All I want is some soft clay, aniseed and salt, of which\nI will compound a mixture, which our birds will like very much, and the\nsmell of which will bring others to share it with them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I can easily get you those things, father.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I shall want some oil of aniseed besides,' said I, 'to put on the\npigeon-holes, so that the birds' feathers may touch it as they pass in\nand out, and become scented with what will attract the wild pigeons.\nThis I can obtain by pounding aniseed; therefore, bring me the mortar\nand some oil.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When this was strongly impregnated with the aromatic oil from the\nseeds (for I did not purpose to distill it in regular style), I\nstrained it through a cloth, pressing it strongly: the result answered\nmy purpose, and the scent would certainly remain for some days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All my preparations being completed, the pigeons were installed in\ntheir new residence, and the slides closed. The European birds were by\nthis time quite friendly with the three beautiful strangers; and when\nthe other boys came home, and scrambled up the ladder to peep in at a\nlittle pane of glass I had fixed in front, they saw them all\ncontentedly picking up grain, and pecking at the 'magic food', as Fritz\ncalled it, although he did not betray my secret arts to his brothers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Early on the third morning I aroused Fritz, and directed him to ascend\nthe rope ladder, and arrange a cord on the sliding door of the\ndove-cot, by which it could be opened or closed from below. Also he\npoured fresh aniseed oil all about the entrance, after which we\nreturned, and awoke the rest of the family, telling them that if they\nliked to make haste, they might see me let the pigeons fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everybody came to the dove-cot, understanding that some ceremony was to\nattend the event, and I waved a wand with mock solemnity, while I\nmuttered a seeming incantation, and then gave Fritz a sign to draw up\nthe sliding panel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently out popped the pretty heads of the captives, the soft eyes\nglanced about in all directions; they withdrew, they ventured forth\nagain, they came timidly out on 'the verandah', as little Franz\nexpressed it; then, as though suddenly startled, the whole party took\nwing, with the shrill whizzing sound peculiar to the flight of pigeons,\nand circling above us, they rose higher, higher, finally darting quite\nout of sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we were yet gazing after them, they reappeared, and settled\nquietly on the dove-cot; but as we congratulated ourselves on a return\nwhich showed they accepted this as a home, up sprang the three blue\npigeons, the noble foreigners, for whom chiefly I had planned the\nhouse, and rising in circles high in air, winged their rapid way direct\ntowards Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Their departure had such air of determination and resolve about it,\nthat I feared them lost to us for ever."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Endeavouring to console ourselves by petting our four remaining birds,\nwe could not forget this disappointment, and all day long the dove-cot\nremained the centre of attraction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing, however, was seen of the fugitives until about the middle of\nnext day; when most of us were hard at work inside the cavern, Jack\nsprang in full of excitement, exclaiming:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'He is there! He is come! He really is!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Who? Who is there? What do you mean?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The blue pigeon, to be sure! Hurrah! Hurrah!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, nonsense!' said Ernest. 'You want to play us a trick.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why should it be \"nonsense\"?' cried I. 'I fully believe we shall see\nthem all soon!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Out ran everybody to the dove-cot, and there, sure enough, stood the\npretty fellow, but not alone, for he was billing and cooing to a mate,\na stranger of his own breed, apparently inviting her to enter his\ndwelling; for he popped in and out at the door, bowing, sidling, and\ncooing, in a most irresistible manner, until the shy little lady\nyielded to his blandishments, and tripped daintily in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, let's shut the door. Pull the cord and close the panel!' shouted\nthe boys, making a rush at the string."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop!' cried I. 'Let the string alone! I won't have you frighten the\nlittle darlings. Besides, the others will be comingâ€”would you shut the\ndoor in their faces?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Here they come! Here they come!' exclaimed Fritz, whose keen eye\nmarked the birds afar, and to our delight the second blue pigeon\narrived, likewise with a mate, whom, after a pretty little flirtation\nscene of real and assumed modesty on her part, he succeeded in leading\nhome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The third and handsomest of the new pigeons was the last in making his\nappearance. Perhaps he had greater difficulty than the others in\nfinding a mate as distinguished in rank and beauty as himself. However,\nwe fully expected them, and the boys talked of the arrival of 'Mr. and\nMrs. Nicobar' as a matter of course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Late in the day Franz and his mother went out to provide for supper,\nbut the child returned directly, exclaiming that we must hasten to the\ndove-cot to see something beautiful."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Accordingly a general rush was made out of the cave, and we saw with\ndelight that the third stranger also had returned with a lovely bride,\nand encouraged by the presence of the first arrivals, they soon made\nthemselves at home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a short time nest-building commenced, and among the materials\ncollected by the birds, I observed a long grey moss or lichen, and\nthought it might very possibly be the same which, in the West Indies,\nis gathered from the bark of old trees, where it grows, and hangs in\ngreat tuft-like beards, to be used instead of horse-hair for stuffing\nmattresses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife no sooner heard of it, than her active brain devised fifty\nplans for making it of use. Would we but collect enough, she would\nclean and sort it, and there would be no end to the bolsters, pillows,\nsaddles, and cushions she would stuff with it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For the discovery of nutmegs we had also to thank the pigeons, and they\nwere carefully planted in our orchard. For some time no event of\nparticular note occurred, until at length Jack, as usual, got into a\nscrape causing thereby no little excitement at home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He went off early on one of his own particular private expeditions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was in the habit of doing this that he might surprise us with some\nnew acquisition on his return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This time, however, he came back in most wretched plight, covered with\nmud and green slime; a great bundle of Spanish canes was on his back,\nmuddy and green like himself; he had lost a shoe, and altogether\npresented a ludicrous picture of misery, at which we could have\nlaughed, had he not seemed more ready to cry!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear boy! What has happened to you? Where have you been?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Only in the swamp behind the powder magazine, father,' replied he. 'I\nwent to get reeds for my wickerwork, because I wanted to weave some\nbaskets and hen-coops, and I saw such beauties a little way off in the\nmarsh, much finer than those close by the edge, that I tried to get at\nthem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I jumped from one firm spot to another, till at last I slipped and\nsank over my ankles; I tried to get on towards the reeds, which were\nclose by, but in I went deeper and deeper, till I was above the knees\nin thick soft mud, and there I stuck!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I screamed and shouted, but nobody came, and I can tell you I was in a\nregular fright."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'At last who should appear but my faithful Fangs! He knew my voice and\ncame close up to me, right over the swamp, but all the poor beast could\ndo, was to help me to make a row; I wonder you did not hear us! The\nvery rocks rang, but nothing came of it, so despair drove me to think\nof an expedient. I cut down all the reeds I could reach round and round\nme, and bound them together into this bundle, which made a firm place\non which to lean, while I worked and kicked about to free my feet and\nlegs, and after much struggling, I managed to get astride on the reeds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There I sat, supported above the mud and slime, while Fangs ran\nyelping backwards and forwards between me and the bank, seeming\nsurprised I did not follow. Suddenly I thought of catching hold of his\ntail. He dragged and pulled, and I sprawled, and crawled, and waded,\nsometimes on my reeds like a raft, sometimes lugging them along with\nme, till we luckily got back to terra firma. But I had a near squeak\nfor it, I can tell you.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A fortunate escape indeed, my boy!' cried I, 'And I thank God for it.\nFangs has really acted a heroic part as your deliverer, and you have\nshown great presence of mind. Now go with your mother, and get rid of\nthe slimy traces of your disaster! You have brought me splendid canes,\nexactly what I want for a new scheme of mine.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The fact was, I meant to try to construct a loom for my wife, for I\nknew she understood weaving, so I chose two fine strong reeds, and\nsplitting them carefully, bound them together again, that when dry they\nmight be quite straight and equal, and fit for a frame. Smaller reeds\nwere cut into pieces and sharpened for the teeth of the comb. The boys\ndid this for me without in the least knowing their use, and great fun\nthey made of 'father's monster toothpicks'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In time all the various parts of the loom were made ready and put\ntogether, my wife knowing nothing of it, while to the incessant\nquestions of the children, I replied mysteriously:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, it is an outlandish sort of musical instrument; mother will know\nhow to play upon it.'*"
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "He has forgotten his dictum about truth even in jest."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And when the time came for presenting it, her joy was only equalled by\nthe amusement and interest with which the children watched her\nmovements while 'playing the loom', as they always said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "About this time, a beautiful little foal, a son of the onager, was\nadded to our stud, and as he promised to grow up strong and tractable,\nwe soon saw how useful he would be. The name of 'Swift' was given to\nhim, and he was to be trained for my own riding."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The interior arrangements of the cavern being now well forward, I\napplied myself to contriving an aqueduct, that fresh water might be led\nclose up to our cave, for it was a long way to go to fetch it from\nJackal River, and especially inconvenient on washing days. As I wanted\nto do this before the rainy season began, I set about it at once."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Pipes of hollow bamboo answered the purpose well, and a large cask\nformed the reservoir. The supply was good, and the comfort of having it\nclose at hand so great, that my wife declared she was as well pleased\nwith our engineering as if we had made her a fountain and marble basin\nadorned with mermaids and dolphins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Anticipating the setting-in of the rains, I pressed forward all work\nconnected with stores for the winter, and great was the in-gathering of\nroots, fruits, and grains, potatoes, rice, guavas, sweet acorns,\npine-cones; load after load arrived at the cavern, and my wife's active\nneedle was in constant requisition, as the demand for more sacks and\nbags was incessant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Casks and barrels of all sorts and sizes were pressed into the\nservice, until at last the raft was knocked to pieces, and its tubs\nmade to do duty in the store-rooms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The weather became very unsettled and stormy. Heavy clouds gathered in\nthe horizon, and passing storms of wind, with thunder, lightning, and\ntorrents of rain swept over the face of nature from time to time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sea was in frequent commotion; heavy groundswells drove masses of\nwater hissing and foaming against the cliffs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everything heralded the approaching rains. All nature joined in\nsounding forth the solemn overture to the grandest work of the year."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was now near the beginning of the month of June, and we had twelve\nweeks of bad weather before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We established some of the animals with ourselves at the salt-cave. The\ncow, the ass, Lightfoot, Storm and the dogs, were all necessary to us,\nwhile Knips, Fangs and the eagle were sure to be a great amusement in\nthe long evenings."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys would ride over to Falconhurst very often to see that all was\nin order there, and fetch anything required."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Much remained to be done in order to give the cave a comfortable\nappearance, which became more desirable now that we had to live\nindoors."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The darkness of the inner regions annoyed me, and I set myself to\ninvent a remedy. After some thought, I called in Jack's assistance, and\nwe got a very tall, strong bamboo, which would reach right up to the\nvaulted roof. This we planted in the earthen floor, securing it well by\ndriving wedges in round it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack ascended this pole very cleverly, taking with him a hammer and\nchisel to enlarge a crevice in the roof so as to fix a pulley, by means\nof which, when he descended, I drew up a large ship's lantern, well\nsupplied with oil, and as there were four wicks, it afforded a very\nfair amount of light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Several days were spent in arranging the different rooms. Ernest and\nFranz undertook the library, fixing shelves, and setting the books in\norder. Jack and his mother took in hand the sitting-room and kitchen,\nwhile Fritz and I, as better able for heavy work, arranged the\nworkshops. The carpenter's bench, the turning lathe, and a large chest\nof tools were set in convenient places, and many tools and instruments\nhung on the walls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "An adjoining chamber was kitted up as a forge, with fire-place,\nbellows, and anvil, complete, all which we had found in the ship,\npacked together, and ready to set up."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the great affairs were settled, we still found in all directions\nwork to be done. Shelves, tables, benches, movable steps, cupboards,\npegs, door-handles and boltsâ€”there seemed no end to our requirements,\nand we often thought of the enormous amount of work necessary to\nmaintain the comforts and conveniences of life which at home we had\nreceived as matters of course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But in reality, the more there was to do the better; and I never\nceased contriving fresh improvements, being fully aware of the\nimportance of constant employment as a means of strengthening and\nmaintaining the health of mind and body. This, indeed, with a\nconsciousness of continual progress toward a desirable end, is found to\nconstitute the main element of happiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our rocky home was greatly improved by a wide porch which I made along\nthe whole front of our rooms and entrances, by levelling the ground to\nform a terrace, and sheltering it with a verandah of bamboo, supported\nby pillars of the same."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest and Franz were highly successful as librarians. The books, when\nunpacked and arranged, proved to be a most valuable collection, capable\nof affording every sort of educational advantage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Besides a variety of books of voyages, travels, divinity, and natural\nhistory (several containing fine coloured illustrations), there were\nhistories and scientific works, as well as standard fictions in several\nlanguages; also a good assortment of maps, charts, mathematical and\nastronomical instruments, and an excellent pair of globes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I foresaw much interesting study on discovering that we possessed the\ngrammars and dictionaries of a great many languages, a subject for\nwhich we all had a taste. With French we were well acquainted. Fritz\nand Ernest had begun to learn English at school, and made further\nprogress during a visit to England. Their mother, who had once been\nintimate with a Dutch family, could speak that language pretty well."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After a great deal of discussion, we agreed to study different\nlanguages, so that in the event of meeting with people of other\nnations, there should be at least one of the family able to\ncommunicate with them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All determined to improve our knowledge of German and French. The two\nelder boys were to study English and Dutch with their mother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, already possessing considerable knowledge of Latin, wished to\ncontinue to study it, so as to be able to make use of the many works on\nnatural history and medicine written in that language."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack announced that he meant to learn Spanish 'because it sounded so\ngrand and imposing'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I myself was interested in the Malay language, knowing it to be so\nwidely spoken in the islands of the Eastern Seas, and thinking it as\nlikely as any other to be useful to us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our family circle by and by represented Babel in miniature, for scraps\nand fragments of all these tongues kept buzzing about our ears from\nmorning to night, each sporting his newly acquired word or sentence on\nevery possible occasion, propounding idioms and peculiar expressions\nlike riddles, to puzzle the rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In this way, the labour of learning was very considerably lightened,\nand everyone came to know a few words of each language."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Occasionally we amused ourselves by opening chests and packages\nhitherto untouched, and brought unexpected treasures to\nlightâ€”mirrors, wardrobes, a pair of console tables with polished\nmarble tops, elegant writing tables and handsome chairs, clocks of\nvarious descriptions, a musical-box, and a chronometer were found; and\nby degrees our abode was fitted up like a palace, so that sometimes we\nwondered at ourselves, and felt as though we were strutting about in\nborrowed plumes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The children begged me to decide on a name for our salt cave dwelling,\nand that of Rockburg was chosen unanimously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The weeks of imprisonment passed so rapidly that no one found time hang\nheavy on his hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Books occupied me so much that but little carpentering was done, yet I\nmade a yoke for the oxen, a pair of cotton-wool carders, and a\nspinning-wheel for my wife."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the rainy season drew to a close, the weather for a while became\nwilder, and the storms fiercer than ever. Thunder roared, lightning\nblazed, torrents rushed towards the sea, which came in raging billows\nto meet them, lashed to fury by the tempests of wind which swept the\nsurface of the deep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The uproar of the elements came to an end at last. Nature resumed her\nattitude of repose, her smiling aspect of peaceful beauty; and soon all\ntraces of the ravages of floods and storms would disappear beneath the\nluxuriant vegetation of the tropics."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Gladly quitting the sheltering walls of Rockburg to roam once more in\nthe open air, we crossed Jackal River, for a walk along the coast, and\npresently Fritz with his sharp eyes observed something on the small\nisland near Flamingo Marsh, which was, he said, long and rounded,\nresembling a boat bottom upwards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Examining it with the telescope, I could form no other conjecture, and\nwe resolved to make it the object of an excursion next day, being\ndelighted to resume our old habit of starting in pursuit of adventure.\nThe boat was accordingly got in readiness; it required some repairs,\nand fresh pitching, and then we made for the point of interest,\nindulging in a variety of surmises as to what we should find."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It proved to be a huge stranded whale. The island being steep and\nrocky, it was necessary to be careful; but we found a landing-place on\nthe further side. The boys hurried by the nearest way to the beach\nwhere lay the monster of the deep, while I clambered to the highest\npoint of the islet, which commanded a view of the mainland from\nRockburg to Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On rejoining my sons, I found them only half-way to the great fish, and\nas I drew near they shouted in high glee:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father, just look at the glorious shells and coral branches we are\nfinding! How does it happen that there are such quantities?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Only consider how the recent storms have stirred the ocean to its\ndepths! No doubt thousands of shellfish have been detached from their\nrocks and dashed in all direction by the waves, which have thrown\nashore even so huge a creature as the whale yonder.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes; isn't he a frightful great brute!' cried Fritz. 'Ever so much\nlarger than he seemed from a distance. The worst of it is, one does not\nwell see what use to make of the huge carcase.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, make train oil, to be sure,' said Ernest. 'I can't say he's a\nbeauty, though, and it is much pleasanter to gather these lovely\nshells, than to cut up blubber.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, let us amuse ourselves with them for the present,' said I, 'but\nin the afternoon, when the sea is calmer, we will return with the\nnecessary implements, and see if we can turn the stranded whale to good\naccount.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were soon ready to return to the boat, but Ernest had a fancy for\nremaining alone on the island till we came back, and asked my\npermission to do so, that he might experience, for an hour or two, the\nsensations of Robinson Crusoe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To this, however, I would not consent, assuring him that our fate, as a\nsolitary family, gave him quite sufficient idea of shipwreck on an\nuninhabited island, and that his lively imagination must supply the\nrest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys found it hard work to row back, and began to beg of me to\nexert my wonderful inventive powers in contriving some kind of rowing\nmachine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You lazy fellows!' returned I. 'Give me the great clockwork out of a\nchurch tower, perhaps I might be able to relieve your labours.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh father!' cried Fritz. 'Don't you know there are iron wheels in the\nclockwork of the large kitchen-jacks? I'm sure mother would give them\nup, and you could make something out of them, could you not?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'By the time I have manufactured a rowing-machine out of a\nroasting-jack, I think your arms will be pretty well inured to the use\nof your oars! However, I am far from despising the hint, my dear\nFritz.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Is coral of any use?' demanded Jack suddenly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In former times it was pounded and used by chemists; but it is now\nchiefly used for various ornaments, and made into beads for necklaces\net cetera. As such, it is greatly prized by savages, and were we to\nfall in with natives, we might very possibly find a store of coral\nuseful in bartering with them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For the present we will arrange these treasures of the deep in our\nlibrary, and make them the beginning of a Museum of Natural History,\nwhich will afford us equal pleasure and instruction.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'One might almost say that coral belongs at once to the animal,\nvegetable, and mineral kingdoms,' remarked Fritz; 'it is hard like\nstone, it has stems and branches like a shrub, and I believe tiny\ninsects inhabit the cells, do they not, father?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You are right, Fritz; coral consists of the calcereous cells of\nminute animals, so built up as to form a tree-like structure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The coral fishery gives employment to many men in the Persian Gulf,\nthe Mediterranean Sea, and other places. The instrument commonly used\nconsists of two heavy beams of wood, secured together at right angles,\nand loaded with stones. Hemp and netting are attached to the under side\nof the beams, to the middle of which is fastened one end of a strong\nrope, by which the apparatus is let down from a boat, and guided to the\nspots where the coral is most abundant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The branches of the coral become entangled in the hemp and network;\nthey are broken off from the rock, and are drawn to the surface of the\nwater."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Left undisturbed, these coral insects, labouring incessantly, raise\nfoundations, on which, in course of time, fertile islands appear,\nclothed with verdure, and inhabited by man.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why father, here we are at the landing-place!' exclaimed Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It has seemed quite easy to pull since you began to tell us such\ninteresting things.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very interesting, indeed; but did you notice that the wind had\nchanged, Jack?' remarked Ernest as he shipped his oar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The animated recital of our adventures, the sight of the lovely shells\nand corals, and the proposed work for the afternoon, inspired my wife\nand Franz with a great wish to accompany us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To this I gladly consented, only stipulating that we should go\nprovided with food, water and a compass. 'For,' said I, 'the sea has\nonly just ceased from its raging, and being at the best of times of\nuncertain and capricious nature, we may chance to be detained on the\nisland, or forced to land at a considerable distance from home.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Dinner was quickly dispatched, and preparations set on foot. The more\noil we could obtain the better, for a great deal was used in the large\nlantern which burnt day and night in the recesses of the cave;\ntherefore all available casks and barrels were pressed into the\nservice; many, of course, once full of pickled herrings, potted pigeons\nand other winter stores, were now empty, and we took a goodly fleet of\nthese in tow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Knives, hatchets, and the boys' climbing buskins, were put on board,\nand we set forth, the labour of the oar being greater than ever, now\nthat our freight was so much increased."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sea being calm, and the tide suiting better, we found it easy to\nland close to the whale; my first care was to place the boat, as well\nas the casks, in perfect security, after which we proceeded to a close\ninspection of our prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Its enormous size quite startled my wife and little boy; the length\nbeing from sixty to sixty-five feet, and the girth between thirty and\nforty, while the weight could not have been less than 50,000 lbs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The color was a uniform velvety black, and the enormous head about\none-third of the length of the entire hulk, the eyes quite small, not\nmuch larger than those of an ox, and the ears almost undiscernable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The jaw opened very far back, and was nearly sixteen feet in length,\nthe most curious part of its structure being the remarkable substance\nknown as whalebone, masses of which appeared all along the jaws, solid\nat the base, and splitting into a sort of fringe at the extremity. This\narrangement is for the purpose of aiding the whale in procuring its\nfood, and separating it from the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The tongue was remarkably large, soft, and full of oil; the opening of\nthe throat wonderfully small, scarcely two inches in diameter."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, what can the monster eat?' exclaimed Fritz; 'he can never\nswallow a proper mouthful down this little gullet!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The mode of feeding adopted by the whale is so curious,' I replied,\n'that I must explain it to you before we begin work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This animal (for I should tell you that a whale is not a fish; he\npossess no gills, he breathes atmospheric air, and would be drowned if\ntoo long detained below the surface of the water); this animal, then,\nfrequents those parts of the ocean best supplied with the various\ncreatures on which he feeds. Shrimps, small fish, lobsters, various\nmolluscs, and medusae form his diet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Driving with open mouth through the congregated shoals of these\nlittle creatures, the whale engulfs them by millions in his enormous\njaws, and continues his destructive course until he has sufficiently\ncharged his mouth with prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Closing his jaws and forcing out, through the interstices of the\nwhalebone, the water which he has taken with his prey, he retains the\ncaptured animals, and swallows them at his leisure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The nostrils, or blow-holes, are placed, you see, on the upper part of\nthe head, in order that the whale may rise to breathe, and repose on\nthe surface of the sea, showing very little of his huge carcase."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The breathings are called \"spoutings,\" because a column of mixed\nvapor and water is thrown from the blow-holes, sometimes to a height of\ntwenty feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And now, boys,' cried I, 'fasten on your buskins, and let me see if\nyou can face the work of climbing this slippery mountain of flesh, and\ncutting it up.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and Jack stripped, and went to work directly, scrambling over the\nback to the head, where they assisted me to cut away the lips, so as to\nreach the whale bone, a large quantity of which was detached and\ncarried to the boat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest laboured manfully at the creature's side, cutting out slabs of\nblubber, while his mother and Franz helped as well as they could to put\nit in casks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently we had a multitude of unbidden guests. The air was filled by\nthe shrill screams and hoarse croaks and cries of numbers of birds of\nprey; they flew around us in ever narrowing circles, and becoming\nbolder as their voracity was excited by the near view of the tempting\nprey, they alighted close to us, snatching morsels greedily from under\nthe very strokes of our knives and hatchets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our work was seriously interrupted by these feathered marauders, who,\nafter all, were no greater robbers than we ourselves. We kept them off\nas well as we could by blows from our tools, and several were killed,\nmy wife taking possession of them immediately for the sake of the\nfeathers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was nearly time to leave the island, but first I stripped off a long\npiece of the skin, to be used for traces, harness, and other\nleather-work. It was about three-quarters of an inch thick, and very\nsoft and oilyâ€”but I knew it would shrink and be tough and durable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I also took a part of the gums in which the roots of the baleen or\nwhalebone was still embedded, having read that this is considered quite\na delicacy, as well as the skin, which, when properly dressed and cut\nin little cubes, like black dice, has been compared, by enthusiastic\n(and probably very hungry) travellers, to cocoanut and cream-cheese."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys thought the tongue might prove equally palatable, but I\nvalued it only on account of the large quantity of oil it contained."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With a heavy freight we put to sea, and made what haste we could to\nreach home and cleanse our persons from the unpleasant traces of the\ndisgusting work in which we had spent the day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning we started at dawn. My wife and Franz were left behind,\nfor our proposed work was even more horrible than that of the preceding\nday; they could not assist, and had no inclination to witness it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was my intention to open the carcase completely, and, penetrating\nthe interior, to obtain various portions of the intestines, thinking\nthat it would be possible to convert the larger ones into vessels fit\nfor holding the oil."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This time we laid aside our clothes and wore only strong canvas\ntrousers when we commenced operations, which were vigorously carried on\nduring the whole of the day; then, satisfied that we could do so with a\nclear conscience, we abandoned the remains to the birds of prey, and,\nwith a full cargo, set sail for land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the way, it appeared to strike the boys (who had made not the\nslightest objection to the singularly unpleasant task I had set them)\nas very strange that I should wish to possess what they had been\nworking so hard to procure for me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What can have made you wish to bring away that brute's entrails,\nfather? Are they of any use?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There are countries,' I replied, 'where no wood grows of which to make\nbarrels, and no hemp for thread, string and cordage. Necessity, the\nmother of all the more valuable inventions, has taught the inhabitants\nof those countries, Greenlanders, Esquimaux and others, to think of\nsubstitutes, and they use the intestines of the whale for one purpose,\nthe sinews and nerves for the other.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were right glad to land, and get rid, for the present, of our\nunpleasant materials, the further preparation of which was work in\nstore for the following day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A refreshing bath, clean clothes, and supper, cheered us all up, and we\nslept in peace."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 11"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now for the finishing up of this dirty job,' cried I, merrily, as we\nall woke up next morning at daybreak. And after the regular work was\ndone, we commenced operations by raising a stand or rough scaffold on\nwhich the tubs full of blubber were placed and heavily pressed, so that\nthe purest and finest oil overflowed into vessels underneath."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The blubber was afterwards boiled in a cauldron over a fire kindled at\nsome distance from our abode, and by skimming and straining through a\ncoarse cloth, we succeeded in obtaining a large supply of excellent\ntrain oil, which, in casks and bags made of the intestines, was safely\nstowed away in the 'cellar', as the children called our roughest\nstore-room."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This day's work was far from agreeable, and the dreadful smell\noppressed us all, more especially my poor wife, who, nevertheless,\nendured it with her accustomed good temper. However, she very urgently\nrecommended that the new island should be the headquarters for another\ncolony, where, said she, 'any animals we leave would be safe from apes\nand other plunderers, and where you would find it so very convenient to\nboil whale-blubber, strain train oil, and the like'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This proposal met with hearty approval, especially from the boys, who\nwere always charmed with any new plan; and they were eager to act upon\nit at once. But when I reminded them of the putrefying carcase which\nlay there, they confessed it would be better to allow wind and storms,\nbirds and insects to do their work in purging the atmosphere, and\nreducing the whale to a skeleton before we revisited the island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The idea of a rowing-machine kept recurring to my brain, and I\ndetermined to attempt to make one. I took an iron bar, which when laid\nacross the middle of the boat projected about a foot each way. I\nprovided this bar in the middle with ribbed machinery, and at each end\nwith a sort of nave, in which, as in a cart wheel, four flat spokes, or\npaddles, were fixed obliquely. These were intended to do the rowers'\npart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then the jack was arranged to act upon the machinery in the middle of\nthe iron cross-bar, in such a way that one of its strong cogwheels bit\nfirmly into the ribs, so that when it was wound up, it caused the bar\nto revolve rapidly, of course turning with it the paddles fixed at\neither end, which consequently struck the water so as to propel the\nboat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Although this contrivance left much to be desired in the way of\nimprovement, still when Fritz and I wound up the machinery, and went\noff on a trial trip across the bay, we splashed along at such a famous\nrate, that the shores rang with the cheers and clapping of the whole\nfamily, delighted to behold what they considered my brilliant success."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone wanted to go on board, and take a cruise, but as it was\ngetting late, I could not consent. A trip next day, however, was\npromised to Cape Disappointment and the little settlement of Prospect\nHill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This proposal satisfied everybody. The evening was spent in preparing\nthe dresses, arms and food which would be required, and we retired\nearly to rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Intending to be out all day, the house was left in good order, and we\ndeparted on our expedition, provided, among other things, with spades\nand mattocks, for I wished to get young cocoanut trees and shrubs of\ndifferent kinds, that, on our way back, we might land on Whale Island,\nand begin our plantation there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We directed our course towards the opposite side of the bay. The sea\nwas smooth, my rowing-machine performed its work easily, and leaving\nSafety Bay and Shark Island behind us, we enjoyed at our ease the\npanorama of all the coast scenery."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Landing near Prospect Hill, we moored the boat, and walked through the\nwoods to our little farm, obtaining some fresh cocoanuts, as well as\nyoung plants, on the way."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before coming in sight of the cottage at the farm, we heard the cocks\ncrow, and I experienced a sudden rush of emotion as the sound recalled\nin a degree painfully vivid, the recollection of many a ride and walk\nat home, when we would be greeted by just such familiar sounds as we\napproached some kind friend's house. Here, but for the unconscious\nanimals, utter solitude and silence prevailed, and I with my dear\nfamily, whose visit would have been hailed with delight in so many\nhomes, advanced unnoticed to this lonely cottage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So long had been our absence that our arrival created a perfect panic.\nThe original animals had forgotten us, and to their progeny, lambs,\nkids, and chickens, who had never seen the face of man, we seemed an\narmy of fierce foes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys found it impossible to milk the goats, until, by the use of\nthe lasso, they captured them one after the other, bound their legs,\nthen giving them salt to lick, they soon obtained a supply of excellent\nmilk which was poured from the cocoanut shells they used into calabash\nflasks, so that we could take with us what was not required at dinner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The fowls were enticed by handfuls of grain and rice, and my wife\ncaught as many as she wished for."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were by this time very ready for dinner, and the cold provisions we\nhad with us were set forth, the chief dish consisting of the piece of\nwhale's tongue, which, by the boys' desire, had been cooked with a\nspecial view to this entertainment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But woeful was the disappointment when the tongue was tasted! One\nafter another, with dismal face, pronounced it 'horrid stuff,' begged\nfor some pickled herring to take away the taste of train-oil, and\nwillingly bestowed on Fangs the cherished dainty."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fortunately there was a sufficient supply of other eatables, and the\nfresh, delicious cocoanuts and goat's milk put everyone in good humour\nagain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While the mother packed everything up, Fritz and I got some sugar-cane\nshoots which I wished to plant, and then returned to the shore and\nagain embarked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before returning to Whale Island, I felt a strong wish to round Cape\nDisappointment and survey the coast immediately beyond, but the\npromontory maintained the character of its name, and we found that a\nlong sandbank, as well as hidden reefs and rocks, ran out a great way\ninto the sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz espying breakers ahead, we put about at once, and aided by a\nlight breeze, directed our course towards Whale Island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On landing, I began at once to plant the sugar-cane shoots we had\nbrought. The boys assisted me for a while, but wearied somewhat of the\noccupation, and one after another went off in search of shells and\ncoral, leaving their mother and me to finish the work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently Jack came back, shouting loudly:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father! Mother! Do come and look. There is an enormous skeleton lying\nhere; the skeleton of some fearful great beastâ€”a mammoth, I should\nthink.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why Jack!' returned I laughing, 'have you forgot our old\nacquaintance, the whale? What else could it be?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh no, father, it is not the whale. This thing has not fish bones, but\nreal good, honest, huge, beast bones. I don't know what can have become\nof the whaleâ€”floated out to sea most likely. This mammoth is ever so\nmuch bigger. Come and see!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As I was about to follow the boy, a voice from another direction\nsuddenly cried:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father! Father! A great enormous turtle! Please make haste. It is\nwaddling back to the sea as hard as it can go, and we can't stop it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This appeal being more pressing, as well as more important, than\nJack's, I snatched up an oar and hastened to their assistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sure enough a large turtle was scrambling quickly towards the water,\nand was within a few paces of it, although Ernest was valiantly holding\non by one of its hind legs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I sprang down the bank, and making use of the oar as a lever, we\nsucceeded with some difficulty in turning the creature on its back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was a huge specimen, fully eight feet long, and being now quite\nhelpless, we left it sprawling, and went to inspect Jack's mammoth\nskeleton, which, of course, proved to be neither more nor less than\nthat of the whale. I convinced him of the fact by pointing out the\nmarks of our feet on the ground, and the broken jaws where we had\nhacked out the whalebone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What can have made you take up that fancy about a mammoth, my boy?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest put it into my head, father. He said there seemed to be the\nskeleton of an antediluvian monster there, so I ran to look closer, and\nI never thought of the whale, when I saw no fish bones. I suppose\nErnest was joking.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Whales are generally considered as fishes by those little acquainted\nwith the animal kingdom, but they belong to the class of mammals, which\ncomprises man, the monkey tribes, the bats, the dogs and cats, all\nhoofed animals, whales and their allies, with other animals, the last\non the list being the sloth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The name by which they are distinguished is derived from the Latin\nword \"mama,\" a breast, and is given to them because all the species\nbelonging to this class are furnished with a set of organs called the\nmammary glands, secreting the liquid known as milk, by which the young\nare nourished."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The bones of the whale differ from those of animals, simply in being\nof a hollow construction, and filled with air so as to render the\ncarcase more buoyant. The bones of birds are also hollow, for the same\nreason, and in all this we see conspicuously the wisdom and goodness of\nthe great Creator.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What a marvellous structure it is, father!' said Fritz. 'What a\nponderous mass of bones! Can we not make use of any of them?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Nothing strikes me at this moment; we will leave them to bleach here\nyet awhile, and perhaps by sawing them up afterwards, make a few\nchairs, or a reading-desk for the museum. But now it is time to return\nhome. Bring the boat round to where the turtle awaits his fate; we must\nsettle how to deal with him.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was soon decided that he must swim. I fastened the empty water-cask\nto a long line, one end of which was made fast to the bow of the boat,\nthe other carefully passed round the neck and fore-paws of the\ncreature, who was then lifted, so as to let him regain his feet; when\nhe instantly made for the water, plunged in, the cask floated after\nhim, and prevented his sinking."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were all on board in a moment; and the worthy fellow, after vainly\nattempting to dive, set himself diligently to swim right forwards,\ntowing us comfortably after him. I was ready to cut the line on the\nleast appearance of danger, and kept him on the course for Safety Bay\nby striking the water with a boat-hook right or left, according as the\nturtle was disposed to turn too much one way or the other."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were delighted with the fun, and compared me to Neptune in his\ncar, drawn by dolphins, and accompanied by Amphitrite and attendant\nTritons."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We landed safely at the usual place, near Rockburg, and the turtle was\ncondemned and executed soon afterwards; the shell, which was quite\neight feet long, and three broad, was, when cleaned and prepared, to\nform a trough for the water supply at the cave, and the meat was\ncarefully salted, and stored up for many a good and savoury meal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It had been my intention to bring a piece of land under cultivation\nbefore the next rainy season, to be sown with different sorts of grain;\nbut many unforeseen circumstances had intervened to hinder this, and\nour animals, unaccustomed to the yoke, were not available for the\nplough."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I therefore gave up the idea for the present, and applied myself, with\nErnest's assistance, to completing the loom, which, although the\nworkmanship was clumsy, I succeeded in making quite fit for use. I had\nfortunately in my younger days spent many hours in the workshops of\nweavers and other artisans, and therefore I understood more than might\nhave been expected of their various crafts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Paste or size was required to smear over the threads; but we could not\nspare flour for such a purpose, and I used isinglass, which kept the\nwarp moist perfectly well, and spared us the necessity of setting up\nthe loom in a damp uncomfortable place, which has often to be done to\nprevent the overdrying of the web."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Of this isinglass I also made thin plates, to be used as window-panes;\nthey were at least as transparent as horn, and when fixed deep in the\nrock and beyond the reach of rain, did good service in admitting light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Success encouraging me to persevere, I next began harness-making; the\nspoils of the chase having furnished us with plenty of leather, with\nwhich I covered light frames of wood, using the hairy moss or lichen\nfor stuffing, and ere long the animals were equipped with saddles,\nstirrups, bridles, yokes and collars, to the very great satisfaction of\ntheir youthful riders and drivers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This occupation was followed by a great deal of work connected with the\nannual return of the herring shoals which now took place; to them\nsucceeding, as on former occasions, shoals of other fish, and many\nseals. More than ever aware of the value of all of these, we did not\nfail to make good use of our opportunities, and captured large numbers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were getting anxious for another shooting expedition; but\nbefore undertaking that, I wished to do some basket-making, as sacks\nwere beginning to fail us, and there was constant demand for baskets in\nwhich to carry and keep our roots and fruits. Our first attempts were\nclumsy enough; but, as usual, perseverance was rewarded, and we\nproduced a good supply of all sorts and sizes. One very large basket I\nfurnished with openings through which to pass a strong stick, so that\nit might, when heavily laden, be carried by two persons."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner did the children see the force of this idea, than they got a\nbamboo, and popping little Franz into the basket, carried him about in\ntriumph."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This amusement suggested a fresh notion to Fritz. 'Oh, father,' cried\nhe, 'don't you think we might make something like this for mother, and\ncarry her much more comfortably than jolting along in the cart?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys shouted with glee at the proposal, and though their mother\nthought the plan feasible enough, she confessed that she did not much\nlike the thought of sitting in the middle of a basket, and just looking\nout now and then over the rim."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "However, I assured her it should be a well-shaped comfortable\nsedan-chair, or litter; and the next question was how it should be\ncarried, since the boys could not play the part of Indian\npalanquin-bearers, either with safety to their mother, or with any\npleasure to themselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The bull and the buffalo!' cried Jack. 'Why not use them for it?\nLet's go and try them now!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Off ran the boys, and in a short time the basket was securely hung\nbetween Storm and Grumble. Fritz and Jack sprang into their saddles,\nand Ernest very gingerly deposited himself in the 'cradle', as Franz\ncalled it; they set forth at a most sober pace, the animals, who were\nperfectly docile, appearing only a little surprised at the new\narrangement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, it is so pleasant, mother, it is a delightful motion,' cried\nErnest, as they passed us. 'It swings and rocks really soothingly.\nQuicker, Fritz! Go quicker!' And the trot pleasing him equally well,\nthe pace gradually quickened, till the animals were going along at a\nrate which shook and jolted the basket about most fearfully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest called and screamed in vain for a halt. His brothers thought it\ncapital fun to 'shake up' the 'professor', and made the circuit of the\nlevel ground near Rockburg, finally pulling up in front of us, like\nperformers stopping to receive the applause of spectators."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was impossible to help laughing, the scene was so ridiculous, but\nErnest was very angry with his brothers, his reproaches provoked high\nwords in reply, and a quarrel was imminent, but I interfered, and\nshowed them how easily a joke carried too far would lead to disputes\nand bad feeling, urging them to avoid on all occasions any breach of\nthe good fellowship and brotherly love which was the mainstay of our\nstrength and happiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Good humour was soon restored, Ernest himself helped to unharness the\nbeasts, and got some handfuls of salt and barley to reward their\nexertions, saying, that they must have some more palanquin-practise\nanother day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was seated with my wife and Fritz beneath the shade of the verandah,\nengaged in wicker-work, and chatting pleasantly, when suddenly Fritz\ngot up, advanced a step or two, gazing fixedly along the avenue which\nled from Jackal River, then he exclaimed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I see something so strange in the distance, father! What in the world\ncan it be? First it seems to be drawn in coils on the ground like a\ncable, then uprises as it were a little mast, then that sinks, and the\ncoils move along again. It is coming towards the bridge.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife took alarm at this description, and calling the other boys,\nretreated into the cave, where I desired them to close up the\nentrances, and keep watch with firearms at the upper windows."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These were openings we had made in the rock at some elevation, reached\nwithin by steps, and a kind of gallery which passed along the front of\nthe rooms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz remained by me while I examined the object through my spy-glass."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is, as I feared, an enormous serpent!' cried I. 'It advances\ndirectly this way, and we shall be placed in the greatest possible\ndanger, for it will cross the bridge to a certainty.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'May we not attack it, father?' exclaimed the brave boy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Only with the greatest caution,' returned I. 'It is far too\nformidable, and too tenacious of life, for us rashly to attempt its\ndestruction. Thank God we are at Rockburg, where we can keep in safe\nretreat, while we watch for an opportunity to destroy this frightful\nenemy. Go up to your mother now, and assist in preparing the firearms;\nI will join you directly, but I must further observe the monster's\nmovements.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz left me unwillingly, while I continued to watch the serpent,\nwhich was of gigantic size, and already much too near the bridge to\nadmit of the possibility of removing that means of access to our\ndwelling. I recollected, too, how easily it would pass through the\nwalls. The reptile advanced with writhing and undulatory movements,\nfrom time to time rearing its head to the height of fifteen or twenty\nfeet, and slowly turning it about, as though on the look-out for prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As it crossed the bridge, with a slow, suspicious motion, I withdrew,\nand hastily rejoined my little party, which was preparing to garrison\nour fortress in warlike array, but with considerable trepidation, which\nmy presence served in a measure to allay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We placed ourselves at the upper openings, after strongly barricading\neverything below, and, ourselves unseen, awaited with beating hearts\nthe further advance of the foe, which speedily became visible to us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Its movements appeared to become uncertain, as though puzzled by the\ntrace of human habitation; it turned in different directions, coiling\nand uncoiling, and frequently rearing its head, but keeping about the\nmiddle of the space in front of the cave, when suddenly, as though\nunable to resist doing so, one after another the boys fired, and even\ntheir mother discharged her gun. The shots took not the slightest\neffect beyond startling the monster, whose movements were accelerated.\nFritz and I also fired with steadier aim, but with the same want of\nsuccess, for the monster passing on with a gliding motion, entered the\nreedy marsh to the left, and entirely disappeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A wonderful weight seemed lifted from our hearts, while all eagerly\ndiscussed the vast length and awful though magnificent appearance of\nthe serpent. I had recognized it as the boa constrictor. It was a vast\nspecimen, upwards of thirty feet in length."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I explained to the children that its name in South America is\nBoaguacu; the first syllable of that name, with the Latin addition,\nwhich indicates that it kills its prey by pressure, or 'constriction,'\ngives the name by which it is commonly known."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The near neighbourhood of this terrific reptile occasioned me the\nutmost anxiety; and I desired that no one should leave the house on any\npretence whatever, without my express permission."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During three whole days we were kept in suspense and fear, not daring\nto stir above a few hundred steps from the door, although during all\nthat time the enemy showed no sign of his presence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In fact, we might have been induced to think the boa had passed across\nthe swamp, and found his way by some cleft or chasm through the wall of\ncliffs beyond, had not the restless behaviour of our geese and ducks\ngiven proof that he still lurked in the thicket of reeds which they\nwere accustomed to make their nightly resting place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They swam anxiously about, and with much clapping of wings and\ndisturbed cackling, showed their uneasiness; finally, taking wing, they\ncrossed the harbour, and took up their quarters on Shark's Island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My quandary increased, as time passed on. I could not venture to\nattack with insufficient force a monstrous and formidable serpent\nconcealed in dense thickets amidst dangerous swamps; yet it was\ndreadful to live in a state of blockade, cut off from all the\nimportant duties in which we were engaged, and shut up with our\nanimals in the unnatural light of the cave, enduring constant anxiety\nand perturbation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Out of this painful state we were at last delivered by none other than\nour good old simple-hearted donkey; not, however, by the exercise of a\npraiseworthy quality, but by sheer stupidity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our situation was rendered the more critical from having no great\nstock of provisions, or fodder for the animals; and the hay failing us\non the evening of the third day, I determined to set them at liberty by\nsending them, under the guidance of Fritz, across the river at the\nford."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was to ride Lightfoot, and they were to be fastened together until\nsafely over."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning we began to prepare for this by tying them in a line, and\nwhile so engaged my wife opened the door, when old Grizzle, who was\nfresh and frolicsome after the long rest and regular feeding, suddenly\nbroke away from the halter, cut some awkward capers, then bolting out,\ncareered at full gallop straight for the marsh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In vain we called him by name. Fritz would even have rushed after him,\nhad not I held him back. In another moment the ass was close to the\nthicket, and with a cold shudder of horror, we beheld the snake rear\nitself from its lair, the fiery eyes glanced around, the dark deadly\njaws opened widely, the forked tongue darted greedily forthâ€”poor\nGrizzle's fate was sealed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Becoming aware on a sudden of his danger, he stopped short, spread out\nall four legs, and set up the most piteous and discordant bray that\never wrung echo from rocks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Swift and straight as a fencer's thrust, the destroyer was upon him,\nwound round him, entangled, enfolded, compressed him, all the while\ncunningly avoiding the convulsive kicks of the agonized animal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A cry of horror arose from the spectators of this miserable tragedy.\n'Shoot him, father! Oh, shoot himâ€”do save poor Grizzle!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My children, it is impossible!' cried I. 'Our old friend is lost to us\nfor ever! I have hopes, however, that when gorged with his prey, we may\nbe able to attack the snake with some chance of success.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But the horrible wretch is never going to swallow him all at once,\nfather?' cried Jack. 'That will be too shocking!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Snakes have no grinders, but only fangs, therefore they cannot chew\ntheir food, and must swallow it whole. But although the idea is\nstartling, it is not really more shocking than the rending, tearing and\nshedding of blood which occurs when lions and tigers seize their prey.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But,' said Franz, 'how can the snake separate the flesh from the\nbones without teeth? And is this kind of snake poisonous?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, dear child,' said I, 'only fearfully strong and ferocious. And it\nhas no need to tear the flesh from the bones. It swallows them, skin,\nhair and all, and digests everything in its stomach.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It seems utterly impossible that the broad ribs, the strong legs,\nhoofs and all, should go down that throat,' exclaimed Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Only see,' I replied, 'how the monster deals with his victim; closer\nand more tightly he curls his crushing folds, the bones give way, he is\nkneading him into a shapeless mass: He will soon begin to gorge his\nprey, and slowly but surely it will disappear down that distended maw!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife, with little Franz, found the scene all too horrible, and\nhastened into the cave, trembling and distressed. To the rest of us\nthere seemed a fearful fascination in the dreadful sight, and we could\nnot move from the spot. I expected that the boa, before swallowing his\nprey, would cover it with saliva, to aid in the operation, although it\nstruck me that its very slender forked tongue was about the worst\npossible implement for such a purpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was evident to us, however, that this popular idea was erroneous.\nThe act of lubricating the mass must have taken place during the\nprocess of swallowing; certainly nothing was applied beforehand. This\nwonderful performance lasted from seven in the morning until noon. When\nthe awkward morsel was entirely swallowed, the serpent lay stiff,\ndistorted, and apparently insensible along the edge of the marsh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I felt that now or never was the moment for attack!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Calling on my sons to maintain their courage and presence of mind, I\nleft our retreat with a feeling of joyous emotion quite new to me, and\napproached with rapid steps and levelled gun, the outstretched form of\nthe serpent. Fritz followed me closely."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack, somewhat timidly, came several paces behind; while Ernest, after\na little hesitation, remained where he was."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The monster's body was stiff and motionless, which made its rolling and\nfiery eyes, and the slow spasmodic undulations of its tail more fearful\nby contrast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We fired together, and both balls entered the skull: the light of the\neye was extinguished, and the only movement was in the further\nextremity of the body, which rolled, writhed, coiled and lashed from\nside to side."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Advancing closer, we fired our pistols directly into its head, a\nconvulsive quiver ran through the mighty frame, and the boa\nconstrictor lay dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we raised a cry of victory, Jack, desirous of a share in the glory\nof conquest, ran close to the creature, firing his pistol into its\nside, when he was sent sprawling over and over by a movement of its\ntail, excited to a last galvanic effort by the shot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Being in no way hurt, he speedily recovered his feet, and declared he\nhad given it its quietus."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I hope the terrific noise you made just now was the signal of\nvictory,' said my wife, drawing near, with the utmost circumspection,\nand holding Franz tightly by the hand. 'I was half-afraid to come, I\nassure you.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'See this dreadful creature dead at our feet; and let us thank God that\nwe have been able to destroy such an enemy.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What's to be done with him now?' asked Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Let us get him stuffed,' said Fritz, 'and set him up in the museum\namongst our shells and corals.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Did anybody ever think of eating serpents?' inquired Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Of course not!' said his mother. 'Why, child, serpents are\npoisonousâ€”it would be very dangerous.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Excuse me, my dear wife,' said I. 'First of all, the boa is not\npoisonous; and then, besides that, the flesh even of poisonous snakes\ncan be eaten without danger; as, for instance, the rattlesnake, from\nwhich can be made a strong and nourishing soup, tasting very like good\nchicken brothâ€”of course, the cook must be told to throw away the head,\ncontaining the deadly fangs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is remarkable that pigs do not fear poisonous snakes, but can kill\nand eat them without injury. An instance of this occurs to my memory. A\nvessel on Lake Superior, in North America, was wrecked on a small\nisland abounding in rattlesnakes, and for that reason uninhabited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The vessel had a cargo of live pigs. The crew escaped to the mainland\nin a boat, but the pigs had to be left for some time, till the owner\ncould return to fetch them, but with the small hope of finding many\nleft alive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To his surprise, the animals were not only alive, but remarkably fat\nand flourishing, while not a single rattlesnake remained on the island.\nThe pigs had clearly eaten the serpents.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But might not some other cause have been assigned for their\ndisappearance?' asked Ernest. 'Suppose, for example, that a great\nflight of secretary birds had arrived, they might have cleared the\nisland of rattlesnakes.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, what is a secretary bird?' interrupted Franz. 'I thought a\nsecretary meant a man who wrote letters?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'So it does, Franz, and the bird Ernest spoke of has curious long\nfeathers projecting from either side of its head, something like pens\nstuck behind a man's ear; hence its name."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is perfectly true that it lives on snakes, lizards, toads, and\nfrogs, but, Ernest, I cannot give up my pigs; for, in the first place,\nthe secretary bird is an inhabitant of Southern Africa, and is never\nseen in North America, neither does it ever fly in a flock; still, so\nravenous is its appetite, that, no doubt, even one or two, had they by\nsome miracle found themselves on Lake Superior, would have been able to\ngive a very good account of the deadly reptiles, and at least shared in\nthe glory of their extermination.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife having gone to prepare dinner, we continued talking as we\nrested in the shade of some rocks, near the serpent, for a\nconsiderable time. The open air was welcome to us after our long\nimprisonment; and we were, besides, desirous to drive off any birds of\nprey who might be attracted to the carcase, which we wished to preserve\nentire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My boys questioned me closely on the subject of serpents in general;\nand I described to them the action of the poison fangs; how they folded\nback on the sides of the upper jaw, and how the poison-secreting\nglands, and reservoir are found at the back and sides of the head,\ngiving to the venomous serpents that peculiar width of head which is so\nunfailing a characteristic."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The fangs are hollow,' said I, 'and when the creature bites, the\npressure forces down a tiny drop of the liquid venom, which enters the\nwound and, through the veins, quickly spreads over the entire system.\nSometimes, if taken in time, cures are effected, but in most cases the\nbite of a serpent is followed by speedy death.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The children were much interested in my account of the snake-charmers\nof India, how they fearlessly handle the most deadly of the serpent\ntribe, the Cobra di Capello-or hooded cobra-, cause them to move in\ntime to musical sounds from a small pipe, twine the reptile about their\narms and bare necks, and then, to prove that the poison fangs have not\nbeen removed, make them bite a fowl, which soon dies from the effects.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'How is it possible to extract the fangs, father?' asked Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No instrument is required,' replied I; 'I have read the account\nwritten by a gentleman in India, who saw a snake-charmer catch a large\ncobra in the jungle, and for the purpose of removing the fangs, held up\na cloth at which the irritated snake flew, and the fangs being caught\nin it, the man seized the reptile by the throat, extracted them, and\nthen squeezed out the poison, a clear oily substance, upon a leaf.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What does the rattle of the rattlesnake look like? And how does it\nsound?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'At the tip of the tail are a number of curious, loose, horny\nstructures formed of the same substance as the scales. A very good idea\nof the structure of the rattle may be formed by slipping a number of\nthimbles loosely into each other."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The rattlesnake lies coiled with its head flat, and the tip of its\ntail elevated; when alarmed or irritated it gives a quivering movement\nto the tail which causes the joints of the rattle to shake against each\nother with a peculiar sound, not easily described; all animals, even\nhorses newly brought from Europe, tremble at this noise, and try to\nescape.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What is the best thing to be done for the bite of a serpent?'\ninquired Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Remedies are very various, very uncertain, and differ with the\nspecies inflicting the bite."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Suction, ammonia, oil, the use of the knife, application of fresh\nmold, lunar caustic, leaves of certain plants, all these and more are\nmentioned. There is a creeping plant, called Aristolodochia indica, the\nleaves of which have in repeated instances done wonders for fearful\nbites. It is found in many parts of the world but most plentifully in\nthe hotter regions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A mode of cure adopted by the natives of India, Ceylon, and parts of\nAfrica, is by the application of a remarkable object called\nsnake-stone. These are described as flattish, something like half an\nalmond with squared ends, rather light, bearing a very high polish, and\nof an intense jetty black."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'On being bitten by a cobra, the sufferer applies one of these stones\nto each puncture, where they adhere strongly for a time, five or six\nminutes being about the average. They seem to absorb the blood as it\nflows from the wound, and, at the last fall off, when the danger is\nconsidered to be over."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But now we must leave this fertile subject of discussion, and I can\nonly say I sincerely trust we may never have cause to resume it from\nthe appearance of another serpent here of any sort, size, or\ndescription."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But come, Ernest, can you not give us an epitaph for our unfortunate\nfriend the donkey? We must afford him more honourable sepulture than he\nenjoys at present, when we proceed, as we speedily must, to disembowel\nhis murderer.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest took the matter quite seriously, and planting his elbows on his\nknees, he bent his thoughtful brow in his hands, and remained wrapt in\npoetic meditation for about two minutes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have it!' cried he. 'But perhaps you will all laugh at me?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No, no, don't be shy, old fellow; spit it out!' and thus encouraged by\nhis brother, Ernest, with the blush of a modest author, began:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Beneath this stone poor Grizzle's bones are laid,\n   'A faithful ass he was, and loved by all.\n   'At length, his master's voice he disobeyed,\n   'And thereby came his melancholy fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A monstrous serpent, springing from the grass,\n   'Seized, crushed, and swallowed him before our eyes.\n   'But we, though yet we mourn our honest ass,\n   'Are grateful; for he thereby saved the lives\n   'Of all the human beings on this shoreâ€”\n   'A father, mother, and their children four.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah for the epitaph! Well done, Ernest!' resounded on all sides,\nand taking out a large red pencil I used for marking wood, the lines\nwere forthwith inscribed on a great flat stone, being, as I told the\nboy, the very best poetry that had ever been written on our coast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then had dinner, and afterwards went to work with the serpent. The\nfirst operation was to recover the mangled remains of the ass, which\nbeing effected, he was buried in the soft marshy ground close by, and\nthe hole filled up with fragments of rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then we yoked Storm and Grumble to the serpent, and dragged it to a\nconvenient distance from Rockburg, where the process of skinning,\nstuffing, and sewing up again afforded occupation of the deepest\ninterest to the boys for several days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We took great pains to coil it round a pole in the museum, arranging\nthe head with the jaws wide open, so as to look as alarming as\npossible, and contriving to make eyes and tongue which were quite\nsufficient to represent nature; in fact, our dogs never passed the\nmonster without growling, and must have wondered at our taste in\nkeeping such a pet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Over the entrance leading to the museum and library were inscribed\nthese words:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "NO ADMITTANCE FOR ASSES"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The double meaning of this sentence pleased us all immensely."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 12"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The greatest danger to which we had yet been exposed was now over, but\nthere remained much anxiety in my mind lest another serpent might,\nunseen by us, have entered the swamp, or might appear, as this had\ndone, from the country beyond Falconhurst."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I projected then two excursions, the first to make a thorough\nexamination of the thicket and morass; the next right away to the Gap,\nthrough which alone the archenemy could have entered our territory."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On summoning my sons to accompany me to the marsh, I found neither\nErnest nor Jack very eager to do so, the latter vowing he had the cold\nshivers each time he thought how his ribs might have been smashed by\nthe last flap of the snake's tail; but I did not yield to their\nreluctance, and we finally set about crossing the marsh by placing\nplanks and wicker hurdles on the ground, and changing their places as\nwe advanced."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nothing was discovered beyond tracks in the reeds and the creature's\nlair; where the rushes, grass, and bog-plants were beaten down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Emerging beyond the thicket we found ourselves on firm ground, near the\nprecipitous wall of rock, and perceived a clear sparkling brook flowing\nfrom an opening, which proved to be a cave or grotto of considerable\nsize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The vaulted roof was covered with stalactites, while many formed\nstately pillars, which seemed as though supporting the roof. The floor\nwas strewn with fine snow-white earth, with a smooth soapy feeling,\nwhich I felt convinced was fuller's earth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, this is a pleasant discovery!' said I. 'This is as good as soap\nfor washing, and will save me the trouble of turning soap-boiler.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Perceiving that the streamlet flowed from an opening of some width in\nthe inner rock, Fritz passed through, in order to trace it to its\nsource, presently shouting to me that the opening widened very much,\nand begging me to follow him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I did so, leaving the other boys in the outer cave, and fired a\npistol-shotâ€”the reverberating echoes of which testified to the great\nextent of the place; and lighting the bit of candle I always carried\nwith me, we advanced, the light burning clear and steadily, though\nshedding a very feeble light in so vast a space."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Suddenly Fritz exclaimed: 'I verily believe this is a second cave of\nsalt! See how the walls glance! And how the light is reflected from the\nroof!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'These cannot be salt crystals,' said I, 'the water which flows over\nthem leaves no track, and tastes quite sweet. I am rather inclined to\nbelieve that we have penetrated into a cave of rock crystal!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, how splendid! Then we have discovered a great treasure!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Certainly if we could make any use of it; otherwise, in our\nsituation, it is about as valuable as the lump of gold found by good\nold Robinson Crusoe.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Anyhow, I will break off a piece for a specimen. See, here is a fine\nbit, only rather dull, and not transparent: what a pity! I must knock\noff another.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You must go more carefully to work, or it will look as dull as the\nfirst. You destroyed its true form, which is that of a pyramid, with\nsix sides or facets.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We remained some time in this interesting grotto, but our light burnt\nlow after we had examined it in different directions; and Fritz having\nsecured a large lump, which exhibited several crystals in perfection,\nwe quitted the place, Fritz discharging a farewell shot for the sake of\nhearing the grand echoes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On reaching the open air we saw poor Jack sobbing bitterly, but as soon\nas we appeared he ran joyfully towards us, and threw himself into my\narms."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My child, what is the matter?' I cried anxiously."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, I thought you were lost! I heard a noise twice, as if the rocks\nhad shattered down; and I thought you and Fritz were crushed in the\nruins! It was horrible! How glad I am to see you!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I comforted the child, and explained the noises he had heard,\ninquiring why he was alone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest is over there among the reeds: I daresay he did not hear the\nshots.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I found Ernest busily engaged in weaving a basket in which to catch\nfish: he had devised it ingeniously, with a funnel-shaped entrance;\nthrough which the fish passing would not easily find their way out, but\nwould remain swimming about in the wide part of the apparatus."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I shot a young serpent while you were away, father,' said he. 'It lies\nthere covered with rushes; it is nearly four feet long, and as thick as\nmy arm.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A serpent!' cried I, hurrying towards it in alarm, and fearing there\nmust be a brood of them in the swamp after all. 'A fine large eel you\nmean, my boy. This will provide an excellent supper for us tonight. I\nam glad you had the courage to kill it, instead of taking to your heels\nand fleeing from the supposed serpent.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, I thought it would be so horrid to be pursued and caught that I\npreferred facing it; my shot took effect, but it was very difficult to\nkill the creature outright, it moved about although its head was\nsmashed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The tenacity of life possessed by eels is very remarkable,' I said. 'I\nhave heard that the best mode of killing them is to grasp them by the\nneck and slap their tails smartly against a stone or post.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We made our way back more easily by keeping close to the cliffs, where\nthe ground was firmer, and found my wife washing clothes at the\nfountain. She rejoiced greatly at our safe return, and was much pleased\nwith the supply of fuller's earth, as she said there was now very\nlittle soap left. The eel was cooked for supper, and during the evening\na full account was given of our passage through the swamp, and\ndiscovery of the rock-crystal cavern."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was most important to ascertain whether any serpent lurked among the\nwoods of our little territory between the cliffs and the sea.\nPreparations were set on foot for the second and greater undertaking of\na search throughout the country beyond the river, as far as the Gap. I\nwished all the family to go on the expedition, a decision which gave\nuniversal satisfaction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Intending to be engaged in this search for several weeks, we took the\nsmall tent and a store of all sorts of necessary provisions, as well as\nfirearms, tools, cooking utensils and torches."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All these things were packed on the cart, which was drawn by Storm and\nGrumble. Jack and Franz mounted them, and acted at once the part of\nriders and drivers. My wife sat comfortably in the cart, Fritz rode in\nadvance, while Ernest and I walked; we were protected in flank by the\ndogs and Fangs, the tame jackal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Directing our course towards Woodlands, we saw many traces of the\nserpent's approach to Rockburg. In some places, where the soil was\nloose, the trail, like a broad furrow, was very evident indeed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At Falconhurst we made a halt and were, as usual, welcomed by the\npoultry, as well as by the sheep and goats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We then passed on to Woodlands, where we arrived at nightfall. All was\npeaceful and in good order; no track of the boa in that direction; no\nsigns of visits from mischievous apes; the little farm and its\ninhabitants looked most flourishing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next day was passed in making a survey of the immediate neighbourhood,\nat the same time collecting a quantity of cotton, which was wanted for\nnew pillows and cushions. In the afternoon Franz was my companion,\ncarrying a small gun, entrusted to him for the first time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We took Fangs and Bruno with us, and went slowly along the left bank of\nthe lake, winding our way among reedy thickets, which frequently turned\nus aside a considerable distance from the water. The dogs hunted about\nin all directions, and raised duck, snipe and heron. These usually flew\ndirectly across the lake, so that Franz got no chance of a shot. He\nbegan to get rather impatient, and proposed firing at the black swans\nwe saw sailing gracefully on the glassy surface of the lake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Just then a harsh booming sound struck our ears. I paused in wonder as\nto whence the noise proceeded, while Franz exclaimed,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father! Can that be Swift, our young onager?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It cannot possibly be Swift,' said I; adding, after listening\nattentively a minute or two, 'I am inclined to think it must be the cry\nof a bittern, a fine handsome bird of the nature of a heron.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh! may I shoot it, father? But I wonder how a bird can make that\nroaring noise! One would think it was an ox, it is more like lowing\nthan braying.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The noise creatures make depends more on the construction of the\nwindpipe, its relation to the lungs and the strength of the muscles\nwhich force out the breath, than on their size. As for example, how\nloud is the song of the nightingale and the little canary bird. Some\npeople say that the bittern booms with his long bill partly thrust into\nthe boggy ground, which increases the hollow muffled sound of its very\npeculiar cry.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz was very anxious that the first trophy of his gun should be so\nrare a bird as the bittern; the dogs were sent into the wood, and we\nwaited some distance apart, in readiness to fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All at once there was a great rustling in the thicket. Franz fired, and\nI heard his happy voice calling out: 'I've hit him! I've hit him!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What have you hit?' shouted I in return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A wild pig,' said he, 'but bigger than Fritz's.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Aha! I see you remember the agouti! Perhaps it is not a hog at all,\nbut one of our little pigs from the farm. What will the old sow say to\nyou, Franz?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I soon joined my boy, and found him in transports of joy over an\nanimal certainly very much like a pig, although its snout was broad and\nblunt. It was covered with bristles, had no tail, and in colour was a\nyellowish grey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Examining it carefully and noticing its webbed feet, and its curious\nteeth, I decided that it must be a capybara, a water-loving animal of\nSouth America, and Franz was overjoyed to find that he had shot 'a new\ncreature', as he said."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was difficult to carry it home, but he very sensibly proposed that\nwe should open and clean the carcase, which would make it lighter.\nThen, putting it in a game-bag, he carried it till quite tired out; he\nasked if I thought Bruno would let him strap it on his back. We found\nthe dog willing to bear the burden, and reached Woodlands soon\nafterwards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There we were surprised to see Ernest surrounded by a number of large\nrats which lay dead on the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Where can all these have come from?' exclaimed I. 'Have you and your\nmother been rat-hunting instead of gathering rice as you intended?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We came upon these creatures quite unexpectedly,' he replied. 'While\nin the rice swamp, Knips, who was with us, sprang away to a kind of\nlong-shaped mound among the reeds, and pounced upon something, which\ntried to escape into a hole."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'He chattered and gnashed his teeth, and the creature hissed and\nsqueaked, and running up, I found he had got a big rat by the tail; he\nwould not let go, and the rat could not turn in the narrow entrance to\nbite him, but I soon pulled it out and killed it with my stick."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The mound was a curious-looking erection, so I broke it open with some\ndifficulty, and in doing this dislodged quite a dozen of the creatures.\nSome I killed, but many plunged into the water and escaped."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'On examining their dwelling I found it a vaulted tunnel made of clay\nand mud, and thickly lined with sedges, rushes, and water-lily leaves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There were other mounds or lodges close by, and seeking an entrance to\none I stretched my game-bag across it, and then hammered on the roof\ntill a whole lot of rats sprang out, several right into the bag. I hit\naway right and left, but began to repent of my audacity when I found\nthe whole community swarming about in the wildest excitement, some\nescaping, but many stopping in bewilderment, while others actually\nattacked me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was anything but pleasant, I assure you, and I began to think of\nBishop Hatto in the Mouse Tower on the Rhine. Knips liked it as little\nas I did, and skipped about desperately to get out of their way, though\nhe now and then seized a rat by the neck in his teeth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Just as I began to shout for help, Juno came dashing through the\nreeds and water, and made quick work with the enemy, all flying from\nher attack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My mother had great difficulty in forcing her way through the marsh to\nthe scene of action, but reached me at last; and we collected all the\nslain to show you, and for the sake of their skins.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This account excited my curiosity, and I went to examine the place\nErnest described: where I found, to my surprise, an arrangement much\nlike a beaver dam, though on a small scale, and less complete."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You have discovered a colony of beaver rats,' said I to Ernest, 'so\ncalled from their resemblance in skill and manner of life to that\nwonderful creature."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Muskrat, musquash, and ondatra are other names given to them. They\nhave, you see, webbed feet and flattened tails, and we shall find that\nthey carry two small glands containing the scented substance called\nmusk. The sooner we strip off the skins the better; they will be useful\nfor making caps.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We went back to the house, and met Fritz and Jack just returned from\ntheir excursion, reporting that no trace of serpents, great or small,\nhad been met with."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack carried in his hat about a dozen eggs; and Fritz had shot a\ncouple of heath fowls, a cock and hen."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We sat down to supper, Franz eager to partake of his capybara. Even he\nhimself made a face at the peculiar flavour of the meat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is the musk which you taste,' said I; and I described to them the\nvarious animals in which this strange liquid is found; the musk deer,\nmusk ox, crocodile, muskrat of India (also called soudeli, which taints\na corked bottle of wine, if it only runs across it) concluding with an\naccount of the civet, also called civet-cat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The civet,' said I, 'is a handsome black and white animal, and the\nperfume obtained from it was formerly considered a valuable medicine;\nin the present day it is used chiefly as a scent. This odoriferous\nsubstance is secreted, i.e., formed, in a double glandular pouch near\nthe tail, and the Dutch keep the creature in captivity, so that it\nshall afford them a continual supply."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The method of removing the civet perfume is ingenious. The animal is\nvery quick and elastic in its movements, and having sharp teeth it is\nnot pleasant to handle. So it is put into a long, narrow cage in which\nit cannot turn around, a horn spoon is then introduced, and the\nperfume, a thick, oily stuff something like butter, is coolly scraped\nfrom the pouch, the plundered civet being then released from strait\ndurance, until the supply is re-formed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently Jack ran for his game-bag, producing some fruit which he had\nforgotten. Several pale green apples, quite new to us, excited general\nattention."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, what are those? Are they good?' I asked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I hope so,' said Jack, 'but Fritz and I were afraid of eating some\nawful poison or other, like the manchineel, so we brought them for the\ninspection of the learned Master Knips.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took one and cut it in two, remarking that it contained a circle of\nseeds or pips, instead of the stone of the manchineel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At that moment Knips slyly came behind me, and snatching up one half,\nbegan to munch it with the liveliest satisfaction, an example which the\nboys were so eager to follow that a general scramble ensued, and I had\nsome trouble in securing a couple of the apples for myself and their\nmother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I imagined this to be the cinnamon apple of the Antilles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everyone seeming wearied by the fatigues of the day, our mattresses and\npillows were arranged, and the inmates of Woodlands betook themselves\nto repose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With early light we commenced the next day's journey, directing our\ncourse to a point between the sugar-brake and the Gap, where we had\nonce made a sort of arbour of the branches of trees; as this remained\nin pretty good condition, we spread a sailcloth over the top of it,\ninstead of pitching the tent, and made it very comfortable quarters for\nthe short time I proposed to stay there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our object being to search the neighbourhood for traces of the boa\nconstrictor, or any of his kindred, Fritz, Jack, and Franz went with me\nto the sugar-cane brake, and we satisfied ourselves that our enemy had\nnot been there. It was long since we had enjoyed the fresh juice of\nthese canes, and we were refreshing ourselves therewith, when a loud\nbarking of dogs and loud rustling and rattling through the thicket of\ncanes disturbed our pleasant occupation, and, as we could see nothing a\nyard off where we stood, I hurried to the open ground, and with guns in\nreadiness we awaited what was coming."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few minutes a herd of creatures like little pigs issued from the\nthicket, and made off in single file at a brisk trot; they were of a\nuniform grey colour, and showed short sharp tusks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My trusty double-barrel speedily laid low two of the fugitives which I\nfelt certain to be peccaries; the others continued to follow the leader\nin line, scarcely turning aside to pass the dead bodies of their\ncomrades, and maintaining the same steady pace, although Fritz and Jack\nalso fired and killed several."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I felt certain that these were peccaries, and recollected that an\nodoriferous gland in the back must be removed immediately, otherwise\nthe meat will become tainted, and quite unfit to eat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This operation, with the help of my boys, I accordingly performed at\nonce."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently, hearing shots in the direction of the hut where we had left\nErnest and his mother, I sent Jack to their assistance, desiring him to\nfetch the cart, that the booty might be conveyed to our encampment,\nemploying the time of his absence in opening and cleaning the animals,\nthus reducing their weight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest came back with Jack and the cart, and told us that the\nprocession of peccaries had passed near the hut, and that he, with\nJuno's help, had secured three of them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was glad to hear this, as I had determined to cure a good supply of\nhams, and we made haste to load the cart; the boys adorned it with\nflowers and green boughs, and with songs of triumph which made the\nwoods ring they conveyed the valuable supply of game to the hut, where\ntheir mother anxiously waited for us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After dinner we set to work upon our pigs, singeing and scalding off\nthe bristles; I cut out the hams, divided the flitches, bestowed\nconsiderable portions of the carcase on the dogs, and diligently\ncleansed and salted the meat, while the boys prepared a shed, where it\nwas to be hung to be cured in the smoke of fires of green wood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This unexpected business of course detained us in the place for some\ntime. On the second day, when the smoking-shed was ready, the boys were\nanxious to cook the smallest porker in the Otaheitean fashion. For this\npurpose they dug a hole, in which they burnt a quantity of dry grass,\nsticks and weeds, heating stones, which were placed round the sides of\nthe pit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While the younger boys made ready the oven, Fritz singed and washed his\npeccary, stuffing it with potatoes, onions and herbs, and a good\nsprinkling of salt and pepper."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He then sewed up the opening, and enveloped the pig in large leaves to\nguard it from the ashes and dust of its cooking-place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The fire no longer blazed, but the embers and stones were glowing hot;\nthe pig was carefully placed in the hole, covered over with hot ashes,\nand the whole with earth, so that it looked like a big mole heap."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Dinner was looked forward to with curiosity, as well as appetite; my\nwife, as usual, distrusting our experiments, was not sanguine of\nsuccess, and made ready some plain food as a pis aller*."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Last resort, backup, poor substitute."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She was well pleased with the curing-hut, which was roomy enough to\nhang all our hams and bacon. On a wide hearth in the middle we kindled\na large fire, which was kept constantly smouldering by heaping it with\ndamp grass and green wood. The hut being closed in above, the smoke\nfilled it, and penetrated the meat thoroughly: this process it had to\nundergo for several days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few hours Fritz gave notice that he was going to open his oven.\nGreat excitement prevailed as he removed the earth, turf, and stones,\nand a delicious appetizing odour arose from the opening. It was the\nsmell of roast pork, certainly, but with a flavor of spices which\nsurprised me, until I thought of the leaves in which the food had been\nwrapped up."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The peccary was carefully raised, and when a few cinders were picked\noff, it looked a remarkably well-cooked dish. Fritz was highly\ncomplimented on his success, even by his mother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The scented leaves were, I thought, those of a tree which I knew to be\nfound in Madagascar, called by the natives ravensara, or 'good leaf.'\nIt is said to combine the scent of the nutmeg, clove, and cinnamon. The\nfruit is a species of nut, possessing the scent of the leaves in a more\ndelicate degree, and from it an oil or essence is distilled, which is\nhighly valued in native cookery."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During the process of curing our large supply of hams and bacon, which\noccupied several days, we roamed about the neighbourhood in all\ndirections, finding no trace of the serpent, but making many valuable\nacquisitions, among which were some gigantic bamboos from fifty to\nsixty feet in length, and of proportionate thickness. These, when cut\nacross near the joints, formed capital casks, tubs, and pots; while the\nlong sharp thorns, which begirt the stem at intervals, were as strong\nand useful as iron nails."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One day we made an excursion to the farm at Prospect Hill, and were\ngrievously provoked to find that the vagabond apes had been there, and\nwrought terrible mischief, as before at Woodlands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The animals and poultry were scattered, and everything in the cottage\nso torn and dirtied, that it was vain to think of setting things right\nthat day. We therefore very unwillingly left the disorder as we found\nit, purposing to devote time to the work afterwards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When all was in readiness for the prosecution of our journey, we\nclosed and barricaded the hut, in which, for the present, we left the\nstore of bacon; and arranging our march in the usual patriarchal style,\nwe took our way to the Gap, the thorough defence of which defile was\nthe main object we had in view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our last halting-place being much enclosed by shrubs, bamboos and\nbrushwood, we had during our stay opened a path through the cane\nthicket in the direction we were about to travel; this we now found of\nthe greatest assistance, and the loaded cart passed on without\nimpediment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ground was open and tolerably level beyond, so that in a few hours\nwe arrived at the extreme limit of our coast territory."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We halted on the outskirts of a little wood behind which, to the\nright, rose the precipitous and frowning cliffs of the mountain gorge,\nwhile to the left flowed the torrent, leaving between it and the rocks\nthe narrow pass we called the Gap, and passing onward to mingle its\nwaters with the sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The wood afforded us pleasant shelter and standing high, and within\ngunshot of the mouth of the rocky pass, I resolved to make it our\ncamping-place. We therefore unpacked the cart, and made our usual\narrangements for safety and comfort, not forgetting to examine the wood\nitself, so as to ascertain whether it harboured any dangerous animals.\nNothing worse than wild cats was discovered. We disturbed several of\nthese creatures in their pursuit of birds and small game, but they fled\nat our approach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By the time dinner was ready we felt much fatigued, and some hours of\nunusually sultry and oppressive heat compelled us to rest until towards\nevening, when returning coolness revived our strength. We pitched the\ntent, and then occupied ourselves with preparations for the next day,\nwhen it was my intention to penetrate the country beyond the defile,\nand make a longer excursion across the savannah, than had yet been\nundertaken."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All was ready for a start at an early hour; my brave wife consented to\nremain in camp with Franz as her companion, while the three elder boys,\nand all the dogs, except Juno, went with me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We expected to find it somewhat difficult to make our way through the\nnarrowest part of the pass, which had been so strongly barricaded and\nplanted with thorny shrubs, but found on the contrary that the fences\nand walls were broken down and disarranged. It was thus very evident\nthat the great snake, as well as the herd of peccaries, had made an\nentrance here."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This barricade was the first check that had been placed by hand of man\nupon the wild free will of nature in this lonely place. With one\nconsent storms, floods, torrents, and the wild beasts of the forest,\nhad set themselves to destroy it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We resolved to make the defences doubly strong, being convinced that\nthe position was capable of being barricaded and fortified so as to\nresist the invaders we dreaded."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The prospect which opened before us on emerging from the rocky pass was\nwide, and varied. Swelling hills and verdant wooded vales were seen on\none hand, while a great plain stretched before us, extending from the\nbanks of the river towards a chain of lofty mountains, whose summits\nwere rendered indistinct in the haze of the distance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We crossed the stream, which we named East River, filling our flasks\nwith water, and it was well we did so, for in continuing our journey,\nwe found the soil become more arid and parched than we had expected; in\nfact we soon appeared surrounded by a desert."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were astonished at the altered appearance of the country, part\nof which had been explored when we met with the buffaloes. I reminded\nthem of the difference of the season; that the expedition had been made\ndirectly after the rains, when vegetation had clothed with transient\nbeauty this region, which, possessing no source of moisture in itself,\nhad become scathed and bare during the blazing heat of summer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our march proceeded slowly, and many were the uncomplimentary remarks\nmade on the 'new country'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was 'Arabia Petrea,' groaned one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Desert of Sahara,' sighed another."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fit abode for demons,' muttered a third. 'Subterranean volcanic fires\nare raging beneath our feet.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Patience, my good fellows!' cried I. 'You are too easily discouraged.\nLook beyond the toilsome way to those grand mountains whose spurs are\nalready stretching forward to meet us. Who knows what pleasant\nsurprises await us amid their steep declivities? I, for my part, expect\nto find water, fresh grass, trees and a lovely resting-place.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were all glad to repose beneath the shade of the first overhanging\nrock we came to, although by pressing further upwards, we might have\nattained to a pleasanter spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Looking back towards the Gap, we marked the strange contrast of the\nsmiling country bordering the river, and the dreary, monotonous plain\nwe had traversed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After gazing on the distant scene, we produced our store of\nprovisions, and were busily engaged, when Knips (our constant\ncompanion) suddenly began to snuff and smell about in a very\nridiculous way; finally, with a shriek which we knew was expressive of\npleasure, he set off at full speed, followed by all the dogs, up a sort\nof glen behind us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We left them to their own devices, being far too pleasantly engaged\nwith our refreshments to care much what fancy the little rogue had got\nin his head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When hunger was somewhat appeased, Fritz once more cast his eyes over\nthe expanse of plain before us, and after looking fixedly for a moment,\nexclaimed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Is it possible that I see a party of horsemen riding at full gallop\ntowards us! Can they be wild Arabs of the desert?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Arabs, my boy! Certainly not; but take the spy-glass and make them out\nexactly. We shall have to be on our guard, whatever they are!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I cannot see distinctly enough to be sure,' said he presently, 'and\nimagination supplies the deficiency of sight in most strange fashion. I\ncould fancy them wild cattle, loaded carts, wandering hay-cocks, in\nfact almost anything I like.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The spy-glass passed from hand to hand; Jack and Ernest agreed in\nthinking the moving objects were men on horseback; but when it came to\nmy turn to look, I at once pronounced them to be very large ostriches."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is fortunate indeed!' I exclaimed. 'We must try to secure one of\nthese magnificent birds; the feathers alone are worth having.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A live ostrich, father! That would be splendid. Why, we might ride\nupon him!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As the ostriches approached, we began to consider in what way we\nshould attempt a capture. I sent Fritz and Jack to recall the dogs, and\nplaced myself with Ernest behind some shrubs which would conceal us\nfrom the birds as they came onwards."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys did not rejoin us for some little time; they found Knips and\nthe dogs at a pool of water formed by a small mountain stream, which\nthe monkey's instinct had detected; his sudden departure was thus\naccounted for, and they availed themselves right gladly of his\ndiscovery, filling their flasks, and hastily bathing before their\nreturn."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ostriches continued to come in our direction, varying their pace as\nthough in sport, springing, trotting, galloping and chasing each other\nround and round, so that their approach was by no means rapid."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I could now perceive that of the five birds one only was a male, the\nwhite plumes of the wings and tail contrasting finely with the deep\nglossy black of the neck and body."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The colour of the females being ashen brown, the effect of their white\nplumes was not so handsome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I do not believe we shall have a chance with these birds,' said I,\n'except by sending Fritz's eagle in pursuit; and for that we must bide\nour time, and let them come as near as possible.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In what way, then, are ostriches caught by the natives of the African\ndeserts?' inquired Fritz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Sometimes by chase on horseback; but their speed is so very great,\nthat even that must be conducted by stratagem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'When these birds are pursued, they will run for hours in a wide\ncircle; the hunter gallops after them, but describes a much smaller\ncircle, and can therefore maintain the pace for a longer time, waiting\nto make the attack until the bird is fatigued."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Among the Bushmen, the hunter sometimes envelops himself in the skin\nof an ostrich, his legs doing duty for those of the bird, and his arm\nmanaging the head and neck so as to imitate the movements of the bird\nwhen feeding. The enterprising hunter is thus enabled to get among a\nflock of ostriches, and to shoot them with arrows one after another."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'When aware of an enemy they defend themselves desperately, using\ntheir powerful legs as weapons, always kicking forwards, and\ninflicting dreadful injuries on dogs, and even on men if attacked\nwithout due precaution. But let us take up our positions, and keep\nperfectly still, for the ostriches are at hand!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We held the dogs concealed as much as possible; the stately birds\nsuddenly perceiving us, paused, hesitated and appeared uneasy. Yet as\nno movement was made, they drew a few steps nearer, with outstretched\nnecks, examining curiously the unwonted spectacle before them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs became impatient, struggled from our grasp and furiously\nrushed towards our astonished visitors. In an instant they turned and\nfled with the speed of the wind; their feet seemed not to touch the\nground, their wings aiding their marvellously rapid progress."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few moments they would have been beyond our reach, but as they\nturned to fly the eagle was unhooded. Singling out the male bird the\nfalcon made his fatal swoop, and, piercing the skull, the magnificent\ncreature was laid low. Before we could reach the spot the dogs had\njoined the bird of prey, and were fiercely tearing the flesh and\nbedabbling the splendid plumes with gore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This sight grieved us. 'What a pity we could not capture this glorious\nbird alive!' exclaimed Fritz, as we took its beautiful feathers. 'It\nmust, I am sure, have stood more than six feet high, and two of us\nmight have mounted him at once!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In the vast sandy deserts where nothing grows, what can flocks of\nthese birds find to live upon?' inquired Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That would indeed be hard to say, if the deserts were utterly barren\nand unfruitful,' returned I, 'but over these sandy wastes a beneficent\nProvidence scatters plants of wild melons, which absorb and retain\nevery drop of moisture, and which quench the thirst as well as satisfy\nthe hunger of the ostriches and other inhabitants of the wilds. These\nmelons, however, do not constitute his entire diet; he feeds freely on\ngrasses, dates and hard grain, when he can obtain them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Does the ostrich utter any cry?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The voice of the ostrich is a deep hollow rumbling sound, so much\nresembling the roar of the lion as to be occasionally mistaken for it.\nBut what does Jack mean by waving his cap, and beckoning in that\nexcited fashion? What has the boy found, I wonder?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He ran a little way towards us, shouting: 'Eggs, father! Ostriches'\neggs! A huge nest-fullâ€”do come quickly!' We all hastened to the spot,\nand in a slight hollow of the ground, beheld more than twenty eggs, as\nlarge as an infant's head."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The idea of carrying more than two away with us was preposterous,\nalthough the boys, forgetting what the weight would be, seriously\ncontemplated clearing the nest. They were satisfied when a kind of\nlandmark had been set up, so that if we returned we might easily find\nthe nest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As each egg weighed about three pounds, the boys soon found the burden\nconsiderable, even when tied into a handkerchief and carried like a\nbasket. To relieve them, I cut a strong elastic heath stick, and\nsuspending an egg in its sling at each end, laid the bent stick over\nJack's shoulder, and like a Dutch dairy-maid with her milkpails, he\nstepped merrily along without inconvenience."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We presently reached a marshy place surrounding a little pool\nevidently fed by the stream which Knips had discovered. The soft\nground was trodden and marked by the footsteps of many different sorts\nof animals; we saw tracks of buffaloes, antelopes, onagers or quaggas,\nbut no trace whatever of any kind of serpent: hitherto our journey in\nsearch of monster reptiles had been signalized by very satisfactory\nfailure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this brook we sat down to rest and take some food; Fangs presently\ndisappeared, and Jack calling to his pet discovered him gnawing at\nsomething which he had dug from the marsh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Taking it for a root of some sort, Jack brought it for my inspection. I\ndipped it in water to clear off the mud, and to my surprise found a\nqueer little living creature, no bigger than half an apple, in my hand.\nIt was a small tortoise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A tortoise, I declare!' cried Fritz. 'What a long way from the sea.\nHow came it here, I wonder?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Perhaps there has been a tortoise-shower,' remarked Ernest. 'One\nreads of frog-showers in the time of the ancient Romans.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hollo, Professor! You're out for once,' said I. 'This is nothing but a\nmud-tortoise, which lives in wet, marshy ground and fresh water. They\nare useful in gardens; for although they like a few lettuce leaves now\nand then, they will destroy numbers of snails, grubs, and worms.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Resuming our journey, we arrived at a charming valley, verdant,\nfruitful, and shaded by clumps of graceful trees. It afforded us the\ngreatest delight and refreshment to pass along this cool and lovely\nvale, which we agreed to call Glen Verdant."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the distance we could see herds of antelopes or buffaloes feeding;\nbut as our dogs continually ranged a long way ahead of us, they were\nquickly startled, and vanished up one or other of the narrow gorges\nwhich opened out of the valley."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Following the imperceptible windings of the vale, we were surprised, on\nquitting it for the more open ground, to find ourselves in country we\nwere already acquainted with, and not far from the Jackal Cave, as we\ncalled the place where Fangs had been captured in cubhood."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On recognizing the spot, Ernest, who was in advance with one of the\ndogs, hastened towards it. We lost sight of him for a few minutes, and\nthen arose a cry of terror, violent barking and deep, surly growls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we rushed forward, Ernest met us, looking white as ashes, and\ncalling out:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A bear, a bear, father! He is coming after me!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boy clung to me in mortal fear. I felt his whole frame quivering."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Courage, my son!' cried I, disengaging myself from his grasp. 'We must\nprepare for instant defence!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs dashed forward to join the fray, whatever it was; and not long\nwere we in doubt. To my no small consternation, an enormous bear made\nhis appearance, quickly followed by another."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With levelled guns, my brave Fritz and I advanced slowly to meet them.\nJack was also ready to fire, but the shock had so unnerved Ernest that\nhe fairly took to his heels. We fired together, one at each bear; but\nthough hit, the monsters were unfortunately only wounded. We found it\nmost difficult to take aim, as the dogs beset them on all sides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "However, they were much disabled, one having the lower jaw broken, and\nthe other, with a bullet in its shoulder, was effectually lamed. The\ndogs, perceiving their advantage, pressed more closely round their\nfoes, who yet defended themselves furiously with frightful yells of\npain and rage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Such was the confusion and perpetual movement of the struggle, that I\ndared not fire again, seeing that even slightly wounding one of our\ngallant hounds would instantly place him in the power of the raging\nbears."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Watching our opportunity, we suddenly advanced with loaded pistols to\nwithin a very few paces of the animals, and firing, both fell dead, one\nshot through the head, the other, in the act of rearing to spring on\nFritz, received his charge in its heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Thank Heaven!' cried I, as with dull groans the brutes sank to the\nground. 'We have escaped the greatest peril we have yet encountered!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs continued to tear and worry the fallen foe, as though\nunwilling to trust the appearance of death. With feelings somewhat\nakin, I drew my hunting-knife, and made assurance doubly sure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Seeing all safe, Jack raised a shout of victory, that poor Ernest\nmight gain courage to approach the scene of conflict, which at last he\ndid, and joined us in examining the dangerous animals, as they lay\nmotionless before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every point was full of interest, their wounds, their sharp teeth,\ntheir mighty claws, the extraordinary strength of neck and shoulder,\nall were remarked and commented on, and observing that the shaded brown\nhair was tipped with glossy white, I thought that these might be the\nsilver bears* mentioned in Captain Clarke's journey to the north-west\ncoasts of America."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Grizzlies, not polar bears"
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, my lads,' said I, 'if we have failed to catch sight of\nserpents, we have at least made good riddance of some other bad\nrubbish! These fellows would one day have worked us woe, or I am much\nmistaken. What's to be done next?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, skin them, to be sure,' said Fritz. 'We shall have a couple of\nsplendid bear-skin rugs.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As this process would take time and evening drew on, we dragged the\nhuge carcases into their den, to await our return, concealing them with\nboughs of trees and fencing the entrance as well as we could. The\nostrich eggs we also left behind us, hidden in a sandy hole."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By sunset we reached the tent, and joyfully rejoined my wife and\nFranz, right glad to find a hearty meal prepared for us, as well as a\nlarge heap of brushwood for the watch-fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When a full account of our adventures had been given, with a minute and\nspecial description of the bear-fight, my wife related what she had\ndone during our absence. She and Franz had made their way through the\nwood up to the rocks behind it, and discovered a bed of pure white\nclay, which it seemed to her might be used for making porcelain. Then\nshe had contrived a drinking-trough for the cattle out of a split\nbamboo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She had arranged a hearth in a sheltered place by building up large\nstones, cemented with the white clay; and, finally, she had cut a\nquantity of canes and brought them, on the cart, to be in readiness for\nthe building we had in hand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I praised the thoughtful diligence which had effected so much that was\nof real and definite use. In order to try the clay I put some balls of\nit in the fire now kindled to burn during the night, and we then betook\nourselves to rest under shelter of our tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I awoke at dawn and aroused my little party. My first idea was to\nexamine the clay balls, which I found baked hard and finely glazed, but\ntoo much melted down by the heatâ€”a fault which, seeing the excellent\nquality of the clay, I knew it would be well worthwhile to remedy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After breakfast, and our accustomed devotions, we harnessed the cart,\nand took the way to the bears' den. Fritz headed the party, and, coming\nin sight of the entrance to the cave, called out softly:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Make haste and you will see a whole crowd of wild turkeys, who seem to\nhave come to attend the funeral obsequies of their respected friend and\nneighbour, Bruin, here. But there appears to be a jealous watcher who\nis unwilling to admit the visitors to the bed of state!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The Watcher, as Fritz called him, was an immensely large bird, with a\nsort of comb on his head, and a loose fleshy skin hanging from beneath\nthe beak. Part of the neck was bare, wrinkled and purplish-red, while\naround it, resting on the shoulders, was a downy collar of soft white\nfeathers. The plumage was greyish-brown, marked here and there with\nwhite patches; the feet appeared to be armed with strong claws. This\ngreat bird guarded the entrance to the cave, occasionally retiring into\nit himself for a few minutes; but as soon as the other birds came\npressing in after him, he hurried out again and they were forced to\nretire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We stopped to observe this curious scene, and were startled suddenly by\na mighty rush of wings in the air above us. We looked up; at the same\nmoment Fritz fired, and an enormous bird fell heavily head foremost on\nthe rocks, by which its neck was broken, while blood flowed from a\nwound in the breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had been holding back the dogs, but they, with Fritz, now rushed\ntowards the cave, the birds rising around them and departing with heavy\nungainly flight, leaving only Fritz's prize, and one of the other\nbirds, killed by the large one in its fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With the utmost caution I entered the cave, and rejoiced to find that\nthe tongue and eyes only of the bears had been devoured: a little later\nand we should have had the handsome skins pecked and torn to rags, and\nall chance of steaks and bears'-paws gone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On measuring the wings of the large bird from tip to tip, I found the\nlength exceeded eleven feet, and concluded it to be a condor; it was\nevidently the mate of the 'Watcher', as Fritz called the first we saw."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To work we now went on the bears, and no slight affair we found it to\nskin and cut them up, but by dint of perseverance we at last succeeded\nin our object."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Determining to smoke the meat on the spot, we cut magnificent hams, and\ntook off the rest of the meat in slices after the manner of the\nbuccaneers in the West Indies, preserving the paws entire to be cooked\nas a delicacy, and obtaining from the two bears together a prodigious\nsupply of lard, which my wife gladly undertook to melt and prepare for\nkeeping."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bones and offal we drew to some distance with the help of our\ncattle, and made the birds of the air most welcome to feast upon it.\nThis, with the assistance of all sorts of insects, they did so\neffectually that before we left the place the skulls were picked\nperfectly clean, the sun had dried them, and they were ready for us to\ncarry off to our museum."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The skins had to be very carefully scraped, washed, salted, cleansed\nwith ashes and dried, which occupied fully two days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was lamenting our distance from the rascusara* tree, the leaves of\nwhich had flavoured our roast peccary so nicely, when I observed among\nthe brushwood which the boys had brought from the thickets around us, a\nclimbing plant, whose leaves had a very strong smell; the stem\nresembled a vine, and the fruit grew in clusters like currants. Some\nwere red, and some of a green colour, which I supposed to denote\nvarious degrees of ripeness. They were hard, and the outer skin was\nquite thin. I recognized in this the pepper plant, a discovery\nparticularly agreeable at this moment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Previously he called it ravensara."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys soon gathered a large supply; the red berries were soaked in\nsalt and water for several days, then washed and rubbed, and finally,\nbecoming perfectly white, were dried in the sun. The treatment of the\ngreen berries was simple; they were merely exposed to the sun's heat\nfor a day or two, and then stored: in this way we obtained enough, both\nof black and white pepper, to last us a very long time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took also a number of young plants, that we might have pepper\ngrowing at Rockburg and our various settlements. Some roots of another\nplant were also taken, which, from the pods, appeared to be a kind of\nbean."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were glad of this occupation during the tedious business of smoking\nthe bears' meat, and availed ourselves of the leisure time by also\npreparing for stuffing the condor and the turkey buzzard, urubu or\nblack vultureâ€”for I could not determine to which species the smaller\nbird belonged."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The four boys at length became so weary of inaction, that I determined\nto let them make an excursion alone on the savannah."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Three of them received this permission with eager delight, but Ernest\nsaid he would prefer to remain with us; to which, as the expedition was\nto be entirely one of pleasure, I could make no objection."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Little Franz, on the other hand, whom I would willingly have kept with\nus, was wild to go with his brothers, and I was obliged to consent, as\nI had made the proposal open to all, and could not draw back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the highest spirits they ran to bring their steeds (as we were fain\nto call the cattle they rode) from their pasturage at a short distance.\nSpeedily were they saddled, bridled and mountedâ€”the three lads were\nready to be off."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was my wish that our sons should cultivate a habit of bold\nindependence, for well I knew that it might be the will of God to\ndeprive them easily of their parents; when, without an enterprising\nspirit of self-reliance, their position would be truly miserable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My gallant Fritz possessed this desirable quality in no small degree,\nand to him I committed the care of his young brothers, charging them to\nlook up to and obey him as their leader."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were well armed, well mounted, had a couple of good dogs; and,\nwith a hearty 'God speed and bless you, my boys!' I let them depart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We who remained behind passed the day in a variety of useful\noccupations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bears' meat, which was being cured in a smoking-shed such as that\nwe set up for the peccary hams, required a good deal of attention from\nmy wife. Ernest had a fancy for making ornamental cups from the ostrich\neggs, while I investigated the interior of the cave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I found the inner wall to consist of a kind of talc, mingled with\nthreads of asbestos, and also indications of mica. Examining further, I\ndetached a large block, and found to my joy that I could split it into\nclear transparent sheets, which would serve admirably for window panes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife saw this substitute for glass with unfeigned satisfaction,\ndeclaring, that although she would not complain, yet the want of glass\nfor windows had been a downright trouble to her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 13"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As evening approached, the bears' paws, which were stewing for supper,\nsent forth savoury odours; and we sat talking round the fire, while\nlistening anxiously for sounds heralding the return of our young\nexplorers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At last the tramp and beat of hoofs struck our ears; the little troop\nappeared, crossing the open ground before us at a sharp trot, and a\nshrill ringing cheer greeted us as we rose and went to meet them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They sprang from their saddles, the animals were set at liberty to\nrefresh themselves, and the riders eagerly came to exhibit their\nacquisitions and give an account of themselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Funny figures they cut! Franz and Jack had each a young kid slung on\nhis back, so that the four legs, tied together, stuck out under their\nchins."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz's game-bag looked remarkably queerâ€”round lumps, sharp points,\nand an occasional movement seemed to indicate a living creature or\ncreatures within."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah, for the chase, father!' cried Jack. 'Nothing like real\nhunting after all. And just to see how Storm and Grumble go along over\na grassy plain! It is perfectly splendid! We soon tired out the little\nantelopes, and were able to catch them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes, father,' said Franz, 'and Fritz has two angora rabbits in his\nbag, and we wanted to bring you some honey. Only think! Such a clever\nbirdâ€”a cuckoo, showed us where it was!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My brothers forget the chief thing,' said Fritz. 'We have driven a\nlittle herd of antelopes right through the Gap into our territory; and\nthere they are, all ready for us to hunt when we likeâ€”or to catch and\ntame!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done!' cried I. 'Here is indeed a list of achievements. But to\nyour mother and me, the chief thing of all, is God's goodness in\nbringing you safe back to us. Now, let us hear the whole story that we\nmay have a definite idea of your performances.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We had a splendid ride,' said Fritz, 'down Glen Verdant, and away to\nthe defile through our Rocky Barrier, and the morning was so cool and\nfresh that our steeds galloped along, nearly the whole way, at the top\nof their speed. When we had passed through the Gap we moderated our\nfurious pace and kept our eyes open on the look-out for game; we then\ntrotted slowly to the top of a grassy hill, from whose summit we saw\ntwo herds of animals, whether antelopes, goats or gazelles, we did not\nknow, grazing by the side of the stream below us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We were about to gallop down and try to get a shot at them, when it\nstruck me that it would be wiser to try and drive the whole herd\nthrough the Gap into our own domain, where they would be shut up, as it\nwere, in a park, free and yet within reach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Down the hill we rode as hard as we could go, formed in a semicircle\nbehind the larger herd of magnificent antelopesâ€”and, aided by the dogs,\nwith shouts and cries drove them along the stream towards the Gap; as\nwe came near the opening they appeared inclined to halt and turn like\nsheep about to be driven into the butcher's yard; and it was all we\ncould do to prevent them from bolting past us; but, at length, one made\na rush at the opening and, the rest following, they were soon all on\nthe other side of the frontier and inhabitants of New Switzerland.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Capital,' I said, 'capital, my boy! But I don't see what is to make\nthem remain inhabitants of our domain, or to prevent them from\nreturning through the Gap whenever they feel inclined.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop, father,' he replied, 'you interrupted me too soon; we thought of\nthat possibility too, and provided against it. We stretched a long line\nright across the defile and strung on it feathers and rags and all\nsorts of other things, which danced and fluttered in the wind, and\nlooked so strange that I am perfectly certain that the herd will never\nattempt to pass it; in fact, Levaillant, from whom I learnt the trick,\nsays in his Voyage au Cap de Bonne Esperance that the Hottentots make\nuse of the method for penning in the antelopes they have caught in the\nchase.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done,' said I, 'I am glad to see that you remember what you have\nread. The antelopes are welcome to New Switzerland, but, my boy,' I\nadded, 'I cannot say the same for the rabbits you have there; they\nincrease so rapidly that if you establish a colony of the little\nwretches your next difficulty will be to get rid of them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'True,' he replied, 'but my idea was to place them upon Whale Island,\nwhere they would find abundant food, and at the same time in no way\ntrouble us. May I not establish a warren there? It would be so useful.\nDo you know my eagle caught these pretty little fellows for me? I saw a\nnumber of them running about and so unhooded him, and in a few minutes\nhe brought me threeâ€”one dead, with whose body I rewarded him, and\nthese two here, unhurt.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, father,' said Jack, interrupting him, 'do listen to me and hear\nmy story, or else Fritz will begin upon my adventures and tire you out\nwith his rigmarole descriptions.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Certainly, Jack,' I said, 'I am quite ready to listen to you. First\nand foremostly, how did you bring down those beautiful little animals\nyou have there?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, we galloped them down. The dogs sniffed about in the grass while\nFritz was away after the rabbits, out popped these little fawns and\naway they went bounding and skipping, at the rate of thirty miles an\nhour, with Storm, Grumble and the dogs at their heels. In about a\nquarter of an hour we had left the dogs behind and were close upon our\nprey. Down went the little creatures in the grass, and, overcome with\nterror and fatigue, were at our mercy. So we shouted to Fritz, andâ€”'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear boy,' said I, 'according to your statement, Fritz must have\nbeen seven miles and a half off.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, well, father, perhaps we did not ride for quite a quarter of an\nhour, and, of course, I can't say exactly how fast we were going; and\nthen, you see, the fawns did not run in a straight line; at any rate\nFritz heard us, and he and Franz and I leashed the legs of the pretty\ncreatures, and then we mounted again, and presently saw a wretch of a\ncuckoo, who led us ever so far out of our course by cuckooing and\nmaking faces at us and then hopping away. Franz declared it must be an\nenchanted princess, and so I thought I would rid it of its spell; but\nFritz stopped me shooting it, and said it was a \"Honey Indicator\", and\nthat it was leading us probably to a bees' byke, so we spared its life,\nand presently, sure enough, it stopped close by a bees' nest in a\nhollow tree."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This was capital, we thought, and, as we were in a great hurry to\ntaste the honey, I threw in a lot of lighted lucifer matches, but\nsomehow it did not kill the bees at all, but only made them awfully\nangry, and they flew out in a body and stung me all over. I rushed to\nStorm and sprang on his back, but, though I galloped away for bare\nlife, it was an age before I got rid of the little wretches, and now my\nface is in a perfect fever. I think I will get mother to bathe it for\nme,' and off rushed the noisy boy, leaving Fritz and me to see to the\nfawns and examine the rabbits."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With these latter I determined to do as Fritz proposed, namely, to\ncolonize Whale Island with them. I was all the more willing to do this\nbecause I had been considering the advisability of establishing on that\nisland a fortress to which we might retreat in any extreme danger, and\nwhere we should be very thankful, in case of such a retreat, to possess\nmeans of obtaining a constant supply of animal food."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having ministered to the wants of the antelopes, I tried to interest\nthe boys in my discovery of the block of talc, but just then their\nmother summoned us to dinner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The principal dish in this meal consisted of the bears' pawsâ€”most\nsavoury-smelling delicacies, so tempting that their close resemblance\nto human hands, and even the roguish 'Fee-fo-fum' from Jack, did not\nprevent a single member of the family from enjoying them most heartily."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Supper over, we lit our watch-fire, retired to our tent and slept\nsoundly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had been working very diligently; the bears' meat was smoked, the\nfat melted down and stored, and a large supply of bamboos collected.\nBut I wished to make yet another excursion, and at early dawn I aroused\nthe boys."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz mounted the mule, I rode Lightfoot, Jack and Franz took their\nusual steeds and, with the two dogs, we galloped offâ€”first to visit\nthe euphorbia to collect the gum, and then to discover whether the\nostrich had deserted her eggs in the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest watched us depart without the slightest look or sigh of regret,\nand returned to the tent to assist his mother and study his books."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our steeds carried us down the Green Valley at a rapid rate, and we\nfollowed the direction we had pursued on our former expedition. We soon\nreached Turtle Marsh, and then, filling our water-flasks, we arrived at\nthe rising ground where Fritz discovered the mounted Arabs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As Jack and Franz wanted a gallop, I allowed them to press forward,\nwhile Fritz and I visited the euphorbia trees. A quantity of the red\ngum had exuded from the incisions I had made, and as this had\ncoagulated in the sun, I rolled it into little balls and stored it in a\nbamboo jar I had brought with me for the purpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we rode after the boys, who were some way ahead, Fritz remarked,\n'Did you not tell me that the juice of that tree was poisonous, father;\nwhy have you collected such a quantity?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I did indeed say so,' I replied, 'it is a most deadly poison. The\ninhabitants of the Cape of Good Hope use it to poison the springs where\nwild animals assemble to quench their thirst; and they thus slaughter\nan immense number of the creatures for the sake of their hides. I\nintend, however, to use it to destroy the apes should they again commit\ndepredations, and also in preparing the skins of animals to protect\nthem from the attacks of insects.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The two boys were still at some distance from us, when suddenly four\nmagnificent ostriches rose from the sand where they had been sitting."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack and Franz perceived them, and with a great shout, drove them\ntowards us. In front ran a splendid male bird, his feathers of shining\nblack, and his great tail plume waving behind. Three females of an\nashen grey colour followed him. They approached us with incredible\nswiftness, and were within gun-shot before they perceived us. Fritz had\nhad the forethought to bind up the beak of his eagle so that, should he\nbring down an ostrich, he might be unable to injure it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He now threw up the falcon which, towering upwards, swooped down upon\nthe head of the foremost bird, and so confused and alarmed him, that he\ncould not defend himself nor continue his flight. So greatly was his\nspeed checked that Jack overtook him, and hurling his lasso, enfolded\nhis wings and legs in its deadly coils and brought him to the ground.\nThe other ostriches were almost out of sight, so leaving them to their\nown devices we leaped from our steeds and attempted to approach the\ncaptured bird. He struggled fearfully, and kicked with such violence\nright and left, that I almost despaired of getting him home alive."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It occurred to me, however, that if we could cover his eyes, his fury\nmight be subdued. I instantly acted upon this idea, and flung over his\nhead my coat and hunting bag, which effectually shut out the light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner had I done this than his struggles ceased, and we were able\nto approach. We first secured round his body a broad strip of sealskin,\non each side of which I fastened a stout piece of cord, that I might be\nable to lead him easily. Then, fastening another cord in a loop round\nhis legs that he might be prevented from breaking into a gallop, we\nreleased him from the coils of the lasso."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do you know,' said I to the boys, 'how the natives of India secure a\nnewly captured elephant?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, yes!' said Fritz. 'They fasten him between two tame elephants.\nWe'll do that to this fine fellow, and tame him double quick.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The only difficulty will be,' remarked Jack, 'that we have no tame\nostriches. However, I daresay Storm and Grumble will have no objection\nto perform their part, and it will puzzle even this great monster to\nrun away with them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So we at once began operations. Storm and Grumble were led up on\neither side of the recumbent ostrich, and the cords secured to their\ngirths. Jack and Franz, each armed with a stout whip, mounted their\nrespective steeds, the wrappers were removed from the bird's eyes, and\nwe stood by to watch what would next occur."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For some moments after the return of his sight he lay perfectly still,\nthen he arose with a bound and, not aware of the cords which hampered\nhim, attempted to dash forwards. The thongs were stout, and he was\nbrought to his knees. A fruitless struggle ensued, and then at length\nseeming to accommodate himself to circumstances, he set off at a sharp\ntrot, his guards making the air re-echo with their merry shouts. These\ncries stimulated the ostrich to yet further exertions, but he was at\nlength brought to a stand by the determined refusal of his four-footed\ncompanions to continue such a race across loose sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys having enjoyed the long run, I told them to walk with the\nprisoner slowly home, while Fritz and I returned to examine the\nostrich's nest. The eggs were quite warm, and I was certain that the\nmother had quite recently left the nest; leaving about half, I packed\nthe rest of the eggs in a large bag I had brought for the purpose, and\nslung it carefully on the saddle before me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We soon caught up our advance guard, and without other notable\nincident reached our tent."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Astonishment and dismay were depicted on the face of my wife as we\napproached."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear husband,' she exclaimed, 'do you think our provisions so\nabundant that you must scour the deserts to find some great beast to\nassist us to devour them? You must discover an iron mine next, for iron\nis what ostriches chiefly live on, is it not?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh! I do wish you would be content with the menagerie you have\nalready collected, instead of bringing in a specimen of every beast you\ncome across. And this is such a useless monster!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Useless! Mother,' exclaimed Jack, 'you would not say so had you seen\nhim run; why he will be the fleetest courser in our stables. I am going\nto make a saddle and bridle for him, and in future he shall be my only\nsteed. Then as for his appetite, father declares it is most delicate,\nhe only wants a little fruit and grass, and a few stones and tenpenny\nnails to help his digestion.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The way in which Jack assumed the proprietorship of our new prize\nseemed to strike his brothers as rather cool, and there was instantly a\ncry raised on the subject."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Very well,' said Jack, 'let us each take possession of the part of the\nostrich we captured. Your bird, Fritz, seized the head; keep that;\nfather shall have the body, I'll have the legs, and Franz a couple of\nfeathers from the tail.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come, come,' said I, 'I think that Jack has a very good right to the\nostrich, seeing that he brought it to the ground, and if he succeeds in\ntaming it and converting it into a saddle-horse it shall be his. From\nthis time, therefore, he is responsible for its training.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The day was now too far advanced to allow us to think of setting out\nfor Rockburg, so we fastened up the ostrich between two trees, and\ndevoted the remainder of the evening to making preparations for our\ndeparture."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At early dawn our picturesque caravan was moving homewards. The\nostrich continued so refractory that we were obliged to make him again\nmarch between Storm and Grumble, and as these gallant steeds were thus\nemployed, the cow was harnessed to the cart, laden with our treasures.\nRoom was left in the cart for my wife, Jack and Franz mounted Storm and\nGrumble, I rode Lightfoot, and Fritz brought up the rear on Swift."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the mouth of the Gap we called a halt, and replaced the cord the\nboys had strung with ostrich feathers by a stout palisade of bamboos. I\nalso took the opportunity of collecting a store of pipe-clay, as I\nintended during the winter months, which were close at hand, to try my\nhand at china making."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When we reached the sugar-cane grove, we again stopped to collect the\npeccary hams we had left to be smoked; and my wife begged me to gather\nsome seeds of an aromatic plant which grew in the neighbourhood, and\nwhich had the scent of vanilla. I obtained a good supply, and we moved\nforward towards Woodlands, where we intended to rest for the night,\nafter our long and fatiguing march."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our tent was pitched, and on our beds of cotton we slept soundly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning early we examined our farmyard, which appeared in a most\nprosperous and flourishing condition. The sight of all these domestic\nanimals made us long even more than ever for our home at Rockburg, and\nwe determined to hasten thither with all possible speed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The number of our pigs, goats and poultry had greatly increased since\nwe had last visited our colony; and some of these, two fine broods of\nchickens especially, my wife wished to take back with her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We found that the herd of antelopes which Fritz and Jack had driven\nthrough the Gap, had taken up their abode in the neighbourhood, and\nseveral times we saw the beautiful animals browsing amongst the trees."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While at the farm, we repaired both the animals' stalls, and our\ndwelling-room, that the former might be more secure against the\nattacks of wild beasts, and the latter fitted for our accommodation\nwhen we should visit the spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everything at length being satisfactorily arranged, we again retired to\nrest, and early next morning completed our journey to Rockburg."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By midday we were once more settled at home. Windows and doors were\nthrown open to admit fresh air; the animals established in their\nstalls; and the cart's miscellaneous cargo discharged and arranged."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As much time as I could spare, I devoted to the ostrich, whom we\nfastened, for the present, between two bamboo posts in front of our\ndwelling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I then turned my attention to the eggs we had brought, and which I\ndetermined to hatch, if possible by artificial heat. For this purpose I\narranged a stove, which I maintained at a uniform temperature, and on\nit I placed the eggs carefully wrapped in cotton wool."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning Fritz and I went off in the boat first to Whale Island,\nthere to establish our colonists, the angora rabbits, and then to Shark\nIsland, where we placed the dainty little antelopes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having made them happy with their liberty and abundance of food, we\nreturned as quickly as possible to cure the bears' skins, and add the\nprovisions we had brought to the stores lying in our cellar."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we returned, we caught up Jack, making his way in great glee\ntowards Rockburg. He was carrying, in a basket, an immense eel, which\nhe and Ernest had secured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest had set, on the previous night, a couple of lines; one had been\ndragged away, but on the other they found this splendid fellow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It proved delicious. Half was prepared for dinner, and the other half\nsalted and stowed away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We now, for a short time, again turned our attention to our duties\nabout the house."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Thinking that the verandah would be greatly improved by some creepers,\nI sowed round the foot of each bamboo pillar, vanilla, and pepper-seed,\nas well as that of other creeping plants, which would not only give the\nhouse a pleasanter aspect, but also afford us shade during the summer\nmonths."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I constructed a couple of hen-coops too, for the hens and their little\nchicks which we had brought from Woodlands, for I knew that if I left\nthem unprotected, the inquisitive dispositions of Knips and Fangs might\ninduce them to make anatomical experiments which would be detrimental\nto the welfare of the youngsters."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest's rat-skins were voted a nuisance within doors, and were tied\ntogether and hung up outside; so powerful was the odour they emitted,\nthat even then Jack would pretend to faint every time he passed near\nthem."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The museum received its additions: the condor and vulture were placed\nthere, to be stuffed when we should find time during the rainy season.\nThe mica and asbestos, too, were brought in for the present, not to lie\nthere idle, but to wait until I could use them as I intended, for china\nand lamp-wicks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having occupied two days in this way, we turned our attention to other\nduties: the cultivation of a wheat, barley and maize field, the\nmanagement of the ostrich's eggs, and the taming of the captives."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As agriculture was, though the least to our taste, the most important\nof these several duties, we set about it first. The animals drew the\nplough, but the digging and hoeing taxed our powers of endurance to the\nutmost."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We worked two hours in the morning and two in the evening. Fully did we\nrealize the words of Scripture: 'In the sweat of thy face shalt thou\neat bread.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the interval we devoted our attention to the ostrich. But our\nefforts on behalf of his education seemed all in vain. He appeared as\nuntameable as ever. I determined, therefore, to adopt the plan which\nhad subdued the refractory eagle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The effect of the tobacco fumes almost alarmed me. The ostrich sank to\nthe ground and lay motionless. Slowly, at length, he arose, and paced\nup and down between the bamboo posts. He was subdued, but to my dismay\nresolutely refused all food. I feared he would die; for three days he\npined, growing weaker and weaker each day."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Food he must have!' cried I. 'Food he must have!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife determined to attempt an experiment. She prepared balls of\nmaize flour, mixed with butter. One of these she placed within the\nbird's beak. He swallowed it, and stretched out his long neck, looking\ninquiringly for a second mouthful. A second, third, and fourth ball\nfollowed the first. His appetite returned, and his strength came again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All the wild nature of the bird had gone, and I saw with delight that\nwe might begin his education as soon as we chose. Rice, guavas, maize\nand corn he ate readilyâ€”'washing it down', as Jack expressed it, with\nsmall pebbles, to the great surprise of Franz, to whom I explained that\nthe ostrich was merely following the instinct common to all birds; that\nhe required these pebbles to digest his food, just as smaller birds\nrequire gravel."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After a month of careful training, our captive would trot, gallop, obey\nthe sound of our voice, feed from our hand; and, in fact, showed\nhimself perfectly docile. Now our ingenuity was taxed to the utmost.\nHow were we to saddle and bridle a bird? First, for a bit for his beak.\nVague ideas passed through my mind, but every one I was obliged to\nreject. A plan at length occurred to me. I recollected the effect of\nlight and its absence upon the ostrich, how his movements were checked\nby sudden darkness, and how, with the light, power returned to his\nlimbs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I immediately constructed a leathern hood, to reach from the neck to\nthe beak, cutting holes in it for the eyes and ears. Over the\neyes-holes I contrived square flaps or blinkers, which were so\narranged with whalebone springs that they closed tightly of\nthemselves. The reins were connected with these blinkers, so that the\nflaps might be raised or allowed to close at the rider's pleasure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When both blinkers were open, the ostrich would gallop straight ahead;\nclose his right eye and he turned to the left, close his left and he\nturned to the right, shut both and he stood stock still."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was justly proud of my contrivance, but, before I could really test\nits utility, I was obliged to make a saddle. After several failures, I\nsucceeded in manufacturing one to my liking and in properly securing\nit; it was something like an old-fashioned trooper's saddle, peaked\nbefore and behindâ€”for my great fear was lest the boys should fall.\nThis curious-looking contrivance I placed upon the shoulders as near\nthe neck as possible, and secured it with strong girths round the wings\nand across the breast, to avoid all possibility of the saddle slipping\ndown the bird's sloping back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I soon saw that my plan would succeed, though skill and considerable\npractise was necessary in the use of my patent bridle. It was difficult\nto remember that to check the courser's speed it was necessary to\nslacken rein, and that the tighter the reins were drawn, the faster he\nwould fly. We at length, however, all learned to manage Master\nHurricane, and the distance between Rockburg and Falconhurst was\ntraversed in an almost incredibly short space of time. The marvellous\nspeed of the bird again revived the dispute as to the ownership, and I\nwas obliged to interfere."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack shall retain the ostrich,' said I, 'for it is most suited to him;\nhe is a lighter weight than either of you his elder brothers, and Franz\nis not yet strong enough to manage such a fleet courser. But he is so\nfar to be considered common property, that all may practise on him\noccasionally; and, in a case of necessity, anyone may mount him.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our field-work was by this time over. The land had been ploughed and\nsown with wheat, barley, and maize. On the other side of Jackal River\nwe had planted potatoes and cassava roots, and all sorts of other seeds\nhad been carefully sown."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We had not neglected the ostrich's eggs, and one day Fritz introduced\nme with great glee to three little ostriches. But alas, the little\ncreatures were not destined to enjoy life for long. One died almost as\nsoon as it was hatched, and the others, after tottering about on their\nstilt-like legs for a few days, followed its example."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now found time to turn my attention to the bears' skins, which\nrequired preparation before they would be fit for use as leather. They\nhad been salted and dried, and now required tanning. I had no tan,\nhowever. This was unfortunate; but not to be deterred from my purpose,\nI determined to use a mixture of honey and water in its place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The experiment proved successful. When the skins were dried they\nremained flexible and free from smell, while the fur was soft and\nglossy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This was not the only result of the experiment, for the honey-water\nwhich I boiled appeared so clear and tempting, that it struck me that I\nmight prepare from it an excellent drink. I put by some of the liquid\nbefore making use of it as tan, and reboiled it with nutmeg and\ncinnamon. The preparation, which much resembled English mead, was\npronounced delicious, and my wife begged me to brew a large supply. As\nour cellar was now well stocked with provisions for the winter, and our\nother preparations were completed, I was able to turn my attention to\ndetails of lesser importance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys had been clamouring for hats, and as my success in so many\ntrades had surprised me, I agreed to turn hatter for the nonce. With\nthe rat-skins and a solution of india-rubber, I produced a kind of\nfelt, which I dyed a brilliant red with cochineal, and stretching this\non a wooden block I had prepared, I passed over it a hot iron, to\nsmooth the nap, and by next morning had the satisfaction of presenting\nto my wife a neat little red Swiss cap, to be lined and finished by her\nfor one of the boys."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife admired the production immensely, and lining it with silk,\nadded yet more to its gay appearance, by adorning it with ribbons and\nostrich feathers, and finally placed it upon the head of little Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So delighted was everyone with the hat, that all were eager to be\nsimilarly provided, and begged me to manufacture more. I readily\nagreed to do so, as soon as they should furnish me with the necessary\nmaterials, and advised them to make half a dozen rat-traps, that they\nmight secure the water rats with which the stream abounded, and whose\nrich glossy fur would serve admirably for felt."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every fifth animal that they brought me I told them should be mine,\nthat I might obtain material for a hat for myself and their mother. The\nboys at once agreed to this arrangement, and began the manufacture of\nthe traps, which were all so made that they should kill the rats at\nonce, for I could not bear the idea of animals being tortured or\nimprisoned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While they were thus engaged I applied myself to the manufacture of\nporcelain. I first cleaned the pipe-clay and talc from all foreign\nsubstances, and made them ready to be beaten down with water into a\nsoft mass, and then prepared my moulds of gypsum plaster. These\npreparations were at length made, and the moulds received a thin layer\nof the porcelain material. When this was partly baked, I sprinkled over\nit a powder of coloured glass beads which I had crushed, and which\nlooked very pretty in patterns upon the transparent porcelain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some of my china vessels cracked with the heat of the stove, some were\nvery ill-shaped; but, after many failures, I succeeded in producing a\nset of white cups and saucers, a cream-jug, a sugar-basin, and half a\ndozen small plates."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I must allow that my china was far from perfect; the shape of some of\nthe vessels was faulty, and none were really transparent;\nnevertheless, the general appearance gave great satisfaction, and when\nthe plates were filled with rosy and golden fruit resting on green\nleaves, and fragrant tea filled the cups, it greatly added to the\nappearance of the table."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 14"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Scarcely had I completed my pottery, when great black clouds and\nterrific storms heralded the approach of another winter. The rainy\nseason having set in, we were compelled to give up our daily\nexcursions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Even in the spacious house which we now occupied, and with our varied\nand interesting employments, we yet found the time dragging heavily.\nThe spirits of all were depressed, and even occasional rapid rides,\nduring a partial cessation of the rain, failed permanently to arouse\nthem. Fritz, as well as I, had perceived this, and he said to me:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Why, father, should we not make a canoe, something swifter and more\nmanageable than those vessels we as yet possess? I often long for a\nlight skiff, in which I might skim over the surface of the water.' The\nidea delighted all hands, but my wife, who was never happy when we were\non the sea, declared that our chances of drowning were, with the\npinnace and canoe, already sufficiently great, and that there was not\nthe slightest necessity for our adding to these chances by constructing\nanother craft which would tempt us out upon the perfidious element."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Her fears were, however, speedily allayed, for I assured her that the\nboat I intended to construct should be no flimsy cockleshell, but as\nsafe and stout a craft as ever floated upon the sea. The Greenlander's\ncajack I intended to be my model, and I resolved not only to occupy the\nchildren, but also to produce a strong and serviceable canoeâ€”a\nmasterpiece of art."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were interested, and the boat-building was soon in operation.\nWe constructed the skeleton of whalebone, using split bamboo canes to\nstrengthen the sides and also to form the deck, which extended the\nwhole length of the boat, leaving merely a square hole in which the\noccupant of the canoe might sit."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The work engrossed our attention most entirely, and by the time it was\ncomplete the rain had passed away and the glorious sun again shone\nbrightly forth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our front door was just wide enough to admit of the egress of our\nboat, and we completed her construction in the open air. We quickly\ncased the sides and deck with seal-skin, making all the seams\nthoroughly watertight with caoutchouc."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cajack was indeed a curious-looking craft, yet so light that she\nmight be lifted easily with one hand, and when at length we launched\nher she bounded upon the water like an india-rubber ball. Fritz was\nunanimously voted her rightful owner, but before his mother would hear\nof his entering the frail-looking skiff she declared that she must\ncontrive a swimming-dress, so that 'should his boat receive a puncture\nfrom a sharp rock or the dorsal fin of a fish and collapse, he might\nyet have a chance of saving his life'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Though I did not consider the cajack quite the soap bubble my wife\nimagined it, I yet willingly agreed to assist her in the construction\nof the dress."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The garment we produced was most curious in appearance, and I must own\nthat I doubted its efficiency. It was like a double waistcoat, made of\nlinen prepared with a solution of india-rubber, the seams being\nlikewise coated with caoutchouc, and the whole rendered perfectly\nairtight. We so arranged it that one little hole was left, by means of\nwhich air could be forced into the space between the outer covering and\nthe lining, and the dress inflated."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile I perceived with pleasure the rapid vegetation the climate\nwas producing. The seeds we had scattered had germinated, and were now\npromising magnificent crops. The verandah, too, was looking pleasant\nwith its gay and sweet-scented creepers, which were already aspiring to\nthe summit of the pillars. The air was full of birds, the earth seemed\nteeming with life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dress was at length completed and Fritz, one fine afternoon,\noffered publicly to prove it. We all assembled on the beach, the boy\ngravely donned and inflated the garment, and amidst roars of laughter\nfrom his brothers, entered the water. Quickly and easily he paddled\nhimself across the bay towards Shark Island, whither we followed in one\nof our boats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The experiment was most successful, and Ernest, Jack and Franz, in\nspite of their laughter at their brother's garment, begged their mother\nto make for each of them a similar dress."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While on the island we paid a visit to the colonists whom we had\nestablished there the previous autumn. All were well; we could\nperceive by the footprints that the antelopes had discovered and made\nuse of the shelter we had erected for them, and feeling that we could\ndo nothing more we scattered handfuls of maize and salt, and strolled\nacross to the other side of the island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The shore was covered with lovely shells, many of which, with\nbeautiful pieces of delicate coral, the boys collected for their\nmuseum; strewn by the edge of the water too lay a great quantity of\nseaweed of various colours, and as the mother declared that much of it\nwas of use, the boys assisted her to collect it and store it in the\nboat."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we pulled back to the land I was surprised to see that my wife\nchose from among the seaweed a number of curious leaves with edges\nnotched like a saw. When we reached home she carefully washed these and\ndried them in the oven. There was evidently something mysterious about\nthis preparation and my curiosity at length prompted me to make an\nattempt to discover the secret."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Are these leaves to form a substitute for tobacco?' said I. 'Do you so\nlong for its refreshing smell?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife smiled, for her dislike of tobacco was well known, and she\nanswered in the same jocular tone:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Do you not think that a mattress stuffed with these leaves would be\nvery cool in summer?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The twinkle in her eyes showed me that my curiosity must still remain\nunsatisfied, but it nevertheless became greater than ever."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys and I had one day made a long and fatiguing expedition, and,\ntired out, we flung ourselves down in the verandah. As we lay there\nresting, we heard the mother's voice:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Could any of you enjoy a little jelly?' She presently appeared,\nbearing a porcelain dish laden with most lovely transparent jelly. Cut\nwith a spoon and laid before us it quivered and glittered in the light."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ambrosia!' exclaimed Fritz, tasting it. It was indeed delicious, and,\nstill marvelling from whence my wife could have obtained a dish so\nrare, we disposed of all that she had set before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Aha,' laughed my wife, 'is not this an excellent substitute for\ntobacco, far more refreshing than the nasty weed itself. Behold the\nproduce of my mysterious seaweed.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear wife,' exclaimed I, 'this dish is indeed a masterpiece of\nculinary art, but where had you met with it? What put it into your\nhead?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While staying with my Dutch friends at the Cape,' replied she,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I often saw it, and at once recognized the leaves on Shark Island.\nOnce knowing the secret, the preparation of the dish is extremely\nsimple: the leaves are soaked in water, fresh every day, for a week,\nand then boiled for a few hours with orange juice, citron and sugar.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were all delighted with the delicacy, and thanked my wife for it\nmost heartily, the boys declaring that they must at once go off again\nto the island to collect as many of the leaves as they could find. I\nagreed to accompany them, for I wished to examine the plantations we\nhad made there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All were flourishing, the palms and mangroves had shot up in a most\nmarvellous manner, and many of the seeds which I had cast at random\namongst the clefts in the rocks had germinated, and promised to clothe\nthe nakedness of the frowning boulders."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A way up among the rocks too we discovered a bright sparkling spring of\ndelicious water, at which, from the footprints around, we saw that the\nantelopes must have refreshed themselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Finding everything so satisfactory, we were naturally anxious to\ndiscover how our colony and plantations on Whale Island had fared. It\nwas evident at a glance that the rabbits had increased, the young and\ntender shoots of the trees bore the marks of many greedy mischievous\nlittle teeth. The cocoanut palms alone had they spared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Such depredations as these could not be allowed, and with the help of\nthe boys I erected round each stem a hedge of prickly thorn, and then\nprepared again to embark; before we did so, however, I noticed that\nsome of the seaweed had also been gnawed by the rabbits, and wondering\nwhat it could have been to tempt them, I collected some of it to\nexamine more fully at home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The skeleton of the whale, too, attracted our attention, for picked\nclean by the birds and bleached by sun and rain the bones had been\npurified to a most perfect whiteness. Thinking that the joints of the\nvertebrae might be made of use, I separated some ten or twelve, and\nrolled them down to the boat, and then returned to the shore, towing\nthem after us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A scheme now occupied my mind for the construction of a crushing\nmachine which would prove of the greatest service to us. I knew that to\nmake such a machine of stone was far beyond my power, but it had struck\nme that the vertebrae of the whale might serve my purpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I determined next morning to look out a tree from which I might cut the\nblocks of wood that I should require to raise my crushers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My expedition was destined to be a solitary one, for when I went to the\nstables for a horse, I discovered that the boys had gone off by\nthemselves with their guns and traps, and had left to me a choice\nbetween the bull and buffalo."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With Storm, therefore, I was fain to be content. I crossed the bridge,\nbut as I reached the cassava field I noticed to my great annoyance that\nit had been overrun and laid waste by some mischievous animals. I\nexamined the footprints, and seeing that they greatly resembled those\nof pigs, determined to follow the trail, and see who these invaders of\nour territory would prove to be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The track led me on for some way until I almost lost sight of it near\nour old potato field. For some time I hunted backwards and forwards\nwithout seeing a sign of the animals; at length a loud barking from\nFloss and Bruno, who were with me, announced that they had been\ndiscovered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The whole family of our old sow, and she herself, were standing at bay,\nshowing their teeth and grunting so savagely, that the dogs feared to\napproach them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I raised my gun and fired twice amongst the herd: two of the pigs\nfell, and the rest fled, followed by the dogs. I picked up the pigs,\nand calling back the pursuers, continued my way through the forest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A tree suited to my purpose was soon found; I marked it, and returned\nhome."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, who had remained at home, assisted me to flay the young\nporkers, and I handed them over to my wife to prepare for supper; by\nwhich time I hoped the other lads would have returned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Late in the evening we heard the sounds of trampling hoofs, and\npresently Jack appeared, thundering along upon his two-legged steed,\nfollowed in the distance by Fritz and Franz. These latter carried upon\ntheir cruppers game-bags, the contents of which were speedily\ndisplayed: four birds, a kangaroo, twenty musk-rats, a monkey, two\nhares and half a dozen beaver rats, were laid before me. Besides these,\nFritz threw down, without a word of explanation, a bundle of thistles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys seemed almost wild with excitement at the success of their\nexpedition, and presently Jack exclaimed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, father, you can't think what grand fun hunting on an ostrich is;\nwe flew along like the wind; sometimes I could scarcely breathe, we\nwere going at such a rate, and I was obliged to shut my eyes because of\nthe terrific rush of air; really, father, you must make me a mask with\nglass eyes to ride with, or I shall be blinded one of these fine days.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Indeed!' replied I, 'I must do no such thing.' 'Why not?' asked he,\nwith a look of amazement upon his face."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For two reasons: firstly, because I do not consider that I must do\nanything that you demand; and, secondly, because I think that you are\nvery capable of doing it yourself. However, I must congratulate you\nupon your abundant supply of game; you must have indeed worked hard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yet I wish that you would let me know when you intend starting on such\na long expedition as this; you forget that though you yourselves know\nthat you are quite safe, and that all is going on well, yet that we at\nhome are kept in a constant state of anxiety. Now, off with you, and\nlook to your animals, and then you may find supper ready.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently the boys returned, and we prepared for a most appetizing meal\nwhich the mother set before us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While we were discussing the roast pig, and washing it down with\nfragrant mead, Fritz described the day's expedition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They had set their traps near Woodlands, and had there captured the\nmusk-rats, attracting them with small carrots, while with other traps,\nbaited with fish and earthworms, they had caught several beaver rats,\nand a duck-billed platypus. Hunting and fishing had occupied the rest\nof the day, and it was with immense pride that Jack displayed the\nkangaroo which he had run down with his swift courser."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Contributions to the garden had not been forgotten, and Fritz handed\nover to his mother several cuttings from cinnamon and sweet-apple\ntrees. Finally, when all the other treasures had been displayed, Fritz\nbegged me to examine his thistles which he had gathered, thinking, he\nsaid, that it was a plant used in the manufacture of wool."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was perfectly right, for I recognized it at once as the 'fuller's\nteazle', a plant whose sharp little thorns, which cover the stem and\nleaves, are used to raise the nap of cloth. We resolved to be up\nbetimes the following morning, that we might attend to the preparation\nof the booty, and as I now noticed that the boys were all becoming\nextremely drowsy, I closed the day with evening devotions."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The number of the creatures we killed rendered the removal of their\nskins a matter of no little time and trouble. It was not an agreeable\ntask at any time, and when I saw the array of animals the boys had\nbrought me to flay, I determined to construct a machine which would\nconsiderably lessen the labour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Amongst the ship's stores, in the surgeon's chest, I discovered a\nlarge syringe. This, with a few alterations, would serve my purpose\nadmirably. Within the tube I first fitted a couple of valves, and then,\nperforating the stopper, I had in my possession a powerful air pump.\nThe boys stared at me in blank amazement when, armed with this\ninstrument, I took up the kangaroo, and declared myself ready to\ncommence operations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Skin a kangaroo with a squirt?' said they, and a roar of laughter\nfollowed the remark."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I made no reply to the jests which followed, but silently hung the\nkangaroo by its hind legs to the branch of a tree. I then made a small\nincision in the skin, and inserting the mouth of the syringe forced air\nwith all my might between the skin and the body of the animal. By\ndegrees the hide of the kangaroo distended, altering the shape of the\ncreature entirely."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Still I worked on, forcing in yet more air until it had become a mere\nshapeless mass, and I soon found that the skin was almost entirely\nseparated from the carcase. A bold cut down the belly, and a few\ntouches here and there where the ligatures still bound the hide to the\nbody, and the animal was flayed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'What a splendid plan!' cried the boys. 'But why should it do it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For a most simple and natural reason,' I replied. 'Do you not know\nthat the skin of an animal is attached to its flesh merely by slender\nand delicate fibres, and that between these exist thousands of little\nbladders or air chambers; by forcing air into these bladders the fibres\nare stretched, and at length, elastic as they are, cracked. The skin\nhas now nothing to unite it to the body, and, consequently, may be\ndrawn off with perfect ease."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This scientific fact has been known for many years; the Greenlanders\nmake constant use of it; when they have killed a seal or walrus they\ndistend the skin that they may tow the animal more easily ashore, and\nthen remove its hide at a moment's notice.' The remaining animals were\nsubjected to the same treatment, and, to my great joy, in a couple of\ndays the skins were all off, and being prepared for use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I now summoned the boys to assist me in procuring blocks of wood for my\ncrushing machine, and the following day we set forth with saws, ropes,\naxes and other tools. We soon reached the tree I had selected for my\npurpose, and I began by sending Fritz and Jack up into the tree with\naxes to cut off the larger of the high branches so that, when the tree\nfell, it might not injure its neighbours."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They then descended, and Fritz and I attacked the stem. As the easiest\nand most speedy method we used a saw, such as is employed by sawyers in\na saw-pit and, Fritz taking one end and I the other, the tree was soon\ncut half through. We then adjusted ropes that we might guide its fall,\nand again began to cut. It was labourious work, but when I considered\nthat the cut was sufficiently deep we took the ropes and pulled with\nour united strength. The trunk cracked, swayed, tottered, and fell with\na crash."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boughs were speedily lopped off, and the trunk sawed into blocks\nfour feet long. To cut down and divide this tree had taken us a couple\nof days, and on the third we carted home four large and two small\nblocks, and with the vertebrae joints of the whale I, in a very short\ntime, completed my machine."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While engaged on this undertaking I had paid little attention to our\nfields of grain, and, accordingly, great was my surprise when one\nevening the fowls returned, showing most evident indifference to their\nevening meal, and with their crops perfectly full. It suddenly struck\nme that these birds had come from the direction of our cornfield. I\nhurried off to see what damage they had done, and then found to my\ngreat joy that the grain was perfectly ripe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The amount of work before us startled my wife. This unexpected\nharvest, which added reaping and threshing to the fishing, salting, and\npickling already on hand, quite troubled her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Only think,' said she, 'of my beloved potatoes and manioc roots! What\nis to become of them, I should like to know? It is time to take them\nup, and how to manage it, with all this press of work, I can't see.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Don't be downhearted, wife,' said I; 'there is no immediate hurry\nabout the manioc, and digging potatoes in this fine, light soil is easy\nwork compared to what it is in Switzerland, while as to planting more,\nthat will not be necessary if we leave the younger plants in the\nground. The harvest we must conduct after the Italian fashion, which,\nalthough anything but economical, will save time and trouble, and as we\nare to have two crops in the year, we need not be too particular.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Without further delay, I commenced leveling a large space of firm\nclayey ground to act as a threshing floor; it was well sprinkled with\nwater, rolled, beaten, and stamped; as the sun dried the moisture it\nwas watered anew, and the treatment continued until it became as\nflat, hard, and smooth as a threshing floor need be."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our largest wicker basket was then slung between Storm and Grumble; we\narmed ourselves with reaping hooks, and went forth to gather in the\ncorn in the simplest and most expeditious manner imaginable. I told my\nreapers not to concern themselves about the length of the straw, but to\ngrasp the corn where it was convenient to them, without stooping; each\nwas to wind a stalk around his own handful, and throw it into the\nbasket; in this way great labour was saved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The plan pleased the boys immensely, and in a short time the basket had\nbeen filled many times, and the field displayed a quantity of tall,\nheadless stubble, which perfectly horrified the mother, so extravagant\nand untidy did she consider our work."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This is dreadful!' cried she; 'you have left numbers of ears growing\non short stalks, and look at that splendid straw completely wasted! I\ndon't approve of your Italian fashion at all.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is not a bad plan, I can assure you, wife, and the Italians do not\nwaste the straw by not cutting it with the grain; having more arable\nthan pasture land, they use this high stubble for their cattle, letting\nthem feed in it, and eat what grain is left; afterward, allowing the\ngrass to grow up among it, they mow all together for winter fodder. And\nnow for threshing, also in Italian fashion. We shall find it spares our\narms and backs as much in that as in reaping.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The little sheaves were laid in a large circle on the floor, the boys\nmounted Storm, Grumble, Lightfoot, and Hurry, starting off at a brisk\ntrot, with many a merry jest, and round they went, trampling and\nstamping out the grain, while dust and chaff flew in clouds about them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife and I were incessantly occupied with hayforks, by means of\nwhich we shook up and moved the sheaves over which the threshers rode,\nso as to throw them in the track."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From time to time the animals took mouthfuls of the tempting food they\nwere beating out; we thought they well deserved it, and called to mind\nthe command given to the Jews, 'Thou shalt not muzzle the ox that\ntreadeth out the corn.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After threshing, we proceeded to winnowing: by simply throwing the\nthreshed corn with shovels high in the air when the land or sea-breeze\nblew strong, the chaff and refuse was carried away by the wind and the\ngrain fell to the ground."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During these operations our poultry paid the threshing-floor many\nvisits, testifying a lively interest in the success of our labours, and\ngobbling up the grain at such a rate that my wife was obliged to keep\nthem at a reasonable distance; but I would not have them altogether\nstinted in the midst of our plenty. I said, 'Let them enjoy themselves;\nwhat we lose in grain, we gain in flesh. I anticipate delicious\nchicken-pie, roast goose, and boiled turkey!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When our harvest stores were housed, we found that we had reaped\nsixty, eighty, even a hundred-fold what had been sown. Our garner was\ntruly filled with all manner of store."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Expecting a second harvest, we were constrained to prepare the field\nfor sowing again, and immediately therefore commenced mowing down the\nstubble. While engaged in this, flocks of quails and partridges came to\nglean among the scattered ears. We did not secure any great number, but\nresolved to be prepared for them next season, and by spreading nets, to\ncatch them in large quantities."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife was satisfied when she saw the straw carried home and stacked;\nour crop of maize, which of course had not been threshed like the other\ncorn, afforded soft leaves which were used for stuffing mattresses,\nwhile the stalks, when burnt, left ashes so rich in alkali as to be\nespecially useful."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I changed the crops sown on the ground to rye, barley and oats, and\nhoped they would ripen before the rainy season."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The shoals of herring made their appearance just as we finished our\nagricultural operations. This year we pickled only two barrels of them;\nbut we were not so merciful towards the seals, which arrived on the\ncoast directly afterwards. We hunted them vigorously, requiring their\nskins for many purposes, more especially for the completion of the\ncajack. On the little deck of that tiny vessel I had made a kind of\nmagazine, in which to store pistols, ammunition, water and provisions,\nand this I meant to cover with seal-skin, so as to be quite watertight.\nA couple of harpoons furnished with seal bladders were to be suspended\nalongside."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 15"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At last came the day when Fritz was to make his trial trip with the\ncajack. Completely equipped in swimming costumeâ€”trousers, and jacket\nand capâ€”it was most ludicrous to see him cower down in the canoe and\npuff and blow till he began to swell like the frog in the fable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All trace of his original figure was speedily lost, and shouts of\nlaughter greeted his comical appearance. Even his mother could not\nresist a smile, although the dress was her own invention."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I got the other boat out, that my wife might see we were ready to go to\nhis assistance the moment it became necessary."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cajack was launched from a convenient shelving point, and floated\nlightly on the sea-green ocean mirror. Fritz with his paddles then\nbegan to practise all manner of evolutions: darting along with arrowy\nswiftness, wheeling to the right, then to the left; and at last,\nflinging himself quite on his side, while his mother uttered a shriek\nof terror, he showed that the tiny craft would neither capsize nor\nsink. Then, recovering his balance, he sped securely on his further\nway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Encouraged by our shouts of approbation, he now boldly ventured into\nthe strong current of Jackal River, and was rapidly carried out to sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This being more than I had bargained for, I lost no time in giving\nchase in the boat, with Ernest and Jack; my wife, urging us to greater\nspeed, and declaring that some accident could not fail to happen to\n'that horrid soap-bubble'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We soon arrived outside the bay, at the rocks where formerly lay the\nwreck, and gazed in all directions for signs of the runaway."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After a time we saw, at a considerable distance, a faint puff of\nsmoke, followed by the crack of a pistol. Upon this we fired a signal\nshot, which was presently answered by another, and, steering in the\ndirection of the sound, we soon heard the boy's cheery halloo; the\ncajack darted from behind a point of land, and we quickly joined\ncompany."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come to this rocky beach,' cried Fritz, 'I have something to show\nyou.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With blank amazement we beheld a fine well-grown young walrus,\nharpooned and quite dead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Did you kill this creature, my dear Fritz?' I exclaimed, looking\nround in some anxiety, and half expecting to see a naked savage come to\nclaim the prize."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To be sure, father! Don't you see my harpoon? Why do you doubt it?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well, I scarcely know,' replied I, laughing, 'but success so speedy,\nso unexpected, and so appropriate, to an amateur Greenlander, took me\nby surprise. I congratulate you, my boy! But I must tell you that you\nhave alarmed us by making this long trip. You should not have gone out\nof the bay. I left your mother in grievous trouble.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Indeed, father, I had no idea of passing out of sight, but once in the\ncurrent, I was carried along, and could not help myself. Then I came on\na herd of walruses, and I did so long to make a prize of one that I\nforgot everything else, and made chase after them when beyond the\ninfluence of the current, until I got near enough to harpoon this fine\nfellow. He swam more slowly, and I struck him a second time; then he\nsought refuge among these rocks, and expired. I landed, and scrambled\nto where he lay; but I took care to give him the contents of my pistol\nbefore going close up, having a salutary recollection of the big\nserpent's parting fling at you, Jack.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You ran a very great risk,' said I. 'The walrus is an inoffensive\ncreature; but when attacked and wounded, it often becomes furious and,\nturning upon its pursuer, can destroy, with its long tusks, a strongly\nbuilt whale boat. However, thank God for your safety! I value that\nabove a thousand such creatures. Now what's to be done with him? He\nmust be quite fourteen feet long, although not full grown.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I am very glad you followed me, father,' said Fritz, 'but our united\nstrength will not move this prodigious weight from among these rocks;\nonly do let me carry away the head, with these grand snow-white tusks!\nI should so like to fasten it on the prow of the cajack, and name it\nthe Sea-horse.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We must certainly carry away the beautiful ivory tusks,' said I, 'but\nmake haste! The air feels so excessively close and sultry, I think a\nstorm is brewing.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But the head! The head! we must have the whole head,' cried Jack,\n'just think how splendid it will look on the cajack!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And how splendid it will smell too, when it begins to putrefy,' added\nErnest. 'What a treat for the steersman!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, we will prepare for that,' said Fritz. 'It shall be soaked and\ncleaned, and dried till it is as hard as a wooden model; it shall not\noffend your delicate nose in the least, Ernest!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I supposed the walrus to be an animal peculiar to the Arctic\nregions,' remarked Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And so it is,' I replied, 'though they may occasionally be seen\nelsewhere; these may have wandered from the Antarctic seas. I know that\non the eastern coast of Africa is found a smaller species of walrus\ncalled the dugong: it has long incisor teeth, but not tusks; and\ncertainly resembles a seal rather than a walrus.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "While thus speaking, we were actively engaged in the decapitation of\nthe walrus, and in cutting off long strips of its skin. This took some\ntime, as we had not the proper implements, and Fritz remarked, that in\nfuture the cajack must be provided with a hunting-knife and a hatchet;\nadding that he should like to have a small compass, in a box with a\nglass top, fixed in front of the hole where the steersman sits. I saw\nthe necessity of this and I promised it should be done."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our work being accomplished, we were ready to go, and I proposed to\ntake Fritz and the canoe on board our boat, so that we might all arrive\ntogether; but I yielded to his earnest wish to return alone as he came;\nhe longed to act as our avant-courier, and announce our approach to his\nmother; so he was soon skimming away over the surface of the water,\nwhile we followed at slower rate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Black clouds meanwhile gathered thick and fast around us, and a\ntremendous storm came on. Fritz was out of sight and beyond our reach."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We buckled on the swimming belts, and firmly lashed ourselves to the\nboat, so that we might not be washed overboard by the towering seas\nwhich broke over it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The horizon was shrouded in darkness, fearful gusts of wind lashed the\nocean into foam, rain descended in torrents, while livid lightning\nglared athwart the gloom. Both my boys faced the danger nobly; and my\nfeelings of alarm were mingled with hope on finding how well the boat\nbehaved."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The tempest swept on its way, and the sky began to clear as suddenly as\nit had been overcast; yet the stormy waves continued for a long time to\nthreaten our frail bark with destruction, in spite of its buoyancy and\nsteadiness."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Yet I never lost hope for ourselvesâ€”all my fears were for Fritz; in\nfact I gave him up for lost, and my whole agonized heart arose in\nprayer for strength to say, 'Thy will be done!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At last we rounded the point, and once more entering Safety Bay,\nquickly drew near the little harbour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "What was our surpriseâ€”our overwhelming delight when there we saw the\nmother with Fritz, as well as her little boy, on their knees in prayer\nso earnest for our deliverance, that our approach was unperceived,\nuntil with cries of joy we attracted their notice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then indeed ensued a happy meeting, and we gave thanks together for the\nmercy which had spared our lives."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Returning joyfully to Rockburg, we changed our drenched garments for\nwarm dry clothes; and, seated at a comfortable meal, considered and\ndescribed at our ease the perils of the storm."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Afterwards, the head of the walrus was conveyed to our workshop; where\nit underwent such a skilful and thorough process of cleaning, embalming\nand drying, that ere long it was actually fixed on the prow of the\ncajack, and a most imposing appearance it presented!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The strips of hide, when well tanned and prepared, made valuable\nleather."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Much damage had been done by the late storm. The heavy rain had\nflooded all the streams, and injured crops which should have been\nhoused and safe before the regular rainy season."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bridge over Jackal River was partly broken down, and the water\ntanks and pipes all needed repair. So that our time was much occupied\nin restoring things to order."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On going to work one day near the cascade, we found a great number of\ndark-red berries, scattered on the ground; they were about the size of\nordinary hazel-nuts, with small leafy coronets at the tip."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys thought them so inviting, that they tasted them at once, but\nangry exclamations and much spitting and spluttering followed the\nexperiment; even Knips rejected them, and they would have been cast\naside with contempt, had not the smell induced me to examine them. I\ndecided that this was the fruit of the clove."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Some plants were immediately set in the nursery garden, and my wife was\npleased to have this excellent spice wherewith to flavour her boiled\nrice and other dishes, in lieu of pepperâ€”a very welcome variety to\neveryone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having a good supply of clay, brought from the bed near Falconhurst, I\nproposed to use it for making aqueducts; and, observing how much the\nrecent rain had promoted the growth of our young corn, I determined to\nirrigate the fields with the drainage from our crushing-mill."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The fishing season was again successful. Large takes of salmon,\nsturgeon and herring rewarded our annual exertions, and our store-room\nagain assumed a well-stocked appearance. Much as I wished that we could\nobtain a constant supply of these fish fresh, I was obliged to reject\nthe naive proposal from Jack, that we should tether a shoal of salmon\nby the gills to the bottom of the bay as we had secured the turtles."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many quiet uneventful days passed by and I perceived that the boys,\nwearied by the routine of farm work at Rockburg, were longing for a\ncruise in the yacht or an expedition into the woods, which would\nrefresh both mind and body."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Father,' said Fritz at length, 'we want a quantity of hurdles, and\nhave scarcely any more bamboos of which to make them. Had we not better\nget a supply from Woodlands? And you said, too, the other day, that you\nwished you had some more of the fine clay: we might visit the Gap at\nthe same time.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I had really no objection to propose; and it was shortly afterwards\nsettled that Fritz, Jack, and Franz should start together; and that\nErnest, who had no great desire to accompany his brothers, should\nremain with his mother and me, and assist in the construction of a\nsugar-mill, the erection of which I had long contemplated."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before they started, Fritz begged some bear's meat from his mother, to\nmake pemmican."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And what may pemmican be?' she asked."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is food carried by the fur-traders of North America on their long\njourneys through the wild country they traverse; and consists of bear\nor deer's flesh, first cooked and then pounded or ground to powder. It\nis very portable, and nourishing.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His mother consented 'to humour him', as she said, although without\nmuch faith in the value of the preparation; and in the course of two\ndays a stock of pemmican, sufficient for a Polar expedition, was\nfabricated by our enthusiastic son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were ready to start, when I observed Jack quietly slip a basket,\ncontaining several pigeons, under the packages in the cart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, oh!' thought I, 'the little fellow has his doubts about that\npemmican, and thinks a tough old pigeon would be preferable.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The weather was exquisite; and, with exhortations to prudence and\ncaution from both me and their mother, the three lads started in the\nvery highest spirits. Storm and Grumble, as usual, drew the cart, and\nwere ridden by Fritz and Franz; while Hurry carried Jack swiftly across\nthe bridge in advance of them; followed by Floss and Bruno, barking\nat his heels."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The sugar-mill occupied us for several days, and was made so much like\nour other mills that I need not now describe it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the evening of the first day, as we sat resting in the porch at\nRockburg, we naturally talked of the absentees, wondering and guessing\nwhat they might be about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest looked rather mysterious, and hinted that he might have news of\nthem next morning."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Just then a bird alighted on the dove-cot, and entered. I could not\nsee, in the failing light, whether it was one of our own pigeons or an\nintruder. Ernest started up, and said he would see that all was right."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few minutes he returned with a scrap of paper in his hand. 'News,\nfather! The very latest news by pigeon-post, mother!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well done, boys! What a capital idea!' said I, and taking the note I\nread:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Dearest parents and Ernest,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A brute of a hyaena has killed a ram and two lambs. The dogs seized\nit. Franz shot it. It is dead and skinned. The pemmican isn't worth\nmuch, but we are all right. Love to all."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Woodlands, 15th instant"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A true hunter's letter!' laughed I. 'But what exciting news. When does\nthe next post come in, Ernest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Tonight, I hope,' said he, while his mother sighed, and doubted the\nvalue of such glimpses into the scenes of danger through which her sons\nwere passing, declaring she would much rather wait and hear all about\nit when she had them safe home again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Thus the winged letter-carriers kept us informed from day to day of the\noutline of adventures which were afterwards more fully described."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On approaching the farm at Woodlands, the boys were startled by\nhearing, as they thought, human laughter, repeated again and again;\nwhile, to their astonishment, the oxen testified the greatest\nuneasiness, the dogs growled and drew close to their masters, and the\nostrich fairly bolted with Jack into the rice swamp."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The laughter continued, and the beasts became unmanageable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Something is very far wrong!' cried Fritz. 'I cannot leave the\nanimals; but while I unharness them, do you, Franz, take the dogs, and\nadvance cautiously to see what is the matter.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Without a moment's hesitation, Franz made his way among the bushes with\nhis gun, and closely followed by the dogs; until, through an opening in\nthe thicket, he could see, at the distance of about forty paces, an\nenormous hyaena, in the most wonderful state of excitement; dancing\nround a lamb just killed, and uttering, from time to time, the ghastly\nhysterical laughter which had pealed through the forest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The beast kept running backwards and forwards, rising on its hind\nlegs, and then rapidly whirling round and round, nodding its head, and\ngoing through most frantic and ludicrous antics."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz kept his presence of mind very well; for he watched till,\ncalming down, the hyaena began with horrid growls to tear its prey; and\nthen, firing steadily both barrels, he broke its foreleg, and wounded\nit in the breast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meanwhile Fritz, having unyoked the oxen and secured them to trees,\nhurried to his brother's assistance. The dogs and the dying hyaena were\nby this time engaged in mortal strife; but the latter, although it\nseverely wounded both Floss and Bruno, speedily succumbed, and was dead\nwhen the boys reached the spot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They raised a shout of triumph, which guided Jack to the scene of\naction; and their first care was for the dogs, whose wounds they\ndressed before minutely examining the hyaena. It was as large as a wild\nboar; long stiff bristles formed a mane on its neck, its colour was\ngrey marked with black, the teeth and jaws were of extraordinary\nstrength, the thighs muscular and sinewy, the claws remarkably strong\nand sharp altogether. But for his wounds, he would certainly have been\nmore than a match for the dogs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After unloading the cart at the farm, the boys returned for the\ncarcase of the tiger-wolf, as it is sometimes called, and occupied\nthemselves in skinning it during the remainder of the day, when after\ndispatching the carrier-pigeon to Rockburg, they retired to rest on\ntheir bearskin rugs, to dream of adventures past and future."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The following day they devised no less a scheme than to survey the\nshores of Wood Lake, and place marks wherever the surrounding marsh was\npracticable and might be crossed either to reach the water or leave it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz in the cajack, and the boys on shore, carefully examined the\nground together; and when they found firm footing to the water's edge,\nthe spot was indicated by planting a tall bamboo, bearing on high a\nbundle of reeds and branches."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They succeeded in capturing three young black swans, after\nconsiderable resistance from the old ones. They were afterwards\nbrought to Rockburg, and detained as ornaments to Safety Bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently a beautiful heron thrust his long neck from among the reeds,\nto ascertain what all the noise on the lake was about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before he could satisfy his curiosity, Fritz unhooded his eagle, and\nthough vainly he flapped and struggled, his legs and wings were gently\nbut firmly bound, and he had to own himself vanquished, and submit to\nthe inspection of his delighted captors."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was their turn to be alarmed next, for a large powerful animal came\npuffing with a curious whistling sound through the dense thicket of\nreeds, passing close by and sorely discomposing them by its sudden\nappearance. It was out of sight immediately, before they could summon\nthe dogs, and from their description it must have been a tapir, the\ncolour dark brown, and in form resembling a young rhinoceros, but with\nno horn on the nose, and the upper lip prolonged into a trunk something\nlike that of an elephant on a smaller scale. It is a gentle creature,\nbut when attacked becomes a fierce opponent, and can wound dogs\ndangerously with its powerful teeth. The tapir can swim and dive with\nperfect ease, and abounds in the densely wooded swamps and rivers of\ntropical America."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz in his cajack followed for a time the direction in which the\ntapir proceeded, but saw no more of it. Meanwhile the other two boys\nreturned to the farm by the rice-fields, and there fell in with a flock\nof cranes, five or six of which they caught alive, among them two\ndemoiselle or Numidian cranes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These birds they shot at with arrows arranged in a skilful and\noriginal way, with loops of cord dipped in birdlime attached to them,\nso that it often happened that the bird aimed at, was entangled and\nbrought down uninjured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The young hunters seemed to have lived very comfortably on peccary ham,\ncassava bread and fruit, and plenty of baked potatoes and milk."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One trial of the pemmican was sufficient, and it was handed over to the\ndogs. Fritz, however, determined again to attempt the manufacture,\nknowing its value when properly prepared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After collecting a supply of rice and cotton, they took their way to\nProspect Hill, 'and,' said Fritz, as he afterwards vividly described\nthe dreadful scene there enacted, 'when we entered the pine wood, we\nfound it in possession of troops of monkeys, who resolved to make our\npassage through it as disagreeable as possible, for they howled and\nchattered at us like demons, pelting us as hard as they could with pine\ncones."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'They became so unbearable, that at last we fired a few shots right and\nleft among them; several bit the dust, the rest fled, and we continued\nour way in peace to Prospect Hill, but only to discover the havoc the\nwretches had made there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Would you believe it, father? The pleasant cottage had been overrun\nand ruined by apes just as Woodlands last summer! The most dreadful\ndirt and disorder met our eyes wherever we turned, and we had hard work\nto make the place fit for human habitation; and even then we preferred\nthe tent. I felt quite at a loss how to guard the farm for the future;\nbut seeing a bottle of the poisonous gum of the euphorbia in the tool\nchest, I devised a plan for the destruction of the apes which succeeded\nbeyond my expectations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I mixed poison with milk, bruised millet and anything I thought the\nmonkeys would eat, and put it in cocoanut shells, which I hung about in\nthe trees, high enough to be out of reach of our own animals. The\nevening was calm and lovely; the sea murmured in the distance, and the\nrising moon shed a beauty over the landscape which we seemed never\nbefore to have so admired and enjoyed. The summer night closed around\nus in all its solemn stillness, and our deepest feelings were touched;\nwhen suddenly the spell was broken by an outburst of the most hideous\nand discordant noises."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As by one consent, every beast of the forest seemed to arise from its\nden, and utter its wild nocturnal cry. Snorting, snarling and shrieking\nfilled the woods beneath us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'From the hills echoed the mournful howl of jackals, answered by Fangs\nin the yard, who was backed up by the barking and yelping of his\nfriends Floss and Bruno. Far away beyond the rocky fastnesses of the\nGap, sounded unearthly hollow snortings and neighings, reminding one of\nthe strange cry of the hippopotamus; above these, occasional deep\nmajestic roarings made our hearts quail with the conviction that we\nheard the voices of lions and elephants."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Overawed and silent, we retired to rest, hoping to forget in sleep the\nterrors of the midnight forest; but ere long the most fearful cries in\nthe adjoining woods gave notice that the apes were beginning to suffer\nfrom the poisoned repast prepared for them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As our dogs could not remain silent amid the uproar and din, we had\nnot a wink of sleep until the morning. It was late, therefore, when we\nrose, and looked on the awful spectacle presented by the multitude of\ndead monkeys and baboons thickly strewn under the trees round the farm.\nI shall not tell you how many there were. I can only say I wished I had\nnot found the poison, and we made all haste to clear away the dead\nbodies and the dangerous food, burying some deep in the earth, and,\ncarrying the rest to the shore, we pitched them over the rocks into the\nsea. That day we travelled on to the Gap.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The same evening that the boys reached the rocky pass, a\nmessenger-pigeon arrived at Rockburg, bearing a note which concluded in\nthe following words:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The barricade at the Gap is broken down. Everything laid waste as far\nas the sugar-brake, where the hut is knocked to pieces, and the fields\ntrampled over by huge footmarks. Come to us, fatherâ€”we are safe, but\nfeel we are no match for this unknown danger.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I lost not an instant, but saddled Swift, late as it was, in order to\nride to the assistance of our boys, desiring Ernest to prepare the\nsmall cart, and follow me with his mother at daybreak, bringing\neverything we should require for camping out for some days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The bright moonlight favoured my journey, and my arrival at the\nGap surprised and delighted the boys who did not expect me till next\nday. Early on the following morning I inspected the footprints and\nravages of the great unknown. The cane-brake had, without doubt, been\nvisited by an elephant. That great animal alone could have left such\ntraces and committed such fearful ravages."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Thick posts in the barricade were snapped across like reeds; the trees\nin the vicinity, where we planned to build a cool summer-house, were\nstripped of leaves and branches to a great height, but the worst\nmischief was done among the young sugar-cane plants, which were all\neither devoured or trampled down and destroyed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It seemed to me that not one elephant, but a troop must have invaded\nour grounds. The tracks were very numerous, and the footprints of\nvarious sizes; but, to my satisfaction, I saw that they could be traced\nnot only from the Gap, but back to it in evidently equal numbers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We did not, therefore, suppose that the mighty animals remained hidden\nin the woods of our territory; but concluded that, after this\nfreebooting incursion, they had withdrawn to their native wilds, where,\nby greatly increasing the strength of our ramparts, we hoped henceforth\nto oblige them to remain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In what manner to effect this we laid many plans, during the night of\nmy arrival, when, sitting by an enormous watch-fire, I chatted with my\nboys, and heard details of their numerous adventures, so interesting\nfor them to relate, and for me to hear, that everyone was more disposed\nto act sentinel than retire to sleep."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife and Ernest arrived next day, and she rejoiced to find all\nwell, making light of trodden fields and trampled sugar-canes, since\nher sons were sound in life and limb."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A systematic scheme of defence was now elabourated, and the erection of\nthe barricade occupied us for at least a month, as it was to be a firm\nand durable building, proof against all invasion."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As our little tent was unsuited to a long residence of this sort, I\nadopted Fritz's idea of a Kamschatkan dwelling and, to his great\ndelight, forthwith carried it out."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Instead of planting four posts, on which to place a platform, we chose\nfour trees of equal size, which, in a very suitable place, grew exactly\nin a square, twelve or fourteen feet apart. Between these, at about\ntwenty feet from the ground, we laid a flooring of beams and bamboo,\nsmoothly and strongly planked. From this rose, on all four sides, walls\nof cane; the frame of the roof was covered so effectually by large\npieces of bark that no rain could penetrate. The staircase to this\ntree-cottage was simply a broad plank with bars nailed across it for\nsteps. The flooring projected like a balcony in front of the entrance\ndoor, and underneath, on the ground, we fitted up sheds for cattle and\nfowls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Various ornaments in Chinese or Japanese style were added to the roof\nand eaves, and a most convenient, cool and picturesque cottage,\noverhung and adorned by the graceful foliage of the trees, was the\nresult of our ingenuity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I was pleased to find that the various birds taken by the boys during\nthis excursion seemed likely to thrive; they were the first inmates of\nthe new sheds, and even the black swans and cranes soon became tame and\nsociable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Constantly roaming through the woods, the children often made new\ndiscoveries."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz brought one day, after an excursion to the opposite side of the\nstream beyond the Gap, a cluster of bananas, and also of cacao-beans,\nfrom which chocolate is made."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The banana, although valuable and nourishing food for the natives of\nthe tropical countries where it grows, is not generally liked by\nEuropeans, and probably this variety was even inferior to many others,\nfor we found the fruit much like rotten pears, and almost uneatable."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The cacao seeds tasted exceedingly bitter, and it seemed wonderful that\nby preparation they should produce anything so delicious as chocolate."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife, who now fancied no manufacture beyond my skill, begged for\nplants, seeds, or cuttings to propagate in her nursery garden, already\nfancying herself in the enjoyment of chocolate for breakfast, and I\npromised to make a cacao plantation near home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Let me have bananas also,' said she, 'for we may acquire a taste for\nthat celebrated fruit, and, at all events, I am sure I can make it into\nan excellent preserve.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The day before our return to Rockburg, Fritz went again to the inland\nregion beyond the river to obtain a large supply of young\nbanana-plants, and the cacao-fruit. He took the cajack, and a bundle of\nreeds to float behind him as a raft to carry the fruit, plants, and\nanything else he might wish to bring back."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the evening he made his appearance, coming swiftly down stream. His\nbrothers rushed to meet him, each eager to see and help to land his\ncargo. Ernest and Fritz were quickly running up the bank, with arms\nfull of plants, branches and fruit, when Fritz handed to Jack a\ndripping wet bag which he had brought along partly under water. A\ncurious pattering noise proceeded from this bag, but they kept the\ncontents a secret for the present, Jack running with it behind a bush\nbefore peeping in, and I could just hear him exclaim:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hullo! I say, what monsters they are! It's enough to make a fellow's\nflesh creep to look at them!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With that he hastily shut up the bag, and put it away safely out of\nsight in water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Securing the cajack, Fritz sprang towards us, his handsome face\nradiant with pleasure, as he exhibited a beautiful water-fowl. Its\nplumage was rich purple, changing on the back to dark green; the legs,\nfeet and a mark above the bill, bright red. This lovely bird I\nconcluded to be the Sultan cock described by Buffon, and as it was\ngentle, we gladly received it among our domestic pets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz gave a stirring account of his exploring trip, having made his\nway far up the river, between fertile plains and majestic forests of\nlofty trees, where the cries of vast numbers of birds, parrots,\npeacocks, guinea-fowls and hundreds unknown to him, quite bewildered\nhim and made him feel giddy."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was in the Buffalo Swamp,' continued he, 'that I saw the splendid\nbirds you call Sultan cocks, and I set my heart on catching one alive,\nwhich, as they seemed to have little fear of my approach, I managed by\nmeans of a wire snare. Farther on I saw a grove of mimosa trees, among\nwhich huge dark masses were moving in a deliberate way. Guess what they\nwere!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Savages?' asked Franz timidly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Black bears, I bet!' cried Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Your words suggest to my mind the manner and appearance of\nelephants,' said Ernest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Right you are, Professor!' exclaimed Fritz gaily, the words producing\nquite a sensation on the whole attentive family. 'From fifteen to\ntwenty elephants were feeding peacefully on the leafy boughs, tearing\ndown branches with their trunks and shoving them into their mouths with\none jerk, or bathing in the deep waters of the marsh for refreshment in\nthe great heat. You cannot imagine the wild grandeur of the scene! The\nriver being very broad, I felt safe from wild animals, and more than\nonce saw splendid jaguars crouched on the banks, their glossy skin\nglancing in the sunlight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While considering if it would be simply foolhardy to try a shot at one\nof these creatures, I was suddenly convinced that discretion is the\nbetter part of valour, and urging my canoe into the centre current,\nmade a rapid retreat down the river. For just before me, in the calm\ndeep water of a sheltered bay where I was quietly floating, there arose\na violent boiling, bubbling commotion, and for an instant I thought a\nhot spring was going to burst forthâ€”instead of that, up rose the\nhideous head and gaping jaws of a hippopotamus, who, with a hoarse\nterrific snort, seemed about to attack me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I can tell you I did not wait to see the rest of him! A glimpse of his\nenormous mouth and its array of white gleaming tusks was quite enough.\n\"Right about face!\" said I to myself, and shot down the stream like an\narrow, never pausing till a bend in the river brought me within sight\nof the Gap, where I once more felt safe, and joyfully made my way back\nto you all.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This narrative was of thrilling interest to us, proving the existence\nof tribes of the most formidable animals beyond the rocky barrier which\ndefended, in so providential a manner, the small and fertile territory\non which our lot was cast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "During the absence of the adventurer we had been busily engaged in\nmaking preparations for our departureâ€”and everything was packed up and\nready by the morning after his return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After some hesitation I yielded to his great wish, which was to return\nby sea in his cajack round Cape Disappointment and so meet us at\nRockburg."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was much interested in examining the outlines of the coast, and the\nrugged precipices of the Cape. These were tenanted by vast flocks of\nsea-fowl and birds of prey; while many varieties of shrubs and plants,\nhitherto unknown to us, grew in the clefts and crevices of the rocks,\nsome of them diffusing a strong aromatic odour. Among the specimens he\nbrought I recognized the caper plant and, with still greater pleasure,\na shrub which was, I felt sure, the tea-plant of Chinaâ€”it bore very\npretty white flowers and the leaves resembled myrtle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our land journey was effected without accident or adventure of any\nkind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack, mounted as usual on Hurry, the ostrich, carried the mysterious\nwet bag very carefully slung at his side, and when near home started\noff at a prodigious rate in advance of us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He let fall the drawbridge, and we saw no more of him until, on\nreaching Rockburg, he appeared leisurely returning from the swamp,\nwhere apparently he had gone to deposit his 'moist secret', as Franz\ncalled it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were all glad to take up our quarters once more in our large and\nconvenient dwelling, and my first business was to provide for the great\nnumber of birds we now had on our hands, by establishing them in\nsuitable localities, it being impossible to maintain them all in the\npoultry-yard. Some were, therefore, taken to the islands; and the black\nswans, the heron, the graceful demoiselle cranes, and our latest\nacquisition, the splendid Sultan cock, soon became perfectly at home in\nthe swamp, greatly adding to the interest of the neighbourhood of\nSafety Bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The old bustards were the tamest of all our feathered pets, and never\nmore so than at meal-times. They were unfailing in their attendance\nwhen we dined or supped in the open air."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Towards evening, as we sat in the verandah listening to Fritz's\naccount of his trip round the Cape, an extraordinary hollow roaring\nnoise sounded from the swamp, not unlike the angry bellowing of a bull."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs barked and the family rose in excitement; but remarked a look\nof quiet humour in Fritz's eye, as he stood leaning against one of the\nverandah pillars, watching Jack, who, in some confusion, started off\ntowards the marsh."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come back, you silly boy!' cried his mother. 'The child has not so\nmuch as a pistol, and is rushing off alone to face he knows not what!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Perhaps,' said I, looking at Fritz, 'this is not a case requiring the\nuse of firearms. It may be only the booming of a bittern which we\nhear.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You need not be uneasy, mother,' said Fritz. 'Jack knows what he is\nabout, only this charming serenade took him by surprise, and I fancy he\nwill have to exhibit his treasures before they reach perfection. Yes,\nhere he comes!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Lugging his 'moist secret' along with him, Jack, flushed and\nbreathless, came up to us, exclaiming:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'They were to grow as big as rabbits before you saw them! Such a\nshame! I never thought they would kick up a row like that. Now for\nit!'â€”and he turned out the bag. 'This is \"Grace\", and this is\n\"Beauty\".'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Two immense frogs rolled clumsily on the ground, and recovering their\nfeet, sat squat before us, swelling and buffing with a ludicrous air of\ninsulted dignity, while peals of laughter greeted them on all sides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ladies and gentlemen, these are two very handsome young specimens of\nthe famous African bull-frog,' said Jack, pretending to be offended at\nthe mingled disgust and amusement occasioned by their appearance; 'they\nare but half-grown, and I hoped to maintain them in seclusion, until\nthey reached full size, when I would have introduced them with proper\neclat. But since their talent for music has brought them precociously\ninto public notice, I must beg for your kind and indulgent patronage\nandâ€”leave to take them back to the swamp.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Great clapping of hands followed Jack's speech."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Grace' and 'Beauty' were examined, and commented on with much\ninterest, and voted decidedly handsome 'in their way'."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Their general colour was greenish-brown, mottled and spotted with\nreddish-brown, and yellow; the sides green and black; the underpart\nyellow, mottled with orange. The eyes were positively beautiful, of a\nrich chestnut hue, covered with golden white dots, which shone with a\nmetallic lustre. The skin of the body was puckered into longitudinal\nfolds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By general consent they were remanded to the swamp. Shortly after our\nreturn to Rockburg, my wife drew my attention to the somewhat\nneglected state of our dear old summer residence at Falconhurst,\nbegging me to devote some time to its restoration and embellishment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This I most willingly undertook, and we removed thither, as soon as the\nboys had completed the arrangement of the artificial salt-lick to their\nsatisfaction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At Falconhurst things were quickly in good order, and we made a great\nimprovement by completing the broad terrace supported on the arching\nroots of the treesâ€”it was better flooredâ€”and rustic pillars and\ntrellis-work sustained a bark roof which afforded pleasant shade."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After this was done, I was compelled to consent to a plan long\ncherished by Fritz, who wished to construct a watch-tower and mount a\ngun on Shark Island. After great exertion, both mental and bodily, this\npiece of military engineering was completed; and a flagstaff erected,\non which the guard at this outpost could run up a white flag to signal\nthe approach of anything harmless from the sea, while a red flag would\nbe shown on the least appearance of danger."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To celebrate the completion of this great work, which occupied us\nduring two months, we hoisted the white flag and fired a salute of six\nguns."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 16"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We spend our years as a tale that is told,' said King David. These\nwords recurred to me again and again as I reviewed ten years, of which\nthe story lay chronicled in the pages of my journal."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Year followed year; chapter succeeded chapter; steadily,\nimperceptibly, time was passing away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The shade of sadness cast on my mind by retrospect of this kind, was\ndispelled by thoughts full of gratitude to God, for the welfare and\nhappiness of my beloved family during so long a period. I had cause\nespecially to rejoice in seeing our sons advance to manhood\nstrengthened by early training for lives of usefulness and activity\nwherever their lot might fall."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And my great wish is that young people who read this record of our\nlives and adventures, should learn from it how admirably suited is the\npeaceful, industrious and pious life of a cheerful and united family,\nto the formation of strong, pure and manly character."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "None take a better place in the great national family, none are\nhappier or more beloved than those who go forth from such homes to\nfulfil new duties, and to gather fresh interests around them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having given a detailed account of several years' residence in New\nSwitzerland, as we liked to call our dominion, it is needless for me to\ncontinue what would exhaust the patience of the most long-suffering, by\nrepeating monotonous narratives of exploring parties and hunting\nexpeditions, wearisome descriptions of awkward inventions and clumsy\nmachines, with an endless record of discoveries, more fit for the pages\nof an encyclopaedia, than a book of family history."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Yet before winding up with the concluding events, I may mention some\ninteresting facts illustrative of our exact position at the time these\ntook place."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Rockburg and Falconhurst continued to be our winter and summer\nheadquarters, and improvements were added which made them more and more\nconvenient as well as attractive in appearance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The fountains, trellised verandahs and plantations round Rockburg,\ncompletely changed the character of the residence which on account of\nthe heat and want of vegetation had in former days been so distasteful\nto my wife. Flowering creepers overhung the balconies and pillars;\nwhile shrubs and trees, both native and European, grew luxuriantly in\ngroves of our planting."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the distance, Shark Island, now clothed with graceful palms,\nguarded the entrance to Safety Bay, the battery and flagstaff\nprominently visible on its crested rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The swamp, cleared and drained, was now a considerable lake, with just\nmarsh and reeds enough beyond it to form good cover for the waterfowl\nwhose favourite retreat it was."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On its blue waters sailed stately black swans, snow-white geese and\nrichly coloured ducks; while out and in among the water-plants and\nrushes would appear at intervals glimpses of the brilliant Sultan,\nmarsh-fowl, crimson flamingos, soft blue-grey demoiselle cranes, and\ncrested heron, all associating in harmony, and with no fear of us,\ntheir masters."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The giant frogs, Grace and Beauty, delighted Jack by actually\nattaining in time to the size of small rabbits; and, perfectly knowing\ntheir very appropriate names, would waddle out of the marsh at his\ncall, to eat a grasshopper or dainty fly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Beneath the spreading trees, and through the aromatic shrubberies, old\nHurry, the ostrich, was usually to be seen marching about, with grave\nand dignified pace, as though monarch of all he surveyed. Every variety\nof beautiful pigeon nested in the rocks and dove-cots, their soft\ncooing and glossy plumage making them favourite household pets."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By the bridge alone could Rockburg be approached; for higher up the\nriver where, near the cascade, it was fordable, a dense and\nimpenetrable thicket of orange and lemon trees, Indian figs, prickly\npears and all manner of thorn-bearing shrubs, planted by us, now formed\na complete barrier."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The rabbit-warren on Shark Island kept us well supplied with food, as\nwell as soft and useful fur; and, as the antelopes did not thrive on\nWhale Isle, they also were placed among the shady groves with the\nrabbits, and their own island devoted to such work as candle-making,\ntanning, wool-cleaning and any other needful but offensive operations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The farm at Woodlands flourished, and our flocks and herds supplied us\nwith mutton, beef and veal, while my wife's dairy was almost more than\nshe could manage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My boys retained their old love for giving names to the animals. They\nhad a beautiful creamy-white cow, called Blanche, and a bull with such\na tremendous voice, that he received the name of Stentor. Two fleet\nyoung onagers were named Arrow and Dart; and Jack had a descendant of\nhis old favourite Fangs, the jackal, which he chose to call Coco,\nasserting that no word could be distinguished at a distance without 'o'\nin it, giving illustrations of his theory till our ears were almost\ndeafened."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Excellent health had been enjoyed by us all during these ten years,\nthough my wife occasionally suffered from slight attacks of fever, and\nthe boys sometimes met with little accidents."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They were all fine handsome fellows: Fritz, now twenty-four, was of\nmoderate height, uncommonly strong, active, muscular and\nhigh-spirited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest, two years younger, was tall and slight; in disposition, mild,\ncalm and studious; his early faults of indolence and selfishness were\nalmost entirely overcome. He possessed refined tastes and great\nintellectual power."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack, at twenty, strongly resembled Fritz, being about his height,\nthough more lightly built, and remarkable rather for active grace and\nagility than for muscular strength."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Franz, a lively youth of seventeen, had some of the qualities of each\nof his brothers; he possessed wit and shrewdness, but not the arch\ndrollery of Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All were honourable, God-fearing young men, dutiful and affectionate to\ntheir mother and myself, and warmly attached to each other."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Although so many years had elapsed in total seclusion, it continued to\nbe my strong impression that we should one day be restored to the\nsociety of our fellow men."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But time, which was bringing our sons to manhood, was also carrying\ntheir parents onwards to old age; and anxious, gloomy thoughts relating\nto their future, should they be left indeed alone, sometimes oppressed\nmy heart."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On such occasions I would not communicate the sense of depression to my\nfamily, but turning in prayer to the Almighty Father, laid my trouble\nbefore Him, with never-failing renewal of strength and hope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My elder sons often made expeditions of which we knew nothing until\ntheir return after many hours; when any uneasiness I might have felt\nwas dissipated by their joyous appearance, and reproof always died away\non my lips."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz had been absent one whole day from Rockburg, and not until\nevening did we remark that his cajack was gone, and that he must be out\nat sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Anxious to see him return before nightfall, I went off to Shark Island\nwith Ernest and Jack, in order to look out for him from the watch-tower\nthere, at the same time hoisting our signal flag, and loading the gun."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Long we gazed across the expanse of ocean glittering in the level\nbeams of the setting sun, and finally discerned a small black speck in\nthe distance which, by the telescope, was proved to be the returning\nwanderer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I remarked that his skiff sailed at a slower rate than usual towards\nthe shore. The cannon was fired to let him know that his approach was\nobserved, and then we joyfully hurried back to receive him at the\nharbour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was easy to see, as he drew near, what had delayed his progress. The\ncajack towed a large sack, besides being heavily laden. 'Welcome,\nFritz!' I cried. 'Welcome back, wherever you come from and whatever you\nbring. You seem to have quite a cargo there!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes, and my trip has led to discoveries as well as booty,' answered\nhe. 'Interesting discoveries which will tempt us again in the same\ndirection. Come, boys, let's carry up the things, and while I rest I\nwill relate my adventures.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as possible all assembled round him. 'I think my absence\nwithout leave deserves reproach instead of this warm reception,\nfather, and I must apologize for it,' he began, 'but ever since I\npossessed the cajack it has been my ambition to make a voyage of\ndiscovery along the coast, which we have never explored beyond the\npoint at which I killed the walrus."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In order to be ready to start without delay when a convenient\nopportunity offered, I made preparations beforehand, such as\nprovisioning my skiff, fixing the compass in front of my seat,\narranging conveniently rifle, harpoon, axe, boat-hook and fishing-net.\nI also resolved to take with me Pounce, my eagle, and this I always\nwill do in future."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This morning dawned magnificently; the calm sea, the gentle breeze,\nall drew me irresistibly to the fulfilment of my purpose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I left the harbour unperceived, the current quickly bore me out to\nsea, and I rounded the point to the left, passing just over the spot\nwhere, beneath the waves, lie the guns, cannon balls, ironwork, and all\nthat was indestructible about our good old wreck. And would you believe\nit? Through the glassy clear water, undisturbed by a ripple, I actually\nsaw many such things strewn on the flat rocky bottom."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Pursuing my way, I passed among rugged cliffs and rocks which jutted\nout from the shore, or rose in rugged masses from the water. Myriads of\nsea-fowl inhabited the most inaccessible of these, while on the lower\nridges, seals, sea-bears and walruses, were to be seen, some basking\nlazily in the sun, some plunging into the water, or emerging awkwardly\nfrom it, hoisting their unwieldy bodies up the rocks by means of their\ntusks."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I must confess to feeling anything but comfortable while going\nthrough the places held in possession by these monsters of the deep,\nand used every effort to pass quickly and unnoticed. Yet it was more\nthan an hour and a half before I got clear of the rocks, cliffs, and\nshoals to which they resorted, and neared a high and precipitous cape,\nrunning far out to sea. Right opposite to me, in the side of this rocky\nwall, was a magnificent archway, forming as it first appeared to me, a\nlofty entrance to an immense vaulted cavern. I passed beneath this\nnoble portal and examined the interior."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was tenanted by numbers of a small species of swallow, scarcely\nlarger than a wren, and the walls were covered by thousands of their\nnests. They were rudely built, and their peculiarity was that each\nrested on a kind of platform, something like a spoon without the\nhandle. I detached a number, and found that they had a curious\nappearance, seemingly made of something fibrous and gelatinous, and\nmore like a set of sponges, corals, or fungi, than nests of birds. I\nhave brought them home in my fishing net.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'If we had commercial dealings with the Chinese,' said I, 'your\ndiscovery would be of value; these are doubtless edible birds' nests.\nThe bird is called the esculent swallow, and the trade in this strange\narticle of diet is a very large one. The nests are of different value,\nbut those which are quite new, and nearly white, are held in such\nesteem that they are worth their weight in silver."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There are tremendous caverns in Java and other places where, at great\nrisk, these nests are procured; the annual weight obtained being\nupwards of fifty thousand pounds, and the value more than ï¿½200,000."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'When placed in water and well soaked, they soften and swell, and are\nmade into soup of very strengthening and restorative quality."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think you might try your hand on these, mother, just for\ncuriosity's sake.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I can't say I fancy the look of the queer things,' said she, 'but I\ndon't mind trying if they will turn to jelly; though boiling birds'\nnests is cookery quite out of my line.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh do, mother, let us taste birds' nests as soon as you can, though\nthe idea makes me fancy my mouth full of feathers!' laughed Jack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It is really a most curious formation,' said Fritz. 'From whence are\nthe swallows supposed to get this kind of gelatine?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It has never been exactly ascertained,' I replied, 'whether the birds\ndiscover or produce this curious substance. But whatever may be its\nbasis, it is clear that a very large portion of it is furnished by\ncertain glands, which pour out a viscid secretion.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After laying in my store of nests,' continued Fritz, 'I pursued my way\nthrough this vaulted cave or corridor; which, presently turning, opened\ninto a very lonely bay, so calm and lake-like, that, although of\nconsiderable size, I concluded at once it must be nearly land-locked.\nIts shores, beyond the rocky boundary through which I penetrated,\nextended in a fertile plain towards what seemed the mouth of a river,\nbeyond which lay rough and probably marshy ground, and a dense forest\nof cedars, which closed the view."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The water beneath me was clear as crystal; and, gazing into its\ndepths and shallows, I perceived beds of shellfish, like large\noysters, attached to the rocks and to each other by tufts of hairy\nfilaments."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"If these are oysters,\" thought I, \"they must be better worth eating,\nas far as size goes, than our little friends in Safety Bay,\" and\nthereupon I hooked up several clusters with my boat-hook, and landing\nsoon after on the beach, I flung them on the sand, resolving to fetch\nanother load, and then tow them after me in the fishing-net."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The hot sun disagreed with their constitution, I suppose; for when I\ncame back the shells were all gaping wide open; so I began to examine\nthem, thinking that after all they were probably much less delicate\nthan the small oysters we have learnt to like so much."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Somehow, when a thing is to be \"examined\", one generally needs a\nknife. The blade met with resistance here and there in the creature's\nbody; and still closer \"examination\" produced from it several pearly\nballs, like peas, of different sizes. Do you think they can be pearls?\nI have a number here in a box.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, show them to us, Fritz!' cried the boys. 'What pretty shining\nthings! And how delicately rounded! And how softly they gleam!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You have discovered treasure, indeed!' I exclaimed. 'Why these are\nmost beautiful pearls! Valueless, certainly, under present\ncircumstances; but they may prove a source of wealth, should we ever\nagain come into contact with the civilized world. We must visit your\npearl-oyster beds at the earliest opportunity.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After resting for some time and refreshing myself with food,' pursued\nFritz, 'I resumed my survey of the coast, my progress somewhat impeded\nby the bag of shellfish, which I drew after me; but I proceeded without\naccident past the mouth of the stream to the further side of the bay,\nwhich was there enclosed by a point corresponding to that through which\nI had entered; and between these headlands I found a line of reefs and\nsand-banks, with but a single channel leading out to the open sea; from\nwhich, therefore, Pearl Bay, as I named it, lies completely sheltered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The tide was setting strongly in shore, so that I could not then\nattempt a passage through it, but examined the crags of the headland,\nthinking I might perchance discover a second vaulted archway. I saw\nnothing remarkable, however, but thousands of sea-fowl of every sort\nand kind, from the gull and sea-swallow to the mighty albatross."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My approach was evidently regarded as an invasion and trespass; for\nthey regularly beset me, screaming and wheeling over my head, till, out\nof all patience, I stood up, and hit furiously about me with the\nboat-hook; when, rather to my surprise, one blow struck an albatross\nwith such force, that he fell stunned into the water."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I now once more attempted to cross the reef by the narrow channel, and\nhappily succeeding, found myself in the open sea, and speeding\nhomewards, joyfully saw our flag flying, and heard the welcome salute\nyou fired.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Here ended the narrative; but next morning Fritz drew me aside, and\nconfided to me a most remarkable sequel, in these words:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There was something very extraordinary about that albatross, father. I\nallowed you to suppose that I left it as it fell, but in reality I\nraised it to the deck of the canoe, and then perceived a piece of rag\nwound round one of its legs. This I removed, and, to my utter\nastonishment, saw English words written on it, which I plainly made out\nto be \"Save an unfortunate Englishwoman from the smoking rock!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This little sentence sent a thrill through every nerve: my brain\nseemed to whirl. I doubted the evidence of my senses."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Is this reality, or delusion?\" thought I, \"Can it be true, that a\nfellow creature breathes with us the air of this lonely region?\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I felt stupefied for some minutes: the bird began to show signs of\nlife, which recalled me to myself; and, quickly deciding what must be\ndone, I tore a strip from my handkerchief, on which I traced the words,\n\"Do not despair! Help is near!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This I carefully bound round one leg, replacing the rag on the other,\nand then applied myself to the complete restoration of the bird. It\ngradually revived; and after drinking a little, surprised me by\nsuddenly rising on the wing, faltering a moment in its flight, and then\nrapidly disappearing from my view in a westerly direction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, father, one thought occupies me continually: will my note ever\nreach this Englishwoman? Shall I be able to find, and to save her?' I\nlistened to this account with feelings of the liveliest interest and\nastonishment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My dear son,' said I, 'you have done wisely in confiding to me alone\nyour most exciting discovery. Unless we know more, we must not unsettle\nthe others by speaking of it; for it appears to me quite possible that\nthese words were penned long ago on some distant shore, where, by this\ntime, the unhappy stranger may have perished miserably. By the \"smoking\nrock\" must be meant a volcano. There are none here.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz was not disposed to look at the case from this gloomy point of\nview; did not think the rag so very old; believed smoke might rise from\na rock which was not volcanic; and evidently cherished the hope that he\nmight be able to respond effectually to this touching appeal. I was in\nreality as anxious as himself on the subject, but judged it prudent to\nabate rather than excite hopes of success which might be doomed to\nbitter disappointment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After earnest consultation on the subject, we decided that Fritz\nshould go in search of the writer of the message, but not until he had\nso altered the canoe as to fit it for carrying two persons, as well as\nprovisions sufficient to admit of his absence for a considerable time.\nImpatient as he was, he could not but see the wisdom of this delay. We\nreturned to the house, and saw the boys busily opening the oysters,\nwhich they had had no time to do the previous night, and greatly\nexcited as ever and anon a pearl was found."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'May we not establish a pearl-fishery at once, father?' shouted they.\n'We might build a hut on the shore of the bay and set about it\nregularly.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "An excursion to Pearl Bay was now the event to which all thoughts\nturned, and for which preparations on a grand scale were made. It was\nto form, as it were, the basis of the more important voyage Fritz had\nin view, and to which, unsuspected by the rest, he could devote all his\nattention."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I took an opportunity, one day, when all were present, to remark in a\nserious tone:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I have been considering, dear wife, that our eldest son is now of an\nage to be dependent on himself. I shall, therefore, henceforth leave\nhim at liberty to act in all respects according to his own judgement;\nand, especially in the matter of voyages or excursions, he must not be\nhampered by the fear of alarming us should he choose to remain absent\nlonger than we expect. I have such entire confidence in his prudence,\nand at the same time in his affection for us, that I am certain he will\nnever needlessly cause us anxiety.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz looked gratefully towards me as I spoke; and his mother ratified\nmy words, embracing him affectionately, and saying, with emotion, 'God\nbless and preserve thee, my boy!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It took some time to make several raking or scraping machines, which I\ninvented for the purpose of detaching and lifting the oysters from\ntheir native rocks; but that gave Fritz leisure to change the fittings\nof his canoe, so as to have a spare seat in it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His brothers naturally concluded he meant to take one of them as\nshipmate on board, and he allowed the mistake to continue."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They occupied themselves in making various articles they expected to be\nof use, and bore the delay with tolerable patience."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At last came the day, when, taking leave of my wife and Franz, we went\non board the yacht, accompanied by some of the dogs; while Jack,\nproudly occupying the new seat beside Fritz in the canoe, shared with\nhim the honour of leading the way in the character of pilots."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We passed safely through the rocks and shoals near Walrus Island into\nan expanse of calm water, sheltered by jutting cliffs, where the sea\nglanced like a mirror, and for the first time we observed the\nfairy-like shells of the paper-nautilus sailing lightly over the\ndazzling surface."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was impossible to see these lovely seafarers without wishing to\nobtain specimens; and the canoe accordingly gave chase, presently\nsecuring half a dozen, which were handed to us in the yacht to be\ncarefully preserved for the museum, and the place was ever after called\nNautilus Creek."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Further on we rounded a short promontory, flat, with an abrupt rock at\nthe extremity, to which we gave the name of Cape Pug-Nose; and then, at\nsome distance, appeared the grand cliffs of a headland running far out\nto sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This I supposed we should have to weather, but my pilots made no\nchange in our course, and, following the canoe, we soon came in sight\nof the majestic archway which offered us a short passage to Pearl Bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The wonderfully architectural appearance of the pillars, arches and\npinnacles, surrounding and surmounting this noble entrance, struck me\nwith admiration, resembling parts of a fine gothic cathedral, and\ninducing me to propose for it the name Cape Minster."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A perfect cloud of little swallows darted from the cavernous entrance\non our approach, divided into flocks, soared, wheeled, flew right and\nleft, and finally returned in a body as swiftly as they came, to the\nsides of the long dark tunnel, which were festooned with their nests."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We detached a number of these as we passed, taking care to leave those\ncontaining eggs or young. The best were at a considerable height, but\nthe broken and shelving rocks afforded, in some places, footing for\nsuch daring and active climbers as Fritz and Jack, and they quickly\nobtained as many as we could possibly require."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our progress was much assisted by the tide, which, like a current, bore\nus onward along the nave of this natural cathedral; aisles, transepts,\nscreens and side-chapels appearing between the columns and arches which\nin the 'dim religious light' were revealed to our wondering eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On emerging into the dazzling sunshine, we found ourselves floating in\nthe calm expanse of Pearl Bay; but it was some minutes before we could\nlook around on the bright and lovely scene."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz had not overrated its beauty, and the romantic islets which\nstudded its waters seemed to give the effect of a pleasant smile to\nfeatures already perfect."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We cruised about for some time, surveying the coast with its fertile\nmeadows, shady groves, gently swelling hills and murmuring brooks,\nseeking a convenient landing-place in the vicinity of the shallows\nwhere lay the oyster-beds."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This we found, close to a sparkling streamlet; and, as the day was fast\ndeclining, we made speedy arrangements for burning a watch-fire; after\nwhich we partook of a hasty supper, and leaving the dogs, with Coco,\nthe jackal, to sleep on shore, we returned on board the yacht for the\nnight, anchoring within gunshot of the land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The coast being quite strange to us, I knew not what wild beasts might\nfrequent it; but, though I did not fear that any would approach us by\nswimming, yet I was glad to have with us our lively little ape, Mercury\n(the successor of our old favourite, Knips, long since gathered to his\nfathers), for he occupied at night a cosy berth on deck, and was\ncertain to give vociferous notice should anything alarming occur."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz moored the cajack alongside, and came on board. The night passed\nin peace, although for a time we were disturbed by the yelping of\njackals, with whom Coco persisted in keeping up a noisy conversation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We awoke at daybreak, and after breakfasting a la fourchette*, we\nrepaired in haste with nets, scrapers and all other requisites, to the\noyster-beds, where we worked with such diligence and success that in\nthe course of two days we had an immense pile of shells built up like a\nstack on the beach, and left to decay. I collected a quantity of\nseaweed to spread over them, which was afterwards burnt to make alkali,\nwhen we returned to secure our harvest of pearls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "lit. in the manner of a fork; from a French saying that\ntranslates \"the fork of Father Adam.\" In other words, they\nate hastily with their fingers."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every evening we went out shooting in the neighbourhood, and kept\nourselves supplied with game of one sort or another. The last day of\nour fishery we started earlier, intending to make a longer excursion\ninto the woods."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest set off first with Floss; Jack and Coco strolling after them.\nFritz and I were still employed in taking on board the last load of our\ntools, when we suddenly heard a shot, a loud cry of pain or fear, and\nthen another shot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the first alarm, the other two dogs rushed away from us towards the\nspot, and Fritz, who had just called Pounce from his perch, to\naccompany us in the ramble, let him fly, and seizing his rifle darted\noff in the same direction."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before I could reach the scene of action, more shots were heard, and\nthen a shout of victory; after which appeared through the stems of the\ntrees the disconsolate figure of Jack, hobbling along like a cripple,\nsupported on each side by his brothers."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When they came near me they stopped; and poor Jack, moaning and\ngroaning, began to feel himself all over, as if to search for broken\nbones, crying out:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I'm pounded like a half-crushed pepper-corn!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On examination I found some severe bruises. 'Who or what has been\npummelling the boy?' I exclaimed. 'One would think he had been\nbeaten.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was a huge wild boar,' said Ernest, 'with fierce eyes, monstrous\ntusks and a snout as broad as my hand.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We took Jack down to the yacht, bathed his bruises, gave him a cooling\ndrink, and he soon fell fast asleep in his berth, where I left him and\nreturned to the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, Ernest,' said I, 'enlighten me on the subject of this adventure!\nWhat you and the boar did, is quite a mystery to me.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Floss and I were going quietly along,' replied he, 'when suddenly\nthere was a rustling and snorting close by, and a great boar broke\nthrough the bushes, making for the outskirts of the wood. Floss gave\nchase directly, and the boar turned to bay. Then up came Jack with\nCoco, and the gallant little jackal attacked the monster in the rear.\nIn another moment, however, he was sent sprawling upon his back, and\nthis so provoked his master that he fired a hasty ill-directed shot.\nThe brute's notice and fury at once turned upon Jack, who prudently\ntook to his heels, while I attempted to check the career of the boar by\na shot, which, however, only slightly wounded it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack stumbled and fell over the root of a tree, just as the animal\ncame up with him. \"Help! Murder,\" shouted he; and if the other dogs had\nnot then arrived, and all together tackled the boar, I fear it would\nhave been a case of murder indeed! As it was, the poor fellow got\nmauled and trampled upon dreadfully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As I was waiting for an opportunity to fire without any risk of\nhitting Jack, Pounce rushed through the air and darted upon the beast,\nand Fritz came quickly up and shot it dead with a pistol."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'While we were helping Jack along, and passing a place where the boar\nhad been grubbing, I noticed some such curious knotty roots or\ntubercles, that I brought away specimens. Are they worth anything, do\nyou think? They have a strong smell.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'If I may trust my nose,' said I, 'you have brought something by no\nmeans to be despised. Yes,' I continued, putting them to my lips,\n'these are very fine truffles! Taste them, Fritz.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Indeed they are excellent,' said he, 'very different from the tough,\nleathery things I remember in Europe: these are tender and\nwell-flavoured.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Because they are fresh,' said I. 'You have before tasted those only\nwhich have been brought from a distance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'They are found in different parts of Europe, buried at a depth of ten\nor twelve inches in the soil of oak or beech woods. A small dog is\nemployed to hunt for them, who perceives their musky odour in a\nsingularly acute way, and at once scratches at the spot where they\nlie.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Have the truffles no leaves or stalks,' inquired Fritz, 'by which they\nmight be found without the help of the dog?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'They have nothing of the sort,' I replied. 'They are discovered\nsimply by scent, and are considered to belong to the tribe of Fungi.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "By this time it was late: we took supper, made up the watch-fire, and\nwithdrew to our yacht, where we slept peacefully."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Early next morning we proceeded to visit the field of battle. The wild\nboar, which I had not before seen, proved to be much larger and more\nformidable in appearance than I had imagined, and Jack's escape seemed\nto me perfectly marvellous."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys took it as a matter of course that we were to cut out hams and\nflitches; and we therefore did so, though I warned them that they need\nnot expect much pleasure in eating bacon from a tough old African boar\nlike this. We conveyed the mighty hams to the beach, each on a sledge\nof plaited boughs and twigs, and drawn by one of the dogs. The\nmonstrous head travelled in the same way, and we collected a large\nnumber of truffles before quitting the forest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As soon as the dogs were released, they rushed back to the scene of\noperations in the wood, comprehending that they were now free to feast\non what remained there."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "There was so much to be done in consequence of this affair, that\nFritz, who had hoped to set out on his solitary expedition that day,\ndeferred it until the next; and was, therefore, fortunately with us,\nwhen late in the evening we desisted from our labours, and having\nsupped, were preparing to retire to rest. All at once a deep fearful\nsound echoed through the neighbouring woods. It made our blood curdle\nin our veins. We listened with straining ears, hoping it would not be\nrepeated. With a shudder we heard the dread voice roar again, yet\nnearer to us, and an answer peal from the distance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We must find out who are the performers in this concert!' exclaimed\nFritz, springing to his feet, and snatching up his rifle. 'Make the\nfire blaze, get on board the yacht, and have all the guns in readiness.\nI am off to reconnoitre in the canoe.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We mechanically obeyed his rapid orders, while the bold youth\ndisappeared in the darkness; and, after heaping fuel on the fire, we\nwent on board and armed ourselves with cutlasses, besides loading all\nthe guns, waiting in readiness either to land again, or to quit the\ncoast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We presently saw the whole pack of our dogs, as well as Coco, the\njackal, and the little ape, Mercury (who had been tempted by the\ntruffles to stay with them in the woods), come galloping at full speed\nup to the fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mercury was evidently excessively discomposed at finding us gone; he\ngnashed his teeth, and chattered, as though in fear, looking\nhopelessly at the water, through which he could not venture."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs planted themselves by the fire, gazing fixedly landward, with\nears erect, and occasionally uttering a barking challenge, or a\nsuppressed howl."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meantime, the horrid roarings approached nearer, and I concluded that a\ncouple of leopards or panthers had been attracted by the scent of the\nboar's carcase."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But not long after I had expressed this opinion, we beheld a large\npowerful animal spring from the underwood and, with a bound and\nmuttered roar, approach the fire. In a moment I recognized the\nunmistakable outlines of the form of a lion, though in size he far\nsurpassed any I had ever seen exhibited in Europe."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The dogs slunk behind the fire, and the lion seated himself almost like\na cat on his hind legs, glaring alternately at them, and at the great\nboar hams which hung near, with doubtless a mixed feeling of irritation\nand appetite, which was testified by the restless movement of his tail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He then arose, and commenced walking up and down with slow and\nmeasured pace, occasionally uttering short, angry roars, quite unlike\nthe prolonged full tones we had heard at first. At times he went to\ndrink at the brook, always returning with such haste, that I fully\nexpected to see him spring."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Gradually his manner became more and more threatening; he turned\ntowards us, crouched, and with his body at full stretch, waved his\ntail, and glared so furiously, that I was in doubt whether to fire or\nretreat, when through the darkness rang the sharp crack of a rifle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That is Fritz!' exclaimed everyone; while, with a fearful roar, the\nlion sprang to his feet, stood stock still, tottered, sank on his\nknees, rolled over, and lay motionless on the sand."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We are saved!' I cried. 'That was a masterly shot. The lion is struck\nto the heart: he will never stir again. Stay on board, boys. I must\njoin my brave Fritz.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a few moments I landed: the dogs met me with evident tokens of\npleasure, but kept whining uneasily, and looking towards the deep\ndarkness of the woods whence the lion had come."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This behaviour made me cautious; and, seeing nothing of Fritz, I\nlingered by the boat, when suddenly a lioness bounded from the shadow\nof the trees, into the light diffused by the fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At sight of the blazing faggots she paused, as though startled; passed\nwith uncertain step round the outskirts of the illuminated circle; and\nuttered roarings, which were evidently calls to her mate, whose dead\nbody she presently discovered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Finding him motionless, her manner betokened the greatest concern; she\ntouched him with her forepaws, smelt round him, and licked his bleeding\nwounds. Then raising her head, she gnashed her teeth, and gave forth\nthe most lamentable and dreadful sound I ever heard; a mingled roar and\nhowl, which was like the expression of grief, rage, and a vow to be\nrevenged, all in one."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Crack! Another shot: the creature's right forepaw was lamed; and the\ndogs, seeing me raise my gun, suddenly gathered courage, and ran\nforward just as I fired. My shot also wounded the lioness, but not\nmortally, and the most terrific combat ensued."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was impossible to fire again, for fear of wounding the dogs. The\nscene was fearful beyond description. Black night surrounded us; the\nfitful blaze of the fire shed a strange, unnatural light on the\nprostrate body of the huge dead lion, and on the wounded lioness, who\nfought desperately against the attack of the four gallant dogs; while\nthe cries, roars and groans of anguish and fury uttered by all the\nanimals were enough to try the stoutest nerves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Old Juno, staunch to the last, was foremost in the fray. After a time,\nI saw her change her plan of attack, and spring at the throat of the\nlioness; who, in an instant, raised her left paw, and at one blow the\ncruel claws had laid open the body of the dog, and destroyed the life\nof the true and faithful companion of so many years."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Just then, Fritz appeared. The lioness was much weakened, and we\nventured to go near enough to fire with safety to ourselves; and\nfinally I dispatched her by plunging a hunting-knife deep in her\nbreast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest and Jack were summoned from the yacht to witness the completed\nvictory; and I regretted having left them on board, when I saw how\ngreatly the noise and tumult had alarmed them, unable as they were to\nascertain what was going on."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They hastened towards us in great agitation, and their joy on seeing us\nsafe was only equalled by the grief they felt on learning of the death\nof Juno."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The night was now far advanced; the fire burnt low; but we piled on\nmore wood, and, by the renewed light, drew poor Juno from between the\npaws of the lioness; and, by the brookside, washed and bound up the\ntorn body, wrapping it carefully in canvas, and carrying it with us on\nboard the yacht, that it might be buried at Rockburg, whither, on the\nfollowing day, it was our purpose to return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Wearied and sorrowful, but full of thankfulness for our personal\nsafety, we at length lay down to sleep, having brought all the dogs on\nboard."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning, before quitting Pearl Bay, we once more landed, that we\nmight possess ourselves of the magnificent skins of the lion and\nlioness, whose visit, fatal to themselves, had caused such a commotion\nduring the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In about a couple of hours we returned to the yacht, leaving the\nflayed carcasses to the tender mercies of the birds of prey sure to be\nattracted to them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Homeward bound,' sang out the boys, as they cheerily weighed anchor,\nand prepared to stand out to sea. I could see, though he did not\ncomplain, that poor Jack had not yet recovered from the boar's rough\ntreatment, and moved very stiffly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You must pilot us through the channel in the reef, this time, Fritz,'\nsaid I; adding, in a lower tone, 'and then is it to be \"farewell\", my\nson!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Yes, dear fatherâ€”Au revoir!' returned he, brightly with a glance full\nof meaning, while he threw into his canoe a cushion and fur cloak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Thanks, Fritz! But I'm going to honour them with the care of my\nbattered bones in the yacht here. You are awfully considerate though,\nold fellow,' remarked Jack, not for a moment doubting that his brother\nexpected him to return, as he came, beside him in the cajack."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz laughed, and commended his decision. Then, springing into his\nskiff, he led the way towards the open sea."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We followed carefully and soon passed the reef; after which the boys\nwere very busy with the sails, putting the vessel on the homeward\ncourse, when, waving his hand to me, Fritz turned in the opposite\ndirection, and quickly vanished behind the point, which I afterwards\nnamed Cape Farewell."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When missed by his brothers, I said he had a fancy to explore more of\nthe coast, and if he found it interesting, he might, instead of only a\nfew hours, remain absent for two or three days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Towards evening, we sailed into Safety Bay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 17"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife and Franz, though somewhat startled by the unexpected absence\nof Fritz, were delighted to see us return safely, and listened with\neager interest to our adventures. My wife shuddered, and scarcely\nsuppressed an involuntary scream as she heard of our desperate\nencounter with the lion and his mate. Jack's danger and providential\nescape, too, made her tremble; and so pale did he still look, that she\ncould scarcely believe he was uninjured."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Tears came into Franz's eyes when he heard of the sad death of poor old\nJuno; and he inquired most tenderly whether her remains had been\nbrought back, that they might be interred near the house which had been\nher home for so many years."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next day he saw her buried carefully; and Ernest, at his request,\nproduced an epitaph, which was inscribed upon a slab of stone above her\ngrave."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'JUNO"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A servant true lies here:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A faithful friend,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A Dog,"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'To all most dear;"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Who met her end"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fighting right bravely in her master's cause."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The flesh of the wild boar and the truffles were handed over to my\nwife, who received them with delight, promising us therefrom many a\nsavoury dish. She would fain have had the boar's head too; but my word\nwas pledged to Ernest that it should adorn his museum, and, though my\nlips watered to taste it baked in Hottentot fashion, I would not break\nmy promise. This splendid head, therefore, together with the lions'\nskins, we carried to the tannery on Whale Island, where they were\ncleaned and dressed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Five days passed, but Fritz still remained absent. I could not conceal\nmy anxiety, and at length determined to follow him. All were delighted\nat the proposal, and even my wife, when she heard that we were to sail\nin the pinnace, agreed to accompany us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boat was stored, and on a bright morning, with a favourable\nbreeze, we five, with the dogs, stepped aboard, and ran for Cape\nMinster."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our beautiful little yacht bounded over the water gaily, and the\nbright sunshine and delicious sea-breeze put us all in the highest\nspirits. The entrance of the archway was in sight, and thither I was\ndirecting the boat's course."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Suddenly, right ahead, I saw a dark and shadowy mass just below the\nsurface of the water. 'A sunken rock,' I thought to myself, 'and yet it\nis strange that I never before noticed it.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I put down the helm in a moment, but a catastrophe seemed inevitable.\nWe surged ahead! A slight shock, and all was over! The danger was\npassed!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I glanced astern, to look again at the dangerous spot; but the rock was\ngone, and, where but a moment before I had distinctly seen its great\ngreen shadow, I could now see nothing."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before we had recovered from our amazement, a shout from Jack\nsurprised me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'There is another,' he exclaimed, 'to starboard, father!' Sure enough,\nthere lay, apparently, another sunken rock."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The rock is moving!' shouted Franz; and a great black body emerged\nfrom the sea, while from the upper extremity rushed a column of water,\nwhich, with a mighty noise, rose upwards, and then fell like rain all\naround. The mystery was explained; for, as the great beast emerged yet\nfurther from the water, I recognized, from its enormous size and great\nlength of head, the cachalot whale."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The monster was apparently enraged at the way we had scratched his\nback; for, retreating to a short distance, he evidently meditated a\nrush upon us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fearful stories occurred to me of the savage temper of this whale, how\nhe has been known to destroy boat after boat, and even to sink great\nships, and with a feeling of desperation I sprang to one of the guns.\nJack leaped to the other, and almost simultaneously we fired. Both\nshots apparently took effect; for the whale, after lashing the water\nviolently for a few seconds, plunged beneath its surface, and\ndisappeared."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We kept a sharp look-out for him, for I was unwilling to lose such a\nvaluable prize and, reloading, stood towards the shore, in which\ndirection he was apparently making. Presently we again sighted him in\nshallow water, lashing fearfully with his tail, and dyeing the waves\naround him with blood. Approaching the infuriated animal as nearly as I\ndared, we again fired."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The struggles of the whale seemed for a few moments to become even yet\nmore frantic, and then, with a quiver from head to tail, he lay\nmotionlessâ€”dead!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys were about to raise a cry of victory, but checked the shout\nupon their very lips; for darting behind a rock they espied a canoe\npaddled by a tall and muscular savage, who now stood up in his skiff\nand appeared to be examining us attentively. Seeing that we were\nstanding towards him, the swarthy native seized his paddle and again\ndarted behind a rock. An awful thought now took possession of me. There\nmust be a tribe of blacks lurking on these shores, and Fritz must have\nfallen into their hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We, however, I determined, should not be easily taken; and our guns\nwere loaded and run out."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently a dusky face appeared, peeping at us from a lofty rock: it\nvanished, and we saw another peeping at us from lower down."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then again the skiff put out as though to make a further reconnoitre.\nAll, even Jack, looked anxious, and glanced at me for orders."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hoist a white flag,' said I, 'and hand me the speaking-trumpet.' I\nseized the instrument and uttered such peaceable words in the Malay\nlanguage as I could recall: neither the flag nor my words seemed to\nproduce any effect, and the savage was about to return to the shore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack hereupon lost patience, and in his turn took up the trumpet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Come here, you black son of a gun,' he exclaimed. 'Come on board and\nmake friends, or we'll blow you and yourâ€”'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Stop! Stop! You foolish boy,' I said. 'You will but alarm the man,\nwith your wild words and gestures.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'No! But see,' he cried, 'he is paddling towards us!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "And sure enough the canoe was rapidly approaching."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently a cry from Franz alarmed me. 'Look! Look!' he shrieked. 'The\nvillain is in Fritz's cajack. I can see the walrus' head.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ernest alone remained unmoved. He took the speaking-trumpet: 'Fritz,\nahoy!' he shouted. 'Welcome, old fellow!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The words were scarcely out of his mouth when I, too, recognized the\nwell-known face, beneath its dusky disguise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In another minute the brave boy was on board, and in spite of his\nblackened face was kissed and welcomed heartily. He was now assailed\nwith a storm of questions from all sides: Where had he been? What had\nkept him so long, and why had he turned blackamoor?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The last question,' replied he, with a smile, 'is the only one I will\nnow answer; the others shall be explained when I give a full account of\nmy adventures. Hearing guns fired, my mind was instantly filled with\nideas of Malay pirates, for I never dreamed that you could be here in\nthe yacht, so I disguised myself as you now see me, and came forth to\nreconnoitre. When you addressed me in Malay you only added to my\nterror, for it left not a doubt in my mind that you were pirates.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having in our turn described to him our adventure with the cachalot\nwhale, I asked him if he knew of a suitable spot for the anchorage of\nthe yacht."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Certainly,' he replied, casting towards me a glance full of meaning.\n'I can lead you to an island where there is splendid anchorage, and\nwhich is itself well worth seeing, for it contains all sorts of strange\nthings.' And after removing the stains from his skin, he again sprang\ninto his canoe and piloted us to a picturesque little island in the\nbay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Now that there could be no doubt as to the success of Fritz's\nexpedition, I no longer hesitated to give to my wife an account of his\nproject, and to prepare her mind for the surprise which awaited her.\nShe was greatly startled, as I expected, and seemed almost overcome\nwith emotion at the idea of seeing a human being, and that being one of\nher own sex."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'But why,' she asked, 'did you not tell me of this at first? Why wait\nuntil the last moment with such joyful news?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I was unwilling,' I replied, 'to raise hopes which might never be\nrealized; but now, thank Heaven, he has succeeded, and there is no need\nfor concealment.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The boys could not at all understand the evident air of mystery and\nsuppressed excitement which neither their mother, Fritz, nor I could\nentirely conceal. They cast glances of the greatest curiosity towards\nthe island, and as soon as the sails were furled and the anchor\ndropped, they sprang eagerly ashore. In a body we followed Fritz,\nmaintaining perfect silence."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Presently we emerged from the thicket through which we were passing,\nand saw before us a hut of sheltering boughs, at the entrance of which\nburned a cheerful fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Into this leafy bower Fritz dived, leaving his brothers without, mute\nwith astonishment. In another moment he emerged, leading by the hand a\nslight, handsome youth, by his dress apparently a young English naval\nofficer. The pair advanced to meet us; and Fritz, with a countenance\nradiant with joy, briefly introduced his companion as Edward Montrose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And,' he continued, looking at his mother and me, 'will you not\nwelcome him as a friend and a brother to our family circle?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'That will we, indeed!' I exclaimed, advancing and holding out my\nhands to the fair young stranger. 'Our wild life may have roughened our\nlooks and manners, but it has not hardened our hearts, I trust.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The mother, too, embraced the seeming youth most heartily. The lads,\nand even the dogs, were not behind-hand in testifying their\ngratification at the appearance of their new friendâ€”the former\ndelighted at the idea of a fresh companion, and the latter won by her\nsweet voice and appearance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From the expressions made use of by Fritz I perceived that the girl\nwished her sex to remain unrevealed to the rest of the party until my\nwife could obtain for her a costume more suited to her real character."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The young men then ran down to the yacht to bring up what was\nnecessary for supper, as well as to make preparations for a camp in\nwhich we might spend the night. This done, my wife hastened to set\nbefore us a substantial meal, while the boys, anxious to make their new\nacquaintance feel at home amongst them, were doing their best to amuse\nher. She herself, after the first feeling of strangeness had worn off,\nentered fully into all their fun; and by the time they sat down to\nsupper was laughing and chatting as gaily as any one of the rest. She\nadmired the various dishes, tasted our mead and, without alluding once\nto her previous life, kept up a lively conversation."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The mere fact of meeting with any human being after so many years of\nisolation was in itself sufficient to raise the boys to the greatest\nstate of excitement; but that this being should be one so handsome; so\ngay, so perfectly charming, seemed completely to have fumed their\nheads; and when I gave the sign for the breaking-up of the feast, and\ntheir new friend was about to be led to the night-quarters which had\nbeen prepared for her on board the yacht, the health of Edward Montrose\nwas proposed, and drunk in fragrant mead, amidst the cheers and\nacclamations of all hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When she was gone, and silence had been restored, Jack exclaimed:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Now, then, Fritz, if you please, just tell me where you came across\nthis jolly fellow. Did you take your mysterious voyage in search of\nhim, or did you meet him by chance? Out with your adventures, while we\nsit comfortably round the fire.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "So saying, Jack cast more wood upon the blazing pile, and throwing\nhimself down in his usual careless fashion, prepared to listen\nattentively."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, after a few moments' hesitation, began: 'Perhaps you remember,'\nsaid he, 'how, when I returned from my expedition in the cajack the\nother day, I struck down an albatross. None but my father at the time\nknew, however, what became of the wounded bird, or even thought more\nabout it. Yet it was that albatross who brought me notice of the\nshipwrecked stranger; and he, too, I determined should carry back a\nmessage, to cheer and encourage the sender."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I first, as you know, prepared my cajack to carry two persons; and\nthen, with a heart full of hope and trust, left you and the yacht, and,\nwith Pounce seated before me, made for the open sea. For several hours\nI paddled steadily on, till, the wind freshening, I thought it\nadvisable to keep in nearer shore; that, should a regular storm arise,\nI might find some sheltered bay in which to weather it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'It was well I did so; for, scarcely had I reached a quiet cove which\npromised to afford me the protection I desired, than the sea appeared\none mass of foam: great surging waves arose; and even in the\ncomparative calm of the bay I felt that I was in some danger."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I passed the night in my cajack; and next morning, after a frugal meal\nof pemmican, and a draught of water from my flask, once more ventured\nforth. The wind had subsided, the sea was tolerably smooth; and,\nkeeping my eyes busily employed in seeking in every direction to\ndetect, if possible, the slightest trace of smoke, or other sign of\nhuman life, I paddled on till noon."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The aspect of the coast now began to change: the shores were sandy,\nwhile further inland lay dense forests, from whose gloomy depths I\ncould ever and anon hear the fierce roar of beasts of prey, the yell of\napes, the fiendish laugh of the hyaena, or the despairing death cry of\na hapless deer. Seldom have I experienced a greater feeling of solitude\nthan whilst listening to these strange sounds, and knowing that I in\nthis frail canoe was the only human being near. Giving myself up to\ncontemplation, I rested my paddle, and allowed my cajack to drift\nslowly on."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As I neared the shore, I noticed a large number of strange-looking\nbirds, who would sometimes flutter round me, and then dart back again\nto the border of the forest, where they were feeding on what appeared\nto be the pepper-plant; they seized the berries in their great\nponderous beaks, threw them up into the air and then dexterously caught\nthem in their fall. Their beaks were really something extraordinary:\nthey looked as though they must give their owners a perpetual headache,\nfrom their immense weight. The only thing that relieved the extreme\nugliness of these great appendages was their gorgeous colour, which was\nonly rivalled by the gay hue of the plumage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I wish now that I had brought home a specimen; but, at the time, I was\nso much amused by watching the grotesque antics of the birds, that I\ndid not think of obtaining one. When I left the spot, I settled in my\nown mind that they were toucans: was I right, Ernest?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The 'Professor', unwilling to interrupt the narrative, merely gave an\noracular nod, and Fritz continued:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'For some hours after this I paddled quickly on, sometimes passing the\nmouth of a stream, sometimes that of a broad river. Had I been merely\non an exploring expedition, I should have been tempted, doubtless, to\ncruise a little way up one of these pathways into the forest; but now\nsuch an idea did not enter my head. On, on, on, I felt I must go, until\nI should reach the goal of my voyage."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The shades of night at length drew on and, finding a sheltered cove, I\nmoored my cajack, and stepped on shore. You may imagine how pleasant it\nwas to stretch my legs, after sitting for so long in the cramped\nposition which my cajack enforces."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It would not do, however, to sleep on shore; so after preparing and\nenjoying my supper, I returned on board, and there spent the night."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Next morning Pounce and I again landed for breakfast. I lit my fire,\nand hung before it a plump young parrot to roast. As I was so doing, I\nheard a slight rustle amongst the long grass behind me. I glanced\nround, and there, with glaring eyes, and his great tail swaying to and\nfro, I saw an immense tiger."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'In another moment his spring would have been made. I should have been\nno more, and our young guest would have been doomed to, God only knows\nhow many, more years of frightful solitude!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My gun was lying by my side. Before I could have stooped to pick it\nup, the monster would have seized me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Pounce saw and comprehended my danger: the heroic bird darted upon my\nenemy, and so blinded him with his flapping wings, and the fierce blows\nof his beak, that his spring was checked, and I had time to recover my\nself-possession. I seized my gun and fired; and the brute, pierced to\nthe heart, gave one spring, and then rolled over at my feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My enemy was dead; but beside himâ€”alas!â€”lay poor Pounce, crushed and\nlifeless. One blow of the great beast's paw had struck him down, never\nto rise again!' Fritz's voice shook as he came to this point; and,\nafter remaining silent for a moment or two, he continued, hurriedly:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'With a sad and desolate feeling at my heart, I buried the faithful\nbird where he had met his death; and then, unable longer to continue\nnear the spot, I returned to my cajack, and leaving the great tiger\nlying where he fell, paddled hastily away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My thoughts were gloomy. I felt as though, now that my companion was\ngone, I could no longer continue the voyage. The albatross, I thought,\nmay have flown for hundreds of miles before it reached me. This\nstranger may be on different shores from these entirely; every stroke\nof my paddle may be carrying me further from the blazing signal: who\nknows?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'This feeling of discouragement was not, however, to be of long\nduration; for in a moment more a sight presented itself, which\nbanished all my doubts and fears, and raised me to the highest pitch of\nexcitement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A high point of land lay before me. I rounded it, and beyond found a\ncalm and pleasant bay, from whose curved and thickly wooded shores ran\nout a reef of rocks. From the point of this reef rose a column of\nsmoke, steadily and clearly curling upwards in the calm air. I could\nscarcely believe my senses, but stopped gazing at it, as though I were\nin a dream; then, with throbbing pulse and giddy brain, I seized my\npaddle, and strained every nerve to reach it."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A few strokes seemed to carry me across the bay, and, securing my\ncanoe, I leaped upon the rock, on which the beacon was blazing, but not\na sign of a human being could I see. I was about to shout, for as the\nfire had evidently been recently piled up, I knew the stranger could\nnot be far off; but, before I could do so, I saw a slight figure\npassing along the chain of rocks towards the spot on which I stood. You\nmay all imagine my sensations."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I advanced a few paces; and then mastering my emotion as best I\ncould, I said, in English:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "\"Welcome, fair stranger! God, in His mercy, has heard your call, and\nhas sent me to your aid!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Miss Montrose came quickly forwardâ€”'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Who? What?' shouted the boys, interrupting the narrative. 'Who came\nforward?' and amid a general hubbub, Ernest, rising and advancing to\nhis brother, said in his quiet way:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I did not like to make any remark till you actually let out the\nsecret, Fritz, but we need no longer pretend not to see through the\ndisguise of Edward Montrose.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, though much disconcerted by the discovery of the secret,\nrecovered his self-possession; and, after bearing with perfect\nequanimity the jokes with which his brothers assailed him, joined in\nthree cheers for their new sister, and when the confusion and laughter\nwhich ensued had subsided, continued his story."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Miss Montrose grasped my hands warmly, and guessing from my\npronunciation, I am afraid, that I was not in the habit of speaking\nEnglish every day of my life, said in French:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'\"Long, long, have I waited since the bird returned with your message.\nThank God, you have come at last!\""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Then, with tears of joy and gratitude, she led me to the shore, where\nshe had built a hut and a safe sleeping-place, like Falconhurst on a\nsmall scale, among the branches of a tree. I was delighted with all she\nshowed me, for indeed her hut and its fittings evinced no ordinary\nskill and ingenuity. Round the walls hung bows, arrows, lances and\nbird-snares; while on her work-table, in boxes and cases, carved\nskilfully with a knife, were fish-hooks of mother-of-pearl, needles\nmade from fishbones, and bodkins from the beaks of birds, fishing-lines\nof all sorts, and knives and other tools."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "These latter she told me were, with a chest of wearing apparel, almost\nthe only things washed ashore after the wreck, when three years ago she\nwas cast alone upon this desolate coast. I marvelled more and more at\nthe wonderful way in which this girl had surmounted obstacles, the\nquarter of which would completely have appalled the generality of her\nsex."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The hut itself was a marvel of skill; stout posts had been driven into\nthe ground, with cross pieces of bamboo, to form a framework; the walls\nhad then been woven with reeds, the roof thatched with palm-leaves, and\nthe whole plastered smoothly with clay, an open space being left in the\ncentre of the roof for a chimney to carry off the smoke of the fire."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'As we entered, a cormorant, with a cry of anger, flew from under the\ntable towards me, and was about to attack me fiercely. Miss Montrose\ncalled it off, and she then told me she had captured and tamed the bird\nsoon after first landing, and since that time had contrived to train it\nto assist her in every conceivable way: it now not only was a pleasant\ncompanion, but brought her food of every description, fish, flesh and\nfowl, for whether it dived into the waters, according to its natural\nhabit, struck down birds upon the wing, or seized rabbits and other\nsmall animals upon the land, it laid all its booty at her feet."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Before darkness closed in, all the curiosities and ingenious\ncontrivances of the place had been displayed the kitchen-stove,\ncooking utensils, skin bottles, shell plates and spoons, the fishing\nraft, and numberless other thingsâ€”and then, sitting down with my fair\nhostess to a most appetizing meal, she gave me a short account of her\nlife:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jenny* Montrose was the daughter of a British officer who had served\nfor many years in India, where she herself was born. At the early age\nof three years she lost her mother."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Some translations give her name as Emily."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After the death of his wife, all the Colonel's love and care was\ncentred upon his only child; under his eye she was instructed in all\nthe accomplishments suited to her sex; and from him she imbibed an\nardent love of field sports. By the time she was seventeen she was as\nmuch at home upon her horse in the field as in her father's\ndrawing-room."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Colonel Montrose now received orders to return home with his regiment\nand as, for certain reasons, he did not wish her to accompany him in\nthe ship with the troops, he obtained a passage for her on board a\nvessel which was about to sail at the same time."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The separation was extremely painful to both the old soldier and his\ndaughter, but there was no alternative. They parted, and Miss Montrose\nsailed in the Dorcas for England. A week after she had left Calcutta, a\nstorm arose and drove the vessel far out of her course; more bad\nweather ensued; and at length, leaks having been sprung in all\ndirections, the crew were obliged to take to the boats."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jenny obtained a place in one of the largest of these. After enduring\nthe perils of the sea for many days, land was sighted; and, the other\nboats having disappeared, an attempt was made to land. The boat was\ncapsized, and Miss Montrose alone reached the shore. For a long time\nshe lay upon the sand almost inanimate; but, reviving sufficiently to\nmove, she at length obtained some shellfish, and by degrees recovered\nher strength."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From that time forth until I appeared she never set eyes upon a human\nbeing. To attract any passing vessel, and obtain assistance, however,\nshe kept a beacon continually blazing at the end of the reef; and, with\nthe same purpose in view, attached missives to the feet of any birds\nshe could take alive in her snares. The albatross, she told me, she had\nkept for some time and partially tamed; but, as it was in the habit of\nmaking long excursions on its own account, she conceived the idea of\nsending it also with a message, that, should it by chance be seen and\ntaken alive, it might return with an answer."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Our supper was over; and, at length, both wearied out with the\nanxieties and excitement of the day, we retired to rest, she to her\nleafy bower, and I to sleep in the hut below."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Next morning, having packed her belongings in the cajack, we both went\non board; and bidding adieu to her well-known bay she took her seat\nbefore me, and I made for home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'We should have reached Rockburg this evening had not an accident\noccurred to our skiff and compelled us to put in at this island. The\nboat was scarcely repaired when I heard your first shots. I instantly\ndisguised myself; and, never doubting that Malay pirates were near,\ncame forth to reconnoitre. Glad, indeed, I was to find my fears\nungrounded.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All had listened attentively to Fritz's story, but now a dreadful yawn\nfrom Franz, followed by others from Jack, Ernest and Fritz, and a great\ndesire on my own part to follow their example, warned me that it was\ntime to dismiss the party for the night. Fritz retired to his cajack,\nthe boys and I to the deck of the yacht, and the remainder of the night\npassed quietly away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Next morning as we assembled for breakfast I took the opportunity of\nbegging Miss Montrose no longer to attempt to continue her disguise,\nbut to allow us to address her in her real character."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jenny smiled; for she had noticed, as the young men met her when she\ncame from the cabin, a great alteration in their manner, and had at\nonce seen that her secret was guessed."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'After all,' she said, 'I need not be ashamed of this attire; it has\nbeen my only costume for the last three years, and in any other I\nshould have been unable to manage all the work which during that time\nhas been necessary.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our pleasant meal over, I prepared to start for home, but Fritz\nreminded me of the cachalot, and although he confessed he should not\ncare to repeat the operation of cutting up a whale, he thought it would\nbe a pity to lose such a chance of obtaining a supply of spermaceti."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I fully agreed with him; and embarking, we quickly reached the\nsandbank on which the monster lay. No sooner did we come near than the\ndogs leaped ashore, and before we could follow, rushed round to the\nother side of the great beast; snarling, growling and howling ensued,\nand when we reached the spot we found a terrific combat going on. A\ntroop of wolves were disputing fiercely with the dogs their right to\nthe prey."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our appearance, however, quickly settled the matter; two of the brutes\nalready lay dead, and those that now escaped our guns, galloped off.\nAmongst the pack were a few jackals, and no sooner did Coco catch sight\nof these, his relations, than, suddenly attracted by his instinct, he\nleft his master's side, and in spite of our shouts and cries, joined\nthem and disappeared into the forest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As it would have been useless and dangerous to attempt to follow the\ndeserter into the woods, we left him alone, trusting that he would\nreturn before we again embarked. Fritz then climbed up the mountain of\nflesh, and with his hatchet quickly laid open the huge skull; Jack and\nFranz joined himâ€”Ernest having remained on the island, where we had\nleft my wife and Jennyâ€”and with buckets assisted him to bail out the\nspermaceti."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The few vessels we possessed were soon full, and having stored them in\nthe yacht, we once more embarked and arrived at the little island\nshortly before the dinner-hour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A capital meal had been prepared for us and, when we had made\nourselves presentable, we sat down to it, and related our adventures.\nThe account of Coco's desertion was received with exclamations of\nsurprise and sorrow. 'Yet,' said Jenny, after a time, 'I do not think\nyou should despair of his recovery, for animals in their native state\nseldom care to allow those that have been once domesticated to consort\nwith them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My poor albatross even, though he was never thoroughly tamed, and\ncertainly did finally desert me, yet used to return at intervals; and I\nam pretty sure that were you, Jack, to search the wood early tomorrow\nmorning, you would find your pet only too willing to come back to\ncivilized life; or, if you like, I will go myself and find him, for I\nshould immensely like to have a paddle in the cajack all by myself.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jack was delighted at the former suggestion, and though he would not\nlisten for a moment to Jenny's request to be allowed to go alone, he\nagreed, if she cared for the fun of an early cruise, to accompany her\nin the canoe next morning, and to return to the yacht in time to start\nfor Rockburg."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At sunrise they were off, armed with 'bait' in the shape of meat and\nbiscuit, and a muzzle and chain which Jack had manufactured in the\nevening to punish the runagate for his offences, should they catch him.\nArrived at the sandbank, they landed; and, after entering the forest\nand shouting 'Coco, Coco!' till the woods rang again, they presently\nespied the truant, slouching disconsolately towards them, looking very\nmiserable and heartily ashamed of himself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With torn ears, and coat ruffled and dirty, he sneaked up. There was no\nneed to use the bait to entice him; and when the poor beast thus came,\nunhappy and begging forgiveness, Jack had not the heart to degrade him\nfurther with the muzzle and chain. He had evidently attempted to join\nhis wild brethren, and by them had been scouted, worried, and hustled,\nas no true jackal; and, as Jenny had foretold, was now only too glad to\nreturn to bondage and to comfort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Poor Coco had recovered his spirits slightly by the time the yacht was\nreached; and, after a hearty meal, again took his place amongst the\ndogs, whom I had little doubt he would never again desert."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All was now bustle and activity; and breakfast over, we went aboard the\nyacht. Fritz and Jack stepped into the canoe; and we soon left Fair\nIsle and Pearl Bay far behind."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The morning was delightful. The sea, excepting for the slight ripple\nraised by the gentle breeze wafting us homewards, was perfectly calm.\nSlowly and contentedly we glided on through the wonders of the splendid\narchway, threaded our passage amongst the rocks and shoals, and passed\nout to the open sea. So slowly did we make our way, that the occupants\nof the cajack announced that they could not wait for us when they had\nonce piloted us out from amongst the shoals and reefs, and plied their\npaddles to such good purpose that they were soon out of sight."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Nautilus Bay and Cape Pug-Nose were in due time passed, however, and\nShark Island hove in sight. With great astonishment Jenny gazed at our\nwatch-tower, with its guard-house, the fierce-looking guns, and the\nwaving flag upon the heights. We landed, that she might visit the\nfortification; then we displayed all our arrangements with great pride.\nWhen they and the herd of lovely gazelles had been sufficiently\nadmired, we again embarked, and steered towards Safety Bay. On\nreaching the entrance, a grand salute of twelve shots welcomed us\nand our fair guest to Rockburg. Not pleased with the even number,\nhowever, Ernest insisted upon replying with thirteen guns, an odd\nnumber being, he declared, absolutely necessary for form's sake."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As we neared the quay, Fritz and Jack stood ready to receive us, and\nwith true politeness handed their mother and Jenny ashore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They turned and led the way to the house through the gardens, orchards\nand shrubberies which lay on the rising ground that sloped gently\nupwards to our dwelling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Jenny's surprise was changed to wonder as she neared the villa\nitselfâ€”its broad, shady balcony, its fountains sparkling in the sun,\nthe dove-cots, the pigeons wheeling above, and the bright, fresh\ncreepers twined round the columns, delighted her. She could scarcely\nbelieve that she was still far from any civilized nation, and that she\nwas amongst a family wrecked like herself upon a lonely coast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My amazement, however, fully equalled that of my little daughter when\nbeneath the shade of the verandah I saw a table laid out with a\ndelicious luncheon. All our china, silver and glass had been called\ninto requisition, and was arranged upon the spotless damask cloth."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Wine sparkled in the decanters, splendid pineapples, oranges, guavas,\napples and pears, resting on cool green leaves, lay heaped in pyramids\nupon the porcelain dishes. A haunch of venison, cold fowl, ham, and\ntongues occupied the ends and sides of the table, while in the centre\nrose a vase of gay flowers, surrounded by bowls of milk and great jugs\nof mead. It was, indeed, a perfect feast, and the heartiness of the\nwelcome brought tears of joy into the lovely eyes of the fair girl in\nwhose honour it had been devised."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All were soon ready to sit down; and Jenny, looking prettier than ever\nin the dress for which she had exchanged her sailor's suit, took the\nplace of honour between my wife and me. Ernest and Franz also seated\nthemselves; but nothing would induce Fritz and Jack to follow their\nexample. They considered themselves our entertainers, and waited upon\nus most attentively, carving the joints, filling our glasses, and\nchanging the plates; for, as Jack declared to Miss Montrose, the\nservants had all run away in our absence, and for the next day or two,\nperhaps, we should be obliged to wait upon ourselves."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the banquet was over, and the waiters had satisfied their\nappetites, they joined their brothers, and with them displayed all the\nwonders of Rockburg to their new sister. To the house, cave, stables,\ngardens, fields and boat-houses, to one after the other did they lead\nher."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Not a corner would they have left unnoticed, had not my wife, fearing\nthey would tire the poor girl out, come to the rescue, and led her back\nto the house."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the following day, after an early breakfast, we started, while it\nwas yet cool, for Falconhurst; and as I knew that repairs and\narrangements for the coming winter would be necessary and would detain\nus for several days, we took with us a supply of tools, as well as\nbaskets of provisions and other things essential to our comfort."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The whole of our stud, excepting the ostrich, were in their paddocks,\nnear the tree; but Jack, saying that his mother and Jenny really must\nnot walk the whole way, to the great amusement of the latter, leaped on\nHurry, and fled away in front of us. Before we had accomplished one\nquarter of the distance, we heard the thundering tread of many feet\ngalloping down the avenue, and presently espied our motley troop of\nsteeds being driven furiously towards us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Storm, Lightfoot, Swift, Grumble, Stentor, Arrow and Dart were there,\nwith Jack, on his fleet two-legged courser, at their heels. At his\nsaddle-bow hung a cluster of saddles and bridles, the bits all jangling\nand clanking, adding to the din and confusion, and urging on the\nexcited animals, who thoroughly entered into the fun, and with tails in\nthe air, ears back, and heels ever and anon thrown playfully out,\nseemed about to overwhelm us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We stepped aside to shelter ourselves behind the trees from the\nfurious onset; but a shout from Fritz brought the whole herd to a\nsudden halt, and Jack spurred towards us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Which of the cattle shall we saddle for you, Jenny?' he shouted.\n'They're all as gentle as lambs, and as active as cats. Every one has\nbeen ridden by mother; and knows what a side-saddle means, so you can't\ngo wrong.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "To his great delight, Jenny quickly showed her appreciation of the\nmerits of the steeds by picking out Dart, the fleetest and most\nspirited in the whole stud."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The ostrich was then relieved of his unusual burden, the animals were\nspeedily equipped, and Lightfoot bearing the baskets and hampers, the\nwhole party mounted and trotted forwards. Jenny was delighted with her\npalfrey, and henceforward he was reserved for her special use."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The work at Falconhurst, as I had expected, occupied us for some time\nand it was a week before we could again return to Rockburg."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Yet the time passed pleasantly; for though the young men were busy from\nmorning to night, the presence of their new companion, her lively\nspirits and gay conversation, kept them in constant good humour."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "When the repairs were all finished we remained yet a day or two\nlonger, that we might make excursions in various directions to bring in\npoultry from Woodlands, stores of acorns for the pigs, and grass,\nwillows and canes, to be manufactured during the winter into mats,\nbaskets, hurdles and hen-coops."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many a shower wetted us through during these days, and we had scarcely\ntime to hurry back to Rockburg and house our cattle and possessions\nbefore the annual deluge began."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Never before had this dreary season seemed so short and pleasant; with\nJenny amongst us the usual feeling of weariness and discontent never\nappeared; the English language was quickly acquired by all hands,\nFritz, in particular, speaking it so well that Jenny declared she could\nscarcely believe he was not an Englishman. She herself already spoke\nFrench, and therefore easily learned our native language and spoke it\nfluently before we were released from our captivity."
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
