  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 18"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Many wondrous tales were told or read in turn by the boys and Jenny\nduring the long evenings as we sat drawing, weaving and plaiting in our\nrosy study. In fact this winter was a truly happy time, and when at\nlength the rain ceased and the bright sun again smiled upon the face of\nnature, we could scarcely believe, as we stepped forth and once more\nfelt the balmy breath of spring, that, for so many weeks, we had been\nprisoners within our rocky walls."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All was once more activity and life; the duties in field, garden and\norchard called forth the energy of the lads, whilst their mother and\nsister found abundant occupation in the poultry-yard and house."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our various settlements and stations required attention. Falconhurst,\nWoodlands, Prospect Hill, Shark and Whale Islands were in turn visited\nand set in order. The duty of attending to the island battery fell to\nJack and Franz."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "They had been busy all day repairing the flagstaff, rehoisting the\nflag, and cleaning and putting into working order the two guns. Evening\nwas drawing on and our day's work over; the rest of us were strolling\nup and down upon the beach enjoying the cool sea breeze. We watched the\nlads as they completed their work. They loaded and ran out their guns\nand, paddling off with an empty tub in the cajack, placed it out to sea\nas a mark for practice. They returned and fired, and the barrel flew in\npieces; with a shout of triumph, they cleaned the guns and ran them in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Scarcely had they done so when, as though in answer to their shots,\ncame the sound of three guns booming across the water from the\nwestward."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We stopped, speechless. Was it fancy? Had we really heard guns from a\nstrange ship? Or had the boys again fired? No! There were the lads\nleaping into their canoe and paddling in hot haste towards us. They,\ntoo, had heard the sound."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A tumult of feelings rushed over usâ€”anxiety, joy, hope, doubt, each in\nturn took possession of our minds. Was it a European vessel close upon\nour shores, and were we about to be linked once more to civilized life?\nOr did those sounds proceed from a Malay pirate, who would rob and\nmurder us? What was to be the result of meeting with our fellow beings;\nwere they to be friends who would help us, enemies who would attack us,\nor would they prove unfortunate creatures in need of our assistance?\nWho could tell?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Before we could express these thoughts in words the cajack had touched\nthe shore, and Jack and Franz were among us."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Did you hear them? Did you hear them?' they gasped. 'What shall we do?\nWhere shall we go?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Oh, Fritz,' continued my youngest son, 'it must be a European ship. We\nshall find her. We shall see our Fatherland once more,' and, in an\nemotion of joy, he grasped his brother's hands."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Till then I knew not what a craving for civilized life had been\naroused in the two young men by the appearance of their European\nsister."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All eyes were turned towards me. What would I advise?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'At present,' I said, 'we can do nothing, for night is drawing on. We\nmust make what preparation we can, and pray for guidance.' In the\ngreatest excitement we returned to the house, all talking eagerly, and\ntill late no one could be persuaded to retire to rest."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Few slept that night. The boys and I took it in turn to keep watch from\nthe verandah, lest more signals might be fired, or a hostile visit\nmight be paid us. But about midnight the wind began to rise, and before\nwe reassembled to discuss our plans a fearful storm was raging; so\nterrific was the sea that I knew no boat could live, and had a\nbroadside been fired at the entrance of the Bay we should not have\nheard it through the howling of the blast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For two days and two nights the hurricane continued, but on the third\nday the sun again appeared, and, the wind lulling, the sea went rapidly\ndown. Full of anxiety I readily complied with the boys' desire to put\noff to Shark Island and discharge the guns; for who could tell what had\nbeen the result of the gale; perhaps the vessel had been driven upon\nthe rocky shore or, fearing such a fate, she had left the coast and\nweathered the storm out at sea; if so she might never return."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With these thoughts I accompanied Jack and Franz to the fort.\nOneâ€”twoâ€”we fired the guns and waited."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For some minutes there was no reply, and then an answering report\nrolled in the distance. There was no longer room for doubt; the\nstrangers were still in the vicinity, and were aware of our presence.\nWe waved the flag as a signal to those on shore that all was well, and\nquickly returned. We found the whole family in a state of the greatest\nexcitement, and I felt it necessary to calm them down as much as\npossible, for neither could I answer the questions with which I was\nbesieged, nor could I conceal the fact that the visit of the vessel\nmight not prove so advantageous as they expected."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and I at once prepared to make a reconnaissance; we armed\nourselves with our guns, pistols and cutlasses, took a spy-glass,\nseated ourselves in the cajack and, with a parting entreaty from my\nwife to be cautious, paddled out of the bay and round the high cliffs\non our left. For nearly an hour we advanced in the direction from which\nthe reports of the guns seemed to proceed. Nothing could we see,\nhowever, but the frowning rocks and cliffs, and the waves beating\nrestlessly at their base. Cape Pug-Nose was reached, and we began to\nround the bluff old point."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a moment all our doubts were dispelled, and joy and gratitude to the\nGreat Giver of all good filled our hearts. There, in the little\nsheltered cove beyond the cape, her sails furled, and anchor dropped,\nlay a brig-of-war with the English colours at her masthead."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With the glass I could discern figures upon the deck and, upon the\nshore beyond, several tents pitched under the shelter of the trees, and\nthe smoke of fires rising amongst them. As I handed the glass to Fritz,\nI felt a sudden misgiving. 'What,' said I to myself, 'can this English\nvessel be doing thus far from the usual track of ships?' and I called\nto mind tales of mutinous crews who have risen against their officers,\nhave chosen some such sheltered retreat as this; have disguised the\nvessel, and then sailed forth to rob and plunder upon the high seas."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz then exclaimed, 'I can see the captain, father, he is speaking to\none of the officers, and I can see his face quite well; he is English,\nI am certain he is English, and the flag speaks the truth!' and he put\nthe glass again in my hand that I might see for myself."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Still keeping under the shelter of the cliff, I carefully surveyed the\nvessel. There was no doubt that Fritz was right, and my fears were once\nmore dispelled; all was neatness and regularity on board; the spotless\ndecks, the burnished steel and brass, and the air of perfect order\nwhich pervaded both ship and camp, betokened that authority and\ndiscipline there reigned."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For some minutes longer we continued our examination of the scene, and\nthen satisfied by the appearance of the camp on shore, that there was\nno chance of the brig quitting the coast for several days, we resolved\nto return without betraying our presence, for I was unwilling to appear\nbefore these strangers until we could do so in better form, and in a\nmanner more in accordance with our actual resources."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We again landed at Rockburg, where our family awaited our arrival in\neager expectation, and as fully as possible we told them of all we had\nseen. They thoroughly approved of our caution, and even Jenny, whose\nhopes had been excited to the highest pitch by our description of the\nEnglish vessel, and who longed to meet her countrymen once more, agreed\nto postpone the visit until the following day, when, having put our\nyacht into good order, we might pay our respects to the captain, not as\npoor shipwrecked creatures begging assistance, but as lords and masters\nof the land, seeking to know for what purpose strangers were visiting\nthe coast."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The rest of the day was occupied in making our preparations. Our\ndainty little craft was made to look her very best; her decks were\nscrubbed, her brass guns burnished, all lumber* removed and put ashore,\nand the flag of England hoisted to her peak."
  },
  {
    "tag": "ul",
    "innerHtml": {
      "list": [
        "Junk, things stored but not in use."
      ]
    }
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My wife overhauled our wardrobes, and the neatest uniforms were put\nready for the boys and me, for though neither my wife nor Jenny had\never dreamed of appearing otherwise than they would have done, had they\nbeen at home amongst civilized people in Europe, yet we, accustomed\ndaily to rough and often even dirty work, had adopted just that costume\nwhich best suited our comfort and inclination. We should indeed have\nsurprised the smart man-o'-war's men, had we appeared in our great\nshapeless wide-brimmed hats, our linen coats and trousers, our broad\nleathern belts and hairy buskins; so we next day readily donned the\nmore becoming costumes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At the break of that eventful morn, when we were destined once more to\nset our eyes upon our fellow men, and to hear news of the outer world,\nfrom which for so many years we had been exiled, we assembled in our\nlittle breakfast-room. The meal was eaten hurriedly and almost in\nsilence, for our hearts were too full, and our minds too busily\noccupied, to allow of any outward display of excitement. Fritz and Jack\nthen slipped quietly out, and presently returned from the garden with\nbaskets of the choicest fruits in fresh and fragrant profusion, and\nwith these, as presents for the strangers, we went on board our yacht."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The anchor was weighed, the sails set, and with the canoe in tow the\nlittle vessel, as though partaking of our hopes and joyous\nexpectation, bounded merrily over the waters of Safety Bay, gave a wide\nberth to the Reef, against whose frowning rocks the sea still lashed\nitself to foam, and kept away for the cove, where the English ship\nunconsciously awaited us. The Pug-nosed Cape was reached, and to the\nsurprise and utter amazement of the strangers, we rounded the point and\nbrought up within hail."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Every eye on board and on shore was turned towards us, every glass was\nproduced and fixed upon our motions; for of all the strange sights\nwhich the gallant crew may have looked for, such an anomaly as a\npleasure yacht, manned by such a party as ours, and cruising upon this\nstrange and inhospitable shore, was the furthest from their thoughts."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz and I stepped into our boat, and pulled for the brig. In another\nminute we were upon her deck. The captain, with the simple frankness of\na British seaman, welcomed us cordially, and having led us into his\ncabin, begged us to explain to what good fortune he owed a visit from\nresidents upon a coast generally deemed uninhabited, or the abode of\nthe fiercest savages."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I gave him an outline of the history of the wreck, and of our sojourn\nupon these shores, and spoke to him, too, of Miss Montrose, and of the\nprovidential way in which we had been the means of rescuing her from\nher lonely position."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Then,' said the gallant officer, rising and grasping Fritz by the\nhand, 'let me heartily thank you in my own name, and in that of Colonel\nMontrose; for it was the hope of finding some trace of that brave girl\nthat led me to these shores. The disappearance of the Dorcas has been a\nterrible blow to the Colonel, and yet, though for three years no word\nof her or of any of those who sailed in her has reached England, he has\nnever entirely abandoned all hope of again hearing of his daughter. I\nknew this, and a few weeks ago, when I was about to leave Sydney for\nthe Cape, I found three men who declared themselves survivors of the\nDorcas, and said that their boat, of four which left the wreck, was the\nonly one which, to their knowledge, reached land in safety."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'From them I learned all particulars, and applying for permission to\ncruise in these latitudes, I sailed in the hopes of finding further\ntraces of the unfortunate crew. My efforts have been rewarded by\nunlooked-for success.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz replied most modestly to the praises which he received, and then\nthe captain begged to be introduced to my wife and Miss Montrose."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And,' he continued, 'if it be not contrary to your rules of\ndiscipline, for the whole ship's company to be absent at once, I will\nnow send a boat for the remainder of your party.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "One of the officers was accordingly dispatched to the yacht with a\npolite message, and the mother, Jenny, and the three boys were\npresently on board."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Our kind host greeted them most warmly, and he and his officers vied\nwith one another in doing us honour. They proved, indeed, most pleasant\nentertainers, and the time passed rapidly away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "At luncheon the captain told us that there had sailed with him from\nSydney an invalid gentleman, Mr. Wolston, his wife, and two daughters;\nbut that though the sea voyage had been recommended on account of his\nhealth, yet it had not done Mr. Wolston so much good as had been\nanticipated, and he had suffered so greatly from the effects of the\nstorm which had driven the Unicorn into the bay for repairs, that he\nhad been eager to rest for a short time on land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "We were anxious to meet the family, and in the afternoon it was\ndecided that we should pay them a visit. Tents had been pitched for\ntheir accommodation under the shady trees, and when we landed we found\nMr. Wolston seated by one of them, enjoying the cool sea-breeze. He and\nhis family were delighted to see us, and so much did we enjoy their\nsociety, that evening found us still upon the shore. It was too late\nthen to return to Rockburg, and the captain kindly offered tents for\nthe accommodation of those who could not find room in the yacht. The\nboys spent the night on land."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "That night I had a long and serious consultation with my wife, as to\nwhether or not we really had any well-grounded reason for wishing to\nreturn to Europe. It would be childish to undertake a voyage thither\nsimply because an opportunity offered for doing so."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Neither knew to what decision the feelings of the other inclined; each\nwas afraid of expressing what might run counter to those feelings; but\ngradually it began to appear that neither entertained any strong wish\nto leave the peaceful island; and finally we discovered that the real\nwish which lay at the bottom of both our hearts was to adopt New\nSwitzerland as thenceforward our home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "What can be more delightful than to find harmony of opinion in those we\nlove, when a great and momentous decision has to be taken?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "My dear wife assured me that she desired nothing more earnestly than to\nspend the rest of her days in a place to which she had become so much\nattached, provided I, and at least two of her sons, also wished to\nremain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From the other two she would willingly part, if they chose to return to\nEurope, with the understanding that they must endeavour to send out\nemigrants of a good class to join us, and form a prosperous colony,\nadding that she thought the island ought to continue to bear the name\nof our native country, even if inhabited in future time by colonists\nfrom England, as well as from Switzerland."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I heartily approved of this excellent idea, and we agreed to mention\nit, while consulting with Captain Littlestone on the subject of placing\nthe island under the protection of Great Britain."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Then came the question as to which of our sons were best suited to\nremain with us, and which to go away."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This point we left undecided, thinking that in the course of a few\ndays, they would probably make a choice of their own accord, which they\ndid, even sooner than we anticipated. After breakfast, it was proposed\nthat Captain Littlestone should bring his ship round to Safety Bay,\nthat we might receive a visit from him and his party, at\nRockburgâ€”where we invited the invalid, Mr. Wolston, and his family, in\nhopes that his health might benefit by a comfortable residence on\nshore."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "No sooner was this plan adopted, than Fritz and Jack hurried off in the\ncanoe to prepare for their reception, being followed in more leisurely\nstyle by the brig and our yacht."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But what words can express the amazement of our guests, when, rounding\nthe Rocky Cape at the entrance, Safety Bay, and the beautiful domain of\nRockburg, lay before them."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Still greater was their astonishment, as a salute of eleven guns\nboomed from the battery on Shark Island, where the royal standard of\nEngland was displayed and floated majestically on the morning breeze."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "A glow of surprise and pleasure beamed on every countenance, and poor\nWolston's spirits appeared to revive with the very idea of the peace\nand happiness to be enjoyed in such a home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He was carried on shore with the utmost care and tenderness, and\ncomfortably established in my room, a camp-bed for Mrs. Wolston being\nadded to the furniture there, that she might be able conveniently to\nattend on her husband."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Meantime the scene at the harbour and all round Rockburg was of the\nliveliest description; merriment and excitement prevailed in all\ndirections, as the beauties and wonders of our residence were\nexplored, so that a summons to dinner scarcely attracted notice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "However, as a visit to Falconhurst was projected, the company was at\nlength induced to be seated, and to partake of our good cheer, but the\nspirit of restlessness soon returned, and the young people kept roaming\nabout through our hitherto quiet lawns, avenues and shrubberies, until\nI was ready to believe their number three times what it actually was."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Towards evening the universal excitement began to abate, and the party\nassembled for supper with tolerable composure."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mr. Wolston was able to join us, as the rest he had enjoyed, and the\npleasure inspired by the hope of a residence among us, seemed to have\ngiven him new life. This wish he now distinctly expressed in his own\nname, and in that of his wife; inquiring what our intentions were, and\nproposing, if agreeable to us, that they, with their eldest daughter,\nwhose health, like his own, was delicate, should make a long stay on\nthe island, while the younger daughter went for the present to her\nbrother at the Cape of Good Hope."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In the event of his ultimately deciding to settle altogether among us,\nMr. Wolston would propose that his son should leave the Cape, and join\nour colony."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "With sincere satisfaction, I welcomed this proposal, saying that it was\nmy wish and that of my wife to remain for the rest of our days in New\nSwitzerland."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Hurrah for New Switzerland! New Switzerland for ever!' shouted the\nwhole company enthusiastically, as they raised their glasses, and made\nthem touch with a musical ring, which so expressively denotes a joyful\nunanimity of sentiment."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Prosperity to New Switzerland; long may she flourish,' echoed on all\nsides."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Long life and happiness to those who make New Switzerland their\nhome!' added Ernest to my great surprise, leaning forward as he spoke,\nto ring his glass with mine, his mother's and Mr. Wolston's."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Won't somebody wish long life and prosperity to those who go away?'\ninquired Jenny with a pretty arch look. 'Much as I long to return to\nEngland and my father, my inclination will waver if all the cheers are\nfor New Switzerland!'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Three cheers for England and Colonel Montrose,' cried Fritz, 'success\nand happiness to us who return to Europe!' and while the vaulted roofs\nrang with the cheering elicited by this toast, a glance from Jenny\nshowed him how much she thanked him for appreciating her wish to return\nto her father, notwithstanding her attachment to our family."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Well,' said I, when silence was restored, 'since Fritz resolves to go\nto England, he must undertake for me the duty of bringing happiness to\na mourning father by restoring to him this dear daughter, whom I have\nbeen ready to regard as my own, by right of finding her cast on the\nshores of my island."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Ernest chooses to remain with me. His mother and I rejoice heartily in\nthis decision, and promise him all the highest scientific appointments\nin our power to bestow."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And now what is Jack's choice? The only talent I can say he possesses\nis that of a comic actor, and to shine on the stage he must needs go to\nEurope.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Jack is not going to Europe, however,' was his reply. 'He means to\nstay here, and when Fritz is gone, he will be the best rider, and the\nbest shot in New Switzerland, which is the summit of his ambition."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'The fact is,' he continued, laughing, 'I rather stand in awe of their\nEuropean schools, and should expect to find myself caught and clapped\ninto one, if I ventured too near them.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'A good school is exactly what I want,' said Franz. 'Among a number of\nstudents there is some emulation and enthusiasm, and I shall have a\nchance of rising in the world."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Fritz will probably return here some day; but it might be well for one\nmember of the family to go home with the intention of remaining there\naltogether, and as I am the youngest, I could more easily than the\nrest, adapt myself to a different life. My father, however, will decide\nfor me.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'You may go, my dear son,' I replied, 'and God bless all our plans and\nresolutions. The whole earth is the Lord's, and where, as in his sight,\nyou lead good and useful lives, there is your home."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'And now that I know your wishes, the only question is, whether\nCaptain Littlestone will kindly enable you to carry them out?'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "All eyes were fixed eagerly upon him, and after a moment's pause the\ngallant officer spoke as follows:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'I think my way in this matter is perfectly clear, and I consider that\nI have been providentially guided to be the means of once more placing\nthis family in communication with their friends and with the civilized\nworld."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'My orders were to search for a shipwrecked crew."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Survivors from two wrecks have been discovered."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Three passengers express a wish to leave my ship here, instead of at\nthe Cape, while, at the same time, I am requested to give to three\npersons a passage to England."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Could anything suit better? I am most willing to undertake the charge\nof those who may be committed to my care."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Every circumstance has been wonderfully ordered and linked together by\nDivine Providence, and if England gains a prosperous and happy colony,\nit will prove a fitting clasp to this fortunate chain of events. Three\ncheers for New Switzerland.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Deep emotion stirred every heart as the party separated for the night.\nMany felt that they were suddenly standing on the threshold of a new\nlife, while, for myself a weight was rolled from my heart, and I\nthanked God that a difficulty was solved which, for years, had\noppressed me with anxiety."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After this nothing was thought of but making preparations for the\ndeparture of the dear ones bound for England. Captain Littlestone\nallowed as much time as he could spare; but it was necessarily short,\nso that incessant movement and industry pervaded the settlement for\nseveral days."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Everything was provided and packed up that could in any way add to our\nchildren's comfort on the voyage, or benefit them after their arrival\nin England, and a large share of my possessions in pearls, corals,\nfurs, spices and other valuables would enable them to take a good\nposition in the world of commerce."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I committed to their care private papers, money, and jewels which I\nknew to have been the personal property of the captain of our\nill-fated ship, desiring them to hand them over, if possible, to his\nheirs. A short account of the wreck, with the names of the crew, a list\nof which I had found, was given to Captain Littlestone."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "His ship, the Unicorn, was amply stored by us with fresh provisions,\nfish, vegetables and fruit, for in our gratitude to him for his\nkindness and sympathy, we felt ready to offer every possible\nassistance."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In a long conversation with my sons I solemnly charged them with the\nfuture responsibilities of their life, in all its varied aspects, of\nduty towards God, their fellow men, and themselves, pointing out the\ntemptations to which their different characters were likely to expose\nthem, and exhorting them affectionately to hold fast to the faith in\nwhich they had been brought up."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fritz, having previously made known to me, what indeed was very\nevident, the attachment between himself and Jenny, I advised him to\nmention it to Colonel Montrose as soon as possible after being\nintroduced to him, and ask for his sanction to their engagement."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I on my part, gladly bestowing mine, as did his mother, who loved the\nsweet girl dearly, and heartily grieved to part with her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "On the evening before our separation, I gave to Fritz the journal in\nwhich, ever since the shipwreck, I had chronicled the events of our\nlife, desiring that the story might be printed and published. 'It was\nwritten, as you well know,' said I, 'for the instruction and amusement\nof my children, but it is very possible that it may be useful to other\nyoung people."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "'Children are, on the whole, very much alike everywhere, and you four\nlads fairly represent multitudes, who are growing up in all\ndirections. It will make me happy to think that my simple narrative may\nlead some of these to observe how blessed are the results of patient\ncontinuance in well-doing, what benefits arise from the thoughtful\napplication of knowledge and science, and how good and pleasant a thing\nit is when brethren dwell together in unity, under the eyes of parental\nlove.'"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Night has closed around me."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "For the last time my united family slumbers beneath my care. Tomorrow\nthis closing chapter of my journal will pass into the hands of my\neldest son."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "From afar I greet thee, Europe!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "I greet thee, dear old Switzerland!"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Like thee, may New Switzerland flourish and prosperâ€”good, happy and\nfree!"
